const QB={
  "U7 / Initiation":[
    {id:"u7q1",cat:"Orientation",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Which way?",d:1,sit:"You just got the puck near center ice. There are two nets. What's the FIRST thing you do?",opts:["Skate as fast as you can any direction","Look up and find which net is yours","Pass to the nearest player","Spin around and wait"],ok:1,why:"Before anything else — look up. A one-second glance tells you which way you're going. The habit of looking first is the most important skill in hockey.",tip:"Got the puck? Look up first. Every time."},
    {id:"u7q2",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Loose pucks",d:1,sit:"The puck is loose in the corner and nobody is near it. What do you do?",opts:["Wait and see who gets it","Skate hard toward the puck no","Stay put and call for it","Go stand in front of the net"],ok:1,why:"Loose pucks belong to whoever wants them most. Going hard after every loose puck is one of the most important habits you can build.",tip:"Loose puck? Go get it. Every time. That's compete."},
    {id:"u7q3",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Whistles",d:1,sit:"The referee blows the whistle and play stops. What should you do?",opts:["Keep skating and playing through the whistle","Stop and look at the ref to see what's next","Sit down on the ice and wait for a teammate no","Skate straight to the bench and sit down fast"],ok:1,why:"When the whistle blows, play is over. Stopping and looking at the ref resets your brain for what comes next.",tip:"Whistle = stop, look, listen. Every time."},
    {id:"u7q4",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Passing",d:1,sit:"You have the puck and a teammate is wide open beside you. Your path to the net is completely blocked. What's the best play?",opts:["Try to skate through the ","Pass to your open teammate","Shoot anyway","Hold the puck and wait fast"],ok:1,why:"Hockey is a team game. Open teammate + blocked path = pass. This is the beginning of understanding that passing can be smarter than carrying.",tip:"Open teammate + your path blocked = pass. That's real hockey thinking."},
    {id:"u7q5",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Shooting",d:1,sit:"You're close to the net with the puck. Nobody is right on you. What's the best thing to do?",opts:["Skate back to center ice now","Shoot at the net","Pass far across to a teamma","Wait for a defender to come"],ok:1,why:"When you're close to the net and open — shoot! Every shot makes the goalie work. Goals come from shooting, not thinking about shooting.",tip:"Close to the net and open? Shoot. Always."},
    {id:"u7q6",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Backchecking",d:1,sit:"The other team has the puck and is skating toward your net. What do you do?",opts:["Skate to center ice and wait for a pass","Skate back toward your net to help defend n","Stand still and watch the play go past you","Go talk to your coach about a line change"],ok:1,why:"When the other team has the puck and is coming your way, your job is to turn around and get back. This is called backchecking.",tip:"Other team coming? Turn around and skate back hard."},
    {id:"u7q7",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Open ice",d:1,sit:"Five teammates are all bunched in one corner chasing the puck. What's a smart thing to do?",opts:["Join the pile and chase the puck even harder","Find empty ice somewhere else and get open","Skate off the ice and ask for a line change now","Stay exactly where you are and call for a pass"],ok:1,why:"Hockey players shouldn't all go to the same spot. Finding open ice gives your team options.",tip:"Everyone's in the corner? Go somewhere else and get open."},
    {id:"u7q8",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Listening",d:1,sit:"Your coach is explaining a drill and you're not sure what to do. What's the best thing?",opts:["Just start skating and just hope you guess the drill ri","Listen carefully, then ask what you didn't understand","Do whatever the kid next to you is doing every time","Sit down on the ice until someone comes to help you fast"],ok:1,why:"Coaches give instructions to help you succeed. Listening well and asking questions is smart, not weak.",tip:"Confused? Listen first, then ask. That's how you get better."},
    {id:"u7q9",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Get close to score",d:1,sit:"You have the puck and you're far away from the net. What should you do first before shooting?",opts:["Shoot from far away right now out there","Skate closer to the net and then shoot","Pass to your teammate who is even fa","Stop and wait"],ok:1,why:"Shots from close to the net are much harder for goalies to stop. Skating closer before shooting gives you a much better chance to score.",tip:"Far away? Skate closer first. Then shoot."},
    {id:"u7q10",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Don't give up",d:1,sit:"You fell down on the ice during a play. What do you do?",opts:["Sit there and wait for a whistle to stop play","Get up as fast as you can and keep playing now","Wave your arms for a quick substitution","Watch the rest of the play from the ice"],ok:1,why:"Falling down happens to every player. Getting up fast and staying in the play is compete. The game doesn't stop — neither do you.",tip:"Fell down? Get up fast. Keep going."},
    {id:"u7q11",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Which net is yours",d:1,sit:"Before the game starts, how can you tell which net your team is trying to score in?",opts:["You can't tell — you just have to guess it","Your goalie is in front of your team's net","Your goalie is set up in the other team's net","It changes every minute of the hockey game"],ok:1,why:"Your goalie always defends your team's net. Finding your goalie tells you which end you're defending — and which end you're trying to score in.",tip:"Not sure which net is yours? Find your goalie. They're in front of it."},
    {id:"u7q12",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Celebrate together",d:1,sit:"Your teammate scores a goal. What should you do?",opts:["Do nothing — you weren't the one who scored","Skate toward them and celebrate together","Skate off the ice for a quick line change","Stand by yourself and wait at center ice now"],ok:1,why:"Hockey is a team sport. When a teammate scores, everyone celebrates — you win together. Learning to celebrate your teammates' goals is part of being a good teammate.",tip:"Teammate scored? Celebrate with them. You're a team."},
    {id:"u7q13",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Near the net",d:1,sit:"Your team has the puck in the offensive zone. You don't have it and nobody is near you. Where's the smartest place to go?",opts:["Stand at center ice for sure","Get to the front of the net","Skate to the corner where t","Go to the bench"],ok:1,why:"Standing in front of the net without the puck is one of the highest-value things a player can do. It creates a screen, puts you in rebound position, and forces a defender to deal with you.",tip:"No puck? Go to the net. Someone will find you there."},
    {id:"u7q14",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Get back",d:1,sit:"Your team just shot the puck and the goalie caught it. The other team will now get the puck. What should you start doing right away?",opts:["Stay where you are and watch the play come back out","Skate back toward your own net to be ready to defend n","Skate fast to the opposing team's end and wait there","Go to the corner and wait for the puck to come to you"],ok:1,why:"After your team's shot is saved, the puck changes possession. Getting back toward your own net right away gets you in position to defend.",tip:"Your shot got saved? Start getting back right away."},
    {id:"u7q15",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Try the drill",d:1,sit:"Your coach shows you a new drill you've never done before. It looks hard. What should you do?",opts:["Refuse to try it","Try your best even if it's hard","Watch other players do it for a long time first","Ask to go home"],ok:1,why:"New drills feel hard at first for everyone. Trying your best — even if you make mistakes — is how you get better. Every great player was a beginner once.",tip:"New drill? Try it. Mistakes are how you learn."},
    {id:"u7q16",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Net front value",d:2,sit:"Your team is in the offensive zone. Your teammate has the puck in the corner. You're standing far away at center ice. What would be the better place to skate to?",opts:["Stay at center ice and wait for the puck to come back out","Skate to the front of the net — right in front of the goalie","Skate to the same corner as your teammate to help them out","Skate all the way to the other end of the rink and wait for it"],ok:1,why:"When a teammate has the puck in the corner, the front of the net is where you can help most. A pass to you there is the most dangerous play, and you're right there for any rebound.",tip:"Teammate in the corner? You go to the net front. That's your spot."},
    {id:"u7q17",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Offsides",d:2,sit:"Your team is skating into the other team's zone. You get there before the puck does. What happens?",opts:["Nothing — you got there first, that's good","The referee calls offsides and play stops","You score automatically","The other team gets to shoot"],ok:1,why:"If you enter the offensive zone before the puck, your team gets called for offsides and play stops. The puck always has to go in first.",tip:"Wait for the puck at the blue line. You can't go in before it."},
    {id:"u7q18",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Board battle",d:2,sit:"You and an opponent both reach a loose puck along the boards at the same time. What do you do?",opts:["Stop skating and let them have the whole puck this time","Use your body to shield the puck and fight to keep it no","Skate away quickly and hope a teammate gets to it","Fall down on the ice and hope the ref stops it fast"],ok:1,why:"Puck battles are won by the player who competes harder. Using your body to create a wall between the opponent and the puck is a real skill.",tip:"Puck battle: get your body between the opponent and the puck."},
    {id:"u7q19",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Spread out",d:2,sit:"You're on a 3-on-1 rush — three of your players against one defender. Where should the three attackers be?",opts:["All three skate together in one tight little group","Spread out so the defender can't cover everyone","Two attackers go left and the third one goes right ","One attacker goes and two wait back at center ice"],ok:1,why:"Spreading out on a rush forces the defender to make an impossible choice. A tight group lets one player cover all three.",tip:"Rush attack: spread out. Make the defender choose."},
    {id:"u7q20",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Good angle",d:2,sit:"You have the puck right beside the net — almost behind it. The angle is really bad. You can barely see the net. What should you do?",opts:["Shoot from right there anyway and hope it goes through the goa","Skate to in front of the net for a better angle before shooting","Pass the puck all the way back to a teammate at center ice","Stop skating and wait for the goalie to move out of the way now "],ok:1,why:"Shooting from behind the net or from a bad angle gives the goalie an easy save. Taking an extra second to find a better angle — like cutting to the front — makes the shot much more dangerous.",tip:"Bad angle? Move to a better one. Then shoot."},
    {id:"u7q21",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defend the front",d:2,sit:"The other team has the puck in the corner of your defensive zone. You're the nearest forward. Your defender has already gone to the corner. What should you do?",opts:["Go into the corner to help your defender battle for it","Stay at the front of the net so nobody is open there","Skate to center ice and wait for a pass to come out","Stand at the blue line and watch your team defend"],ok:1,why:"When your defender goes to the corner, you cover the front of the net. If you both go to the corner, the most dangerous spot on the ice is completely empty.",tip:"Defender goes to the corner? You go to the net front. Always."},
    {id:"u7q22",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Icing",d:2,sit:"Your team is tired and you just want a break. You shoot the puck all the way down the ice from your own end. What will probably happen?",opts:["Your team gets to change lines and take a nice long break to rest ","The referee calls icing and the puck comes back — no line change no","The other team gets a penalty shot from the center ice red dot","Nothing happens at all — the play just keeps going like normal"],ok:1,why:"Shooting the puck from your own side of center all the way down the ice without it being touched is called icing. Play stops and comes back — no line change allowed.",tip:"Icing = no break. If you need a line change, do it the right way."},
    {id:"u7q23",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Find the open ice",d:2,sit:"You're in the offensive zone without the puck. Your teammate has it. Three of their teammates are all crowded around them. What should you do?",opts:["Go join the crowd and chase the puck with your teammates near the boards","Find an open space away from the crowd — near the net or at the blue line","Stand still in your spot and wait for someone to pass you the puck there no","Skate to the bench and take a quick rest while your teammates keep playing"],ok:1,why:"Crowding around the puck carrier makes it harder for them, not easier. Finding open ice gives them a passing option and stretches the defense.",tip:"Teammate has the puck and everyone's crowding them? Go find open ice. Give them an option."},
    {id:"u7q24",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Get to the puck first",d:2,sit:"A puck is sliding toward the boards. You and an opponent are racing to it. You're slightly behind them. What's the smart play as you approach?",opts:["Give up on the race — they'll probably beat you to it by a mile anyway","Angle your body to get to the inside position before they reach the puck","Skate straight at them as fast as you can and try to knock them off it","Stop skating altogether and call loudly for a teammate to come help you out"],ok:1,why:"Getting to the inside position — between your opponent and the puck — before they reach it gives you the advantage even if they arrive first.",tip:"Race to a puck: focus on getting inside position, not just getting there first."},
    {id:"u7q25",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Watching from the bench",d:2,sit:"You're sitting on the bench watching the game. What's the best thing to do while you're waiting for your turn?",opts:["Talk to your friends about things that are not about the game","Watch the game and learn from what's happening on the ice","Look around at the crowd and wave at your family and friends","Ignore the game completely and just rest for your next shift"],ok:1,why:"Watching the game from the bench isn't just resting — it's learning. Players who pay attention to the game while on the bench come back on the ice knowing what's happening.",tip:"On the bench? Watch the game. Learn what's happening before you go back on."},
    {id:"u7q26",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Be a good sport",d:2,sit:"The other team scores a goal against you. What do you do?",opts:["Argue with the referee","Say something mean to the other team right now now","Skate back to your position and get ready for the","Sit down on the ice"],ok:2,why:"Goals happen in every game — even the best teams give them up. The response to a goal against is to regroup and get ready to play. Good sportsmanship means handling both winning and losing the right way.",tip:"Goal against? Head up. Get back to your position. The game's not over."},
    {id:"u7q27",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Follow your shot",d:2,sit:"You shoot the puck at the net. The goalie doesn't quite catch it — the puck bounces off them. What should you do?",opts:["Skate away — you already took your one s","Chase the rebound and try to shoot again","Celebrate even though it didn't go in now","Just wait for the referee to blow it dead"],ok:1,why:"Rebounds from your own shot are one of the easiest scoring chances in hockey. Chasing your shot to the net means you might get a second chance.",tip:"Follow your shot. Rebounds are your friend."},
    {id:"u7q28",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Watch your man",d:2,sit:"You're defending in your end of the ice. The puck is in the corner far away from you. Should you just watch the puck?",opts:["Yes — always watch where the puck is and skate toward it no matter where other players are on the ice","No — find the player near you and keep them in front of you. You can still see the puck with your eyes.","Yes — the puck is the most important thing and nothing else on the ice really matters for you at all","Yes — skate straight to where the puck is and forget about all the other players on the ice during a play"],ok:1,why:"In your defensive zone, every defender needs to cover a player — not just watch the puck. If you lose your man, they could get an open pass.",tip:"Defending in your own zone? Find a player to cover. Watch them AND the puck."},
    {id:"u7q29",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Line changes",d:2,sit:"You've been skating hard for a long time and your legs are getting tired. The puck goes out of play and the whistle blows. What should you do?",opts:["Keep playing hard even though your legs are feeling very tired","Skate to the bench so a fresh teammate can take your place","Stop skating in the middle of the ice and catch your breath","Ask the referee nicely if your team can have a quick break"],ok:1,why:"Changing lines keeps your team fresh. When there's a stoppage and you're tired, getting off the ice and letting a fresh teammate on helps your team.",tip:"Tired during a stoppage? Get to the bench. Let a fresh teammate in."},
    {id:"u7q30",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck in the corner",d:2,sit:"The puck goes into the corner and you're the nearest player. It's going to be a tough battle to get it. What do you do?",opts:["Wait near the blue line for a pass to you","Go get it — compete hard in the corner now","Let the other team have it this time","Skate away from the corner and wait"],ok:1,why:"Corners are where compete happens in hockey. The player who battles hardest in the corners usually wins the puck — and that matters for the whole game.",tip:"Puck in the corner? Go battle for it. Compete wins corners."},
    {id:"u7q31",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Triangle",d:2,sit:"Your team has the puck in the corner. You're a forward without the puck. The net front is empty and so is the area at the top of the face-off circle. Where do you go?",opts:["Go into the corner to help you","Take the net front position","Skate to center ice right now n","Stay at the blue line"],ok:1,why:"When a teammate has the puck in the corner, covering the net front is the highest-value position. It creates options and puts you in position to score.",tip:"Puck in the corner? Someone cover the net. That's usually the job of the nearest forward."},
    {id:"u7q32",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Help your teammate",d:2,sit:"Your teammate is trying to get the puck but they're getting pushed around by an opponent. You're nearby and don't have the puck. What can you do to help?",opts:["Watch — there's nothing you can do without the puck so just wait and let them handle it ","Skate toward your teammate — being close creates support and could help them make a play","Skate to the other end of the rink and wait there for the puck to come down to you","Call out to the referee and ask them to blow the whistle and stop the play right now fast"],ok:1,why:"Being close to a teammate who's in a battle gives them a passing option and moral support. Hockey is about playing together — be there for your teammates.",tip:"Teammate in a battle? Get close and be their option. Support them."},
    {id:"u7q33",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Where to aim",d:2,sit:"You're about to shoot the puck at the net. The goalie is standing in the middle. Where's the best place to aim?",opts:["Right at the goalie's chest — they'll move out of the way","Try to shoot around them — aim for a corner of the net","Aim high for the crossbar every single time you shoot","Shoot as hard as you can without ever taking time to aim"],ok:1,why:"Shooting right at the goalie makes their job easy. Aiming for the corners of the net — where the goalie isn't — gives you a much better chance to score.",tip:"Aiming for the net? Pick a corner. Shoot where the goalie isn't."},
    {id:"u7q34",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Penalty",d:2,sit:"A player on your team does something against the rules and gets a penalty. What happens next?",opts:["Your team gets to add one extra player out on the ice for a while","Your team has to play with one less player for a period of time no","Nothing changes at all — the game keeps going just like before","The other team also has to lose one of their players for a while"],ok:1,why:"When your team takes a penalty, you have to play shorthanded — with fewer players. This is why avoiding penalties is important. The other team has an advantage until the penalty is over.",tip:"Your team has a penalty? You're playing with fewer players. Everyone has to work harder."},
    {id:"u7q35",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Shot block",d:2,sit:"A player from the other team is about to shoot the puck at your net. You're between them and the net. What could you try to do?",opts:["Move out of the way so the puck doesn't hit you or any of your teammates","Get in the shooting lane and try to block the shot with your body or stick","Skate to your bench and let your goalie handle the shot all on their own again","Turn around and look away fast so the puck can't hit you right in your face m"],ok:1,why:"Blocking shots is a way every player can help their team. Getting in the lane between the shooter and your net might deflect or block the shot.",tip:"Player about to shoot? Try to get in the lane and block it."},
    {id:"u7q36",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Rush attack lanes",d:3,sit:"Your team is rushing toward the other team's net — you have more players than the other team right now. Where should you be on the ice to help most?",opts:["Skate as close to the puck carrier as you possibly can every time","Spread across the ice so the defenders have to cover more space","Skate behind the puck carrier the whole way and follow them","Stop skating and watch the puck carrier handle it by themselves no"],ok:1,why:"Spreading out on a rush forces defenders to cover more space, opening up passing lanes and shooting opportunities.",tip:"Rush attack? Spread across the ice. Give the defenders more to think about."},
    {id:"u7q37",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Call for the puck",d:3,sit:"You're in a great open spot in the offensive zone with no defenders near you. Your teammate has the puck but hasn't seen you. What do you do?",opts:["Stay quiet — yelling for the puck is rude to the other team's players no","Call your teammate's name or yell 'here!' to let them know you're open","Skate toward them quickly to get the puck yourself and try to score it","Wait patiently and hope they turn around and spot you all by themselves"],ok:1,why:"Letting your teammate know you're open is the right play. A loud 'here!' gives them a target and might lead directly to a scoring chance.",tip:"Open and your teammate can't see you? Call for the puck. Let them know."},
    {id:"u7q38",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Rebound position",d:3,sit:"Your teammate is shooting the puck at the net from the blue line. You're the nearest forward. What should you do?",opts:["Stay where you are — the shot might just go wide of the net","Skate hard toward the net to get in position for a rebound n","Skate away from the net in case the shot ends up going wide","Skate to the corner and wait for the puck to come out there"],ok:1,why:"Shots from the blue line often produce rebounds. Getting to the front of the net before the shot arrives puts you in position to score on the rebound.",tip:"Teammate shooting from far away? Crash the net. Be ready for the rebound."},
    {id:"u7q39",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck out of play",d:3,sit:"The puck goes over the boards and out of play. What happens next?",opts:["The game keeps going","Play stops and there's a faceoff to restart the game","The team that shot it gets a penalty right now always","Nothing — the referee gets a new puck and th"],ok:1,why:"When the puck leaves the playing surface, play stops. The game restarts with a faceoff at the nearest faceoff dot.",tip:"Puck over the boards? Play stops. Get ready for the faceoff."},
    {id:"u7q40",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Going to the front of the net",d:3,sit:"Skating to the front of the other team's net when you don't have the puck can be scary because defenders are there. Why is it worth doing anyway?",opts:["It isn't worth doing — always stay far away from defenders so you don't have to battle anyone during play or get pushed around in front","Because standing there creates scoring chances for your team — rebounds, screens, tips. The best chances come from the front of the net.","Because referees give you a whole bunch of extra points for being brave and skating into a really tough spot that nobody else wants t","Because it tires out the goalie faster when you stand in front of them for a really long time during every single play of the game always"],ok:1,why:"The front of the net is the most dangerous area in hockey. Going there creates screens, rebound chances, and tip opportunities — even though defenders are there. Competing in tough spots is how goals are scored.",tip:"Front of the net is hard. Go there anyway. That's where goals come from."},
    {id:"u7q41",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Don't follow the crowd",d:3,sit:"The puck is in the offensive zone corner. All five of your teammates are chasing it in the corner. The entire front of the net and the blue line are empty. What should you do?",opts:["Join the crowd — the more teammates fighting for the puck in one spot the better for your team again","Pick one of the empty spots — net front or blue line — and get there. Give your team an option.","Skate to the bench right away and take a quick rest while your teammates fight for the puck for you","Watch and wait for one of your teammates to pass the puck to you right there in the corner they are"],ok:1,why:"When everyone goes to the same spot, all the other spots open up. Finding the empty space — net front, blue line — gives your team a passing option and makes the defense split.",tip:"Everyone in the corner? Pick the empty spot. You're more useful there."},
    {id:"u7q42",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Feedback",d:3,sit:"After a drill, your coach tells you something you did wrong and shows you how to do it better. How should you react?",opts:["Argue — you're sure you did it right the first t","Ignore it — just do it your own way next time now n","Say thank you and try it the way they showed you","Feel really bad and not even try the drill anymore"],ok:1,why:"Feedback from coaches is how you get better. A coach who corrects you is investing in you. Listening, saying thank you, and trying the correction is exactly what the best players do.",tip:"Coach gave you feedback? Say thanks and try it their way. That's how you improve."},
    {id:"u7q43",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Win together, lose together",d:3,sit:"Your team loses the game. A teammate is feeling really sad. What do you say or do?",opts:["Tell them loudly that it was their fault your team lost the whole game today","Ignore them and just walk away — you're feeling really bad about the loss too","Say 'good game' and encourage them — you'll work hard and get better together no","Blame the referee loudly for every bad call they made against your team this ga"],ok:1,why:"Losing is part of sports. Being a good teammate means supporting each other even when things go wrong. Encouraging a sad teammate is one of the most important things you can do.",tip:"Team lost and a teammate is sad? Encourage them. You're in it together."},
    {id:"u7q44",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Tip it in",d:3,sit:"A teammate takes a shot from far away. The puck is coming at the net. You're standing right in front of the goalie. What could you try?",opts:["Move out of the way so the puck doesn't hit you and so your goalie can try to save the shot too","Try to tip or deflect the puck with your stick — even a small touch can change where it goes","Skate away fast toward the blue line so you don't get in the way of your teammate's shot on net","Watch the shot very carefully to see if it goes right in the net or the goalie makes a big save "],ok:1,why:"Deflecting or tipping a shot is one of the hardest things for goalies to stop. Even a small touch from your stick can change the puck's direction enough to score.",tip:"Shot coming and you're in front? Try to tip it. Even a little touch helps."},
    {id:"u7q45",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Protect the front",d:3,sit:"An attacker is trying to stand right in front of your goalie. Your goalie can't see the puck with the attacker there. What should you try to do?",opts:["Ignore the attacker — the goalie can figure out where the puck is n","Move the attacker out of the crease area so your goalie can see","Go get the puck in the corner and leave the attacker alone for now","Stand beside the attacker and watch them block the goalie's view"],ok:1,why:"An attacker screening your goalie is a real problem. Moving them out of the crease area is the defender's job so the goalie can see the puck coming.",tip:"Attacker in front of your goalie? Move them out. Your goalie needs to see."},
    {id:"u7q46",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Faceoffs",d:3,sit:"There's a faceoff near your team's net. You're not the one taking the faceoff. Where should you be standing?",opts:["Wherever you feel like standing — it doesn't really matter where you are for any faceoff at all","In your assigned faceoff position — usually covering a player or an area near the faceoff dot no","Standing right on top of the faceoff dot so you can grab the puck before anyone else on the ice","All the way back at center ice so you can be ready if the puck ever comes out to you later"],ok:1,why:"Faceoffs are set plays. Everyone has a position — you're not just watching the center take the draw. Being in position before the puck drops means your team is ready to win the faceoff and execute.",tip:"About to have a faceoff? Get to your position before the puck drops. Be ready."},
    {id:"u7q47",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck on the boards",d:3,sit:"The puck is pushed hard along the boards. You're racing an opponent to get it before it slides to the corner. You're even with them. What's the smart move?",opts:["Slow down a lot — they'll probably win the race to the puck before you can even get there","Use your body to angle between them and the puck's path — cut them off before they get there","Skate away and go to a totally different spot — let your teammates try to race for the puck instead","Wait for it to bounce back off the boards and then go and try to get it from your opponent"],ok:1,why:"Angling your body to cut off the opponent's path to the puck — even when you're even with them — uses body position to win the race. It's smarter than just skating straight.",tip:"Racing to a puck along the boards? Angle your body to cut off their path. Position beats pure speed."},
    {id:"u7q48",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Two on one rush",d:3,sit:"Your team has a 2-on-1 — two of you and only one defender. You don't have the puck. Your teammate does. What should you do?",opts:["Stop skating and watch your teammate handle the whole play all by themselves — they've got it from here","Skate into open space — go to the side where the defender isn't. Give your teammate a pass option.","Skate straight toward your teammate and get right next to them so you can help them handle the puck","Skate straight to the bench and take a break — your teammate can handle this 2-on-1 rush all by themselves"],ok:1,why:"On a 2-on-1, the player without the puck needs to get to the open side. If the defender takes your teammate, you're wide open for the pass.",tip:"2-on-1 without the puck? Get to the open side. Be the option."},
    {id:"u7q49",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Practice habits",d:3,sit:"Practice is almost over. You're tired. The coach announces one more drill. What do you do?",opts:["Complain loudly to your teammates about how tired you feel and how unfair it is","Do the drill at half speed the whole time — you're tired so it's totally fine","Go as hard as you can on the last drill — finishing strong is a good habit","Sit down on the ice and wait for the whole drill to finish before getting up"],ok:1,why:"How you finish practice is a habit. Players who go hard on the last drill develop the discipline to push through when it's hard — and that matters in games.",tip:"Last drill of practice? Go hard. Finishing strong is a habit."},
    {id:"u7q50",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Include everyone",d:3,sit:"During a drill, one player on your team keeps getting left out — nobody passes to them. You have the puck and they're open. What do you do?",opts:["Just ignore them — pass to your closest friend instead","Pass to them — they're open and they're your teammate n","Try a really hard move by yourself and try to score","Tell them to skate over to a better open spot first"],ok:1,why:"Every player on your team deserves to be part of the game. If they're open, pass to them. Including everyone makes the whole team better.",tip:"Teammate left out and open? Pass to them. Everyone is part of the team."},
    {id:"u7q51",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Shoot from a good spot",d:3,sit:"You have the puck right in front of the net, 5 feet away. The goalie has stepped far out of the net to cut the angle. There's barely any net to shoot at. What do you do?",opts:["Shoot anyway — just blast it right at the goalie's chest ","Try to go around the goalie since they've come so far out","Stop skating and pass it back to a teammate behind you now","Skate backward away from the net and try a better angle"],ok:1,why:"When a goalie comes way out to cut the angle, going around them or pulling the puck wide and shooting on an open net is often better than trying to beat them on the shot.",tip:"Goalie way out cutting the angle? Go around them or pull wide. Don't just blast it at their chest."},
    {id:"u7q52",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Cover the pass",d:3,sit:"You're defending in your zone. The puck is in the corner. You see an opposing player standing in the slot with nobody covering them. What do you do?",opts:["Watch the puck in the corner — that's where the action is and where all eyes on the ice should be looking during the play","Cover the open player in the slot — they're in the most dangerous area and if they get a pass, it'll likely be a goal","Skate to the corner where the puck is and help your teammates battle for it so your team gets the puck back quickly","Stand way back at the blue line and wait for the puck to come out of the corner so you can grab it and skate up the ice no"],ok:1,why:"An uncovered player in the slot is the biggest danger on the ice. Covering them — even when the puck is in the corner — prevents the most dangerous play from happening.",tip:"Open player in the slot? Cover them immediately. The slot is the most dangerous spot."},
    {id:"u7q53",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Off-sides entry",d:3,sit:"Your team is rushing into the offensive zone together. You're the fastest skater and you could easily get into the zone before the puck. Should you?",opts:["Yes — just get into the zone first and the puck will follow you in along with your teammates no n","No — wait for the puck. If you go in before the puck, your team gets called for offsides.","Yes — it's always better to go as fast as possible and be the first one into the zone every ti","Yes — the offsides rules don't apply to you when you're fast enough to beat everyone to the zone"],ok:1,why:"No matter how fast you are, entering the offensive zone before the puck is offsides. The puck has to enter first — always. Wait at the blue line if you have to.",tip:"You're fast, but the puck enters first. Always. Wait for it at the blue line."},
    {id:"u7q54",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Hard work is for everyone",d:3,sit:"Your team is losing by a lot of goals with not much time left. Some of your teammates are giving up and not skating hard. What do you do?",opts:["Give up too — the game is basically already over by this point","Keep working hard and encourage your teammates to do the same no","Blame your teammates for how badly the team is playing right now","Argue with the coach about all the bad calls the ref made tonig"],ok:1,why:"Effort is something every player controls, no matter what the score is. Playing hard until the final whistle shows character, and it's how teams build the habit of never giving up.",tip:"Down by a lot? Keep playing hard. Every shift is a chance to practice compete."},
    {id:"u7q55",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Practice in your head",d:3,sit:"You're on the bench and your coach just taught you something new about positioning. While you're sitting there, what's the best way to use that time?",opts:["Forget about it for now — you'll probably remember the idea when you get back on the ice","Picture yourself doing it correctly in your head while you watch the play on the ice","Talk to your friends on the bench about something totally different from the hockey game ","Wait until the next hockey practice to think about it some more with your teammates"],ok:1,why:"Visualizing yourself doing a skill correctly — especially right after learning it — helps your brain learn faster. Athletes at all levels use mental practice to improve.",tip:"Learned something new? Picture yourself doing it right while you're on the bench. Mental practice is real practice."},
    {id:"u7q56",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Communicate",d:3,sit:"You see the puck is coming toward your teammate's blind side — they can't see it. What do you shout?",opts:["Nothing — don't distract them","'Man on!' or 'Puck!' so they know it's coming","'Watch out!' but quietly so you don't","Wait to see what happens right now right now"],ok:1,why:"Communicating what you see to a teammate is one of the most important things in hockey. A quick loud 'man on' or 'puck' gives them the information they need to protect themselves or make a play.",tip:"See something your teammate can't? Shout it. Loud and fast. That's communication."},
    {id:"u7q57",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D-man stay back",d:3,sit:"Your team is attacking and both defensemen have skated deep into the offensive zone. Now the puck turns over. What problem does this create?",opts:["No problem at all — having more attackers in the zone is always better for scoring goals now","The other team can break out fast with nobody to stop them — your defensemen are too deep","Your goalie has to skate forward to help out the defensemen who went too deep into the atta","Your team gets a penalty from the referee for having too many players in the offensive zone"],ok:1,why:"When both defensemen go too deep, there's nobody to stop the other team from breaking out quickly. At least one defenseman should always be thinking about the space behind the rush.",tip:"Both D going deep into the attack? Dangerous. Someone needs to be ready for the other team to break out."},
    {id:"u7q58",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Traffic in front",d:3,sit:"You're the defenseman at the blue line with the puck. There's lots of traffic — players from both teams — right in front of the goalie. Should you shoot?",opts:["No — you might accidentally hit one of your own teammates who is standing in front of the goalie","Yes — traffic in front makes it hard for the goalie to see, so shots through traffic are dangerous no","No — wait patiently at the blue line until all of the traffic in front of the net finally clears out","No — just pass to another teammate instead — passing is always way better than taking a shot on net"],ok:1,why:"Traffic in front of the net blocks the goalie's view of the puck — making your shot more dangerous, not less. Shooting through traffic creates screens and rebounds.",tip:"Traffic in front of the goalie? Shoot. The traffic helps you."},
    {id:"u7q59",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Don't all go to the puck",d:3,sit:"Three players from the other team are in your defensive zone. Two of your defenders are fighting for the puck in the corner. A third opposing player is wide open near the net. What should you — a forward — do?",opts:["Skate into the corner to help your teammates battle for the puck even though they got it","Cover the open player near the net — they're in a dangerous position and nobody has them","Watch the whole play happen from center ice until the puck comes out of the corner to you","Skate all the way back toward the blue line and wait for the puck to come to you there"],ok:1,why:"When two teammates are already in the corner, you don't need to be a third player there. The open player near the net is the danger — cover them.",tip:"Two teammates already in the corner? Cover the open player near the net. Don't all go to the puck."},
    {id:"u7q60",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Penalties cost your team",d:3,sit:"You're feeling frustrated and you want to hit the other player really hard. But it might be against the rules. What should you do?",opts:["Hit them hard anyway — it's fine because you'll just take the penalty","Control yourself — taking a penalty hurts your whole team, not just you","Ask the referee if it's okay to hit them hard before you actually do it","Hit them as hard as you possibly can and then just apologize after the play"],ok:1,why:"Taking a penalty doesn't just punish you — it puts your whole team at a disadvantage. Learning to control your frustration is an important skill that the best players have.",tip:"Feeling frustrated? Control it. A penalty hurts your whole team."},
    {id:"u7q61",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"After a mistake",d:3,sit:"You made a mistake — you passed the puck to the other team by accident and they scored. Your teammates are looking at you. What do you do?",opts:["Blame someone else on your team for the mistake you just made out there on the ice now","Apologize a lot and then feel really terrible about it for the rest of the game","Put your head up and keep going — everyone makes mistakes. Focus on the next play.","Stop trying to make any more passes to your teammates for the rest of the hockey game"],ok:1,why:"Mistakes happen to every player in every game. The best response is to acknowledge it quickly and refocus on the next play. Staying in the moment instead of dwelling on a mistake is a real skill.",tip:"Made a mistake? Head up. Next play. Everyone does it."},
    {id:"u7q62",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck on the goal line",d:3,sit:"The puck is sitting on the goal line right beside the post. You and a goalie are both racing to it at the same time. What do you try to do?",opts:["Stop skating and back off — the goalie will surely get there fi","Try to bat the puck into the net before the goalie covers it now","Skate away from the net and let the goalie cover the puck","Wait for the referee to come over and blow the whistle dead"],ok:1,why:"Pucks on the goal line are live. If you can get a stick on it before the goalie covers it, it counts as a goal. Competing hard right to the edge of the crease is how goals are scored.",tip:"Puck on the goal line? Compete! Try to jam it in before the goalie covers it."},
    {id:"u7q63",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Support the puck carrier",d:3,sit:"Your teammate has the puck and they're trying to skate with it but defenders are around them. You're 10 feet away and completely open. What do you do?",opts:["Stand completely still right there — you don't have the puck so there's nothing you can do to help your teammate at this very mome","Skate to a spot slightly behind and to the side of your teammate — support them with your positioning and be the easy pass option","Skate toward them right away to make the space around the puck carrier a lot tighter and force the defenders closer to everyone now","Skate all the way down to the other end of the ice so you can be ready to grab the puck when it comes back down to you"],ok:1,why:"Supporting the puck carrier by positioning yourself behind and to the side gives them an easy outlet if they get pressured. You don't need the puck to help your teammate.",tip:"Teammate with the puck? Position yourself behind them to the side. Be the easy option."},
    {id:"u7q64",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Ask the right way",d:3,sit:"You disagree with something your coach told you to do. You think your way is better. What's the best way to handle it?",opts:["Do it your own way during the whole game and then tell the coach about it later aft","Argue with the coach right now in front of the whole team out there on the ice","Try the coach's way during the game, then ask questions respectfully afterward","Just refuse to do it the coach's way and then sit on the bench for the rest of it no"],ok:1,why:"Coaches make decisions based on more information than you see. Trying their way first — then asking questions respectfully — is how good players and good people handle disagreement.",tip:"Disagree with your coach? Try their way first. Ask questions respectfully after. That's how you build trust."},
    {id:"u7q65",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"What's a power play?",d:3,sit:"The other team takes a penalty. Your team is now on the power play — you have more players on the ice than the other team. What does this mean your team should do?",opts:["Play exactly the same way as you usually do — nothing special needs to change about the way your team plays right now","Use the extra player advantage — move the puck to find the player who's open because the other team is short","Play more cautiously since the other team could score a shorthanded goal if your team makes even one small mistake","Change all your players every 5 seconds so everyone on the bench gets a chance to play during the power play"],ok:1,why:"A power play means the other team has fewer players — so someone on your team is always open. Moving the puck to find that open player is how power plays create scoring chances.",tip:"On the power play? You have the extra man. Move the puck to find them."},
    {id:"u7q66",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck to the net",d:3,sit:"You have the puck in the offensive zone. You're not sure if you should shoot or pass. What's the most important thing to think about?",opts:["Which option looks the coolest to all your friends, teammates, and parents who are watching you from the stands","Which option is most likely to get the puck on net — either a shot or a pass to a teammate with a better shot no","Whatever your parents and the rest of your family members are probably thinking right now from the stands","How many people are watching the hockey game right now from both the stands and the benches around the ice"],ok:1,why:"The best decision in the offensive zone is the one most likely to put the puck on the net. Sometimes that's shooting, sometimes that's passing to a teammate with a better look. Always think about getting the puck on net.",tip:"Shoot or pass? Pick whichever one is most likely to get the puck on net."},
    {id:"u7q67",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Get back fast",d:3,sit:"Your team just took a shot and the goalie saved it. All five of your players are in the offensive zone. The other team gets the puck and starts skating the other way fast. What's the most important thing for your forwards to do?",opts:["Stay in the offensive zone because the puck might come back to you and your team in a mome","Turn around and get back as fast as possible — a team caught all up the ice is in trouble","Keep attacking the goalie and the puck will probably come back to your team in a moment now","Skate back slowly toward your own net and watch the other team come down the ice at you"],ok:1,why:"When the puck turns over and the other team has speed, getting back fast is the most important thing forwards can do. A team caught all in the offensive zone is wide open for a fast counter-attack.",tip:"Puck turned over and they have speed? Everyone turn around and go back. Fast."},
    {id:"u7q68",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Skating hard every shift",d:3,sit:"You've been playing hard and you're tired. You have one more shift before practice ends. What's the right mindset?",opts:["Coast through your last shift — you're tired and nobody on the team or the coaches will notice","Skate as hard as you did on your very first shift — your last shift should look like your first","Give up on any compete plays — save your energy for the next practice with your teammates instead","Skate a lot slower than normal and just try your hardest to hide that you're tired from the coach "],ok:1,why:"Your last shift of practice should look like your first. Players who compete hard even when tired build real toughness — and coaches notice every shift, especially the last ones.",tip:"Tired on your last shift? Go just as hard as your first. That's the standard."},
    {id:"u7q69",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Warm up right",d:3,sit:"You arrive at the rink early for practice and your coach wants everyone to do a proper warm-up. You feel fine and want to just start skating hard. What should you do?",opts:["Skip the warm-up completely — you feel totally ready and your muscles already feel warm","Do the warm-up with the team — your coach knows why it matters even if you feel fine","Do only half of the whole warm-up and then go skate fast around the rink by yourself","Warm up only if you feel stiff or tight — otherwise go straight into skating drills"],ok:1,why:"Warm-ups protect your body even when you feel fine. Coaches build warm-ups because they help prevent injuries and prepare your muscles for the work ahead. Following the team routine is part of being coachable.",tip:"Want to skip the warm-up? Do it anyway. Your coach included it for a reason."},
    {id:"u7q70",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Compliment a teammate",d:3,sit:"Your teammate makes a really good pass that leads to a goal. What do you say to them?",opts:["Nothing at all — it was just a regular pass like any other one","Nice pass! or Great play! — tell them they did something good now","Tell them you could have done it so much better than they did","Say absolutely nothing to them and just skate away from the play"],ok:1,why:"Complimenting a teammate when they do something well builds team chemistry and encourages them to keep making good plays. Great teams cheer each other on.",tip:"Teammate made a great play? Tell them. Positive teams perform better."},
    {id:"u7q71",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Use both sides of your stick",d:3,sit:"You have the puck on your backhand — the weaker side of your stick. A good shot would be on your forehand. There's a small amount of time to switch. What do you do?",opts:["Shoot with your backhand right away — you don't have any extra time to switch the puck to your stronger foreh","Take the split second to switch the puck to your forehand if you safely have time — forehand is more accurate","Throw your hockey stick down on the ice and use your hands and gloves to try and bat the puck into the net now","Pass it instead — you should never ever shoot the puck directly from the backhand side of your hockey stick"],ok:1,why:"If you have time, switching to your forehand gives you a more accurate shot. But the backhand is also a real shot — if you don't have time to switch, use the backhand.",tip:"Puck on your backhand? Switch to forehand if you have time. If not, shoot the backhand — it's a real shot too."},
    {id:"u7q72",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Stay in your lane",d:3,sit:"There's a 2-on-1 rush and you're the second attacker — you don't have the puck. The defender is moving toward the puck carrier. You're on the right side. Where do you stay?",opts:["Skate right toward the puck carrier so you can grab the puck and shoot it","Stay on the right side — keep the lane open so the pass can get to you","Skate straight to the net no matter where the defender is positioned","Slow down and let the puck carrier handle the whole 2-on-1 rush themselves"],ok:1,why:"On a 2-on-1, the second attacker needs to hold their lane. If you drift to the middle, the pass lane closes. Stay on your side and be ready when the puck comes.",tip:"2-on-1 without the puck? Hold your lane. Don't drift. Stay ready for the pass."},
    {id:"u7q73",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Stay between puck and net",d:3,sit:"An attacker has the puck and they're trying to skate around you to get to the net. What's the most important thing you keep between you and the net?",opts:["Your stick — keep it out in front of you to poke at the puck no n","Your body — stay between the attacker and your net at all times","Your skates — keep them pointed toward the attacker at all tim","Your helmet — keep it facing the attacker at all times out there"],ok:1,why:"The golden rule of defense is to keep your body between the attacker and your net. If you do that, they have to go through you — and that's where you have the advantage.",tip:"Defending 1-on-1? Keep your body between the attacker and your net. Always."},
    {id:"u7q74",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Read the ref",d:3,sit:"The referee raises their arm during play but hasn't blown the whistle yet. What does this mean?",opts:["Nothing important at all — the referee is just stretching their sore arm from the game and needs to loosen it up a bit","A penalty is about to be called. Play continues for now, but when the puck goes dead, the penalty will be announced. no","The game is officially over because the referee just signaled the end of regulation play by putting their arm up","Your team just scored a goal and the referee is raising their arm in the air to signal it to everybody in the arena"],ok:1,why:"A referee with their arm raised is signaling a delayed penalty. Play continues until the team being penalized touches the puck — then the whistle blows. This is actually good for your team because you can pull your goalie for an extra attacker.",tip:"Ref's arm is up? Delayed penalty. Keep playing — the whistle comes when they touch the puck."},
    {id:"u7q75",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Battle in practice",d:3,sit:"In a practice drill, you're paired with your best friend and they're trying to win the puck from you. Should you compete hard against them?",opts:["No — they're your good friend so you should be really nice and not try too hard against them","Yes — competing hard in practice with everyone, including friends, makes both of you better","Only compete hard if they compete hard against you first — otherwise you should just take it easy","No — practice time is just for having fun with your friends so you shouldn't really compete"],ok:1,why:"Practicing compete — even against friends — is how you both get better. Real practice competition prepares you for real games. Your friend can handle your compete, and you can handle theirs.",tip:"Competing against a friend in practice? Go hard. You both get better."},
    {id:"u7q76",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Try it a new way",d:3,sit:"You've always held your stick one way. Your coach tells you there's a better way that will help you skate faster with the puck. It feels weird at first. What do you do?",opts:["Keep doing it the same old way — it feels right to you and your coach is pretty much wrong here about th","Try the new way, even though it feels weird. New things feel weird at first — that's part of learning.","Do half of it the new way that the coach is telling you and then half of it the old way you always did","Ask your parents about it all after practice and see if they really think the coach is right or wrong now"],ok:1,why:"Almost every skill improvement feels awkward at first. The feeling of 'weird' is your brain and body adjusting to something new. Sticking with the new way through the awkward phase is how you improve.",tip:"New way feels weird? Keep trying it. Weird is what improvement feels like at first."},
    {id:"u7q77",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Encourage on the bench",d:3,sit:"A teammate comes off the ice after making a mistake and they look down. Nobody has said anything to them. What do you do?",opts:["Just say nothing — they already know they made a mistake on the ice now","Say something encouraging — 'You've got it next time' or 'good effort'","Tell them exactly what they did wrong and how they should not do it ag","Ignore them completely and wait for the coach to come talk with them"],ok:1,why:"A teammate who feels supported after a mistake is more likely to bounce back quickly and play well. One encouraging word from a teammate can make a real difference.",tip:"Teammate came off after a mistake? Encourage them. That's what good teammates do."},
    {id:"u7q78",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Shoot on the move",d:3,sit:"You're skating with the puck toward the net at full speed. A defender is chasing you from behind. Should you slow down to take a better shot?",opts:["Yes — slow down and aim really carefully so you can pick a spot in the corner of the net to hit","No — shoot while moving at full speed. A moving shooter is harder for the goalie to track. again n","Stop completely first and then shoot the puck when you are standing still and you can aim it well","Pass it to one of your teammates who is wide open on the other side of the net instead of shoot"],ok:1,why:"Shooting while moving at full speed is harder for a goalie to track than a stationary shot. Slowing down also lets the defender catch up. Shoot while moving.",tip:"Full speed toward the net? Shoot while moving. Don't slow down."},
    {id:"u7q79",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Watch out for the back door",d:3,sit:"The other team has the puck in the corner. You're covering a player at the far post of your net — far away from the puck. They're just standing there. Do you stop covering them?",opts:["Yes — they don't have the puck at all and they are far away from where the puck is now so they can't score on your team","No — a player standing at the far post is waiting for a back-door pass. That's actually one of the most dangerous plays.","Yes — you should move toward the puck in the corner instead of staying to cover the open player at the far post of the net","Yes — go and stand next to the goalie in the crease instead of covering the open player all the way at the far post"],ok:1,why:"A player standing at the back post in the offensive zone is set up for a back-door pass — one of the hardest plays for a goalie to stop. Leaving them means giving up a dangerous scoring chance.",tip:"Player hanging at the far post? Keep covering them. They're waiting for the back-door pass."},
    {id:"u7q80",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Pull the goalie",d:3,sit:"Your team is losing by one goal with one minute left. Suddenly your coach pulls your goalie off the ice and puts a sixth skater on. Why would they do that?",opts:["Your goalie made a mistake","Your goalie is tired","Having an extra skater gives your team a better chance to score and tie the game — even though your ne","Your goalie needs a rest right now right now"],ok:2,why:"Pulling the goalie for an extra attacker is a calculated risk. Your net is empty, but the extra skater gives your team more firepower to try to tie the game. It's a real strategy coaches use.",tip:"Coach pulled the goalie? They want the extra attacker to score. Protect the empty net on defense and attack hard on offense."},
    {id:"u7q81",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Hold the door",d:3,sit:"You're the first player coming off the ice for a line change. Your teammate is about to jump on. What should you make sure of before you leave the bench door area?",opts:["Nothing special at all — just get off the ice as fast as you possibly can so your teammate can jump on and go get the puck","Make sure your teammate is clearly coming on and is at the boards before you fully leave. The exchange has to be clean.","Run off the ice and back to the bench as fast as possible no matter where your teammate is on the ice or at the door","Wait until you are fully off the ice and all the way to the bench before your teammate even starts to move from the bench"],ok:1,why:"A clean line change means the incoming player is ready before the outgoing player leaves. A messy change can result in too many men on the ice. Coordinating the exchange is both players' responsibility.",tip:"Line change: make sure the exchange is clean. Incoming player ready, then you leave. No gaps, no overlaps."},
    {id:"u7q82",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Hard shot vs. accurate shot",d:3,sit:"You're shooting the puck at the net. Should you always try to shoot as hard as you possibly can?",opts:["Yes — the hardest shot you can take always wins and beats the goalie every single time you take one of them","Not always — an accurate shot that goes where the goalie isn't is better than a hard shot right at them fast","Yes — goalies simply can't stop a shot that is hard enough to get past their pads and into the back of the ","Hard shots are rude — always just shoot very softly and gently at the goalie so they don't get hurt at all"],ok:1,why:"Accuracy beats power when it comes to shooting. A perfect hard shot right at the goalie is an easy save. A well-placed shot — even if it's softer — that goes where the goalie isn't is more likely to score.",tip:"Hard shot vs. accurate shot? Pick the corner first. Power helps, but location wins."},
    {id:"u7q83",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Help your goalie",d:3,sit:"A shot is coming from far away and your goalie will probably make the save. But an opposing player is sneaking toward the front of your net. What should you do?",opts:["Watch the shot — it's way more exciting than covering someone who doesn't even have the puck","Go cover the player sneaking toward the front of your net — your goalie can handle the shot","Cheer loudly for your goalie so they know that you believe they will make the save on the shot n","Skate over toward the shooter and try to get in their face before they take the shot on the net"],ok:1,why:"Your goalie can handle the shot from far away. Your job is to clear the player moving to the front of the net before they can get the rebound. Dividing the responsibility is how defense works.",tip:"Shot from far away and a player sneaking to the net? Go cover the sneaker. Your goalie has the shot."},
    {id:"u7q84",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Battle through a check",d:3,sit:"An opponent bumps you hard along the boards. You didn't fall but it knocked you sideways. What do you do?",opts:["Stop skating and just wait for the referee to make a penalty call for you","Regain your balance and keep playing — getting bumped is part of hockey","Fall down to try to get a penalty call from the referee for your team","Bump them right back even harder before they get a chance to bump you again"],ok:1,why:"Getting physically bumped along the boards is part of hockey. Regaining your balance quickly and continuing to play is what compete looks like. Stopping every time you get touched makes you easy to stop.",tip:"Got bumped? Regain your balance fast and keep playing. That's compete."},
    {id:"u7q85",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck drops",d:3,sit:"You're at a faceoff. The referee is about to drop the puck. What are you thinking about right before it drops?",opts:["Nothing really special at all — just react to whatever happens with the puck right after the referee drops it between both the centers","Your assignment: what you're doing if your center wins it, and what you're doing if they lose it. Be ready before the puck drops.","Whether you're hungry or thirsty right now and what you might want to eat or to drink when the hockey game is finally over later","What happened earlier in the game so you can think about all the mistakes you have made out there on the ice up to this very moment"],ok:1,why:"A faceoff is a set play. Knowing your assignment before the puck drops — win or lose — means you're already moving in the right direction when play starts.",tip:"Before the faceoff: know your assignment. Win or lose — be ready to go."},
    {id:"u7q86",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Read the play",d:3,sit:"You're watching the play develop. You can see a pass is about to be made by the other team across the ice. You're in a spot where you could skate to intercept it. What do you do?",opts:["Wait to see where the puck goes first before you decide whether you should skate over to intercept","Start skating to intercept it now — before the pass is made — so you're there when it arrives now n","Stay right where you are on the ice and wait for the pass to come to one of the other players","Skate right at the player who is about to receive it and try to check them before they get the p"],ok:1,why:"Reading a pass before it's made — and moving early — is how you intercept pucks. Moving after the pass is made means you're always too late.",tip:"See a pass about to happen? Start moving to intercept now — before the pass is made."},
    {id:"u7q87",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Talk to your linemates",d:3,sit:"Your two linemates are on the bench beside you. You're about to go on for your next shift. What's a good thing to say to them?",opts:["Nothing at all — just go and hop on the ice and start playing the game without saying even one thing to your linemates on the bench","Something short about what you're trying to do: 'let's get pucks deep' or 'let's play hard in the corners' — even a quick plan helps","Tell them in detail what they did wrong last shift so they know exactly what to fix and what to do differently this time out on the ice no","Say that you're really nervous about this shift and you hope you don't mess up when you get out on the ice in front of everyone at the ga"],ok:1,why:"A quick word with your linemates before a shift helps everyone get on the same page. Even one sentence about what you're going to do builds communication and team chemistry.",tip:"About to go on for a shift? Say something to your linemates. Even one word. Communicate."},
    {id:"u7q88",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"One-timer",d:3,sit:"A pass is coming to you and the goalie is not ready for a quick shot. If you stop the puck and aim, the goalie will have time to set. What should you try instead?",opts:["Always stop the puck first and then aim carefully at the net before you take your shot every time","One-time it — shoot it right when it arrives. A quick one-touch shot catches the goalie off guard.","Pass it to someone else instead — you should never ever shoot the puck without stopping it first","Wait for a better time to shoot — hold the puck a few more seconds until the goalie is out of position"],ok:1,why:"A one-timer — shooting the puck on the first touch without stopping it — can catch a goalie before they're set. Even at a young age, learning to take the puck in stride is a skill worth practicing.",tip:"Pass coming and goalie not ready? One-time it. Quick release before they can set."},
    {id:"u7q89",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck along the boards in D zone",d:3,sit:"The puck is sliding along the boards in your defensive zone. An opponent is racing to it. You're slightly closer. What's the most important thing you do when you get there?",opts:["Touch the puck first and then skate away fast before the opponent can get anywhere near you or the puck","Get your body between the puck and the opponent — win the inside position before you touch the puck","Kick the puck out of your defensive zone as fast as you possibly can before the opponent gets to it","Call out loudly for your goalie to come and help you battle for the puck before the opponent gets there"],ok:1,why:"Inside position on a loose puck along the boards is what wins the battle. Getting your body between the opponent and the puck — before you touch it — means you control the puck.",tip:"Racing to the puck along the boards in your own zone? Get inside position first. Body between the opponent and the puck."},
    {id:"u7q90",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Pre-game warmup compete",d:3,sit:"During warmups before the game, your team is doing skating drills. Some players are coasting. What do you do?",opts:["Coast through it too — it's just warmups and doesn't count","Go hard. How you warm up sets the tone for how you play. no","Warm up halfway through and then just watch the other team","Only go hard on the last drill of the warmup before the ga"],ok:1,why:"Warming up hard prepares your body, sharpens your mind, and signals to your teammates that you're ready to compete. Players who coast in warmups often coast in the game.",tip:"Warmup drills? Go hard. Your first rep sets the tone for everything after."},
    {id:"u7q91",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Film and feedback",d:3,sit:"Your coach shows the team a video of your last game and points out something you did wrong in front of everyone. How should you react?",opts:["Feel embarrassed and give up","Argue that the coach is wrong","Listen carefully — coaches show video to help the whole team learn, not to embarrass anyone","Pretend you weren't watching"],ok:2,why:"Video feedback is a coaching tool used at every level of hockey. Being pointed out in video is a chance to learn — the coach is trusting you to handle it and improve. That trust is earned by the players who respond well.",tip:"Coach showed video of your mistake? Listen and learn. Video feedback is how pros get better too."},
    {id:"u7q92",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Offsides on a rush",d:3,sit:"Your team is on a 2-on-1 rush and you're slightly ahead of your teammate who has the puck. You cross the blue line before the puck. What happens?",opts:["Nothing — you were a bit faster than the puck","Offsides — your team loses the scoring chance","You get a penalty for crossing the blue line early","Other team skates to center ice for a new faceoff n"],ok:1,why:"Even on a rush, the puck has to enter the offensive zone before or at the same time as the players. Going in ahead of the puck — even on a rush — is offsides.",tip:"On a rush? Stay even with the puck carrier until the puck is across the blue line. Don't jump offsides."},
    {id:"u7q93",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Set up your teammate",d:3,sit:"You're skating toward the net with the puck. A defender is focusing only on you. Your teammate is completely open on the other side of the net. What do you do?",opts:["Shoot anyway no matter what — you really want to score so you should just take the shot all by yourself now n","Pass to your open teammate — a player who sets up a teammate for a goal is just as important as the scorer","Try to do a fancy trick move with the puck to try and get around the defender and score a goal by yourself","Skate away from the net and pass the puck back to one of your defensemen so they can set up a brand new play"],ok:1,why:"Setting up a teammate who's open for a goal is one of the most important plays in hockey. A pass to an open teammate is often the highest-percentage play — and assists matter as much as goals.",tip:"Open teammate? Pass. Setting up a goal is just as important as scoring one."},
    {id:"u7q94",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"First to every puck",d:3,sit:"Every time a puck is loose, you and your opponents are racing to it. What habit should you build for every loose puck in every game?",opts:["Wait to see if the loose puck eventually comes over to you before you skate ov","Race to be first — make it a habit to win every loose puck race. First wins. no","Only race for the puck if you are sure that you are going to win the race","Wait for the other team to get the puck first and then try to take it from them"],ok:1,why:"Making it a habit to race to every loose puck — not just the ones you think you'll win — is what separates compete players from passive ones. Even if you don't always win the race, the habit itself makes you better.",tip:"Loose puck anywhere on the ice? Race to it. Make it a habit. Every single time."},
    {id:"u7q95",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Contain not commit",d:3,sit:"An attacker is coming at you 1-on-1 and they're trying to deke you. They dangle the puck to the left. You start to reach for it. What should you do instead?",opts:["Reach out with your stick and try to poke the puck from th","Stop your feet and reset — don't fully commit to the reach","Fall flat on the ice and try to block their shot somehow no","Skate backward as fast as you can and hope they fall down"],ok:1,why:"Reaching for a puck during a deke is how you get beaten. A skilled attacker uses the deke to bait you into committing. Stopping your feet and resetting keeps you in front of them.",tip:"Attacker trying to deke you? Don't reach. Stop your feet and reset. Don't commit."},
    {id:"u7q96",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Take notes in your brain",d:3,sit:"Your coach explains something technical — like how to angle your feet on a crossover turn — and then moves on quickly. You only understood half of it. What do you do?",opts:["Pretend that you understood everything and just hope for the best in the drill","Try to use what you understood, then ask the coach after to clarify the rest","Ask the coach to repeat the whole thing five times in the middle of the drill","Ignore what the coach said and just keep doing what you normally do out there n"],ok:1,why:"Getting partial information and trying to apply it — then asking for clarification afterward — is mature and effective learning. Coaches appreciate players who try first, then ask.",tip:"Understood half the instruction? Try what you got, then ask to clarify the rest after. Coaches respect that."},
    {id:"u7q97",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"What is icing?",d:3,sit:"A defender shoots the puck from their own end all the way down the ice and it crosses the goal line without anyone touching it. What is this called and what happens?",opts:["A goal — it crossed the goal line and the referee pointed at the goal now","Icing — play stops and a faceoff comes back to the defending team's end","A penalty shot for the other team because the puck went all the way down","Nothing happens — play just continues like nothing ever happened at all"],ok:1,why:"Icing is when the puck is shot from behind the center line all the way down the ice across the opposing goal line without being touched. Play stops, and the faceoff comes back to the team that iced the puck.",tip:"Shot from your own end all the way down? That's icing. Play stops. Know the rule."},
    {id:"u7q98",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Share the puck",d:3,sit:"You have the puck and you've already made three great passes to teammates who scored. Now you have the puck again and a good shot. Your teammates are yelling for you to pass. Should you always pass just because they're calling?",opts:["Yes — you should always pass the puck to any teammate who is calling for it no matter where you are on the ice or how good your chance is","No — if you have a great scoring opportunity and a teammate in a worse spot is calling, shoot. Read the situation, don't just react to noise. no","Yes — passing is always better than shooting, so whenever a teammate calls for the puck you should pass to them no matter what chance you have","No — never pass even if they are calling for it and are wide open for a chance, just keep the puck and shoot it yourself every time you have it"],ok:1,why:"Hockey requires reading the situation. Passing is often the right play, but sometimes — especially when you have the best chance — shooting is smarter. Develop the judgment to know which is right.",tip:"Teammate calling for a pass? Read the situation. Sometimes shoot, sometimes pass. Use your judgment."},
    {id:"u7q99",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defensive zone faceoff position",d:3,sit:"There's a faceoff in your defensive zone right beside your net. The referee is about to drop the puck. Where should all the players except the centers be?",opts:["Wherever they feel like on the ice — it doesn't really matter where the non-center players stand before the puck drops for the face","In their assigned positions — covering specific areas and players based on what the coach set up. Be there before the puck drops.","In one big group right near the puck so they can all race to the puck quickly if your center wins the faceoff draw in your zone fast n","Standing all the way back at center ice so they can be ready to attack if the other team wins the faceoff draw in your defensive zone"],ok:1,why:"Defensive zone faceoffs are critical moments. Every player except the centers should be in their assigned position before the puck drops — covering a player or an area. The setup before the drop is part of the play.",tip:"Defensive zone faceoff? Get to your position before the puck drops. Every player has a job."},
    {id:"u7q100",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Finish every play",d:3,sit:"You're racing to a puck in the corner and you know the opponent will probably get there first. You're tired. Do you keep going?",opts:["No — if they will get there first, there really is no point in trying to skate hard for a puck that you are not going to win","Yes — keep going at full speed. Maybe they make a mistake, maybe you get there, maybe your effort helps a teammate. Never quit.","Only go after the puck hard if you are sure that you will win the race otherwise it is just a really big waste of energy on you","Stop trying to get to the puck and call out for a different play from your teammates who are around you on the ice right now now"],ok:1,why:"Going hard to every puck — even ones you might not get — is what elite compete looks like. You never know when the opponent will bobble it, or when your effort puts pressure on them that leads to a mistake.",tip:"Won't get there first? Go anyway. Full speed. You never know what happens, and your effort always matters."},
  ,
    {id:"u7g1",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Your net",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"You're the goalie. The other team has the puck and is skating toward your net. Where should you be standing?",opts:["In one of the two far back corners of your own goal net","Right in the middle of the net, between the two posts","Skating out from your crease to meet them at center","Sitting down on the ice right in front of your net"],ok:1,why:"The goalie's job is to protect the net. Standing in the middle between the two posts gives you the best chance to stop the puck no matter which side it comes from.",tip:"Always come back to the middle. That's your home."},
    {id:"u7g2",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Stay on your feet",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"A player is skating toward you with the puck. You're nervous and want to fall down to block the shot. What should you do instead?",opts:["Fall down on the ice right away so you can cover the whole bottom of the net","Stay on your feet as long as possible — you can see the puck better standing up no","Skate all the way out to the blue line and try to poke the puck off of the player","Turn around so you can face the net and get ready to dig the puck out if they sco"],ok:1,why:"Staying on your feet keeps you in the game. The moment you fall down, you lose the ability to move left or right. Stay up and track the puck.",tip:"Stay up as long as you can. Watch the puck. Drop when you have to."},
    {id:"u7g3",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Watch the puck",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"A lot of players are moving around in front of your net. It's hard to see. What's the most important thing you focus on?",opts:["Watch the players moving around in front","Watch the puck — always know where it is","Just look at your teammates and follow them","Close your eyes and just guess where it is"],ok:1,why:"The puck is what scores goals. No matter what else is happening, the goalie always tracks the puck. Players move — but the puck tells you where the danger is.",tip:"Eyes on the puck. Always. That's the number one goalie rule."},
    {id:"u7g4",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Rebounds",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"You stop a shot but the puck bounces out in front of your net. What should you do?",opts:["Stand still and just wait for the other team to take another shot on goal","Try to cover the puck or push it to the corner so your team can get it","Skate out of the crease and try to pass the puck up to one of your teammates","Skate to the bench and leave the net wide open for a new goalie to come in no"],ok:1,why:"A rebound right in front of your net is dangerous — the other team can shoot again immediately. Try to cover it with your glove or paddle it to the corner where your team can get it.",tip:"Stop it once, then smother it or push it away. Don't let the rebound sit in front."},
    {id:"u7g5",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Calling for help",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is loose behind your net and you can't see it. A teammate is right there. What do you do?",opts:["Stay quiet and just hope that your teammate can somehow figure it out all by themselves","Yell to your teammate to let them know where the puck is and that you need help","Skate out of the crease and try to get the puck behind the net all by yourself","Leave the net wide open and skate all the way over to the other end of the ice"],ok:1,why:"Goalies can see things from their angle that teammates can't — and teammates can see things goalies can't. Communicating out loud helps your whole team.",tip:"Talk out there! Goalies who communicate help their whole team."},
    {id:"u7g6",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Crease awareness",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"A player from the other team is standing right in front of your net blocking your view. What do you do?",opts:["Ignore them completely and just trust that your teammates will come push them out of the ","Try to see around them — move side to side a little to get a better view of the puck again","Skate into them and try to push them out of the front of the crease all by yourself","Sit down on the ice so you can try to see the puck underneath the player's legs and skates"],ok:1,why:"Goalies can move slightly side to side to peek around a screener. Your teammates should also be pushing that player out, but you can help yourself by moving to find the puck.",tip:"Screener in front? Move to find the puck. Don't just stand still."},
    {id:"u7g7",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Short side",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"A player is coming at you from the right side of the net. They have a very bad angle — almost behind the net. What do you do?",opts:["Leave the net and chase them behind it to try and poke the puck off them before they get any chance to take a shot","Move toward them and take away the near post — give them the long side shot which is much harder to score on","Stay in the exact middle of the net no matter where they are skating — let them shoot from whatever angle they want","Fall down on the ice and try to cover the bottom of the net with your legs so they can't score there at all"],ok:1,why:"When a player has a bad angle, the goalie moves toward them to take away the short side — the close post. This forces them to shoot across the whole crease which is much harder.",tip:"Bad angle? Take away the short side. Hug the near post."},
    {id:"u7g8",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Getting up fast",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"You went down to make a save and the puck is still loose. What's the most important thing to do now?",opts:["Stay down on the ice and rest for a second before you even try to get back up","Get back up to your feet as fast as you can so you're ready for the next shot","Wait for the whistle to blow dead before you try to get back up on your feet","Slide all the way to the corner and just cover the far post from the ice below"],ok:1,why:"Getting up quickly after going down is one of the most important goalie skills. The puck can come back any second — you need to be back on your feet and in position.",tip:"Down? Get up fast. Every second on the ice is a second you can't make a save."},
    {id:"u7g9",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Freeze or play?",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"You make a save and have your glove on the puck. Your team is tired and needs a rest. What can you do?",opts:["Throw the puck back out into play with your glove so the game keeps going without any whistle now","Cover it completely with your glove — the referee will blow the whistle and your team gets a rest","Kick the puck to one of your defensemen so they can skate out of your zone and give the team a r","Stand up and skate with the puck out to the blue line before passing it to one of your teammates"],ok:1,why:"When a goalie covers the puck completely, the referee stops play. This lets both teams rest and reset — very useful when your team is tired or under heavy pressure.",tip:"Need a rest? Cover the puck completely. The whistle will come."},
    {id:"u7g10",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Talking to your D",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"Your defenseman is behind the net and can't see where the other team's players are. You can see everything from your angle. What should you do?",opts:["Stay quiet — it's their job to figure out pressure and cover players by themselves","Tell them where the pressure is coming from: 'Left side!' or 'Man coming right!' no","Skate out of your crease to help your defenseman battle for the puck behind the net","Go back to the crease and ignore the whole play happening behind the net with your"],ok:1,why:"The goalie has the best view of the whole ice. Telling your defenseman where pressure is coming from is one of the most valuable things a goalie can do — it helps your whole team.",tip:"You see it all from back there. Talk to your D. They need your eyes."},

    // === SEQUENCE ORDERING QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u7seq1",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Getting ready to play",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"Put these steps in the right order for getting ready when your shift starts.",items:["Listen for your coach to call your line","Hop over the boards onto the ice","Skate to your position","Watch the puck and get ready to play"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"A good shift starts before you even get on the ice. Listen, hop on, get to your spot, and then focus on the puck. Doing it in order means you're ready right away.",tip:"Good shift: listen, hop on, get to your spot, watch the puck."},
    {id:"u7seq2",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Scoring a goal steps",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"You want to score a goal. Put these steps in the right order.",items:["Get the puck","Skate toward the net","Pick a spot to aim at","Shoot the puck at the net"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"Scoring starts with getting the puck, then moving toward the net, picking your target, and shooting. Skipping steps — like shooting from far away without aiming — makes it harder.",tip:"Get it, skate close, pick your spot, shoot. That's how goals happen."},
    {id:"u7seq3",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"What to do when they score",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"The other team just scored a goal. Put what happens next in the right order.",items:["Skate back to center ice for the faceoff","Line up in your position","Get ready for the puck to drop","Play hard on the next shift — one goal doesn't matter"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"After a goal against, you reset. Go to center, line up, get ready, and compete. Getting upset wastes time — the next shift is what matters.",tip:"They scored? Reset. Line up. Next shift. That's how tough players respond."},
    {id:"u7seq4",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Making a good pass",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"You want to pass the puck to your teammate. Put these steps in order.",items:["Look up and find your teammate","Make sure they're open and ready","Put the puck on their stick — aim your pass","Call out to let them know it's coming"],correct_order:[0,3,1,2],why:"A great pass starts with looking up, letting your teammate know, making sure they're ready, and then putting it right on their stick. Calling out first helps them get ready.",tip:"Look, call, check they're ready, pass it on their stick. That's teamwork."},
    {id:"u7seq5",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Chasing a loose puck",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"The puck is loose in the corner. Put these steps in order.",items:["See the loose puck","Skate hard toward it — don't wait","Get your stick on the puck first","Look up and make a play with it"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"Loose pucks go to whoever gets there first. See it, go hard, get it, then look up. Standing and watching lets the other team grab it.",tip:"See it, go get it, win it, use it. Every loose puck."},
    {id:"u7seq6",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"After the whistle routine",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"The referee just blew the whistle. Put what you should do in order.",items:["Stop playing — the whistle means stop","Look at the referee","Listen to where the faceoff will be","Skate to your position for the faceoff"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"When the whistle blows, everything resets. Stop, look at the ref, listen, then get to your spot. Players who keep playing after the whistle get penalties.",tip:"Whistle: stop, look, listen, get to your spot. Every time."},
    {id:"u7seq7",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Learning a new drill",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"Your coach is teaching a new drill. Put these steps in order.",items:["Stop skating and look at the coach","Listen to the instructions carefully","Watch if the coach demonstrates it","Try the drill and do your best"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"Learning works best when you stop and focus first. Listen to the words, watch the demo, then try it. Players who skip the listening part make more mistakes.",tip:"Stop, listen, watch, try. That's how you learn new things fast."},
    {id:"u7seq8",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Starting a shift",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"Your coach says your line is up next. Put these steps in order.",items:["Get to the door of the bench","Watch the play so you know what's happening","Jump on when your teammate comes off","Skate hard to where you need to be"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"A quick, smart line change starts before you leave the bench. Be ready at the door, watch what's happening, jump on at the right time, and get into the play fast.",tip:"Be at the door, watch the play, jump on, skate hard. Good changes start on the bench."},

    // === SPOT THE MISTAKE QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u7mis1",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Everyone in one spot",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"All five players on your team are chasing the puck in the same corner. The other team's player is standing alone in front of your net. What's the mistake?",opts:["Your team is skating too slow","Everyone is in the same spot — some players should be spread out, especially someone covering the front of the net","Your goalie should come out more","The coach should call a timeout"],ok:1,why:"When everyone bunches up, the rest of the ice is wide open. Spreading out means your team covers more ice and doesn't leave players wide open near the net.",tip:"All in one corner? Spread out. Cover the ice. Someone needs to be near the net."},
    {id:"u7mis2",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Watching instead of skating back",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"The other team gets the puck and starts skating toward your net. Your teammate stands at center ice and watches instead of skating back. What's the mistake?",opts:["They should have shot the puck","They're standing still instead of skating back — when the other team has the puck heading to your net, you skate back to help defend","They should go to the bench","They need better skates"],ok:1,why:"Watching the play from center ice doesn't help your team. Skating back puts you in a position to help your goalie and your teammates on defense.",tip:"Other team coming? Don't watch. Skate back. Help your team."},
    {id:"u7mis3",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Shooting from too far",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"You have the puck near center ice with nobody between you and the net. Instead of skating closer, you shoot from center. The puck barely reaches the goalie. What went wrong?",opts:["The ice was too bumpy","You shot from too far away — skate closer to the net first so your shot is harder and more accurate","Your stick is too small","The goalie was too good"],ok:1,why:"Shots from far away are weak and easy for goalies to stop. Getting closer makes your shot harder and gives you a better angle. Skate in first, then shoot.",tip:"Far from the net? Skate closer first. Close shots score more goals."},
    {id:"u7mis4",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Never passing",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"A player on your team gets the puck and skates around by themselves every single time, even when teammates are wide open. They lose the puck a lot. What's the mistake?",opts:["They need to skate faster","They're not passing to open teammates — hockey is a team game and passing to open players creates better scoring chances","They should switch positions","Their stick is wrong"],ok:1,why:"Trying to do everything alone is tough, even for the best players. Passing to open teammates creates chances and keeps the other team guessing.",tip:"Open teammate? Pass. Hockey is a team game. You'll score more together."},
    {id:"u7mis5",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Giving up on the play",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"Your teammate loses a race to the puck and stops skating. They stand still for the rest of the play. What's the mistake?",opts:["They should have been faster","They gave up — even if you lose the race, keep skating. You can still pressure the player or get open for the next play.","They should go to the bench","The other player cheated"],ok:1,why:"Losing one race doesn't mean the play is over. Keep going — you might force a mistake, get in a passing lane, or be ready for the next chance.",tip:"Lost the race? Keep going anyway. The play isn't over."},
    {id:"u7mis6",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Playing after the whistle",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"The referee blows the whistle to stop play. One player keeps skating and pushes an opponent. The ref gives them a penalty. What was the mistake?",opts:["The ref was wrong","They kept playing after the whistle — when the whistle blows, you stop. Pushing someone after the whistle is a penalty.","The opponent started it","They were just finishing their check"],ok:1,why:"The whistle means stop. Anything you do after the whistle — especially pushing or hitting — can be a penalty. Control yourself the moment you hear it.",tip:"Whistle blows? Stop. Right away. Don't take a penalty for something after the play."},
    {id:"u7mis7",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Not listening to the coach",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"Your coach tells the team to line up on the blue line for a drill. Two players keep skating around and shooting pucks instead. What's the mistake?",opts:["The drill sounds boring","They're not listening to the coach — when the coach gives instructions, everyone stops and listens. That's how the whole team gets better together.","They need more practice time","The coach should let them keep shooting"],ok:1,why:"Practice only works when everyone is on the same page. Listening to your coach is how you learn and how you show respect to your teammates and coaches.",tip:"Coach is talking? Stop and listen. That's how teams get better."},
    {id:"u7mis8",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Standing behind your own goalie",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"During a play, one of your teammates skates behind your own net and just stands there. They're right behind the goalie doing nothing. What's the mistake?",opts:["They're in a good spot","They're hiding behind the goalie instead of being in a useful position — get to open ice where you can help your team","They should talk to the goalie","They need a rest"],ok:1,why:"Standing behind your own goalie doesn't help anyone. Get to open ice where you can receive a pass, help on defense, or support the play.",tip:"Behind your own net doing nothing? Get to open ice. Be useful. Help your team."},

    // === WHAT HAPPENS NEXT QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u7next1",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Rebound chance",d:1,type:"next",sit:"Your teammate shoots the puck and the goalie stops it, but the puck bounces right out in front of the net. You're standing right there. What happens next?",opts:["You skate away","You wait for someone else to get it","You shoot the puck at the net — it's right there and the goalie is out of position","You pass it back to your teammate"],ok:2,why:"A rebound right in front of the net with the goalie scrambling is one of the best chances to score. Shoot it right away before the goalie can get set again.",tip:"Rebound in front? Shoot it. Fast. Before the goalie gets back."},
    {id:"u7next2",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Goalie has the puck",d:1,type:"next",sit:"Your goalie catches the puck and holds onto it. The referee blows the whistle. What happens next?",opts:["You keep playing","Everyone stops and there's a faceoff in your zone — use this time to catch your breath and get to your position","You go to the bench","The game is over"],ok:1,why:"When the goalie freezes the puck, play stops. There will be a faceoff. Use the stoppage to rest for a second and get into your faceoff position.",tip:"Goalie freezes it? Quick rest, then get to your faceoff spot."},
    {id:"u7next3",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Teammate falls down",d:1,type:"next",sit:"Your teammate is carrying the puck and falls down. The puck slides free. You're the closest player. What happens next?",opts:["You wait for them to get up","You pick up the loose puck and keep the play going — your teammate will get up and join back in","You fall down too","You stop and ask if they're okay"],ok:1,why:"When a teammate falls, the play keeps going. The closest player picks up the puck and continues. Your teammate will get up and rejoin. The game doesn't wait.",tip:"Teammate down? Grab the puck and keep going. They'll catch up."},
    {id:"u7next4",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Penalty called",d:2,type:"next",sit:"The referee raises their arm and blows the whistle. They point at a player on the other team and send them to the penalty box. What happens next?",opts:["The game is over","Your team gets a power play — you have more players on the ice than them, so this is a great chance to score","Nothing changes","Both teams lose a player"],ok:1,why:"When the other team gets a penalty, your team has a power play — more players on the ice. This is a big advantage and a great time to try to score.",tip:"Other team gets a penalty? Power play! More players for you. Try to score."},
    {id:"u7next5",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck goes in the corner",d:1,type:"next",sit:"The puck gets shot into the corner of the rink. Nobody is near it. You and an opponent both see it at the same time. What happens next?",opts:["You both wait to see who goes first","Whoever skates harder gets there first — race to the puck and compete for it","You let them have it","You go to the bench"],ok:1,why:"When a puck is loose and both teams see it, it becomes a race. The player who wants it more and skates harder gets there first. That's compete.",tip:"Both see the puck? Race for it. Skate hard. Want it more."},
    {id:"u7next6",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"After a goal",d:1,type:"next",sit:"Your team just scored a goal! Everyone celebrates. What happens next?",opts:["You keep celebrating for the rest of the game","You celebrate quickly with your teammates, then skate back to center ice and line up for the next faceoff","You go straight to the bench","You do a long dance"],ok:1,why:"Celebrating is great — but keep it quick. After a goal, you need to get back to center ice and line up for the faceoff. The game keeps going.",tip:"Score a goal? Celebrate quick, then line up at center. The game isn't over."},
    {id:"u7next7",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Coach calls your line",d:1,type:"next",sit:"You're on the bench and your coach says 'Next line, get ready!' You're on the next line. What happens next?",opts:["You keep sitting and wait","You stand up, get to the door, and get ready to jump on the ice as soon as your teammates come off","You start stretching","You ask which line you're on"],ok:1,why:"When the coach calls your line, you need to be ready immediately. Stand up, get to the door, watch the play, and hop on when it's time. Being ready shows you're a good teammate.",tip:"Your line is up? Get to the door. Be ready. Don't make your team wait."},

    // === TRUE/FALSE QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u7tf1",cat:"Compete",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Try your hardest",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"It's okay to stop trying if the other team is winning by a lot.",ok:false,why:"You always play hard no matter the score. Games can change fast, and the habits you build when it's tough are the habits that make you better. Never stop competing.",tip:"Down by a lot? Doesn't matter. Keep going. Hard work is always worth it."},
    {id:"u7tf2",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Celebrate teammates",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"When your teammate scores a goal, you should celebrate with them even if you didn't help on the play.",ok:true,why:"Hockey is a team sport. Celebrating together builds team spirit. Your teammate's goal is your team's goal — every player matters, even when you're not the one who scored.",tip:"Teammate scored? Celebrate with them. That's what teams do."},
    {id:"u7tf3",cat:"Game Awareness",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Whistle means stop",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"When the referee blows the whistle, you should stop playing immediately.",ok:true,why:"The whistle means play is dead. Anything you do after the whistle doesn't count and could get you a penalty. Stop right away, every time.",tip:"Whistle = stop. Immediately. No exceptions."},
    {id:"u7tf4",cat:"Scoring",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Only stars shoot",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"Only the best player on the team should shoot the puck.",ok:false,why:"Every player should shoot when they have a chance. The more shots your team takes, the more chances you have to score. You don't have to be the best player to put the puck on net.",tip:"Got a chance to shoot? Shoot. Every player. Every shot counts."},
    {id:"u7tf5",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Everyone plays defense",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"Everyone on the team needs to help on defense — not just the defensemen.",ok:true,why:"Defense is everyone's job. Forwards backcheck. Centers cover the middle. When the whole team defends, the other team has a much harder time scoring.",tip:"Defense isn't just for D. Everyone helps. The whole team defends together."},
    {id:"u7tf6",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Follow the puck",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"Every player on the team should always skate directly to wherever the puck is.",ok:false,why:"If everyone goes to the puck, the rest of the ice is empty. Smart players spread out and find open ice. Only one or two players need to be near the puck — everyone else should be open for a pass.",tip:"Not everyone goes to the puck. Spread out. Find open ice. Be ready for a pass."},
    {id:"u7tf7",cat:"Coachability",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Mistakes are okay",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"Making mistakes during practice and games is part of getting better at hockey.",ok:true,why:"Every player makes mistakes — even the pros. Mistakes are how you learn what works and what doesn't. The important thing is to keep trying and learn from them.",tip:"Made a mistake? Good. Now you know. Try again. That's how you get better."},
  ],
  "U9 / Novice":[
    {id:"u9q1",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Pass or shoot",d:1,sit:"You enter the offensive zone with speed. A defender is square in front of you, but your linemate is wide open on the left wing. What do you do?",opts:["Try to deke around the defender alone now","Pass to your open linemate immediately","Dump the puck in and chase right away","Slow down and wait for help right away"],ok:1,why:"The defender is committed to you — which means your teammate is open. Defender takes you = give it up.",tip:"Defender takes you + teammate is open = pass. Almost always."},
    {id:"u9q2",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defensive transition",d:1,sit:"Your team just turned the puck over in the offensive zone. The other team has it and is skating the other way. You're the nearest forward. What's your first move?",opts:["Stay in the offensive zone in case","Immediately turn and skate back hard","Skate slowly back and watch hard","Go to the bench as fast as you can"],ok:1,why:"The instant the puck changes hands, your job changes. You go from attacker to backchecker immediately.",tip:"Turnover = turn around. Don't wait. Go now."},
    {id:"u9q3",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Open ice",d:1,sit:"You're in the offensive zone without the puck. Three players including you are all crowded near the puck carrier. What's the smart move?",opts:["Get as close to the puck as possible and avoid the dangerous area","Find open ice away from the puck — near the net or at the blue line","Go to the bench — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Stand still and call for the puck — the puck will sort itself out"],ok:1,why:"Clustering around the puck is one of the most common mistakes at this age. Open ice is where plays are made.",tip:"Where's the open ice? Go there. That's where the play will come."},
    {id:"u9q4",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Man on call",d:1,sit:"You can see a defender coming at your teammate who has the puck but can't see behind them. What do you do?",opts:["Say nothing and see what happens and hope for the best","Yell 'man on!' so your teammate knows pressure is coming","Skate over to point at the defender as fast as you can","Wait until the check happens — it's not the right call now"],ok:1,why:"Communication is a decision. 'Man on' gives your teammate a split-second to protect the puck.",tip:"See something your teammate can't? Tell them. Loud and clear. That's hockey."},
    {id:"u9q5",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F"],concept:"Slot shot",d:1,sit:"You catch a pass in the slot, 15 feet from the net. The goalie is leaning slightly right. You have a clear shooting lane to the left. What should you do?",opts:["Pass to a teammate on the perimeter — that's important here now","Shoot quickly to the left where the goalie is out of position","Stickhandle and wait for a better angle — that's a bad read","Turn and skate back — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"When you catch the puck in the slot with a shooting lane and an out-of-position goalie, shoot immediately. Every second you wait, the goalie adjusts.",tip:"Slot + open lane + quick release = shoot. Don't think. Shoot."},
    {id:"u9q6",cat:"Starts",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Faceoff reaction",d:1,sit:"You lose a faceoff in your own zone. The other team's center has the puck. What's your immediate priority?",opts:["Argue with the ref — that's a bad read","Go pressure the puck carrier immediately","Skate to the bench — that's a bad read","Stand still and watch as fast as you can"],ok:1,why:"Lost faceoffs happen — what matters is the reaction. Going immediately to pressure the puck forces a mistake or delays the play.",tip:"Lost the draw? Go hard immediately. The puck is right there."},
    {id:"u9q7",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout wall",d:1,sit:"Your defenseman picks up the puck in your own corner. As a winger, where should you be going?",opts:["Stand in the corner with the defenseman hard","Get up the wall to give the D an outlet option","Skate to center ice immediately immediately hard","Stay near the net in case of a rebound hard"],ok:1,why:"Breakout positioning means getting to spots that give your defenseman real options. As a winger, that's typically up the wall.",tip:"D has the puck in the corner? Get up the wall. Give them an out."},
    {id:"u9q8",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Backchecking",d:1,sit:"The other team has the puck and is skating toward your net. You're a forward behind the play. What's your job?",opts:["Stand at center ice and wait right away","Skate back hard to give your D support","Skate to the other team's end hard","Yell at your teammates to handle it hard"],ok:1,why:"When the other team has the puck and is coming your way, your job is to turn around and get back — always.",tip:"Other team going the other way? Turn around and go back hard."},
    {id:"u9q9",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Net front",d:1,sit:"Your team has the puck in the offensive zone. You don't have it and there's no one near you. Where's the smartest place to go?",opts:["Stand at center ice hard hard","Get to the front of the net","Skate to the corner where","Go to the bench right away"],ok:1,why:"Standing in front of the net without the puck is one of the highest-value things a player can do. It creates a screen, puts you in rebound position, and forces a defender to deal with you.",tip:"No puck? Go to the net. Someone will find you there."},
    {id:"u9q10",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Gap control basics",d:1,sit:"You're a defender and an opposing player is skating toward you with the puck, 20 feet away. What's right?",opts:["Skate straight at them as fast as you can — just get it out of there","Back up and maintain a steady gap while angling them toward the boards","Turn around and skate backward immediately to your crease right away","Stand completely still — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a"],ok:1,why:"Gap control means not giving up too much — but also not closing too fast. Skating straight at a puck carrier lets them pull the puck past you.",tip:"Don't rush a puck carrier. Control your gap. Make them go where you want."},
    {id:"u9q11",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Simple outlet",d:1,sit:"You have the puck in your own zone. A forechecker is right on you. Your D partner is five feet away and completely open. What do you do?",opts:["Try to skate out yourself immediately","Pass immediately to your open D partner","Shoot the puck down the ice right away now","Wait for a better option immediately"],ok:1,why:"The open D partner five feet away is the easy, correct play. Under pressure the simple play is almost always right.",tip:"Open partner right beside you? Give it to them. Simple."},
    {id:"u9q12",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F"],concept:"Rebounds",d:1,sit:"Your teammate takes a shot from the point. The goalie makes the save but the rebound bounces out to the slot. You're 10 feet away. What do you do?",opts:["Wait to see where the puck goes immediately","Skate hard to the rebound and shoot immediately","Pass to a teammate further away immediately","Back off to give the goalie space immediately now"],ok:1,why:"Rebounds are the highest-percentage scoring opportunities in hockey. The player who gets there first and shoots first wins most of those battles.",tip:"Rebound in the slot? Go get it. Shoot first, think later."},
    {id:"u9q13",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Quick puck after a save",d:1,sit:"Your goalie makes a save and has the puck. The other team has forecheckers coming in. Your winger is breaking back toward the goalie. What should the goalie do?",opts:["Hold the puck and freeze it for a faceoff right away now","Pass to the winger breaking back — beat the forecheck","Shoot it down the ice and trust the play to develop","Rim it around the boards — just get it out of there"],ok:1,why:"A goalie with the puck can start the breakout before the forecheck resets. A crisp pass to the returning winger beats the pressure.",tip:"Goalie has it and a winger is coming back? Start the breakout fast."},
    {id:"u9q14",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Spread out on a rush",d:1,sit:"Your team is attacking 3-on-2. Where should the three forwards position themselves?",opts:["All three skate together in a tight group — that's important here","Spread out across the ice so the two defenders can't cover everyone","Two go left and one goes right — you'll figure the rest out later","One attacker goes while two wait at center no matter what happens"],ok:1,why:"Spreading out on a rush forces the defenders to make an impossible choice. A tight group lets two players cover all three.",tip:"Rush attack: spread out. Make the defenders choose."},
    {id:"u9q15",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Support play",d:1,sit:"Your teammate has the puck in the offensive zone and is pressured from behind. You're five feet away with no defender on you. What do you do?",opts:["Watch to see what they do and trust the play to develop","Get open and call for the puck — give them an easy outlet","Skate to the corner — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Go to the net and wait and let your teammates handle it"],ok:1,why:"When a teammate is pressured, your job is to get open and give them an easy option. The call helps them know you're there.",tip:"Teammate pressured? Get open and let them know. Be the easy option."},
    {id:"u9q16",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D-to-D reset",d:2,sit:"Your defenseman has the puck behind the net. Both wingers are covered. The other defenseman is open on the far side. What's the best option?",opts:["Force a pass to a covered winger and hope for the best","Walk out from behind the net alone — that's a bad read","Pass across to the open defenseman to reset the breakout","Shoot the puck around the boards and hope for the best now"],ok:2,why:"When your outlets are covered, the D-to-D pass behind the net resets the play. It switches the point of attack and gives the other side time to get open.",tip:"Outlets covered? Go D-to-D. Reset and rebuild."},
    {id:"u9q17",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Weak side",d:2,sit:"Your team is in the offensive zone. The puck is in the left corner. You're the right winger. Where's your best spot?",opts:["Go into the left corner to help your teammate now now","Stay on the right side near the net — the weak side","Go to the blue line and trust the play to develop","Skate to center ice and trust the play to develop"],ok:1,why:"As the weak-side winger, your job is to stay available on the opposite side. Pucks go cross-ice constantly — you need to be ready.",tip:"Puck in the far corner? Stay on your side near the net. That's where the cross-ice pass goes."},
    {id:"u9q18",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Neutral zone read",d:2,sit:"Your team just got the puck in your own zone. The other team's forecheckers are still in your end. What do you do with the puck?",opts:["Shoot it down the ice immediately — you'll figure the rest out later right","Skate it out calmly — the forecheckers are out of position and you have time","Wait behind your net for them to regroup until someone tells you otherwise","Pass it back to your goalie — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a"],ok:1,why:"When the other team's forecheckers are caught deep in your zone, they're out of position. That's your window to carry the puck out with speed.",tip:"Forecheckers caught deep? Carry it out. You have time."},
    {id:"u9q19",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Hold vs release",d:2,sit:"You receive a pass at the blue line on the power play. A penalty killer is closing fast. The slot is open. You have one second. What's right?",opts:["Hold the puck and wait for a better option hard","One-time it or shoot immediately into the open slot","Pass back to the other point — that's a bad read hard","Skate into the zone yourself — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"One second on the power play point with the slot open is a shooting opportunity — not a thinking opportunity. The PK player closing on you takes that lane away in two seconds.",tip:"Point with an open shot? Release it fast. The lane closes quick."},
    {id:"u9q20",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"When NOT to shoot",d:2,sit:"You're in the offensive zone with the puck. You have a shooting lane but your teammate is streaking to the net completely unmarked. The goalie hasn't seen them yet. What do you do?",opts:["Shoot — you have the lane and hope for the best","Pass to your unmarked teammate cutting to the net","Dump it to the corner — it's not the right call","Hold the puck and stickhandle as fast as you can now"],ok:1,why:"An unmarked teammate cutting to the net with the goalie unaware is a higher-percentage chance than your open shot. The selfless play is also the smart play.",tip:"Teammate cutting to the net unmarked? Give it up. That's the better chance."},
    {id:"u9q21",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"2-on-1 as D",d:2,sit:"You're the lone defender on a 2-on-1 against you. The puck carrier has a teammate to their right. What's the most important thing you do?",opts:["Rush at the puck carrier to take the puck — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Take away the pass — stay in the middle, force the shooter, and let the goalie handle the shot","Chase the trailer player — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read and hope for","Back up to your crease immediately — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"On a 2-on-1, the defender's job is to take away the pass. If you rush the puck carrier, the pass kills you. Force the shot — your goalie is ready for that.",tip:"2-on-1 as D: take away the pass. Make them shoot. That's your job."},
    {id:"u9q22",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Third forward safety",d:2,sit:"Your team is forechecking. Two forwards are already deep in the offensive zone. You're the third forward. Where do you set up?",opts:["Go deep into the zone with the other two as fast as you can","Stay at the top of the zone near the blue line as the safety","Go to the bench for a line change before anyone else moves","Skate to the half-wall — you'll figure the rest out later"],ok:1,why:"The third forward on a forecheck is the safety valve. If you all go deep, you leave yourself exposed to a quick breakout and a 3-on-2 against you.",tip:"Two forwards deep on the forecheck? You're the safety. Hold the blue line."},
    {id:"u9q23",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Quick transition attack",d:2,sit:"Your team just won a puck battle in the corner in your own zone. The other team has four players still deep in your end. You have speed. What's the call?",opts:["Reset and regroup — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Go — skate it out fast and attack while they're out of position","Pass to your D and let them decide — just get it out of there now","Shoot it down the ice — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"When you win a puck battle and the other team is caught deep, that's a transition opportunity. Going immediately puts them on their heels.",tip:"Other team caught deep? Go now. Transition kills before they reset."},
    {id:"u9q24",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Pressure reads",d:2,sit:"You have the puck behind your own net. A forechecker is coming at you hard. You have a defenseman open to your left. What do you do?",opts:["Try to outskate the forechecker and carry it yourself right away","Quickly pass to the open defenseman before the forechecker arrives","Stop behind the net and wait — you'll figure the rest out later","Shoot the puck down the ice — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"Decision timing is everything. The forechecker closing on you is information — it tells you to move the puck before you get pressured.",tip:"See pressure coming? Move the puck before it gets there."},
    {id:"u9q25",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F"],concept:"Shot location",d:2,sit:"You have the puck near the goal line, way out to the side. The goalie has the near post covered completely. A teammate is at the far post. What do you do?",opts:["Shoot from where you are — any shot is good — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Pass across to your teammate at the far post — the goalie can't get there in time","Skate to center and shoot — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Dump the puck behind the net — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad"],ok:1,why:"Shooting from the goal line with the near post completely covered gives the goalie an easy save. A far-post pass forces the goalie to move across the entire crease.",tip:"Goalie has your side? Pass across. Make them move all the way."},
    {id:"u9q26",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Cycling below dots",d:2,sit:"Your team is cycling in the offensive zone below the dots. You're low in the corner with the puck. A defender is on you. Your winger is at the half-wall. What do you do?",opts:["Try to hold the puck alone in the corner immediately","Pass to the half-wall winger and let the cycle continue","Shoot from the corner — the puck will sort itself out","Pass all the way back to the point as fast as you can"],ok:1,why:"When you're pressured low in the corner, passing to the half-wall winger moves the puck to a player with more options — they can shoot, pass to the slot, or continue the cycle.",tip:"Pressured in the corner? Pass to the half-wall. They have more options than you do."},
    {id:"u9q27",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Angling",d:2,sit:"An attacker is carrying the puck along the right boards toward your net. You're the defender. What's the goal of your positioning?",opts:["Stop them by skating straight at them — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Angle your body to steer them along the boards and away from the middle of the ice","Back up all the way to your crease — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a hard","Wait for them to shoot and block it — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"Angling means steering the puck carrier where you want them — along the boards and away from the dangerous middle of the ice.",tip:"Angling: push them to the boards. Keep them out of the middle."},
    {id:"u9q28",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Strong vs weak side",d:2,sit:"Your D picks up the puck. The strong-side winger is covered. The weak-side winger is open on the far side. What's the breakout call?",opts:["Force the pass to the covered strong-side winger right away","Pass to the open weak-side winger — they're the clean option","Carry it out yourself — you'll figure the rest out later","Rim it around the boards until someone tells you otherwise now"],ok:1,why:"A covered winger is not an option. The clean outlet is the open player — even if they're on the far side. Read the ice, not just the default option.",tip:"Strong side is covered? Go weak side. Find the open player."},
    {id:"u9q29",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Crash the net",d:2,sit:"Your teammate is about to take a shot from the point. Nobody is near the net. What should you do right now?",opts:["Stay where you are — it might miss wide — that's a bad read hard","Skate hard to the front of the net and get ready for a rebound","Back up to the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later","Call for a pass instead of letting them shoot immediately"],ok:1,why:"Getting to the net before the shot arrives means you're in position for a rebound before the goalie can cover it. Net-front presence wins games.",tip:"Teammate about to shoot? Crash the net. Get there before the puck does."},
    {id:"u9q30",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Stretch pass",d:2,sit:"You have the puck in your own zone. A defender is pressuring you. Your teammate is breaking into the neutral zone. They're 40 feet away but wide open. What's the read?",opts:["Dump the puck out and trust the play to develop","Attempt the stretch pass to the breaking teammate","Skate it out yourself — it's not the right call","Hold the puck behind the net as fast as you can"],ok:1,why:"A stretch pass to a breaking forward turns a defensive zone puck into an immediate odd-man rush. The risk is the pass — but if the lane is open, it's the highest-reward play.",tip:"Breaking teammate wide open? Thread the stretch pass. Big reward if you make it."},
    {id:"u9q31",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Talk on D",d:2,sit:"You're defending in your own zone. Your D partner goes behind the net to get a puck. A forward is crashing to the net and nobody is covering them. What do you do?",opts:["Wait for your D partner to come back and handle it immediately","Call out the open player to your teammates and cover them yourself","Ignore it — the goalie will handle it — just get it out of there now","Stand in front of your own net and do nothing as fast as you can"],ok:1,why:"When your D partner leaves to get the puck, you need to cover the open attacker. Calling it out also helps your team organize.",tip:"D partner left? You cover the open man. Call it out loud."},
    {id:"u9q32",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Contain the rush",d:2,sit:"An attacker is rushing the puck at you at full speed. You're the only defender. The attacker is fast. What do you do?",opts:["Charge at them at full speed to meet them until someone tells you otherwise","Back up at a controlled pace — keep your gap and angle them toward the","Turn around and race them to your net — you'll figure the rest out later","Stand completely still — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"Charging a fast attacker lets them blow past you. Backing up at a controlled pace while angling forces them to slow down or go where you want.",tip:"Fast attacker coming? Back up controlled. Don't chase. Angle them."},
    {id:"u9q33",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Center option on breakout",d:2,sit:"Your D picks up the puck. Both wingers are tied up by forecheckers. But your center is open in the middle of the ice. What's the breakout call?",opts:["Force the pass to a covered winger as fast as you can","Pass to the open center in the middle — they're clean","Carry it yourself until someone tells you otherwise","Rim it around the boards — just get it out of there"],ok:1,why:"The center in the middle is often the hidden option on a breakout. If both wingers are covered, the center up the middle is the smart outlet.",tip:"Both wingers covered? The center in the middle might be the cleanest option."},
    {id:"u9q34",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F"],concept:"One-timer",d:2,sit:"You're on the power play at the half-wall. The puck carrier passes it to you in stride. The goalie is leaning to their left. What's the right play?",opts:["Stop the puck and look for a pass and avoid the dangerous area","One-time it to the right side where the goalie hasn't moved yet","Stickhandle and wait — you'll figure the rest out later right","Pass it back to the point — you'll figure the rest out later"],ok:1,why:"A one-timer on the power play catches the goalie before they can reset. Stopping the puck gives them time to adjust — a quick release doesn't.",tip:"Pass comes in stride with the goalie leaning? One-time it. Quick release wins."},
    {id:"u9q35",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Forward becoming a defender",d:2,sit:"The puck turns over in the neutral zone and now the other team has a 2-on-2 going toward your net. You're one of the two defenders. What's your priority?",opts:["Chase the puck carrier and try to get the puck back — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Take your side — one defender takes the carrier, the other takes the second attacker — and protect the middle","Both defenders collapse to the crease — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the now","Go to the bench immediately — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"A 2-on-2 defense requires each defender to take a side. The most dangerous play is a middle pass — stay in the lanes and make them go wide.",tip:"2-on-2 against you: each take a side. Protect the middle."},
    {id:"u9q36",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Chip and chase",d:2,sit:"Your team is entering the offensive zone. The defender is set at their blue line — they're not going to let you carry it in. What's the best entry option?",opts:["Carry it in at full speed and hope to blow past them — that's important here","Chip the puck into the zone behind the defender and skate hard to get it first","Stop at the blue line and wait — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a","Pass back and regroup — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read now"],ok:1,why:"A set defender at the blue line means you probably can't carry it in cleanly. Chipping the puck into space behind them and racing to get it first beats the defender's positioning.",tip:"Defender set at the line? Chip it in and go get it. Don't force the carry."},
    {id:"u9q37",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Moving without the puck",d:2,sit:"You don't have the puck in the offensive zone and your teammate is being pressured. The defender covering you is watching the puck. What do you do?",opts:["Stand still and call for the puck — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read hard","Skate to a new open spot — cut to the net or find a seam. Your defender will have to follow.","Skate toward your covered teammate — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Go to the bench — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right"],ok:1,why:"Moving without the puck forces your defender to follow you — and every step they take to follow you is a step away from the puck carrier. Create problems by moving.",tip:"No puck and defender watching the play? Move. Make them follow you. Create space."},
    {id:"u9q38",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Covering the point",d:2,sit:"Your team is on the penalty kill. The power play passes to the point. You're the near penalty killer forward. What do you do?",opts:["Go all the way to the corner — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Close on the point player to pressure the shot or take away the dangerous pass options","Stay in the middle of the ice — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Back up to your crease — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right"],ok:1,why:"Closing on the point player on the PK takes away a clean shooting lane or forces a rushed decision. You don't have to get the puck — just make them uncomfortable.",tip:"PK: close on the point player. Make it hard for them to get a clean shot."},
    {id:"u9q39",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck support",d:2,sit:"Your teammate just won a puck battle in the corner in the defensive zone. They have the puck but defenders are still around them. You're nearby without a defender on you. What do you do?",opts:["Skate away to center ice — you'll figure the rest out later right","Get close enough to be an easy pass — support behind or beside them","Call for a long pass to the blue line and avoid the dangerous area now","Stand still and watch — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"When a teammate wins a puck battle in a tough spot, they need immediate support. Getting close gives them a safe, quick outlet before the next pressure arrives.",tip:"Teammate won the puck battle? Get close and give them a quick option."},
    {id:"u9q40",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Timing the breakout",d:2,sit:"Your D picks up the puck behind your net. Two forecheckers are coming but they haven't arrived yet. You have 2 seconds. What's the key thing your D should do?",opts:["Wait until the forecheckers arrive before deciding — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Look up immediately and read which outlet is open before the pressure arrives — decide early","Rim it around the boards automatically — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad","Skate out with the puck no matter what — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"Reading the breakout before the pressure arrives — deciding early — is the difference between a clean exit and getting trapped. The D needs to see the ice before the forechecker takes the options away.",tip:"D with the puck and pressure coming? Look up and decide early. Don't wait."},
    {id:"u9q41",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Rush read — shoot or pass",d:3,sit:"You're the puck carrier on a 2-on-1. The lone defender commits fully to your teammate. The goalie slides across expecting your pass. What's the right call now?",opts:["Pass to your teammate as planned — it's not the right call now","Shoot — the goalie has moved and there's a lane on your side","Pass to the other side — you'll figure the rest out later","Pull up and regroup — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"When the defender commits to your teammate AND the goalie slides to take away the pass, they've left your side open. Shoot — the goalie has moved.",tip:"2-on-1: if the goalie chases the pass, shoot. Read the goalie."},
    {id:"u9q42",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Reading a 3-on-2",d:3,sit:"Your team turned the puck over and now three attackers are coming at your two defensemen. You're the left D. The puck carrier is on your side. What's your job?",opts:["Rush the puck carrier immediately — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad","Take your side and force the carrier wide — your partner protects the middle attacker","Chase the trailer — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","Back up to your crease — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right"],ok:1,why:"On a 3-on-2, each D takes a side and the D on the puck side forces the carrier wide. The partner covers the middle — the most dangerous attacker.",tip:"3-on-2 against you: take your side. Protect the middle. Don't both go one way."},
    {id:"u9q43",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Pre-read before receiving",d:3,sit:"You're about to receive a pass in the offensive zone. Before the puck reaches you, what should you already be doing?",opts:["Waiting with your stick ready to receive — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Looking up and deciding where you're going with the puck before it arrives — pre-reading the play","Calling for the puck louder — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read and hope for hard","Watching the pass to make sure you catch it — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"Pre-reading the play — deciding where you're going before the puck arrives — is what separates slow players from fast ones. By the time the puck hits your stick, your decision should already be made.",tip:"Pass coming? Decide what you're doing with it before it arrives. Pre-read."},
    {id:"u9q44",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Counter attack timing",d:3,sit:"Your team is on the power play. The penalty kill gets the puck and two players immediately break the other way 2-on-2. What should your team do?",opts:["Chase immediately and attack the puck carrier and let your teammates handle it","One forward pressures the puck, the others recover their positions — don't panic","All five players retreat to your own zone — you'll figure the rest out later","Ignore it — the PP will get another chance — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"A PP counter-attack is dangerous but not a guaranteed goal. One player pressures, everyone else recovers. Panicking and chasing creates a turnover.",tip:"PK breaks out on a counter? One pressures, others recover. Don't all chase."},
    {id:"u9q45",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F"],concept:"Screen and tip",d:3,sit:"Your team has a power play. You're standing in front of the goalie. Your teammate at the point winds up for a shot. What's your job?",opts:["Get out of the way so the goalie can see the shot — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Stay planted and block the goalie's sightline — screen them, and be ready to tip the shot","Skate to the corner for the rebound — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Call for a pass instead — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away"],ok:1,why:"A screener in front of the net on the power play is one of the highest-value positions. You block the goalie's view and tip shots — that combination creates goals.",tip:"In front of the net on the PP? Screen the goalie and tip the shot. Stay planted."},
    {id:"u9q46",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Switch on defense",d:3,sit:"You're the right defenseman covering an attacker on your side. Another attacker cuts across in front of the net toward your side. Your partner calls 'switch!' What do you do?",opts:["Stay with your original assignment — ignore the switch call and hope for the best","Take the attacker cutting to your side, let your partner recover their original man","Call the referee — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","Back up to the crease and cover both — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"A switch call means you take the player coming to your side while your partner recovers their original man. It's communication and trust.",tip:"Partner calls switch? Take the player coming to you. Trust the call."},
    {id:"u9q47",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Seal on puck battles",d:3,sit:"You're the defenseman and the opposing team's winger wins a puck battle in the corner in your defensive zone. They're about to pass to someone in the slot. What do you do?",opts:["Go into the corner and try to re-win the battle — you'll figure the rest out later right","Seal off the passing lane to the slot — get between the puck carrier and the dangerous area","Skate to the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read and hope for now","Watch and react when the pass is made — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"Once the puck battle is lost, the priority shifts to cutting off the next play — which is almost always a slot pass. Get between the puck carrier and the slot immediately.",tip:"Lost the puck battle? Don't chase the puck. Seal the passing lane to the slot."},
    {id:"u9q48",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Beating the forecheck",d:3,sit:"Your team is under heavy forecheck pressure. Your D picks up the puck behind your net. Two forecheckers are pinching in from both sides. What breakout option gives you the best chance?",opts:["Wheel and try to carry it out yourself — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the","Reverse the puck to the other side — one forechecker can't follow, buying time for your winger to get position","Rim it around the boards hard — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call","Shoot it down the ice for icing — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"Under heavy forecheck pressure with two pinching forecheckers, the reverse gives you an extra second. One forechecker can't cover both sides simultaneously.",tip:"Two forecheckers pinching? Reverse the puck. One of them can't follow."},
    {id:"u9q49",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Recognize the trap",d:3,sit:"The other team is sitting back in a 1-2-2 neutral zone setup. Every time your team tries to enter, they get stopped at the red line. What adjustment do you make?",opts:["Keep trying to carry it in — eventually you'll break through — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read hard now","Pull the puck back to your defensemen, use a D-to-D pass to overload one side, or try a stretch pass to a breaking forward","Dump the puck in every time — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for","Skate around the outside of the trap — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"A 1-2-2 trap is designed to stop straight-line carries. The answer is patience and lateral movement.",tip:"Against a trap: go backward to go forward. Change the angle. Be patient."},
    {id:"u9q50",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defensive zone faceoff role",d:3,sit:"Your team is taking a defensive zone faceoff. Before the puck drops, what should every player already know?",opts:["Nothing — just react to where the puck goes — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read hard","Their assignment — who they're covering and where they're going based on whether you win or lose the draw","Where the nearest door to the bench is — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","To skate as fast as possible after the puck — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read hard"],ok:1,why:"A faceoff is a set play. Every player should know their assignment before the puck drops — what to do if you win, what to do if you lose. The setup before the drop is as important as the drop itself.",tip:"Before the faceoff drops: know your assignment. Win or lose — be ready to execute."},
    {id:"u9q51",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Angling at top speed",d:3,sit:"An opposing winger has broken the puck out of their own zone and is coming at you with speed. You're at the red line. The attacker is fast and has a step on you. What's your priority?",opts:["Charge at them and take the puck — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the","Back up at a pace that doesn't let them get speed on you, angle them toward the boards, and wait for","Turn and race them to your net — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the hard","Stand completely still and wait — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the"],ok:1,why:"An attacker with speed is trying to blow past you. Backing up at the right pace while angling keeps you ahead of them and denies the clean entry.",tip:"Fast attacker with a step on you? Back up fast and angle. Don't let them get speed going."},
    {id:"u9q52",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F"],concept:"Quick release in tight",d:3,sit:"You're in tight to the net — five feet out. The goalie is set. You have the puck on your backhand but there's barely any time. What do you do?",opts:["Try to switch the puck to your forehand for a better shot as fast as you can","Release your backhand immediately — the goalie is set for the forehand anyway","Pass to a teammate outside — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad","Skate around to get a better angle — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"In tight to the net with time running out, a quick backhand release is often better than taking the time to switch to your forehand. The goalie is already positioned for the forehand.",tip:"In tight with time running out? Shoot what you've got. Don't switch hands."},
    {id:"u9q53",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Cycle breakdown",d:3,sit:"Your team is cycling in the offensive zone. The cycle isn't working — the defenders have perfectly matched your movement for 20 seconds and nothing is opening. What should you do?",opts:["Keep cycling — eventually something will open until someone tells you otherwise now","Stop the cycle — dump the puck deep, change lines, and come back with a new entry","Shoot from the corner — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Pass all the way back to the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later right"],ok:1,why:"A cycle against a perfectly matched defense is just burning your legs. Recognize when the cycle isn't creating opportunities and make the change — dump, line change, come back fresh.",tip:"Cycle going nowhere? Dump and change. Come back with a fresh entry."},
    {id:"u9q54",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Winning position after a penalty",d:3,sit:"Your team just got called for a penalty. Before you leave the ice, what should the remaining four players know?",opts:["Nothing — just defend hard — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best","Their specific penalty kill assignments — who covers the point, who covers the half-wall, and what the plan is if they get the puck","To skate as fast as possible — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best","To surround the puck carrier at all times — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call right"],ok:1,why:"The penalty kill is a system. The four remaining players need to know their assignments before the power play sets up. Improvising on the PK gives up goals.",tip:"Going on the PK? Know your assignment. The system works when everyone knows their job."},
    {id:"u9q55",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Last man read",d:3,sit:"You're the last defender back and two attackers are coming at you on a 2-on-1. Your goalie is set. One attacker has the puck on the left. One is cutting to the net on the right. What do you do?",opts:["Commit to the puck carrier on the left — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right","Stay in the middle — take away the pass to the cutter and force the shot. Your goalie handles the shot.","Chase the cutter to the right — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the hard","Back up all the way to your crease — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read and hope for"],ok:1,why:"Last man back on a 2-on-1: take away the pass, force the shot, trust your goalie. Don't commit to either attacker until they force your hand.",tip:"Last man back on a 2-on-1: take away the pass. Let the goalie have the shot."},
    {id:"u9q56",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Read the goalie on a breakaway",d:3,sit:"You're on a breakaway. The goalie is skating aggressively out to cut your angle. What's the most effective play?",opts:["Shoot blocker side immediately from distance — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Pull the puck wide, make the goalie commit to one side, then shoot or go to the other side","Try a straight backhand shot immediately — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad","Slow down and wait until you're right on top of them — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"An aggressive goalie is looking for an early shot or for you to go straight. Make them commit — take the puck wide, let them follow, then shoot or go opposite.",tip:"Aggressive goalie on a breakaway: make them commit first. Then go where they're not."},
    {id:"u9q57",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP point read",d:3,sit:"Your power play is in a 1-3-1 and has been set up for 30 seconds without generating a shot. Two PK forwards are pressuring the top. What should the top player do?",opts:["Try to hold the puck and fight through both PK forwards — that's important here now","Move the puck quickly across to the half-wall before both pressure players arrive","Shoot from distance through traffic — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Pass it back to your own zone and reset — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"Two PK forwards pressuring one point means the rest of the formation has a gap — the half-wall is almost always where that gap is. Move the puck before both arrive.",tip:"Two PKers coming? Move the puck before they get there. They can't cover two spots at once."},
    {id:"u9q58",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Late game puck management",d:3,sit:"Your team is winning by one goal with two minutes left. You win a faceoff in the offensive zone. What's most important?",opts:["Take a big shot immediately to extend the lead — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a","Control the puck, cycle below the dots, use every second — only shoot on a high-quality chance now","Dump the puck to the corner and chase — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Pass it back to your own zone to be safe — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"Late-game puck management is a skill. Cycling below the dots forces the other team to chase, burns clock, and keeps the puck away from their skilled players.",tip:"Leading late: the clock is your ally. Protect the puck. Make them chase."},
    {id:"u9q59",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading the forechecker's angle",d:3,sit:"You're the D and you pick up the puck in your own corner. The forechecker is coming from your left. Your left winger is up the wall on your left — open, but the forechecker is between you and that pass. Your right winger is also up the wall on the right, completely open. What do you do?",opts:["Force the pass to the left winger — they're your first option immediately","Pass to the right winger — the forechecker has already cut off the left","Carry it out yourself — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Rim it around the boards — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad"],ok:1,why:"Reading the forechecker's angle tells you which options they've taken away. If they're cutting off the left, the right side is the clean exit.",tip:"Forechecker cutting off one side? The other side is your outlet. Read the angle."},
    {id:"u9q60",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Contain without committing",d:3,sit:"A skilled forward is coming at you 1-on-1 at full speed. They're a good stickhandler and have already made two players fall down tonight. What do you avoid doing?",opts:["Backing up and staying patient as fast as you can","Poking check from maximum distance or charging them","Angling them toward the boards as fast as you can","Waiting for their first move before reacting hard now"],ok:1,why:"A skilled stickhandler wants you to commit early — a premature poke check gives them exactly the step they need to blow past you. Stay patient and contained.",tip:"Skilled forward 1-on-1? Don't commit early. Stay patient. Make them decide first."},
    {id:"u9q61",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Back pass under pressure",d:3,sit:"You have the puck at the offensive blue line. A defender is closing hard from your right. Your center is open five feet behind you. Your only shooting lane is gone. What do you do?",opts:["Try to hold the puck and fight through the pressure as fast as you can hard","Drop a back pass to your center — they have time and space and you don't","Shoot into the defender — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a","Dump the puck to the corner — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"When your shooting lane is gone and a player is closing fast, a back pass to a player with time and space is the right play. Don't force the situation — solve it.",tip:"Shooting lane gone with pressure coming? Drop it back. Someone behind you has time."},
    {id:"u9q62",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F"],concept:"Read the goalie pre-shot",d:3,sit:"You're about to shoot from the slot. Before you release, you have a split second to look at the goalie. They're leaning hard to your right. Where should you shoot?",opts:["Top right — over their shoulder on the side they're leaning — that's a bad read","Low left — the opposite side of where they're leaning. They can't recover in time.","Right at them — power wins — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Wait for them to reset before shooting — you'll figure the rest out later right"],ok:1,why:"Pre-shot reads of the goalie give you a target before you even release. A goalie leaning hard to one side is leaving the other side vulnerable — shoot there.",tip:"Goalie leaning hard one way? Shoot the opposite side. They can't recover in time."},
    {id:"u9q63",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading your linemates",d:3,sit:"You're on a line change. Your linemates are still on the ice finishing a rush. The play is still alive. When do you go on?",opts:["Go immediately — you're fresh and need to help — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read and hope for","Wait until the puck is dead, there's a stoppage, or your teammates are safely at the bench and can't be caught short","Jump on as soon as your teammate steps off the ice, even if they're still in the play and avoid the dangerous area now","Go as soon as you feel like it — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"Taking a too-many-men penalty on a rush because you jumped on too early is a critical mistake. The line change is clean only when the puck is dead or your teammate is safely off.",tip:"Line change during a rush: wait for a stoppage or until your teammate is safely off. Don't jump on early."},
    {id:"u9q64",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Timing the attack",d:3,sit:"Your team just won a puck battle in your own zone. Two of your forwards are already at center ice. The other team has one player back. A 3-on-1 is developing. What's the trigger?",opts:["Wait until all three forwards are in the neutral zone as fast as you can","Go immediately — the 3-on-1 window closes fast as the other team gets back","Regroup at your own blue line — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Dump it in and change lines — you'll figure the rest out later right away now"],ok:1,why:"Transition opportunities close fast. If two forwards are already at center and you have a 3-on-1 developing, going immediately before the other team recovers is how you exploit it.",tip:"Transition chance opening? Go now. Those windows close in seconds."},
    {id:"u9q65",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Reading the pass pre-emptively",d:3,sit:"You're a defenseman in your own zone. The opposing winger has the puck in the corner and keeps looking at the player in the slot. What do you do?",opts:["Watch the puck carrier and wait for the pass to happen as fast as you can now","Step in front of the anticipated pass lane — intercept it before it arrives","Go into the corner to pressure the puck carrier — it's not the right call","Back up to your crease — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad"],ok:1,why:"Reading a puck carrier's eyes tells you where the pass is going. If they keep looking at the slot, get in that lane before the pass is made — not after.",tip:"Puck carrier keeps looking at one spot? Get in that lane. Intercept before the pass arrives."},
    {id:"u9q66",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Neutral zone puck management",d:3,sit:"Your team has the puck in the neutral zone. You're being pressured. The other team has a 2-on-1 developing in your end. You have the puck behind you. What do you do?",opts:["Keep skating toward the offensive zone — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","Recognize the 2-on-1 developing and get the puck to your D immediately so they can deal with the threat now","Dump the puck in and hope for the best — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","Stop and wait for teammates to come back — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right"],ok:1,why:"Reading the play behind you — a developing 2-on-1 — is an important defensive awareness skill. Getting the puck to your D before the 2-on-1 is established gives them a chance to deal with it.",tip:"2-on-1 developing in your end and you have the puck? Get it back to your D. Don't skate forward."},
    {id:"u9q67",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Communicate the switch",d:3,sit:"You're defending in your own zone. An attacker cuts from the left side to the right side in front of the net. Your partner was covering them but now they're on your side. What do you do?",opts:["Ignore them — your partner will follow — you'll figure the rest out later right","Call switch and take the attacker coming to your side so your partner can recover","Call the referee for a penalty — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad now","Back up to the crease and let it happen — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"When an attacker cuts across in front of the net, the defending pair needs to communicate a switch. You take the player coming to your side — your partner recovers.",tip:"Attacker cuts to your side? Call switch and take them. Let your partner recover."},
    {id:"u9q68",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Overload read on offense",d:3,sit:"Your team is in the offensive zone. All three forwards are on the left side of the ice — bunched up. The entire right side is empty. You're the right winger. What do you do?",opts:["Stay on the left side — that's where the puck is — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Move immediately to the right side — the space is there and the D will have to follow you or leave you open","Go to the bench — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call right away","Stand in front of the net — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call now"],ok:1,why:"When everyone goes to the same side, the other side opens up completely. Moving to the open side as the right winger creates an immediate passing option and forces a defensive reaction.",tip:"Everyone bunching up on one side? Go the other way. The space is there."},
    {id:"u9q69",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"PK box integrity",d:3,sit:"Your team is on the penalty kill and in a box formation. The power play moves the puck quickly around the outside. One of your PK players starts chasing every pass. What goes wrong?",opts:["Nothing — chasing is fine on the PK — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the now","Chasing breaks the box — gaps open up and the power play gets into the dangerous areas you were protecting","Chasing tires out the power play — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the","Chasing makes the power play hesitate — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read and hope for"],ok:1,why:"The box on the penalty kill works because every player holds their position and protects the dangerous areas. Chasing every pass breaks the structure and creates gaps the power play exploits.",tip:"PK box: hold your spot. Don't chase every pass. The box works when everyone stays in it."},
    {id:"u9q70",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading the whole ice",d:3,sit:"You're at center ice with the puck. You see a 3-on-2 developing in the offensive zone. One winger is on the left, one is on the right, and a third forward is trailing. Both defenders are inside. What's the read?",opts:["Pass immediately to the left winger — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call right","Look at both defenders first — pass to whichever winger the defenders are leaving more open, or drive the middle if it's open","Shoot from center ice — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best","Dump the puck in and chase — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the"],ok:1,why:"On a 3-on-2, reading both defenders first tells you which option is actually open before you commit. The best puck carrier reads the whole ice, not just one option.",tip:"3-on-2 developing? Read both defenders before picking your option. Don't just default to one side."},
    {id:"u9q71",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F"],concept:"Off the rush shot selection",d:3,sit:"You're the center on a rush. The defenders are both backing up. You're at the top of the circles moving at full speed. You have a shooting lane. What do you do?",opts:["Pass to a winger immediately — always pass first on a rush as fast as you can","Shoot — you're at full speed and the goalie has to set against a moving shooter","Pull up and stickhandle — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read now","Dump the puck in and reset — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad"],ok:1,why:"A moving shooter at full speed at the top of the circles is harder for the goalie to set against than a stationary shooter. Use the speed — shoot.",tip:"Full speed at the circles with a lane? Shoot. Moving shooters are harder to stop."},
    {id:"u9q72",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reverse when both sides blocked",d:3,sit:"Your D picks up the puck. The forechecker is coming from the left. Your left winger is covered. Your right winger is also covered. Your center is late getting back. What's the option?",opts:["Force a pass to a covered winger — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right","Reverse behind the net — the forechecker on the left has to follow, which buys time for the center to get back","Carry it out yourself into the forechecker — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","Shoot it down the ice for icing — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"When all outlets are covered and a forechecker is coming from one side, reversing behind the net forces the forechecker to follow — buying a few seconds for outlets to get open.",tip:"All outlets covered and a forechecker coming? Reverse behind the net. Buy time."},
    {id:"u9q73",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Reading screens",d:3,sit:"Your team is on the penalty kill. A power play player is standing right in front of your goalie screening them. The puck is at the point. What's your immediate priority?",opts:["Go pressure the point player with the puck — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the hard","Move the screener out of the crease — your goalie can't see the shot and that's more dangerous than the shot itself","Stay in a passing lane — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call right away","Back up to the crease yourself — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"A screener blocking your goalie's sightline on the PK is the most dangerous player on the ice. Moving them out is the priority — before the shot is taken.",tip:"Screener blocking your goalie on the PK? Move them out. Your goalie needs to see."},
    {id:"u9q74",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Supporting the shooter",d:3,sit:"Your teammate is about to shoot from the half-wall. The goalie is set. You're the weak-side winger. What should you be doing?",opts:["Staying where you are in case the shot misses wide — you'll figure the rest out later right","Crashing the net hard on the weak side — be there for the rebound before the goalie can cover","Backing up to the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","Calling for a pass instead of the shot — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"The weak-side winger crashing the net on a shot is one of the highest-value plays without the puck. Rebounds bounce weak side — being there before the shot lands is how goals are scored.",tip:"Teammate shooting? Crash the net. Weak-side rebound is your job."},
    {id:"u9q75",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Faceoff strategy",d:3,sit:"Your team wins a faceoff in the offensive zone. The opposing center had to tie the draw. The puck goes back to your defenseman at the point. Before the opposing center gets their bearings, what should you do?",opts:["Wait for the play to develop normally — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the","Drive hard to the net immediately — the opposing center just spent all their energy on the draw and the lane to the net may be briefly open","Skate to the corner — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best and see what hard","Call for a pass from the point — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best hard"],ok:1,why:"Winning a faceoff in the offensive zone creates a split-second window where the opposing center is off-balance. Driving hard to the net immediately exploits that window before they recover.",tip:"Win the OZ faceoff? Drive the net immediately. The center just fought the draw — they're recovering."},
    {id:"u9q76",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck to right player",d:3,sit:"You have the puck in the offensive zone. Two teammates are available — one is at the half-wall with a clear shot lane, and one is right in front of the net with no lane but good positioning. Which do you pass to?",opts:["The one in front of the net — they're in the best scoring position as fast as you can","The one at the half-wall — they have the open lane right now and can shoot immediately","Hold the puck yourself — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right","Pass back to the point — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away"],ok:1,why:"The immediate open lane wins over the better position without a lane. The half-wall player can shoot right now — the net-front player would need to receive, control, and find a lane. Open lane first.",tip:"Two options — one with a lane, one without? Give it to the one who can shoot right now."},
    {id:"u9q77",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defensive zone rotation",d:3,sit:"Your team is in the defensive zone. The puck goes from the corner to the half-wall. As the nearest forward, you move to pressure the half-wall player. Who covers your corner assignment?",opts:["Nobody — you handle both — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad now","Your D partner rotates to cover the corner behind you — that's the rotation","Your winger on the other side skates across and trust the play to develop","You stay in both spots somehow — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"When a forward pressures the half-wall, the D partner behind them rotates to cover the area the forward left. This is how defensive zone rotations work — everyone shifts together.",tip:"You go pressure the half-wall? Your D rotates behind you to cover. Everyone shifts."},
    {id:"u9q78",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Rush gap management",d:3,sit:"Three attackers are rushing at your two defensemen. All three attackers are at top speed. What's the biggest mistake a defenseman can make here?",opts:["Backing up too fast — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right","Pinching up — closing aggressively on the puck carrier at the offensive zone instead of backing up","Staying in the middle of the ice — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","Talking to their partner — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the"],ok:1,why:"Pinching up against a fast rush hands the attacking team a massive speed advantage. Backing up at the right pace — not too fast, not too slow — is the correct response to a rush with speed.",tip:"Rush coming with speed? Back up controlled. Never pinch up against a fast rush."},
    {id:"u9q79",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Timing your break",d:3,sit:"Your team is under heavy forecheck pressure in your own zone. Your D has the puck and is looking to pass. You're a winger and you're currently covered. When should you break to the wall to get the pass?",opts:["Stay where you are — the D will figure it out — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","Skate to the wall hard, using your speed to lose the forechecker for a split second — make the D's decision easy","Don't break until the forechecker is gone — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the now","Stay still and call for the puck — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"Creating separation from your forechecker — even for a split second — is how you get open. Skate hard to the wall to create the separation that makes the pass possible.",tip:"Covered on the breakout? Skate hard to create separation. Make yourself open."},
    {id:"u9q80",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"High danger vs. safe play",d:3,sit:"You have the puck in the offensive zone. You can shoot from where you are — a decent but not great angle. OR you can pass to a teammate in the slot who's slightly covered but would have a much better shot. What do you do?",opts:["Shoot — you have the puck and a shot — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad","Pass to the slot player — the higher danger location is worth the slight coverage risk","Hold the puck and wait — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right","Pass back to the point — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away"],ok:1,why:"A slightly covered player in the slot still represents a higher-danger chance than a clean shot from a poor angle. The math of chance quality favors the slot, even with some risk.",tip:"OK angle vs. slightly covered slot? The slot wins. Higher danger is worth the risk."},
    {id:"u9q81",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F"],concept:"One-touch in stride",d:3,sit:"You're breaking into the offensive zone with speed and a pass is coming to you in stride. The goalie is set in the middle of the net. You have a half-second. What's the best play?",opts:["Stop the puck and look for a pass — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right","One-time it low blocker side — the goalie hasn't moved yet and a one-touch in stride catches them off-balance","Stickhandle to slow down and aim — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right","Pass across to a winger — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"A one-touch shot in stride catches the goalie before they can set against a stationary shooter. Stopping the puck gives the goalie time to adjust.",tip:"Pass coming to you in stride with a lane? One-time it. Don't stop the puck."},
    {id:"u9q82",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Loose puck in own zone",d:3,sit:"There's a loose puck in your defensive zone right in front of your net. You and an opposing player are racing to it at the same time. What's your priority?",opts:["Get to the puck first and try to skate it out — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right","Get your body between the opponent and the puck — inside position wins this battle even if you get there second","Poke it with your stick from distance — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the","Call for your goalie to come get it — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the"],ok:1,why:"Inside position on a loose puck in front of your own net wins the battle even if you get there a step late. Body between opponent and puck — that's the priority.",tip:"Loose puck in your own zone? Get inside position. Body between opponent and puck."},
    {id:"u9q83",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Power play entry",d:3,sit:"Your team is on the power play trying to enter the offensive zone. The penalty killers are set at their blue line — two of them. How should your team attack?",opts:["Carry it in straight — you have the extra man — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read hard","Use the extra man advantage: hold the puck until one PK player commits, then exploit what they've given up","Dump the puck in and chase — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call","Skate back and regroup continuously — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the"],ok:1,why:"The extra man on the power play means someone is always open. Don't just carry into a set defense — hold until a PK player commits, then move the puck to who they left open.",tip:"PP zone entry vs. set PK: hold until they commit. Then use the extra man."},
    {id:"u9q84",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Off-puck movement",d:3,sit:"The puck carrier has the puck in the offensive zone but is being smothered by defenders. You don't have the puck and a defender is near you. What's the best thing you can do?",opts:["Stand still and call for the puck — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the","Skate into open space — cut to the net, move to a seam. Make yourself available AND drag your defender out of the puck carrier's area.","Go help the puck carrier in the battle — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for","Skate to the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best right away"],ok:1,why:"Off-puck movement does two things: it makes you available for a pass and it drags your defender away from the puck carrier — creating more space for them.",tip:"Puck carrier in trouble? Move without the puck. Create space for them by dragging your defender away."},
    {id:"u9q85",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"PK breakout under pressure",d:3,sit:"Your penalty kill clears the puck down the ice. Icing is called and the faceoff comes back to your defensive zone. Your two PK players are tired. What matters most before the next faceoff?",opts:["Change lines immediately even if it causes confusion — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the now","Get your two best faceoff players and PK coverage players out — fresh legs and the right assignments matter more than speed","Stay out — the familiar lineup is better — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call","Send out the power play line instead — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call hard"],ok:1,why:"A faceoff after an icing on the PK is a chance to reset with the right personnel. Getting the right PK players and faceoff specialist on the ice matters more than rushing.",tip:"PK icing faceoff? Get the right players out. Fresh legs and right assignments."},
    {id:"u9q86",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Read the rush before it happens",d:3,sit:"You're in the offensive zone and the puck is about to turn over. Before it does, where should you already be moving?",opts:["Stay put — wait to see if the turnover actually happens — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a","Start transitioning early — turn toward your own zone before the turnover is complete. Get a head start.","Skate to the bench — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call","Go to the corner — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call hard"],ok:1,why:"The best backcheckers start their transition before the puck has fully changed hands. Reading that a turnover is about to happen and moving early gives you a huge head start.",tip:"Turnover about to happen? Start moving early. Get a head start on the backcheck."},
    {id:"u9q87",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Passing into traffic",d:3,sit:"You have the puck in the offensive zone. A teammate is in the slot but a defender is between you and them. You can see a sliver of the teammate. What do you do?",opts:["Force the pass through the defender — your teammate is in the slot — you'll figure the rest out later","Find a better option — a covered pass through a defender is high-risk. Look for the winger or the point.","Hold the puck — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call right away","Shoot from where you are — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"A pass through a defender risks a turnover and an immediate counter-attack. If a defender is between you and your target, find a different option — the pass isn't open.",tip:"Defender in your passing lane? Find a different option. A blocked pass is a turnover."},
    {id:"u9q88",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D pinching decision",d:3,sit:"You're the defenseman at the offensive blue line. Your winger just gained possession in the corner. Should you pinch to join the attack below the dots?",opts:["Yes — always get involved in the attack — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read and hope for","Only if the other winger or center is positioned to cover the blue line behind you — otherwise hold the line","Yes — pinch every time your winger gets the puck — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","No — never pinch under any circumstances — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away now"],ok:1,why:"Pinching is right only when someone is positioned behind you to cover the blue line. Pinching without coverage gives up a breakout against you if the puck turns over.",tip:"Want to pinch? Make sure someone covers the line behind you first. Then go."},
    {id:"u9q89",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Box in the neutral zone",d:3,sit:"The other team is trying to enter your zone 4-on-4. Your team has set up in the neutral zone with all four players between the puck and your net. The puck carrier is coming at you. What's the key to making this work?",opts:["Everyone chase the puck carrier at the same time — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away now","Hold your positions and make the puck carrier make a decision — force them one way and take away the easiest options","All four players back up to your blue line immediately — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read hard","One player challenges while three retreat all the way — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right"],ok:1,why:"A neutral zone defensive structure works when everyone holds their lane and forces the puck carrier into a decision. If everyone chases, the structure collapses.",tip:"Neutral zone defense: hold your lane. Force the puck carrier to decide. Don't all chase."},
    {id:"u9q90",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Faceoff assignment win",d:3,sit:"Your team wins a faceoff in the neutral zone and the puck goes back to your defenseman. You're the center — you just took the faceoff. What do you do now?",opts:["Stand and watch what your D does with it — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best and see what happens next right away","Transition immediately to your assignment — if you won the draw, get to your position in the rush development. The faceoff result gives your team the advantage if everyone executes.","Go to the bench — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best and see what happens next — the puck will sort itself out","Celebrate winning the draw — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best and see what happens next — the puck will sort"],ok:1,why:"Winning a faceoff is just the start — executing the assignment immediately after is what turns a faceoff win into a scoring chance. The center transitions to their rush role.",tip:"Win the faceoff? Execute your next assignment immediately. Don't watch — go."},
    {id:"u9q91",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F"],concept:"Tip drill",d:3,sit:"A shot comes from the blue line. You're standing in front of the net. The puck is coming at the middle of the net right at the goalie. What's your job?",opts:["Get out of the way — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call right","Tip the puck — even a slight redirection completely changes the trajectory and defeats the goalie's","Call for it to go wide — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call hard","Skate away from the crease — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"Tipping a shot on net is one of the most effective plays in hockey. Even a small deflection changes the trajectory enough to beat a goalie who is tracking the original shot.",tip:"Shot coming from the point right at the goalie? Tip it. Any deflection beats their tracking."},
    {id:"u9q92",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Simple first",d:3,sit:"You have the puck in your own zone under pressure. You have two options: a tricky cross-ice pass to a teammate at the blue line, or a simple short pass to your D partner three feet away. Which do you take?",opts:["The tricky cross-ice pass — it leads to a faster breakout — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read and hope for","The simple short pass to your D partner — take the safe option under pressure and let them move the puck from a better position","Try to carry it yourself — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best","Wait for a better option to appear — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call right away now"],ok:1,why:"Under pressure in your own zone, the simple play is almost always right. A tricky cross-ice pass into pressure risks a turnover in the worst possible area.",tip:"Two options under pressure? Take the simple one. Safe pass first, then build."},
    {id:"u9q93",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defensive zone triangle",d:3,sit:"Your team is defending in your own zone. The puck is in the far corner. The other team has three attackers in the zone and you have two defenders and one forward back. Where should the forward position?",opts:["Go into the corner to help your partner — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read now","Hold the high slot — be between the corner player and the open attackers in the high-danger area","Go to the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right","Follow the nearest attacker everywhere — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"With three attackers in the zone and only three defenders, the forward holds the high slot to take away the most dangerous pass options. Going to the corner leaves the front of the net completely open.",tip:"Three attackers, you're the lone forward back? Hold the high slot. Don't go to the corner."},
    {id:"u9q94",cat:"Defense",pos:["D"],concept:"Prevent the second shot",d:3,sit:"The other team takes a shot and your goalie makes the save. The rebound goes to the corner. An opposing player is racing to it. What do you do?",opts:["Watch to see if your goalie covers it — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the","Get to the rebound before the opposing player — or at least get your body position between them and the puck","Call for your goalie to come out — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right","Back up to the crease — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call hard"],ok:1,why:"Beating the opposing player to the rebound — or at minimum getting inside position — prevents the second shot. Letting them get a clean rebound in the corner means a second chance against you.",tip:"Rebound in the corner? Race to it or get inside position. Prevent the second shot."},
    {id:"u9q95",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout communication",d:3,sit:"Your D picks up the puck in your own corner. They're looking up but they can't see behind them. Your winger is open up the wall but a forechecker is about to close on them from the blind side. What do you do?",opts:["Say nothing — the D will figure it out — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad","Call out 'man on!' or tell the winger to hold — give the information that only you can see","Skate over to get between the forechecker and the winger — the puck will sort itself out now","Call for the pass yourself — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right"],ok:1,why:"You can see something neither the D nor the winger can see. That information is valuable — communicating it immediately makes the play better.",tip:"You see something others can't? Say it loud and fast. That's your job."},
    {id:"u9q96",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Attack after the clear",d:3,sit:"Your penalty kill clears the puck all the way into the other team's zone. You're the first PK player over the other team's blue line. What do you do?",opts:["Slow down — it's probably just going to come back — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read and hope for","Attack hard — a PK icing or clear can become a shorthanded chance if you pursue it aggressively. Speed wins that race.","Go to the bench for a line change — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call","Wait for your teammate to come with you — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"A PK clear that gets into the other team's zone is a chance for a shorthanded goal if you pursue aggressively. The other team is coming back for it — getting there first wins the race.",tip:"PK clear going deep? Attack it. Speed wins the race and shorthanded goals are game-changers."},
    {id:"u9q97",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Win the possession battle",d:3,sit:"Your team has been hemmed in your own zone for 45 seconds. Your D picks up the puck. Before they do anything else, what's the single most important question they should answer?",opts:["What's the score? — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right away","Which outlet is actually open — not which one I want to use, but which one is actually free?","Where is the nearest bench? — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","What did the coach say before the game? — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad"],ok:1,why:"Under pressure after a long zone time, the temptation is to default to a favorite outlet. But reading which option is actually open — not which one you want — is what leads to a clean exit.",tip:"Long zone time, D finally has the puck? Read what's actually open. Don't default."},
    {id:"u9q98",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck tracker vs. player",d:3,sit:"You're defending in your own zone. The puck is in the corner behind your net. Your assignment is an attacker near the half-wall on the opposite side. The puck is far away from them. Do you watch the puck or watch your man?",opts:["Watch the puck — it's more important to know where the puck is — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Watch your man — keep them in front of you so you know when they move. You can track the puck with your peripheral vision.","Watch both equally — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best","Go get the puck yourself — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the"],ok:1,why:"In man coverage, losing sight of your assignment is how they get open for a pass. Keep them in front of you and use your peripheral vision for the puck.",tip:"Man coverage in your own zone: watch your man, not the puck. Use your peripheral vision for the puck."},
    {id:"u9q99",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Line change awareness",d:3,sit:"You're playing hard in the offensive zone on a long shift. The puck turns over and the other team is breaking out. Your legs are tired. What's the responsible play?",opts:["Push through — the play needs you — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right","If you can't backcheck at full speed, get off and get a fresh player on. A tired player is worse than no player.","Slow jog back — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the now","Call for the other team to stop — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"A tired player who can't backcheck at full speed is a liability, not an asset. The responsible play is to get off the ice and get a fresh player in who can actually defend.",tip:"Legs gone and the other team is breaking out? Get off. Fresh player is better than a tired one."},
    {id:"u9q100",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Read the whole play",d:3,sit:"You have the puck at center ice. Three options: your winger is open on the left but a defender is closing on them. Your center is open in the slot with a clear lane. Your D is open at the blue line on the right. What do you do?",opts:["Pass to the winger on the left — they were first in your vision no matter what happens","Pass to the center in the slot — open lane, dangerous position, immediate scoring threat","Pass to the D on the right — they're the safest option — the puck will sort itself out","Carry it yourself — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the now"],ok:1,why:"Reading all three options before picking tells you the center in the slot with a clear lane is the best play. The winger has a closing defender and the D is the safest but least dangerous option. Best chance wins.",tip:"Multiple options? Read all of them before you pick. The open slot beats everything else here."},
  ,
    {id:"u9g1",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Angle basics",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"A forward is coming at you on a breakaway. You're standing on your goal line. What should you do with your position?",opts:["Stay on the goal line — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read now","Skate out toward the shooter to cut the angle — give them less net to shoot at","Skate all the way out to the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later","Lie down on the ice immediately — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"Coming out toward the shooter cuts down the angle — the shooter sees less net. A goalie who stays on the goal line gives the shooter a huge target. Move out and take space away.",tip:"Come out toward the shooter. Take away the angle. Give them less net."},
    {id:"u9g2",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Reading the 2-on-1",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"Two attackers are coming at your lone defenseman on a 2-on-1. The puck carrier has the puck. What's the goalie's job?",opts:["Skate out to challenge the puck carrier — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the","Stay in your crease, be ready for a shot, and watch for the pass — the D takes away the pass, you take the shot","Yell at your D to do something — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call","Come out past the crease — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call hard"],ok:1,why:"On a 2-on-1, the defender takes away the pass and the goalie takes the shot. The goalie stays set in the crease and is ready for either — but primarily prepared for the shot.",tip:"2-on-1: your D takes the pass, you take the shot. Stay set and read it."},
    {id:"u9g3",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Butterfly basics",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"A shot is coming low along the ice. What's the most effective way to stop it?",opts:["Try to kick it with one foot — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right","Drop into butterfly position — both knees down, pads flared out to cover the bottom of the","Fall sideways — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call","Stand still and hope it hits you — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read hard"],ok:1,why:"The butterfly position drops both pads to the ice and covers the bottom of the net effectively. Low shots along the ice are best stopped this way.",tip:"Low shot coming? Butterfly. Pads down, cover the bottom of the net."},
    {id:"u9g4",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Rebound control",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"You make a save but you can direct where the rebound goes. Where should you try to send it?",opts:["Straight back into the slot as fast as you can","Into the corner where your team can retrieve it","Over the boards out of play as fast as you can","Anywhere away from the net as fast as you can now"],ok:1,why:"Directing rebounds to the corner keeps the puck away from the most dangerous area — the slot. Your team can retrieve it in the corner and start a breakout.",tip:"Control your rebounds. Aim for the corners, not the middle."},
    {id:"u9g5",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Screen handling",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"A player from the other team is standing right in front of you, blocking your view of a point shot. The puck is about to be shot. What do you do?",opts:["Give up — you can't see — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","Move laterally to try to find a sightline, and be ready to react to tips and deflections","Skate into the screener — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","Call for your teammates and wait — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"Screeners are a real problem but not impossible. Moving slightly helps you find the puck, and being ready for a deflection means you're not just frozen behind the screen.",tip:"Screener in front? Move to find the puck. Expect a tip. React."},
    {id:"u9g6",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Puck handling",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck comes behind your net. Your winger is coming back to get it but they're a second away. You can get there first. Should you play it?",opts:["Never touch the puck — it's too risky — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the","Yes — if you can get there first and your winger is a step away, stop it for them so they have a clean pickup","Only if the other team isn't coming — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the","Kick it with your skate — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"Goalies who can handle the puck are a huge asset. If you can get to it first and stop it for your winger, you've started the breakout and taken pressure off your defense.",tip:"Comfortable behind the net? Play it. Stop it for your winger. Be an extra D."},
    {id:"u9g7",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Breakaway read",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"A player is on a breakaway coming straight at you. They're moving fast. When should you commit to going down?",opts:["Right away — drop immediately — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","Wait until they've made their move — commit when you see what they're going to do, not before","Never go down — always stay up — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","As soon as they cross the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"The goalie who commits too early loses. A patient goalie who waits for the shooter's move before committing forces the shooter to beat them rather than just beat the commit.",tip:"Breakaway: be patient. Make them show you something first. Then commit."},
    {id:"u9g8",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Post awareness",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is in the corner to your left. An attacker has it but hasn't shot. Where should you be in your net?",opts:["In the middle of the net and hope for the best","Touching the left post — take away the near side","All the way to the right post as fast as you can","Out of the crease and avoid the dangerous area now"],ok:1,why:"When the puck is in the corner, the goalie moves to the near post. This takes away the short side — the most dangerous option for that angle. The long side is much harder to score from.",tip:"Puck in the corner? Move to the near post. Take away the short side."},
    {id:"u9g9",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Communication — mine",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is bouncing in the crease area and both you and your defenseman are going for it. What should you say?",opts:["Nothing — just grab it — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Yell 'Mine!' loud and clear so your defenseman knows to get out of the way","Tap them on the shoulder — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad","Wait until after the play to figure it out and trust the play to develop"],ok:1,why:"'Mine!' is one of the most important calls in hockey. It tells your defender to clear out and lets you take control of the puck without a collision or confusion.",tip:"'Mine!' — say it loud and say it early. Own your crease."},
    {id:"u9g10",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Tracking through traffic",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"Three players from both teams are battling in front of your net. Sticks and bodies everywhere. The puck is somewhere in the mess. What's your priority?",opts:["Watch the bodies — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call","Keep your eyes moving — track the puck through the traffic. Move with the puck, not with the players.","Wait for the puck to emerge — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the","Drop immediately into butterfly — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read and hope for"],ok:1,why:"Traffic in front is the hardest goalie situation. The key is to track the puck through the bodies, not get distracted by movement. The puck is what can score — bodies can't.",tip:"Traffic in front? Track the puck, not the bodies. The puck tells you everything."},
    {id:"u9g11",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Backdoor coverage",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is on the half-wall. You're set on the post. A player cuts to the back door completely open on the far side. What do you do?",opts:["Stay on your post — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the","Quickly push across to take away the back-door pass — your near post is less dangerous now","Skate out toward the puck — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read right away","Stay completely still — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read and hope for"],ok:1,why:"A back-door pass to an open player is one of the highest-danger plays in hockey. When you see the cut, you have to push across quickly to take away that option — the shooter at the half-wall is less dangerous than an open player at the back post.",tip:"Back-door cut? Push across. The post can wait — the open player is the emergency."},
    {id:"u9g12",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Freeze or play — decision",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"You make a save and the puck is loose right in front of you. Two opposing players are about to get to it before your team. Should you cover it or try to play it?",opts:["Always cover it — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best","Read the situation — if two opponents are about to get it, cover it immediately. If your team has it, leave it for them.","Always leave it for your team — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call right away","Kick it away — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best right away"],ok:1,why:"The decision to freeze or play is a real read. If opponents are about to get to a dangerous rebound, cover it. If your team has control, leaving it lets them start the breakout faster.",tip:"Freeze or play? Read who's going to get it. Cover when opponents are closest."},
    {id:"u9g13",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Shooter body language",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"A shooter is coming at you. You notice their shoulder is turned slightly toward the left side of the net before they shoot. What does this tell you?",opts:["Nothing — ignore it — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call right away now","They're likely shooting to your right — their body is opening to the left which usually means the shot goes right","They're going to deke — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call right away","They'll pass — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the"],ok:1,why:"Reading a shooter's body language — especially shoulder position — is an advanced skill that top goalies develop. A shoulder turning left often means the shot goes right because the body follows the shot direction.",tip:"Read the shooter's shoulders and hips before they release. They tell you where it's going."},
    {id:"u9g14",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Desperation save",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"You're down and out of position — the shooter has a completely open net. You can't get back to your feet in time. What do you do?",opts:["Give up — it's a goal — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best and see what happens","Use whatever you can reach — your stick, your glove, your skate — to get something in the way. Any part of you in the lane is better than nothing.","Stay still — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best and see what happens next hard","Call for help — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call and hope for the best and see what happens next"],ok:1,why:"Desperation saves are real. Even if you're out of position, getting any part of your body or equipment into the shooting lane can change a goal into a save. Never stop until the whistle.",tip:"Out of position? Reach for it anyway. Desperate saves happen. Never quit."},
    {id:"u9g15",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Post-to-post movement",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck moves quickly from the left corner to the right corner. You were on your left post. What's the fastest way to get to the right post?",opts:["Skate slowly across the crease — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right","Push off the left post and use a strong T-push or shuffle across — keep your eyes on the puck the whole time","Turn around and skate — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the right call hard now","Stay on the left post — it's too far — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read — it's not the"],ok:1,why:"A T-push off the post is the fastest way for a goalie to move across the crease. You push with your post foot and slide across, keeping your eyes on the puck.",tip:"Post-to-post: T-push off the near post. Stay low, eyes on puck. It's a race."},

    // === SEQUENCE ORDERING QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u9seq1",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout basics",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"Your team's goalie stops the puck. Put the basic breakout steps in order.",items:["Goalie leaves the puck for the defenseman or makes a short pass","Wings skate to their lanes along the boards","D picks up the puck and looks up for an option","D passes to the open winger and the team moves up ice"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"A breakout starts with the goalie, then wings get open, D retrieves and reads, then makes the pass. Everybody has a job and the order matters.",tip:"Breakout: goalie starts it, wings get open, D reads, pass and go."},
    {id:"u9seq2",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Shot sequence",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"You receive a pass in the offensive zone. Put the steps for taking a good shot in order.",items:["Receive the pass and control the puck","Get your head up and pick your target","Get the puck into shooting position on your stick","Release the shot at the target"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"A good shot starts with a clean reception. Then you look where to shoot, get the puck ready, and release. Rushing past the target-picking step means you're just throwing it at the net.",tip:"Catch it clean, pick your spot, set it up, let it go. Good shots follow a sequence."},
    {id:"u9seq3",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defending a 2-on-1",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"You're the lone defender on a 2-on-1 rush. Put your defensive steps in order.",items:["Skate backward and get between the two attackers","Take away the pass by positioning your stick in the passing lane","Force the puck carrier to the outside","Trust your goalie to handle the shot"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"On a 2-on-1, the defender's job is to take away the pass and force a shot. Get position, stick in the lane, steer the shooter wide, and let the goalie do their job.",tip:"2-on-1 defense: get between, take the pass away, force wide, trust your goalie."},
    {id:"u9seq4",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Offensive transition",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"Your team just intercepted a pass in your own zone. Put the transition to offense in order.",items:["Recognize you have the puck — transition starts now","Puck carrier looks up for options","Forwards sprint up ice to create passing lanes","Pass ahead to a forward with speed through the neutral zone"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"Fast transitions catch the other team off guard. The moment you get the puck, everyone's job changes — recognize it, read options, create lanes, and move the puck quickly.",tip:"Got the puck? Transition now. Forwards go. Move it fast while they're caught flat."},
    {id:"u9seq5",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Offensive zone positioning",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"Your team enters the offensive zone with the puck. Put the positioning steps in order.",items:["Puck carrier drives wide or deep","One forward goes to the net for screens and rebounds","Third forward supports high — near the top of the circles","Defensemen hold the blue line and keep the puck in"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"Good offensive zone structure means everyone has a role. Puck goes deep, someone covers the net, someone supports high, and D hold the line. Structure creates chances.",tip:"In the O-zone: puck deep, player at the net, support high, D on the line. Structure."},
    {id:"u9seq6",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Helping a teammate in trouble",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"Your teammate has the puck along the boards and two opponents are closing on them. Put the support steps in order.",items:["See that your teammate is in trouble","Skate toward them and get open for a pass","Call out 'I'm here!' so they know you're an option","Be ready to receive the puck and make a quick play"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"Good teammates read when someone needs help. See the trouble, get open, communicate, and be ready. That sequence turns a bad situation into a clean play.",tip:"Teammate in trouble? See it, get open, call for it, be ready. That's support."},
    {id:"u9seq7",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Zone entry decision",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"You're carrying the puck through the neutral zone toward the offensive blue line. Put your decision-making steps in order.",items:["Read the defender's position at the blue line","Check if teammates are available for a pass","Decide: carry it in, pass it in, or dump and chase","Execute your choice with speed and commitment"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"Zone entry is a read, not a guess. Read the D, check your options, pick the best one, and commit. Players who don't read first make bad entries.",tip:"At the blue line: read, check options, decide, commit. Don't guess — read."},
    {id:"u9seq8",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Penalty kill positioning",d:3,type:"seq",sit:"The other team gets a power play. Put your PK steps in order.",items:["Get into your box formation as the puck enters the zone","Stay in your zone — cover passing lanes, not players","Pressure the puck when it comes to your side of the box","Clear the puck out of the zone when you get the chance"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"The penalty kill is about structure and discipline. Get in the box, stay in your zone, pressure when it's your turn, and clear when you can. Chasing kills the PK.",tip:"PK: box up, stay in your zone, pressure your side, clear when you can."},

    // === SPOT THE MISTAKE QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u9mis1",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Slow transition back",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"Your team loses the puck at the other team's blue line. Two of your forwards keep skating toward the other team's net instead of turning back. The other team rushes 3-on-2. What's the mistake?",opts:["The defensemen were too deep","The forwards didn't transition back — when your team loses the puck, everyone turns around immediately. Staying in the offensive zone creates an odd-man rush against you.","The goalie should have come out","The coach should have called timeout"],ok:1,why:"Transition is instant. The moment the puck changes hands, your forwards must get back. Lingering in the offensive zone after a turnover gives the other team a numbers advantage.",tip:"Lost the puck? Turn around. Now. Every forward, every time."},
    {id:"u9mis2",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Fancy deke instead of shooting",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"You're in close to the net with a clear shot. Instead of shooting, you try a fancy deke move you saw on TV. You lose the puck. What's the mistake?",opts:["Your deke wasn't good enough","You had an open shot and didn't take it — when you have a clear look at the net, shoot. Trying to be fancy when a simple shot works is how you waste chances.","You should have passed","The goalie was too good"],ok:1,why:"A clear shot from close range is one of the best chances in hockey. Taking it is almost always better than trying something fancy. Shoot when you can score.",tip:"Clear shot? Take it. Don't try to be highlight-reel when simple works."},
    {id:"u9mis3",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Cherry picking",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"One of your teammates stays at center ice while the rest of the team is defending in your own zone. They're waiting for a long pass. Your team is defending 4 against 5. What's the mistake?",opts:["They're being smart and waiting for a breakaway","They're cherry picking — not helping on defense. Everyone needs to defend when the puck is in your zone. Hanging back leaves your team short-handed.","The coach told them to stay","They're too tired to skate back"],ok:1,why:"Cherry picking leaves your team playing 4-on-5 in the defensive zone. Even if you get the odd breakaway, the goals you give up from being short a player far outweigh it.",tip:"Everyone defends. No cherry picking. Help your team first, then attack together."},
    {id:"u9mis4",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Panic clearing",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"Your defenseman gets the puck behind your net. Under pressure, they blindly shoot it up the middle of the ice. An opposing player intercepts it at your blue line and scores. What's the mistake?",opts:["The D wasn't fast enough","They made a blind pass up the middle — under pressure, the safe play is the boards. Passing up the middle without looking is the most dangerous turnover in hockey.","The other players didn't call for it","The goalie should have played it"],ok:1,why:"A blind pass up the middle of the ice in your own zone is extremely dangerous. The safe play under pressure is always the boards — rim it out, chip it off the glass, or find a winger on the wall.",tip:"Under pressure in your zone? Use the boards. Never throw it up the middle blind."},
    {id:"u9mis5",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Holding the puck too long",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"Your center picks up the puck and skates through the neutral zone. Three teammates are open for passes. Instead, they hold the puck until two defenders close on them and strip it away. What's the mistake?",opts:["They should have skated faster","They held the puck too long — with three open teammates, making a pass early creates a much better play than trying to carry through traffic. Read and move the puck.","Their teammates weren't calling for it","The defenders got lucky"],ok:1,why:"Holding the puck when teammates are open is a common mistake. The puck moves faster than any skater. Making the pass early when options are available keeps the play moving.",tip:"Open teammates? Move the puck. The puck is always faster than your skates."},
    {id:"u9mis6",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck watching in the D-zone",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"In the defensive zone, your winger watches the puck on the other side of the ice. Meanwhile, the player they should be covering sneaks behind them and gets a wide-open pass for a goal. What's the mistake?",opts:["The goalie should have saved it","The winger was puck watching instead of covering their player — in the D-zone, you need to know where your player is at all times, not just stare at the puck","The defenseman should have helped","The pass was too good to stop"],ok:1,why:"Puck watching in the defensive zone is one of the most common mistakes. You need to track both the puck and your man. If you lose your man, they get open for an easy chance.",tip:"D-zone: know where your man is. Watch the puck AND your check. Lose your man, lose the game."},
    {id:"u9mis7",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Not talking on ice",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"Your teammate has the puck behind the net. A forechecker is coming hard from the left. Your teammate can't see them. Nobody on your team says anything. Your teammate gets hit and loses the puck. What's the mistake?",opts:["The teammate should have eyes in the back of their head","Nobody communicated — someone should have yelled 'man on left!' to warn their teammate about the pressure coming. Communication prevents turnovers.","The forechecker was too fast","The teammate should have passed sooner"],ok:1,why:"Communication saves possession. A simple 'man on!' call gives your teammate time to protect the puck or make a play. Silent teams give up easy turnovers.",tip:"See pressure coming at a teammate? Call it out. 'Man on!' saves the play."},
    {id:"u9mis8",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Offside trap",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"Your team is entering the offensive zone. The puck carrier slows down at the blue line, but two teammates have already crossed into the zone ahead of the puck. The whistle blows for offside. What's the mistake?",opts:["The puck carrier was too slow","The two teammates entered the zone before the puck — the puck must cross the blue line first. Players without the puck need to time their entry and stay onside.","The ref made a bad call","The blue line is confusing"],ok:1,why:"Offside kills momentum and gives the puck away. Players entering the zone need to watch the puck carrier and time their entry so the puck crosses the line first.",tip:"Entering the zone? Watch the puck. Don't cross the line until it does. Stay onside."},

    // === WHAT HAPPENS NEXT QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u9next1",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Goalie out of position",d:2,type:"next",sit:"You're in the slot with the puck. The goalie just made a save on the other side and is sliding back. They're not set yet. You have a clear look at the open side of the net. What happens next?",opts:["You wait for the goalie to get set","You pass to a teammate","You shoot immediately at the open side — the goalie is out of position and you have the net to shoot at","You skate closer first"],ok:2,why:"When a goalie is out of position and you have a clear look, shoot immediately. Every fraction of a second you wait is a fraction they use to recover. Quick release scores.",tip:"Goalie moving and you have the open side? Shoot now. Don't wait. They're recovering."},
    {id:"u9next2",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Turnover at their blue line",d:2,type:"next",sit:"The other team tries to clear the puck out of their zone but your defenseman intercepts it at their blue line. Their forwards are all deep in their zone. What happens next?",opts:["Your D shoots from the blue line immediately","Your D passes to a forward who's driving the net — their team is caught deep and your forwards should be attacking with speed","Your D passes it back to your goalie","Everyone stops and regroups"],ok:1,why:"An interception at the blue line with the other team caught deep is a prime scoring chance. Get the puck to a forward driving the net before they can recover their positions.",tip:"Interception at their blue line? Attack fast. Get it to the forwards. They're caught."},
    {id:"u9next3",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakaway developing",d:2,type:"next",sit:"An opposing forward gets past your defensemen and has a clear path to your net. You're the closest forward and you're behind them but skating hard. You can't catch them. What happens next?",opts:["You give up — they're gone","You keep skating hard and try to get your stick in the shooting lane — even a stick in the lane can disrupt the shot or force a wider angle","You yell at your defensemen","You coast back slowly"],ok:1,why:"Even if you can't catch the breakaway, closing the gap and getting your stick in the lane can disrupt the shot, force a bad angle, or make the shooter rush. Never stop chasing.",tip:"Can't catch the breakaway? Get your stick in the lane anyway. Every bit of pressure helps."},
    {id:"u9next4",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Screen in front",d:2,type:"next",sit:"You have the puck at the point. Two of your teammates are standing in front of the goalie, blocking their view. The goalie can't see you. What happens next?",opts:["You pass to the corner","You shoot through the screen — the goalie can't see the puck, so even a low shot through traffic has a great chance of going in or creating a rebound","You skate in closer","You wait for a better passing lane"],ok:1,why:"A shot through a screen is one of the most effective plays in hockey. The goalie can't track what they can't see. Low shots through traffic create goals and rebounds.",tip:"Teammates screening the goalie? Shoot low through the traffic. They can't stop what they can't see."},
    {id:"u9next5",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout under pressure",d:2,type:"next",sit:"Your D has the puck behind the net. Two forecheckers are coming from both sides. Your center is open in the middle of the ice, but the middle is risky. Your winger is on the wall. What happens next?",opts:["D tries to carry it out alone","D makes the safe play and passes to the winger on the wall — the middle is too risky with two forecheckers closing, and the boards are the safe route out","D shoots it down the ice","D freezes the puck"],ok:1,why:"Under heavy forecheck pressure, the boards are the safe play. The middle of the ice is where turnovers turn into goals against. Get it to the winger on the wall and live to attack another day.",tip:"Pressure from both sides? Go to the wall. The boards are your friend under pressure."},
    {id:"u9next6",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Line change opportunity",d:1,type:"next",sit:"Your team dumps the puck into the offensive zone. Your line has been on the ice for over a minute and everyone is tired. The other team is retrieving the puck behind their net. What happens next?",opts:["You forecheck hard even though you're tired","Your line changes — the puck is deep in their zone and they're behind their net, so this is the perfect time for a line change. Fresh legs coming on.","You stand still and rest on the ice","You call timeout"],ok:1,why:"A dump-in with the other team retrieving behind their net is the ideal time to change. Fresh legs are always better than tired legs trying to forecheck. Smart changes win games.",tip:"Puck dumped deep and you're gassed? Change. Fresh legs over tired legs, every time."},
    {id:"u9next7",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"3-on-2 developing",d:3,type:"next",sit:"Your team has a 3-on-2. The puck carrier drives wide and draws one defender. The second defender is cheating toward the puck carrier too, leaving the far-side forward wide open. What happens next?",opts:["Puck carrier keeps going alone","Puck carrier sees the second defender cheat and makes the cross-ice pass to the wide-open forward for a high-quality scoring chance","Puck carrier dumps it in","Puck carrier stops and waits"],ok:1,why:"When both defenders commit to the puck carrier, the far-side forward is wide open. The cross-ice pass in this situation is the highest-percentage play because the goalie can't get across in time.",tip:"Both D cheat to you on a 3-on-2? Cross-ice pass to the open man. Goalie can't get there."},

    // === TRUE/FALSE QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u9tf1",cat:"Decision Making",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Dump every time",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"You should always dump the puck into the offensive zone instead of carrying it in.",ok:false,why:"Dumping is one option, but if you have speed and space, carrying it in keeps possession and creates better chances. Read the situation — dump when you have to, carry when you can.",tip:"Dump or carry? Read the defense. Carry when you can, dump when you must."},
    {id:"u9tf2",cat:"Defense",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Forwards backcheck",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"Forwards should skate back hard to help on defense when the other team has the puck.",ok:true,why:"Backchecking is every forward's responsibility. A forward who doesn't backcheck leaves the team short in the defensive zone and creates odd-man rushes against.",tip:"Forwards backcheck. Period. It's not optional. Your team needs you back there."},
    {id:"u9tf3",cat:"Shooting",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Always top corner",d:2,type:"tf",sit:"You should always aim for the top corner of the net when you shoot.",ok:false,why:"Top corner is a great target, but low shots create rebounds, five-hole shots catch goalies off guard, and sometimes a quick release matters more than perfect placement. Read the situation.",tip:"Top corner isn't the only option. Low shots, far side, five-hole — read the goalie and pick the best target."},
    {id:"u9tf4",cat:"Positioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Spread out on offense",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"In the offensive zone, your team should spread out and use the whole ice instead of bunching up near the puck.",ok:true,why:"Spreading out creates passing lanes, opens up space, and makes it harder for the defense to cover everyone. Bunching up makes the defense's job easy — they can cover everyone at once.",tip:"Use the whole ice on offense. Spread out. Bunching up helps the other team, not yours."},
    {id:"u9tf5",cat:"Teamwork",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Communication helps",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"Calling out 'man on!' when a teammate is about to get hit helps your team keep the puck.",ok:true,why:"A 'man on' call gives your teammate a split second to protect the puck, make a pass, or brace for contact. That one call can be the difference between keeping possession and a turnover.",tip:"'Man on!' saves the play. One call, one second of warning, total difference."},
    {id:"u9tf6",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Middle ice is always safe",d:2,type:"tf",sit:"When breaking out of your own zone, passing up the middle of the ice is always the safest play.",ok:false,why:"The middle of the ice in your own zone is the most dangerous area for a turnover. A picked-off pass in the middle goes straight to the slot. The boards are the safe breakout route.",tip:"Middle ice in your own zone is danger. Use the boards to break out safely."},
    {id:"u9tf7",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Transition is instant",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"When your team loses the puck, you should immediately start skating back toward your own net.",ok:true,why:"Transition defense is instant. Every second you wait is a step the other team gains. The fastest backchecking teams give up the fewest goals on the rush.",tip:"Lose the puck? Instant backcheck. No thinking. No watching. Go."},
  ],
  "U11 / Atom":[
    {id:"u11q1",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"2-on-1 basic",d:1,sit:"You're on a 2-on-1. You have the puck. The defender is right in front of you. Your teammate is wide open. What do you do?",opts:["Shoot right away right away","Pass to your open teammate","Slow down and wait hard","Dump it in the corner now"],ok:1,why:"When you have a 2-on-1 and the defender takes you, your open teammate is the play.",tip:"2-on-1: If the D takes you, pass."},
    {id:"u11q2",cat:"Coverage",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Find your man",d:1,sit:"The other team has the puck in your defensive zone. What's the most important thing every player on your team should be doing?",opts:["Watching the puck now","Finding a man to cover","Skating to the blue","Waiting for a turnover"],ok:1,why:"In your defensive zone, every player needs to find a man. Watching the puck without picking up a check is how goals happen.",tip:"Own zone: find your man first. Then watch the puck."},
    {id:"u11q3",cat:"Blue Line Decisions",pos:["D"],concept:"Keep puck in",d:1,sit:"Your team has the puck in the offensive zone. It's sliding toward the blue line. You're the defenseman. What do you do?",opts:["Let it go out — it's not the right call","Skate to the puck and keep it in the zone","Back up to give room as fast as you can now","Go to the net — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"Keeping the puck in the offensive zone is the defenseman's first job.",tip:"Puck going to the line? Keep it in. That's your job as D."},
    {id:"u11q4",cat:"Offensive Pressure",pos:["F"],concept:"Forecheck basics",d:1,sit:"Your team is forechecking. The opposing D just picked up the puck behind their net. You're the first forward in. What's your goal?",opts:["Get the puck no matter what and let your teammates handle it","Put pressure on the D so they can't make an easy breakout pass","Wait for your teammates before moving no matter what happens","Skate back to center ice — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"The first forward on the forecheck pressures the puck carrier to take away easy options and force a mistake.",tip:"Forechecking: pressure the D. Take away their easy out."},
    {id:"u11q5",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Transition basics",d:1,sit:"Your team just lost the puck in the offensive zone. The other team is breaking out. What should every forward on your team do immediately?",opts:["Stay in the offensive zone and wait right away now","Turn around and skate back toward your own zone","Stop and call for a pass — that's a bad read","Stand still and watch — that's important here"],ok:1,why:"The instant your team loses possession, every forward transitions back. Not eventually — immediately.",tip:"Lost the puck? Turn around. Right now."},
    {id:"u11q6",cat:"Puck Protection",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Body position",d:1,sit:"You have the puck along the boards and a defender is coming at you from behind. What's the right thing to do with your body?",opts:["Turn to face the defender — that's a bad read","Put your body between the defender and the puck","Spin and try to skate through them right away","Pass immediately before they arrive right away"],ok:1,why:"Puck protection is about body position. Getting your body between the puck and the defender gives you time to make a play.",tip:"Defender behind you? Get your body between them and the puck."},
    {id:"u11q7",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Gap basics",d:1,sit:"You're a defender and an attacker is coming at you with the puck. You're backing up. Should you give them a lot of space or a little?",opts:["A lot of space — give them room — that's a bad read","A steady controlled gap — not too much, not too little","No space — close on them immediately as fast as you can","It doesn't matter — you'll figure the rest out later"],ok:1,why:"Gap control means maintaining the right distance. Too much space lets them get speed and options. Too little and they go around you.",tip:"Gap control: close enough to be a threat, far enough to react."},
    {id:"u11q8",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP basics",d:1,sit:"Your team is on the power play. You have the extra skater. What's the most important thing you have that the other team doesn't?",opts:["Faster players right away","One more player on the ice","A better goalie right away","The home crowd right away now"],ok:1,why:"The power play advantage is the extra skater. Every decision should exploit that — move the puck to find the player who isn't covered.",tip:"Power play: you have the extra man. Find them."},
    {id:"u11q9",cat:"Decision Timing",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Simple decisions",d:1,sit:"You receive the puck in your own zone with a forechecker right on you. Your D partner is five feet away and completely open. What do you do?",opts:["Try to skate out yourself immediately now","Pass immediately to your open D partner","Shoot the puck down the ice right away","Wait for a better option immediately"],ok:1,why:"The open D partner five feet away is the easy, correct play. Under pressure the simple play is almost always right.",tip:"Open partner right beside you? Give it to them. Simple."},
    {id:"u11q10",cat:"Cycle Play",pos:["F"],concept:"Why cycle",d:1,sit:"Your team has the puck below the dots in the offensive zone. Why is it good to cycle the puck down low rather than always shooting from outside?",opts:["It wastes time — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","It gets your team closer to the net and creates better scoring chances","It makes the game boring — you'll figure the rest out later right away","It helps the other team — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"Cycling below the dots draws defenders away from the net, creates open shooting lanes, and generates rebounds close to the crease.",tip:"Cycle: closer to the net = better chances."},
    {id:"u11q11",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout basics",d:1,sit:"Your defenseman picks up the puck in your own corner. As a winger, where should you immediately skate to?",opts:["Into the corner to help right away","Up the boards — give the D an outlet","To the front of your own net hard hard","To center ice — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"The winger's breakout job is to get up the wall fast and give the defenseman an outlet option.",tip:"D in the corner? You go up the wall. Get open."},
    {id:"u11q12",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK basics",d:1,sit:"Your team is on the penalty kill. The power play has set up in your zone. What's your team's main job?",opts:["Score a shorthanded goal — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Keep the puck away from dangerous areas and get it out of your zone","Stay in a tight group in front of the net — that's important here","Challenge every pass aggressively — the puck will sort itself out now"],ok:1,why:"The penalty kill's job is to keep the puck out of dangerous areas and clear the zone.",tip:"Penalty kill: protect danger areas and get it out."},
    {id:"u11q13",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Trailer role",d:1,sit:"Your team rushes 3-on-2. The two defenders take your two wingers. You're the trailing center. Where do you position?",opts:["Race to the net as fast as possible as fast as you can","Stay high and be ready for a drop pass or rebound shot","Skate to the corner and let your teammates handle it","Stop at the red line — the puck will sort itself out"],ok:1,why:"The trailer on a 3-on-2 stays high — ready for a drop pass if the play breaks down or to get a rebound shot from the top.",tip:"Trailer on a rush: stay high. You're the safety and the extra option."},
    {id:"u11q14",cat:"Coverage",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Weak side awareness",d:1,sit:"The puck is in the offensive zone corner on your left. You're the right winger. You don't have the puck. Where should you be?",opts:["In the corner helping your teammate — that's a bad read","On the right side near the net, ready for a cross-ice pass","At the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later hard","On the bench — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"As the weak-side winger, staying on your side near the net puts you in position for a cross-ice pass.",tip:"Puck in the far corner? Stay weak side near the net."},
    {id:"u11q15",cat:"Decision Timing",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Time and space",d:1,sit:"You receive a pass in the offensive zone with nobody near you. You have lots of time. What should you do before shooting or passing?",opts:["Shoot immediately no matter what — that's a bad read","Look up and read what's happening — find the best play","Skate to the corner and let your teammates handle it now","Pass backward to the blue line and hope for the best"],ok:1,why:"When you have time and space, use it. Looking up before making your play is what separates reactive players from smart ones.",tip:"Got time? Look up first. Read the ice. Then play."},
    {id:"u11q16",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"2-on-1 timing",d:2,sit:"You're the puck carrier on a 2-on-1. The lone defender is backing up in the middle, not committing to either side. What do you do?",opts:["Pass immediately since it's a 2-on-1 and avoid the dangerous area","Drive wide to force the defender to fully commit first, then decide","Shoot from where you are — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Pull up and regroup — you'll figure the rest out later right away now"],ok:1,why:"If the defender isn't committing, you haven't created the advantage yet. Drive wide to force their decision.",tip:"Defender not committing? Make them. Drive wide first."},
    {id:"u11q17",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"3-on-2 middle lane",d:2,sit:"Your team rushes 3-on-2. Both defenders take your two wingers. The middle lane is completely open. You're the center. What do you do?",opts:["Pass to the right winger — you'll figure the rest out later hard now","Pass to the left winger — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Drive the middle lane and shoot — the defenders opened it for you","Pull up and regroup — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:2,why:"When both defenders go to the wings, they've given you the middle. Driving the lane and shooting catches the goalie off-guard.",tip:"Both D go wide on a 3-on-2? Drive the middle. Shoot."},
    {id:"u11q18",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Rush regroup",d:2,sit:"Your team is on a rush but you're outnumbered — 2-on-3 against you. What's the right call?",opts:["Attack anyway — speed is on your side","Pull up, regroup, and get set up properly","Dump it in and chase as fast as you can","Pass back to the blue line immediately"],ok:1,why:"Attacking a 3-on-2 against you gives the other team the transition they want. Pulling up and regrouping resets the play on your terms.",tip:"Outnumbered on the rush? Pull up. Don't attack into a trap."},
    {id:"u11q19",cat:"Coverage",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Corner coverage",d:2,sit:"The puck goes into the corner in your defensive zone. You're the nearest forward. Your D is already there. What do you do?",opts:["Go help in the corner — two players are better","Hold the front of the net — don't leave it empty","Go to the blue line — just get it out of there now","Skate to center ice — just get it out of there"],ok:1,why:"When your D goes to the corner, you hold the front of the net. Two players in the corner leaves the crease empty.",tip:"D goes to the corner? You hold the net front. Don't follow them in."},
    {id:"u11q20",cat:"Coverage",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Center coverage",d:2,sit:"Three attackers enter your zone. You're the center on defense. Your two wingers pick up the two opposing wingers. Who do you cover?",opts:["The puck right away","The opposing center","The open space in","Go help a winger hard"],ok:1,why:"In standard defensive zone coverage, the center picks up the opposing center.",tip:"Three attackers in your zone? As center, you've got their center."},
    {id:"u11q21",cat:"Blue Line Decisions",pos:["D"],concept:"Pinch risk",d:2,sit:"You're the defenseman at the offensive blue line. The puck goes to the corner. Your nearest winger is there but about to get pressured. No coverage behind you. Should you pinch?",opts:["Yes — go help your winger — you'll figure the rest out later immediately hard","No — hold the blue line. If your winger loses the puck you'll be caught deep.","Go to the net front — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Skate behind the net — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"Pinching when there's no coverage behind you and your winger is under pressure is high-risk. If the puck turns over, you're caught deep with a 2-on-1 against you.",tip:"No coverage behind you? Don't pinch. Hold the line."},
    {id:"u11q22",cat:"Blue Line Decisions",pos:["D"],concept:"D-to-D pass",d:2,sit:"You're the right defenseman in the offensive zone. A defender is closing on you hard. Your D partner on the left side is wide open. What do you do?",opts:["Hold the puck and try to beat the pressure — it's not the right call","Make a quick D-to-D pass to your partner — they're open and you're not now","Shoot the puck through traffic — you'll figure the rest out later","Pass back into the corner — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"Under pressure at the point, the D-to-D pass is the reset. Your partner has time and a better look.",tip:"Pressure coming? D-to-D. Let your partner reset the play."},
    {id:"u11q23",cat:"Blue Line Decisions",pos:["D"],concept:"Shooting through traffic",d:2,sit:"You're the defenseman at the point on the power play. The slot is full of traffic. You have a shooting lane to the net. What do you do?",opts:["Hold the puck and wait for traffic to clear as fast as you can","Shoot immediately — traffic in front means screens and rebounds","Pass cross-ice to the other point while reading the situation now","Skate in yourself — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"Traffic in front of the net is an asset, not a problem. Shoot through it — the screen blocks the goalie's view and the traffic creates rebounds.",tip:"Traffic in front? Shoot. That's exactly what you want."},
    {id:"u11q24",cat:"Offensive Pressure",pos:["F"],concept:"High forward 2-1-2",d:2,sit:"Your team is in a 2-1-2 forecheck. The puck is in the corner. As the high forward, where do you position?",opts:["Go into the corner and chase the puck — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Stay high between the two defensemen — cut off passes and take away the middle","Go to the net front — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Back up to the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"In a 2-1-2 forecheck, the high forward cuts off outlet passes through the middle.",tip:"High forward in a 2-1-2: sit between the D. Cut off the middle outlet."},
    {id:"u11q25",cat:"Offensive Pressure",pos:["F"],concept:"Forecheck angles",d:2,sit:"You're forechecking. The D picks up the puck behind the net and looks to the left winger up the wall. What's your angle?",opts:["Go straight at the D as fast as possible — that's a bad read now","Cut off the pass to the left — force the D to go right instead","Stop and let them make the pass and avoid the dangerous area","Back off completely — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"Forechecking with angles means reading where the D wants to go and cutting that off.",tip:"Forecheck: read where they want to go. Cut it off."},
    {id:"u11q26",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Weak-side entry",d:2,sit:"Your team is entering the offensive zone. Two defenders are both already back. You're the center. What's the best thing you can do?",opts:["Drive straight to the net — you'll figure the rest out later","Peel off and go to the weak side — create a triangle of options","Stop at the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Go to the corner with the puck carrier no matter what happens"],ok:1,why:"When two defenders are back, you need to spread them out. Going weak side as the center creates a triangle that forces the defense to split.",tip:"Two D back? Go weak side and stretch the defense."},
    {id:"u11q27",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Neutral zone delay",d:2,sit:"Your team is in the neutral zone with the puck. The other team has three players sitting back. What's the best way to attack?",opts:["Skate at them full speed — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Delay — use a D-to-D pass or drop pass to find a lane that opens up","Dump the puck in immediately — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Regroup and come back the same way — the puck will sort itself out"],ok:1,why:"Three players waiting is designed to stop straight-line rushes. Delaying and using lateral movement creates a different angle of attack.",tip:"Three players waiting? Delay and find a lane."},
    {id:"u11q28",cat:"Puck Protection",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Chip off boards",d:2,sit:"You have the puck in the corner. A defender has you pinned against the boards. Your winger is at the half-wall. What do you do?",opts:["Try to power through the defender and let your teammates handle it","Use a quick spin move or chip the puck off the boards to your winger","Try to pass between their legs — you'll figure the rest out later","Fall down to draw a penalty — you'll figure the rest out later hard now"],ok:1,why:"When you're pinned, use a chip pass off the boards or a spin to create separation and move the puck.",tip:"Pinned in the corner? Chip it off the boards to your teammate."},
    {id:"u11q29",cat:"Puck Protection",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reverse behind net",d:2,sit:"You're behind your own net with the puck. A forechecker is coming around the left side. Your left D is covered. Your right D is open. What do you do?",opts:["Try to carry it out to the left immediately hard","Spin to the right and find your open defenseman","Stop and wait for the forechecker immediately","Shoot it down the ice — that's important here"],ok:1,why:"Reading which side the pressure is coming from and reversing to the open side is basic puck protection under pressure.",tip:"Forechecker coming from the left? Spin right. Go where they're not."},
    {id:"u11q30",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Closing gap",d:2,sit:"You've been backing up and the attacker is now near the top of your face-off circles. They haven't shot or passed yet. What do you do?",opts:["Keep backing up indefinitely — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Close the gap slightly — you've given them enough space. Force them to make a play. now","Turn and race toward your own net — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Poke check from where you are — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"Backing up forever isn't gap control — it's retreating. At some point you have to close and force the attacker's hand.",tip:"You've backed up enough. Close the gap and force a decision."},
    {id:"u11q31",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Angling to boards",d:2,sit:"An attacker is carrying the puck along the right boards. You're the defenseman. You want to angle them into the corner. Which direction should you push them?",opts:["Toward the middle of the ice now","Into the corner toward the","Straight backward toward your net","It doesn't matter immediately"],ok:1,why:"Angling means steering the puck carrier away from the dangerous middle and into the corner.",tip:"Angling: push them to the boards, away from the middle."},
    {id:"u11q32",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP move early",d:2,sit:"Your team has a power play in a 1-3-1. The puck is at the top. A penalty killer closes on the top player hard. What should the top player do?",opts:["Hold the puck and fight through the pressure — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Move the puck quickly before the pressure arrives — pass to the half-wall or the other side","Shoot under pressure — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out","Back up to the red line — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out now"],ok:1,why:"On the power play, moving the puck before pressure arrives is the key. One extra skater means someone is always open.",tip:"PP with pressure coming? Move the puck early. Someone is open."},
    {id:"u11q33",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP net-front",d:2,sit:"Your team is on the power play. A shot comes from the point. You're standing in front of the net. What's your job on that shot?",opts:["Get out of the way so the goalie can see immediately hard","Screen the goalie and be ready to tip or deflect the shot","Skate to the corner for the rebound — that's a bad read","Back off to the half-wall and trust the play to develop"],ok:1,why:"The net-front player on the power play screens the goalie and tips shots. Getting out of the way defeats the purpose of being there.",tip:"Net front on the PP: screen the goalie and get ready to tip."},
    {id:"u11q34",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK timing challenges",d:2,sit:"You're on the penalty kill. The power play is cycling below the dots but not shooting. When should you challenge?",opts:["Immediately every time the puck moves — the puck will sort itself out","When they slow down or seem to be setting up a shot — not on every pass","Every time they're near the boards — you'll figure the rest out later","Never — just stay back — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"On the PK, challenging on every pass runs you out of position. Pick your moments.",tip:"PK: don't bite on every pass. Pick your moment. Challenge when it counts."},
    {id:"u11q35",cat:"Decision Timing",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Shoot the out-of-position goalie",d:2,sit:"You receive the puck at the half-wall. The goalie is slightly out of position and you have a shooting lane. What do you do?",opts:["Pass to a breaking winger right away","Shoot at the exposed net immediately","Hold the puck and wait immediately now","Pass back to the point immediately"],ok:1,why:"An out-of-position goalie with a shooting lane is an opportunity. Shoot before they recover.",tip:"Goalie out of position with a lane? Shoot. Right now."},
    {id:"u11q36",cat:"Decision Timing",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Protect under dual pressure",d:2,sit:"You have the puck in the offensive zone. Two defenders are collapsing on you from both sides. You have no open teammates. What do you do?",opts:["Try to deke through both defenders — the puck will sort itself out","Protect the puck along the boards and wait for a teammate to support","Pass blindly into traffic — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Shoot from where you are — you'll figure the rest out later hard hard"],ok:1,why:"When two defenders collapse on you and there's nobody open, protecting the puck and waiting for support is smarter than forcing a bad play.",tip:"Two defenders collapsing and nobody open? Protect it. Wait for support."},
    {id:"u11q37",cat:"Cycle Play",pos:["F"],concept:"Cycling purpose",d:2,sit:"Your team is cycling in the offensive zone. The defenders are staying tight to the net. What should the cycling players be trying to create?",opts:["Time of possession for its own sake — you'll figure the rest out later right away now","A gap or opening — a shot lane, a pass to the slot, or a player breaking to the net","Confusion by passing as fast as possible — you'll figure the rest out later hard","A penalty by forcing contact — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"Cycling isn't just possession — it's designed to create something. Possession without purpose is just skating.",tip:"Cycle: you're looking for the opening. Possession is the means, not the goal."},
    {id:"u11q38",cat:"Cycle Play",pos:["F"],concept:"Board pass in cycle",d:2,sit:"You're low in the corner with the puck. Your winger is at the half-wall. A defender is pressuring you hard from behind. What do you do?",opts:["Try to power through and hold the puck as fast as you","Bank a quick pass off the boards to your half-wall winger","Spin and try to skate into open ice — that's a bad read","Shoot from the corner until someone tells you otherwise"],ok:1,why:"A quick board pass to the half-wall winger is the reliable escape when you're being pressured in the corner. The boards are your extra teammate.",tip:"Pressured in the corner? Bank it off the boards to the half-wall. Use the boards."},
    {id:"u11q39",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Quick breakout",d:2,sit:"Your team wins a puck battle in your own corner. The other team's forecheckers are still coming hard. What's the fastest way out?",opts:["Hold the puck and wait for them to stop until someone tells you otherwise","Move the puck quickly — first open option up the wall or through the","Rim it around the boards — you'll figure the rest out later right away hard","Shoot it down the ice for icing — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"When forecheckers are bearing down, speed of decision matters more than finding the perfect option. First clean outlet — take it.",tip:"Forecheckers coming fast? Move the puck. First clean option. Go."},
    {id:"u11q40",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Forechecker committed",d:2,sit:"Your D picks up the puck behind your net. One forechecker is coming around the right side. Your right winger is up the wall. Your left winger is covered. What's the breakout pass?",opts:["Force the pass to the covered left winger — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Pass to the right winger — they're open and the forechecker has committed to that side","Carry it out yourself — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","Rim it around the boards — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call now"],ok:1,why:"The forechecker coming from the right creates a brief opening on that same side — the winger who got up the right wall is open because the forechecker has already committed.",tip:"Forechecker committed to one side? The outlet on that same side may be the cleanest."},
    {id:"u11q41",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Goalie reads the 2-on-1",d:3,sit:"You're the puck carrier on a 2-on-1. The defender commits fully to your teammate. The goalie slides across expecting your pass. What's the right call now?",opts:["Pass to your teammate as planned — it's not the right call now","Shoot — the goalie has moved and there's a lane on your side","Pass to the other side — you'll figure the rest out later","Pull up and regroup — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"When the defender commits to your teammate AND the goalie slides to take away the pass, they've left your side open. Shoot — the goalie has moved.",tip:"2-on-1: if the goalie chases the pass, shoot becomes the right play. Read the goalie."},
    {id:"u11q42",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"3-on-2 D split",d:3,sit:"Your team turns the puck over in the offensive zone. The other team breaks out with a 3-on-2 against you. You're the far defenseman. The puck carrier is coming up your side. What's your priority?",opts:["Rush the puck carrier — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself","Take your side, force the carrier wide, and trust your partner to take the middle player","Back up to the crease — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself","Chase the trailer — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out"],ok:1,why:"On a 3-on-2, the two D split responsibility. You take your side and force the carrier wide — your partner protects the middle.",tip:"3-on-2 against you: each D takes a side. Don't cross unless called."},
    {id:"u11q43",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Backcheck weak side",d:3,sit:"Your team turns the puck over. The other team has a 2-on-1 and you're the only forward close enough to get back. You can't catch the puck carrier. What do you do?",opts:["Skate as fast as you can directly at the puck carrier no matter what happens","Skate back hard on the weak side — get between the second attacker and the net","Stop skating — you can't help — you'll figure the rest out later right away hard","Go to the bench for a line change — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"You can't catch the puck carrier, but you can take away the pass option on the weak side.",tip:"Can't catch the puck carrier? Get to the weak side. Take away the pass."},
    {id:"u11q44",cat:"Coverage",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Overload coverage",d:3,sit:"Three attackers enter your zone. They overload the left side — two attackers on the left and one on the right. Both your D are back. How should they adjust?",opts:["Both D go to the left to cover the two attackers — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","One D takes the two on the left, the other holds the middle and takes the weak-side attacker — both D communicate","Both D go to the right — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice","One D goes behind the net — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the now"],ok:1,why:"An overload means the D have to communicate and adjust. One D takes the strong side with two attackers, while the partner takes the weak-side player and the slot.",tip:"Overload coverage: communicate. One takes the strong side, the other holds the middle and weak side."},
    {id:"u11q45",cat:"Coverage",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Late attacker uncovered",d:3,sit:"Two attackers entered your zone and both D picked them up. A third attacker trails in 5 seconds later — nobody picked them up. You're the center on defense. What do you do?",opts:["Stay with your current assignment — you'll figure the rest out later right away hard","Pick up the late attacker — your winger on that side needs to find their assignment","Call it out and let someone else handle it — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Ignore it — your D will figure it out — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"A late attacker entering the zone creates a coverage breakdown. The center needs to pick them up or communicate a switch.",tip:"Late attacker uncovered? Call it and pick them up. Coverage gaps get exploited."},
    {id:"u11q46",cat:"Blue Line Decisions",pos:["D"],concept:"When to pinch advanced",d:3,sit:"You're the offensive zone D. The puck went to the corner. Your winger got there first and has possession, but a defender is closing. No coverage behind you. Your other winger is at the half-wall. Should you pinch?",opts:["Yes — go help your winger in the corner — you'll figure the rest out later right away","No — your winger has possession and your half-wall winger can support. Hold the blue line.","Yes — any time there's a puck battle, pinch — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Go to the net front instead — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"Your winger has possession and the half-wall winger can support. You don't need to go. Pinching here with no coverage behind you risks a breakout against you.",tip:"Winger has it and half-wall can help? Hold the line."},
    {id:"u11q47",cat:"Blue Line Decisions",pos:["D"],concept:"Shot fake PP",d:3,sit:"You're the point on the power play. You have the puck and a shooting lane — but two PK forwards are closing on you hard. You have one second. What's the best play?",opts:["Shoot immediately before they close — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out","Fake the shot to freeze them, then pass to the half-wall player who opened up when they committed to you","Hold the puck and wait for a lane — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out hard","Pass back to the other point — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on"],ok:1,why:"When two PK players commit to you, they've left someone open. A shot fake freezes them for a split second — the half-wall opens up the instant they both lean at you.",tip:"Two PKers closing? Fake the shot. Someone opened up when they committed."},
    {id:"u11q48",cat:"Offensive Pressure",pos:["F"],concept:"Two-man forecheck trap",d:3,sit:"You're forechecking. The D picks up the puck behind the net and starts to walk out to the left. You're closing from the right. Your linemate is on the left. How do you split?",opts:["Both go directly at the D — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the","You force the D's direction from the right, your linemate cuts off the outlet to the left — trap them between you","You back off and let your linemate handle it — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out","Both back off and reset — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice"],ok:1,why:"A two-player forecheck trap works by forcing the puck carrier in a direction while the other player cuts off the outlet in that direction.",tip:"Two-man forecheck: one forces, one cuts the outlet. Trap them."},
    {id:"u11q49",cat:"Offensive Pressure",pos:["F"],concept:"High forward intercept",d:3,sit:"Your team is forechecking and the other team wins a battle in the corner. They're about to break out with speed. You're the high forward. What's the most important thing you do right now?",opts:["Chase the puck into the corner — you'll figure the rest out later hard now","Hold your position and intercept the first outlet pass — you're the plug","Immediately skate back to your own zone — the puck will sort itself out","Go to the bench — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"When the puck changes in the corner, the high forward's job is to be the first interceptor — not to chase.",tip:"They won the corner battle? High forward reads the breakout. Don't chase — intercept."},
    {id:"u11q50",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Transition timing",d:3,sit:"Your team just won a puck battle in your own zone. Two of your forwards are already at center ice. The other team has one player back. A 3-on-1 is developing. What's the trigger?",opts:["Wait until all three forwards are in the neutral zone as fast as you can","Go immediately — the 3-on-1 window closes fast as the other team gets back now","Regroup at your own blue line — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Dump it in and change lines — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"Transition opportunities close fast. If two forwards are already at center and you have a 3-on-1 developing, going immediately is how you exploit it.",tip:"Transition chance opening? Go now. Those windows close in seconds."},
    {id:"u11q51",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D pinching up",d:3,sit:"Your team breaks out. As you cross the red line you see both opposing defensemen are pinching up — they're at the red line, not their blue line. What do you do?",opts:["Slow down and let them set up — you'll figure the rest out later immediately","Skate hard behind them — you have a breakaway if you beat them to their blue line","Dump the puck in — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call hard","Pass across to a winger — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"Defensemen pinching up means they've given up the space behind them. If you can beat them to the puck, you have a breakaway or a clean zone entry.",tip:"Both D pinching up? Burn them. Get behind them before they recover."},
    {id:"u11q52",cat:"Puck Protection",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Wheel the net",d:3,sit:"You're protecting the puck behind the net with a defender leaning on you. Two teammates are in the zone but both are covered. What do you do?",opts:["Force a pass to a covered teammate — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","Wheel to the other side of the net — moving forces the defender to move and may open a teammate","Try to power through the defender — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","Fall down and hope for a penalty — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call now"],ok:1,why:"Wheeling behind the net when both outlets are covered forces the defender to move with you, which can open a teammate, and it resets the pressure.",tip:"Both outlets covered behind the net? Wheel. Force the defense to move."},
    {id:"u11q53",cat:"Puck Protection",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Dual pressure protection",d:3,sit:"You have the puck in the corner. Two defenders are collapsing on you from different angles. Your only open teammate is at the blue line — a long pass blocked by two defenders. What do you do?",opts:["Attempt the long pass to the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out hard","Protect the puck tight to the boards with your body, wait for the angle to open, then make a short chip pass","Try to spin through both defenders — you'll figure the rest out later until someone tells you otherwise","Shoot the puck around the boards randomly — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out"],ok:1,why:"Under dual pressure with a long pass blocked, protecting tight and waiting for an opening is the disciplined play. Two defenders can't both have perfect angles — one will leave a gap.",tip:"Two defenders collapsing? Protect tight and wait. The gap will open."},
    {id:"u11q54",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Get in the lane",d:3,sit:"A skilled attacker gets a step on you at the blue line and is now skating toward your net with speed. You can't catch them. What's the right approach?",opts:["Give up and let the goalie handle it — you'll figure the rest out later and let your teammates handle it","Get your stick into their lane — angle them toward the boards and get your body in front of the shooting lane","Try to grab them — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice","Chase from behind and hope to catch up — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out"],ok:1,why:"When you can't catch an attacker, get in their lane. Angling them toward the boards takes away the shooting lane.",tip:"Can't catch them? Get your body in the lane. Take away the shooting angle."},
    {id:"u11q55",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Don't commit to a fake",d:3,sit:"You're the defenseman and an attacker is coming in at speed. They fake to the backhand. You start to move with the fake. What do you do next?",opts:["Keep moving with the fake — commit fully — you'll figure the rest out later","Stop your movement, reset your feet, and regain your gap — don't fully commit","Fall down to block — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read hard","Poke check immediately — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"Getting caught on a fake is recoverable if you stop your feet and reset quickly. Fully committing to the fake loses the gap entirely.",tip:"Bit on a fake? Stop your feet immediately and reset. Don't chase the fake."},
    {id:"u11q56",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP seam pass",d:3,sit:"Your power play is in a 1-3-1. The half-wall player has the puck. The near PK forward is cheating toward the half-wall. The seam pass to the middle player is now open. What's the right play?",opts:["Hold the puck at the half-wall — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","Thread the seam pass to the middle player — the PK forward cheating toward you opened that","Shoot from the half-wall — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out","Pass back to the point — you'll figure the rest out later and let your teammates handle it hard"],ok:1,why:"When the PK forward cheats toward you, they've vacated the seam. The middle player is open. The seam pass is the highest-danger play.",tip:"PK forward cheated toward you? The seam is open. Thread it."},
    {id:"u11q57",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP adjustment",d:3,sit:"Your team's power play is struggling. The PK has collapsed everything to the slot and the point. What adjustment do you make?",opts:["Keep shooting from the point — you'll figure the rest out later and let your teammates handle it hard","Pull the puck back out of the zone, reset, and come in with a new entry that attacks a different spot","Dump the puck to the corner — you'll figure the rest out later until someone tells you otherwise","Have every player rush the net — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out"],ok:1,why:"When the PK has your power play figured out and collapsed, pull back and re-enter with a different attack angle.",tip:"PP getting shut down? Pull back and reset. Come in differently."},
    {id:"u11q58",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK mindset",d:3,sit:"Your penalty kill gets the puck out of your zone. It's a 2-on-3 as you exit. Do you try to score shorthanded or just clear?",opts:["Go for the shorthanded goal — attack — that's important here","Clear the zone and get back — a clean clear is a win on the PK","Pass back to your goalie — you'll figure the rest out later","Dump it right back in — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"A clean clear on the PK is a win — it kills clock and resets the power play.",tip:"PK clear: clean exit = success. Don't gamble on a shorthanded goal."},
    {id:"u11q59",cat:"Decision Timing",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Pre-read the pass",d:3,sit:"You're about to receive a pass in the offensive zone. Before the puck reaches you, what should you already be doing?",opts:["Waiting with your stick ready to receive — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Looking up and deciding where you're going with the puck before it arrives — pre-reading the play","Calling for the puck louder — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out hard","Watching the pass to make sure you catch it — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"Pre-reading the play — deciding where you're going before the puck arrives — is what separates slow players from fast ones. By the time the puck hits your stick, your decision should already be made.",tip:"Pass coming? Decide what you're doing with it before it arrives. Pre-read."},
    {id:"u11q60",cat:"Decision Timing",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Plans change",d:3,sit:"You skate into the offensive zone with speed. You planned to shoot from the right side, but as you enter you see the goalie has that side covered and a teammate is breaking to the net on the left. What do you do?",opts:["Shoot to the right as planned — stick to the plan — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Read and react — pass to your breaking teammate. The plan changes when the situation changes.","Slow down and think — you'll figure the rest out later until someone tells you otherwise","Dump it in and regroup — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out hard"],ok:1,why:"Plans are starting points, not locks. If the situation changes, read it and react.",tip:"Read what's actually there. Your plan is a starting point, not a commitment."},
    {id:"u11q61",cat:"Cycle Play",pos:["F"],concept:"Cycle timing — attack it",d:3,sit:"You're cycling below the dots. Your partner passes to you at the half-wall. The slot is completely empty. What's the play?",opts:["Continue cycling — pass back to the corner and avoid the dangerous area now","Shoot immediately into the open slot or pass to a teammate breaking there","Hold the puck — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Drop it back to the point — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"The slot opening up is exactly what the cycle is designed to create. The instant you see it, attack it — don't keep cycling for its own sake.",tip:"Slot opens during the cycle? That's the goal. Attack it immediately."},
    {id:"u11q62",cat:"Cycle Play",pos:["F"],concept:"Half-wall with time",d:3,sit:"You're at the half-wall with the puck. The point defender is cheating toward the net. The slot defender is watching the corner. Nobody is tight on you. What's the play?",opts:["Pass to the corner — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Shoot from the half-wall — you have time and the slot defender is distracted","Pass up to the point — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Drop the puck behind you — you'll figure the rest out later immediately"],ok:1,why:"When the slot defender is watching the corner and nobody's tight on you at the half-wall, you have a shooting opportunity. Take it.",tip:"Nobody on you at the half-wall and slot D is distracted? Shoot."},
    {id:"u11q63",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D carry out",d:3,sit:"Two forecheckers are deep in your zone. Your winger is up the wall but covered. Your center in the middle is also covered. Your D has the puck behind the net. What's the best option?",opts:["Force a pass to a covered teammate — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice","Wheel and carry it out — both forecheckers are committed to your forwards. The D carrying it out is the best option.","Shoot it around the boards — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice","Wait behind the net — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice"],ok:1,why:"When both forecheckers have committed to your forwards and left the D unguarded, the D carrying it out is the right play.",tip:"Both forecheckers on your forwards? D carry it out. The lane is open."},
    {id:"u11q64",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Stretch pass",d:3,sit:"Your D picks up the puck in your own zone. Two forecheckers are on them but both wingers are covered. Your center breaks free through the neutral zone — 40 feet away but completely open. What's the call?",opts:["Don't attempt it — too risky — you'll figure the rest out later","Thread the stretch pass to the center — they're breaking and open","Rim it around the boards — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Wait behind the net for the forecheckers to leave immediately hard"],ok:1,why:"A stretch pass to a breaking center turns a defensive zone puck into an immediate rush chance. The reward — an odd-man rush — is worth the risk when the lane is clean.",tip:"Breaking center open on the stretch? Thread it. Risky but the reward is a rush."},
    {id:"u11q65",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"1-on-1 rush patience",d:2,sit:"You're on a clean 1-on-1 rush. The defenseman is the only one back. They're skating backward. What's the best approach?",opts:["Skate directly at them as fast as possible — just get it out of there hard","Skate with control, read their skates, and make a move when they commit","Shoot immediately from outside the zone and trust the play to develop","Slow down and wait — you'll figure the rest out later as fast as you can"],ok:1,why:"On a 1-on-1 rush, patience wins. Skating directly at full speed gives the D control. Skating with control and reading their feet lets you make a move when they commit.",tip:"1-on-1 rush: patience. Read their feet. Move when they commit."},
    {id:"u11q66",cat:"Coverage",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Switch call",d:3,sit:"You're the left defenseman. Your partner calls switch as an attacker cuts from the right side to the left in front of the net. What do you do?",opts:["Stay with your original assignment — don't switch — the puck will sort itself out","Take the attacker coming to your side, let your partner clean up their original man","Call the referee — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out","Back up to the crease — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"A switch call means you take the player coming to your side while your partner recovers their original man. Communication and trust make it work.",tip:"Partner calls switch? Take the player coming to you. Trust the communication."},
    {id:"u11q67",cat:"Offensive Pressure",pos:["F"],concept:"Cut off the breakout lane",d:2,sit:"Your team is in the offensive zone. The other team won a puck battle and is trying to break out. You're the nearest forward. What's the most effective way to maintain pressure?",opts:["Chase the puck carrier at top speed — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad","Read their breakout pass options and cut them off — be in the lane before the pass is","Give up and change lines — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call hard","Back off to the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"Maintaining offensive pressure is about reading the breakout, not chasing. Getting into passing lanes before the pass happens is more effective than chasing from behind.",tip:"They won the puck battle? Get in the breakout lane — don't just chase."},
    {id:"u11q68",cat:"Puck Protection",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Delay game",d:3,sit:"Your team is winning by one goal with 90 seconds left. You win a puck battle in the neutral zone. What's the right thing to do with the puck?",opts:["Attack immediately and try to score another goal — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Control the puck along the boards, protect it, and force the other team to come get it — use every second","Dump it into the other team's zone — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out","Shoot it down the ice — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice hard"],ok:1,why:"Game management late means using the clock. Protecting the puck in the neutral zone and making the other team come to you burns precious seconds.",tip:"Leading late and you won the puck? Protect it. Use the clock."},
    {id:"u11q69",cat:"Decision Timing",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Low on aggressive goalie",d:3,sit:"You receive a pass in the slot. The goalie is way out of their net, cutting the angle aggressively. Where should you shoot?",opts:["High to the blocker side — beat them over the shoulder hard","Low and to one side — an aggressive goalie is exposed low","Straight at them — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Deke and go around them — the puck will sort itself out"],ok:1,why:"A goalie playing aggressively out of the net is vulnerable low. They've taken away the high areas, but low shots exploit their aggressive position.",tip:"Goalie aggressive and out of the net? Go low. They've taken away high."},
    {id:"u11q70",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK clear priority",d:2,sit:"Your team is on the penalty kill. You win the puck along the boards in your own zone. What's the priority?",opts:["Pass around until you find a perfect option — the puck will sort itself out","Get the puck out of your zone as fast as possible — any clean clear is a win","Hold the puck and wait for the power play to tire out — that's a bad read","Try to score shorthanded immediately — you'll figure the rest out later"],ok:1,why:"Clearing the zone on the PK is priority one. Every second you hold the puck in your zone is a second the power play can set up.",tip:"PK with the puck? Get it out. First clean option. Don't hold."},
    {id:"u11q71",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP counter-attack",d:3,sit:"Your team is on the power play. The penalty kill gets the puck and two players immediately break the other way 2-on-2. What should your team do?",opts:["Chase immediately and attack — you'll figure the rest out later immediately","One forward pressures the puck, the others recover their positions — don't panic","All five players retreat to your own zone — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Ignore it — the PP will get another chance — you'll figure the rest out later"],ok:1,why:"A power play counter-attack is dangerous but not a guaranteed goal. One player pressures the puck, everyone else recovers position. Panicking creates a turnover.",tip:"PK breaks out on a counter? One pressures, others recover. Don't panic."},
    {id:"u11q72",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Defending the cycle",d:3,sit:"The other team is cycling below the dots in your zone. You're the weak-side defenseman. When do you leave your position to challenge?",opts:["Every time the puck moves — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out","When a player with the puck is in a dangerous spot — near the slot or about to pass to the slot","Never — always hold your spot — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","When your partner tells you to — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call hard"],ok:1,why:"Defending the cycle means picking your moments. You don't challenge every pass — you protect your position and challenge when the puck is in a truly dangerous spot.",tip:"Defending the cycle: stay in position. Challenge when dangerous, not just moving."},
    {id:"u11q73",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Rush breakdown pressure",d:3,sit:"Your team is attacking 3-on-2. The play breaks down and the other team gets the puck. You're the center, close to the play. What do you do first?",opts:["Go to the bench immediately and avoid the dangerous area now","Pressure the puck carrier immediately to slow the breakout","Skate to the blue line until someone tells you otherwise","Stand still and watch — you'll figure the rest out later"],ok:1,why:"When a rush play breaks down and the other team gets the puck, the nearest forward pressures immediately. Slowing their first move buys your teammates time to recover.",tip:"Rush broke down? Pressure the puck immediately. Buy your team two seconds."},
    {id:"u11q74",cat:"Cycle Play",pos:["F"],concept:"D stepped in",d:3,sit:"You're low in the offensive zone with the puck. The D at the point just stepped down from the blue line because they saw a lane. They're now inside the zone at the top of the circles. What's the play?",opts:["Ignore the D — pass to the corner — you'll figure the rest out later","Pass to the D who stepped in — they now have a shot from a dangerous area","Shoot from the corner yourself — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Pass up the boards to a winger — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"A defenseman stepping down from the point into the top of the circles has created a scoring chance from a dangerous area. Hitting them in stride while inside the dots is a high-danger play.",tip:"D stepped in from the point? Hit them in stride. That's a dangerous shot location."},
    {id:"u11q75",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Short-side breakout",d:3,sit:"Your team is breaking out. The strong-side winger is completely covered. The D picks up the puck on the right side. The center is in the middle and the left winger is open on the short side. What's the right read?",opts:["Force the pass to the covered strong-side winger — the puck will sort itself out","Pass to the open left winger on the short side — shortest distance, cleanest","Carry it out yourself — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read hard","Rim it around the boards — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"The short-side winger being open is the clean, low-risk breakout pass. The shortest distance pass under pressure is usually the right one.",tip:"Short-side winger open? Take the short pass. Shortest distance = cleanest option."},
    {id:"u11q76",cat:"Coverage",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Screener coverage",d:2,sit:"The other team is on the power play. Their point man has the puck. One of their forwards is screening your goalie in front of the crease. What's your job as the nearest PK forward?",opts:["Chase the point man to stop the shot and avoid the dangerous area","Push the screener out of the crease area — your goalie needs to see","Stay in the passing lane — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Back up to your own blue line — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"The screener in front of the crease is the most dangerous player on the power play. Your job is to move them out — not chase the puck.",tip:"Screener in the crease? Move them out. Your goalie needs to see."},
    {id:"u11q77",cat:"Decision Timing",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Timeout assignment",d:3,sit:"Your coach calls a timeout with 30 seconds left and your team down by one. You're going back on after the timeout. What should be the first thing in your mind?",opts:["Just play hard — you'll figure the rest out later until someone tells you otherwise hard","Know your specific job for the next 30 seconds — faceoff role, where to go, who to cover","Try to score the first time you touch the puck — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Get pumped up and skate fast — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"A timeout is a chance to execute a specific play. Walking back on the ice with a clear assignment is more valuable than general energy.",tip:"Timeout: know your specific job before you go back out. Assignment over energy."},
    {id:"u11q78",cat:"Blue Line Decisions",pos:["D"],concept:"Cheat back slightly",d:3,sit:"You're the defenseman at the point. You see the opposing center beginning to break toward your blue line for a potential counter. Your team still has the puck. What do you do?",opts:["Follow the center toward your own zone — you'll figure the rest out later","Hold the blue line but cheat back slightly — be ready if the puck turns over","Ignore them — focus on the attack — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Call for the puck yourself — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"Reading a player beginning to position for a counter-attack lets you cheat back slightly. You stay at the line but you're ready. If the puck turns, you're in position.",tip:"Center positioning for counter? Cheat back slightly. Ready for the turnover."},
    {id:"u11q79",cat:"Offensive Pressure",pos:["F"],concept:"Second wave attack",d:3,sit:"Your first two forecheckers won the puck battle. They passed it to you as the third forward coming in. The D is still scrambling. What do you do?",opts:["Stop and wait to see what happens — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Attack the scrambled D immediately — they haven't recovered. Be the second wave.","Pass back to your own D — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read now","Skate to the corner — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"The second wave of a forecheck attacks the scramble. If the first two forwards won the battle and the D hasn't recovered, the third forward attacks the confusion immediately.",tip:"First wave won and D is scrambling? Second wave attacks immediately. Go."},
    {id:"u11q80",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Partial breakaway shoot fast",d:2,sit:"Late in a shift, you beat a tired defenseman at center ice and you're a step ahead but they're right behind you. What's the priority?",opts:["Try a complex deke to make it look good until someone tells you otherwise","Shoot as quickly as possible once you're in range — don't let the D recover","Pull up and wait for a teammate — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Skate slowly to get your breath — you'll figure the rest out later hard hard"],ok:1,why:"With a tired D right behind you, the clock is against you. Get in range and shoot before they recover. Complex moves give them time to catch up.",tip:"D right behind you on a partial break? Get in range and shoot fast. Don't deke."},
    {id:"u11q81",cat:"Coverage",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Net-front battle",d:2,sit:"The other team has a player parked in front of your net. You're the defenseman. What's the most effective way to move them?",opts:["Slash their stick — you'll figure the rest out later right away now","Get your body low and push them away from the crease — no penalty","Ignore them and focus on the puck and trust the play to develop","Try to lift their stick — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"Moving a player out of the crease is a legal physical battle. Getting low and pushing with your body — without using your stick — is how it's done without taking a penalty.",tip:"Player in your crease? Get low and move them with your body. No stick."},
    {id:"u11q82",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Goalie starts breakout",d:2,sit:"Your goalie stops a shot and has the puck. One winger is coming back and available. The forecheckers are still deep. What's the goalie's best move?",opts:["Freeze the puck for a faceoff — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Pass to the winger coming back — beat the forecheck before they can set up now","Rim it around the boards — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Shoot it down the ice — you'll figure the rest out later as fast as you can"],ok:1,why:"A goalie handling the puck can start the breakout before the forecheck resets. A crisp pass to the returning winger beats the pressure.",tip:"Goalie has it and a winger is coming back? Goalie starts the breakout. Beat the forecheck."},
    {id:"u11q83",cat:"Cycle Play",pos:["F"],concept:"Weak-side crash",d:2,sit:"Your team is cycling. The half-wall player shoots. You're the weak-side winger. What should you do the moment the shot is taken?",opts:["Stay on the weak side in case the shot goes wide immediately","Drive hard to the net — be there for the rebound on the weak side","Stay at the half-wall — you'll figure the rest out later hard hard","Back up to the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"The weak-side winger's job on a shot is to crash the net. Rebounds bounce wide to the weak side — being there before the shot lands is how you score on second chances.",tip:"Shot taken? Weak-side winger crashes the net. Every time."},
    {id:"u11q84",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK faceoff forward",d:3,sit:"Your team is on the penalty kill. You're the center taking a defensive zone faceoff. The power play wants to win the draw back to the point for a shot setup. What's your goal on this draw?",opts:["Win it backward to your D — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Win it forward — kick it toward the corner or boards to prevent the PP shot","It doesn't matter — just win it — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Tie up the opposing center after the draw — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"On a PK defensive zone faceoff, winning it forward — toward the boards or corner — takes away the PP's plan. Winning backward gives the PP exactly what they want.",tip:"PK faceoff in your own zone: win it forward. Take away the point shot."},
    {id:"u11q85",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Goalie breakout read",d:2,sit:"Your team is defending. The goalie makes a save and controls the puck. The other team has three forecheckers in your zone. Your wingers are pinned. What's the right breakout option?",opts:["Goalie holds the puck for a faceoff — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice","Goalie finds the center breaking through the middle or a winger escaping — don't give the puck to a covered player","Goalie shoots it down the ice — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice","Goalie rims it around the boards — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice"],ok:1,why:"After a save under forecheck pressure, the goalie needs to read the breakout. Finding the center or an escaping winger breaks the forecheck immediately.",tip:"Goalie made the save under pressure? Find the breaking player. Read the breakout."},
    {id:"u11q86",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Back up fast on 2-on-1",d:3,sit:"Two attackers are coming at you on a 2-on-1. They both have speed. The puck carrier is on your left. What's the first thing you do?",opts:["Commit to the puck carrier immediately — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Back up fast enough to not get beaten by their speed, stay in the middle, and force the shooter","Race toward the net — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on","Skate to the weak side — you'll figure the rest out later and let your teammates handle it"],ok:1,why:"Speed on a 2-on-1 is the attacker's advantage. Backing up fast enough while staying in the middle to take away the pass is the correct positioning.",tip:"Fast 2-on-1? Back up fast. Stay in the middle. Force the shot."},
    {id:"u11q87",cat:"Decision Timing",pos:["F","D"],concept:"First shot is best shot",d:2,sit:"You catch a pass in the slot. You see an opening to the top corner. But you hesitate for two seconds while repositioning the puck. The goalie recovers. What should you have done?",opts:["Always wait for the perfect shot — you'll figure the rest out later immediately","Released immediately on the catch — the opening was there when you first received it","Passed to a teammate instead — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read now","Skated in closer first — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"Hesitating in the slot gives the goalie time to recover. If there's an opening when you catch the puck, release immediately.",tip:"Opening in the slot? Release immediately. The best shot is the first one."},
    {id:"u11q88",cat:"Offensive Pressure",pos:["F"],concept:"Tire the D",d:2,sit:"Your team is in the offensive zone for a long shift. The defenders are getting tired. What should your forwards be doing to take advantage?",opts:["Slow down to save your own energy — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Keep cycling and creating traffic — tired defensemen make mistakes under sustained","Shoot from everywhere — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out","Change lines immediately — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out"],ok:1,why:"Sustained offensive zone pressure tires defensemen. Tired defenders make bad reads, miss sticks, and give up inside position.",tip:"D getting tired in your zone? Keep the pressure going. Fatigue creates mistakes."},
    {id:"u11q89",cat:"Cycle Play",pos:["F"],concept:"Open point",d:3,sit:"Your team is cycling and the slot is clogged. All four opponents are below the dots. What's the play?",opts:["Keep cycling and wait for the slot to open — you'll figure the rest out later as fast as you can","Pass back to the open point — four defenders below the dots means the point shot is uncontested","Shoot from the corner — you'll figure the rest out later until someone tells you otherwise","Dump the puck and change lines — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"When all four defenders collapse below the dots, the point is wide open. A point shot from there is uncontested and generates traffic and rebounds.",tip:"Four D collapsed below the dots? The point is open. Give it up. Free shot."},
    {id:"u11q90",cat:"Coverage",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Last man back",d:3,sit:"You're the last man back as two attackers come in on you. Your goalie is set. One attacker has the puck on the left. One is cutting to the net on the right. What do you do?",opts:["Commit to the puck carrier on the left — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","Stay in the middle — take away the pass to the cutter and force the shot. Your goalie handles the shot.","Chase the cutter to the right — you'll figure the rest out later until someone tells you otherwise","Back up to your crease — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice"],ok:1,why:"Last man back on a 2-on-1: take away the pass, force the shot, trust your goalie.",tip:"Last man back on a 2-on-1: take away the pass. Let the goalie have the shot."},
    {id:"u11q91",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Counter read after dead puck",d:3,sit:"Your team just had a power play chance and the goalie covered the puck. Faceoff in the offensive zone. You win the draw. Two of the other team's forwards are already breaking out. What's the immediate play?",opts:["Set up the power play again — you'll figure the rest out later and let your teammates handle it","Get the puck to a breaking teammate immediately — the 2-on-2 counter is better than resetting the PP","Hold the puck and regroup — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Dump it in and chase — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice"],ok:1,why:"Reading a counter-opportunity after a dead puck is advanced hockey sense. If two forwards are breaking and you win the draw, the counter is a better chance than resetting the power play.",tip:"Win the draw and teammates are breaking? Go. Counter-attack beats a reset every time."},
    {id:"u11q92",cat:"Blue Line Decisions",pos:["D"],concept:"Don't pinch on lost possession",d:3,sit:"You're the D at the offensive blue line. Your forward is about to lose possession to a defender. If that defender gets the puck clean, they can break with speed. Should you pinch?",opts:["Yes — pinch and help — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice","No — if possession is about to be lost, pinching puts you deep with no coverage during a fast","Go to the net instead — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the","Take a shot from the line as a distraction — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read hard"],ok:1,why:"The moment possession is about to be lost is the worst time to pinch. If the D gets the puck clean, they'll have a speed advantage with you caught deep.",tip:"Possession about to be lost? Don't pinch. Hold the line for the breakout."},
    {id:"u11q93",cat:"Puck Protection",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck battle at the net",d:3,sit:"You have the puck right in front of the opponent's net. A defender has grabbed your stick and a second is pushing you from behind. The goalie is scrambling. What do you do?",opts:["Stop and call for a penalty — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","Keep your feet moving and get your stick free — any shot or swipe on net is worth taking","Fall down to draw a penalty — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","Pass it out of the area — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"In front of the net under pressure, stopping your feet is the worst thing you can do. Keep moving, get your stick free, and put anything on net.",tip:"Front of net with defenders on you? Keep your feet moving. Get the stick free. Shoot anything."},
    {id:"u11q94",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reverse breakout",d:3,sit:"Your D picks up the puck. The left side breakout is shut down — the forechecker has cut it off. Your right side has a winger breaking free. What's the play?",opts:["Force the pass to the covered left side as fast as you can","Reverse — walk behind the net and find the open right side now","Rim it around — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Hold the puck and wait until someone tells you otherwise"],ok:1,why:"When one side of the breakout is shut down, reversing behind the net opens the other side. The forechecker can't cover both sides at once.",tip:"One side blocked? Reverse. The forechecker can't cover both."},
    {id:"u11q95",cat:"Decision Timing",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Read the ice not the noise",d:3,sit:"It's late in the third period. Your team is down by one. You get the puck in the offensive zone with one minute left. Your coach is yelling to shoot. You see a teammate in a clearly better position. What do you do?",opts:["Shoot immediately because your coach said to and hope for the best","Pass to the better position — the right play is still the right play","Hold the puck and think — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Skate to the bench — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"Coaches yell shoot to create urgency — but the right play is still the right play. A teammate in a clearly better position is worth the pass even late in the game.",tip:"Coach says shoot but a teammate has a better look? Pass. Read the ice, not just the noise."},
    {id:"u11q96",cat:"Cycle Play",pos:["F"],concept:"Quit the cycle",d:3,sit:"Your team has been cycling for 30 seconds. The defenders have perfectly matched your cycle. Nothing is opening. What should you do?",opts:["Keep cycling — eventually something will open — the puck will sort itself out","Stop cycling — dump the puck deep, change lines, and come back with a new entry","Shoot from the corner — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","Give the puck to your D at the point — you'll figure the rest out later hard hard"],ok:1,why:"A cycle against a perfectly matched defense that isn't creating anything is just burning your legs. Recognize when the cycle isn't working and come in with a different look.",tip:"Cycle going nowhere? Dump and change. Come back with a fresh entry."},
    {id:"u11q97",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP last 10 seconds",d:3,sit:"Your team has a power play with only 10 seconds left. You're in the offensive zone at the half-wall. No clear shot lane. What's the play?",opts:["Dump the puck in the corner and chase — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Shoot from wherever you are — any shot is better than nothing with 10 seconds left","Regroup and try to get set up — you'll figure the rest out later as fast as you can","Hold the puck and protect it — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"With 10 seconds left on a PP, the time to set up is gone. Shoot from wherever you are — any shot is better than the power play expiring with no attempt.",tip:"10 seconds left on the PP? Shoot from anywhere. Time's up."},
    {id:"u11q98",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Stick in the lane",d:3,sit:"You're a forward backchecking on a 2-on-1. Your D is in the middle taking away the pass. The shooter pulls up just inside the blue line and winds up for a slap shot. You're close. What can you still do?",opts:["Keep skating — you can't help anymore — you'll figure the rest out later","Get your stick in the shooting lane to deflect or block — you're close enough","Dive on the ice — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","Call for your D to rush the shooter — you'll figure the rest out later hard"],ok:1,why:"A backchecker who's close to the shooter has one job — get your stick in the lane. A deflected or blocked shot is massive. Every stick in the lane matters.",tip:"Shooter winding up and you're close? Get your stick in the lane. Deflect it."},
    {id:"u11q99",cat:"Offensive Pressure",pos:["F"],concept:"Third forward stays high",d:3,sit:"Your team forechecks 2-1-2. Both D and one forward are along the boards below the dots. You're the second high forward. The D has rimmed the puck to the far winger position. Who gets it?",opts:["You go — you're the nearest high player — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","The near winger goes — they're in better position. You stay high and be the next pass option.","Both of you go for it — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out right away","The D comes up to get it — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out"],ok:1,why:"The near winger retrieves the rim — that's their assignment. You stay high as the next option. If both forwards go deep, you lose your high forward safety.",tip:"Rim going to the far winger? Let them get it. You stay high. Don't both go deep."},
    {id:"u11q100",cat:"Decision Timing",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Back post is the best play",d:3,sit:"You're in the slot with the puck. The goalie is square. A defender is closing. Your teammate is breaking to the back post, completely open. The goalie has no idea. You have one second. What do you do?",opts:["Shoot — you're in the slot — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice","Pass to the breaking teammate — open player at the back post with goalie unaware is the highest-percentage play","Hold the puck — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice on","Skate behind the net — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice"],ok:1,why:"An open teammate at the back post with the goalie unaware is a higher-percentage chance than a slot shot against a set goalie. The selfless play is also the smart play — and recognizing it in one second is elite hockey IQ.",tip:"Teammate open at the back post with the goalie unaware? Pass. That's the highest-percentage play in hockey."},
  ,
    {id:"u11g1",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Angle cutting",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"A forward is coming in on a clean breakaway. You're on your line. As they cross the dots, what should you be doing?",opts:["Stay on your goal line — you'll figure the rest out later right away","Skate out to the top of the crease — cut the angle and take away net","Skate all the way out to meet them — the puck will sort itself out","Butterfly immediately — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"Coming out to the top of the crease dramatically cuts the shooting angle. The shooter sees far less net than if you stay on the line. You control how much net is available.",tip:"Breakaway coming? Get to the top of your crease. Take the net away."},
    {id:"u11g2",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Reading the 2-on-1",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"It's a 2-on-1. Your D has taken the middle and is forcing the shot. The puck carrier is cutting wide. What do you do?",opts:["Cheat toward the pass option — you'll figure the rest out later","Set for the shot — your D is taking away the pass, you take the shot now","Rush at the puck carrier — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Come out of your crease — you'll figure the rest out later right away"],ok:1,why:"When your D is properly taking away the pass on a 2-on-1, the goalie sets and takes the shot. Trust your D to do their job. Cheating toward the pass gives up the shot.",tip:"2-on-1 with D in position: trust them. Set for the shot."},
    {id:"u11g3",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Seam pass read",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"The power play has the puck at the half-wall. You're set slightly to that side. Suddenly the puck moves to the seam player at the top of the slot — close range. What happens?",opts:["Stay where you are — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","Push hard across — you're out of position for the new shot location. Get there fast.","Drop into butterfly immediately — you'll figure the rest out later as fast as you can","Come out of your crease — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"A seam pass that moves the puck from the half-wall to the high slot changes the shot angle completely. You have to push hard to get square to the new shooter — you were out of position for the half-wall shot.",tip:"Puck moves to the seam? Push hard to get square. Don't just react — move."},
    {id:"u11g4",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Tracking through screens",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"The point man is winding up for a shot and there's a screener standing right in your sightline. You can't see the puck. What do you do?",opts:["Give up — you can't see it — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later","Move laterally to find a gap around the screener, call to your D to move them, and be ready for a tip","Drop into butterfly and cover the bottom — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","Stay completely still — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice"],ok:1,why:"Screeners require active problem-solving. Moving to find the puck, calling for your D to move the screener, and being ready for a tip is the full response. Passive goalies get scored on by screens.",tip:"Screened shot: find the puck, call for help, expect a tip. Don't be passive."},
    {id:"u11g5",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Rebound control — direction",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"You make a save from the left side. You can control where the rebound goes. Where's the best place to send it?",opts:["Back to the shooter — you'll figure the rest out later hard now","To the right corner — opposite side from where the shot came","Straight up into the air until someone tells you otherwise","Anywhere in front of the net and trust the play to develop"],ok:1,why:"Sending the rebound to the far corner moves it away from the original shooter and the slot. Your defenseman on the right side can retrieve it and start the breakout.",tip:"Control your rebounds to the far corner. Away from the shooter, away from the slot."},
    {id:"u11g6",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Puck handling — pressure",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"A forechecker is coming hard around the left side. The puck is sitting behind your net. You get there first. What do you do with it?",opts:["Try to carry it yourself — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","Stop it for your left defenseman who is coming to get it — get the puck to their forehand now","Shoot it down the ice — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out","Freeze it — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice"],ok:1,why:"A goalie who handles the puck well under pressure is a huge asset. Stopping it cleanly for your D's forehand — not their backhand — sets them up for a clean breakout pass.",tip:"Play the puck to your D's forehand. Clean stop, clean pickup, clean exit."},
    {id:"u11g7",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Breakaway — shooter committed",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"A shooter is on a breakaway and dekes hard to their backhand. You start to go with them. They pull back to their forehand. What do you do?",opts:["Commit fully to the backhand — you're already going that way immediately","Stop your feet immediately and try to reset — don't fully commit to the fake","Fall down and cover the post — you'll figure the rest out later right away now","Come out further — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read"],ok:1,why:"Getting caught on a deke is recoverable if you stop your feet quickly. Fully committing to the first move gives the shooter the open side. Reset as fast as possible.",tip:"Caught on a deke? Stop your feet. Reset. Don't fully commit to the fake."},
    {id:"u11g8",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Post integration",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck carrier is tight to the right side, almost at the goal line. You've moved to your right post. They cut hard toward the middle. What do you do?",opts:["Stay on the post — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the","Push off the post and move with them — they've changed the angle and you need to stay square to the puck","Drop into butterfly on the post — you'll figure the rest out later and let your teammates handle it","Come way out into the crease — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on hard"],ok:1,why:"When the puck carrier moves, you move. Staying on the post as they cut to the middle leaves you square to the wrong angle. Push off and stay square to the puck.",tip:"Puck carrier moving? You move. Stay square to the puck, not to the post."},
    {id:"u11g9",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Coverage call",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"Your two defensemen are both going to the corner to battle for a puck. An attacker is cutting to the front of the net with nobody covering them. What do you do?",opts:["Do nothing — it's not your problem — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call hard","Call out loudly to your nearest forward — 'Front! Front!' — so they know to pick up the open player","Skate out to cover them yourself — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out","Drop into butterfly and wait — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out"],ok:1,why:"When your D are both going to the corner, the front of the net is exposed. The goalie sees this happening and must call for a forward to cover it. That verbal communication can prevent a goal.",tip:"D both going to the corner? Call 'Front!' immediately. Get someone on that player."},
    {id:"u11g10",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Low-high read",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"Your team is on the penalty kill. The power play passes it from the low corner up to the point quickly. You were set for the low play. What do you have to do?",opts:["Stay in your current position — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice","Move out to the top of your crease immediately — the point shot requires a different position than the low play","Drop into butterfly — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice","Back up to your goal line — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice"],ok:1,why:"Moving from a low play to a high point shot requires the goalie to reset position. Coming out to the top of the crease gives you the best angle on the point shot.",tip:"Puck goes from low to high? Push out to the top of your crease immediately."},
    {id:"u11g11",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Desperation technique",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"You're down and out of position. The puck is sliding toward an open corner of the net and you can't get up in time. What do you try?",opts:["Give up — it's a goal — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice on the ice","Throw your stick or extend whatever body part you can reach into the path of the puck — any contact can change its direction","Call for a penalty — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice on the ice hard","Stay still — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice on the ice on the ice"],ok:1,why:"Out-of-position desperation is a real skill. Throwing your blocker hand, extending your toe, or reaching with your stick can deflect a puck that would have been a sure goal. Never give up on a play.",tip:"Out of position? Reach with anything. A blocker or a toe can make a save."},
    {id:"u11g12",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Back-door coverage",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"You're set on the right post. The puck is on the right half-wall. A player cuts backdoor to the left post — completely open. The pass is about to happen. What do you do?",opts:["Stay on the right post — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the","T-push hard across to the left post — the backdoor player is the immediate danger, the half-wall shooter is not","Come out of your crease toward the puck — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out","Drop into butterfly on the right — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice"],ok:1,why:"A backdoor cut with a pass coming is one of the hardest situations for a goalie. You have to move fast — T-push to the new post before the puck arrives. Half a second matters.",tip:"Backdoor cut? T-push now. Get to the left post before the pass arrives."},
    {id:"u11g13",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Shooter telegraph",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"A shooter is coming down the right wing at full speed. Before they shoot you notice their elbow is dropping low. What does this usually mean?",opts:["Nothing — it's random — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read now","They're likely shooting high — a dropping elbow often indicates a high release","They're going to pass — you'll figure the rest out later — that's a bad read","They'll deke — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"Shooter reads are a real goalie skill at higher levels. A dropping elbow often indicates a high shot because the mechanics of a high release require the elbow to come down. Reading this gives you a fraction of a second head start.",tip:"Watch the elbow — dropping elbow often means high shot. Read the body before the release."},
    {id:"u11g14",cat:"Goalie",concept:"5-hole awareness",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"A shooter has the puck in tight and is trying to shoot between your legs. What's the best position to take away the 5-hole?",opts:["Spread your legs wide — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on","Keep your pads together or slightly overlapping and squeeze your knees — make the 5-hole as small as possible","Drop to the butterfly immediately — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on","Stand with feet shoulder width apart normally — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call"],ok:1,why:"The 5-hole — between a goalie's legs — is a target for good shooters. Keeping your pads together and squeezing your knees reduces that gap without sacrificing your ability to move.",tip:"Puck going low and center? Squeeze your knees. Close the 5-hole."},
    {id:"u11g15",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Freeze read — late game",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"Your team is winning by one goal with 90 seconds left. You make a save and the puck is loose at your feet. Your team has it covered nearby. Should you freeze it?",opts:["Freeze it immediately — kill the clock — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice","Leave it for your team — freezing it gives the other team a faceoff in your zone with 90 seconds left, which is dangerous","Kick it away — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice on the ice on hard","Throw it to the corner — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice on the"],ok:1,why:"Late game freeze decisions matter. Freezing the puck in your own zone gives the other team a faceoff set play — potentially with their best players — in your zone. If your team has control, leaving it lets them clear and kill more clock.",tip:"Leading late? Don't automatically freeze. If your team has it, let them clear. Faceoffs in your zone are dangerous."},
    {id:"u11g16",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Communication — D-to-D pass",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"You can see that both opposing forwards are sneaking behind your defensemen as your D make a D-to-D pass in the offensive zone. What do you do?",opts:["Say nothing — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice","Call out immediately — 'Two coming!' — to warn your D that forwards are breaking behind them","Wait to see if they notice — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","Call for a line change — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out hard"],ok:1,why:"Goalies see the whole ice and see counter-attack threats forming before anyone else. Calling out 'Two coming!' gives your D a chance to adjust before they make the pass and get caught.",tip:"You see the counter developing before anyone else. Call it out. Your voice is a defensive tool."},
    {id:"u11g17",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Rush positioning",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"Your team is defending a 3-on-2. The puck carrier has the puck on the right side. Where should you be in your net?",opts:["Dead center of the net — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later hard","Slightly cheated to the right — toward the puck carrier's side — while staying square to the puck","All the way to the right post — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out","All the way to the left post — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out"],ok:1,why:"On a rush with the puck on one side, the goalie cheats slightly toward that side while staying square to the puck. This takes away the near-side shot while leaving you positioned to move to cover a pass.",tip:"Rush with puck on one side? Cheat slightly toward it. Stay square. Be ready to move."},
    {id:"u11g18",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Wraparound read",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"An attacker carries the puck behind your net at speed, going from your left to your right. They're about to try a wraparound. What do you do?",opts:["Stay in the middle and wait — you'll figure the rest out later until someone tells you otherwise","Move with them — push to the right post as they come around and seal it. Don't let them get the post.","Come out of the crease to stop them — you'll figure the rest out later — it's not the right call","Drop to the butterfly immediately — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out"],ok:1,why:"On a wraparound, the goalie moves with the puck carrier and seals the near post as they come around. If you get to the post before they do, there's no open net to stuff the puck into.",tip:"Wraparound coming? Move with them. Seal the post before they get there."},
    {id:"u11g19",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Penalty shot read",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"A player is awarded a penalty shot. They're coming straight at you. They haven't shown you anything yet. What's your strategy?",opts:["Come all the way out to the blue line — you'll figure the rest out later — the puck will sort itself out","Come to the top of the crease, stay on your feet as long as possible, and force them to make the first move","Drop into butterfly immediately — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on hard","Stay on your goal line — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice"],ok:1,why:"On a penalty shot, coming to the top of the crease cuts the angle without over-committing. Staying on your feet as long as possible forces the shooter to make a decision — and every second they have to make a decision is a second you can read them.",tip:"Penalty shot: crease top, stay up, make them decide first. Patience wins."},
    {id:"u11g20",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Rebound — second shot danger",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"You make a save but the rebound goes to the slot. A player is right there and shoots immediately before you recover. What did you do wrong and what should you do differently?",opts:["Nothing — it's just bad luck — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice on the ice on the","Your rebound went to the most dangerous area. Direct rebounds to the corner, not the slot — or cover the puck if you can't direct it","Your position was wrong — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice on the ice on the ice","You should have frozen the first shot — you'll figure the rest out later — you'll figure the rest out later on the ice on the ice on the ice"],ok:1,why:"Rebound management is a key goalie skill. A rebound to the slot is the second-most dangerous play in hockey after an open net. Directing it to the corner or covering it prevents the second shot.",tip:"Rebound to the slot = danger. Direct to corners or cover. Never leave it in the slot."},

    // === SEQUENCE ORDERING QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u11seq1",cat:"Exiting the Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout sequence",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"Put the steps of a basic breakout in the correct order.",items:["D retrieves the puck behind the net","Wingers get up the boards and create outlet options","D makes a pass to the open winger","Center supports through the middle of the ice"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"A clean breakout starts with the D retrieving the puck, wingers getting open along the boards, then the D makes a pass, and the center fills through the middle for support.",tip:"Breakout: D gets it, wingers get open, pass, center supports. In that order."},
    {id:"u11seq2",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"3-on-2 rush sequence",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"Your team has a 3-on-2 rush. Put these steps in the correct order.",items:["Puck carrier enters the zone with speed and draws the first defender","Wide players drive the net and get open","Puck carrier reads the D and passes to the open player","Receiver shoots or makes the next play"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"A 3-on-2 works when the puck carrier draws attention first, wide lanes get filled, the read is made, and then the shot or next play happens.",tip:"3-on-2: draw, fill lanes, read, finish. Speed and sequence."},
    {id:"u11seq3",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Power play setup",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"Your team just got a power play. Put these steps in the right order to get set up in the offensive zone.",items:["Win the faceoff or gain possession","Enter the zone with control — carry or pass it in","Get to your assigned PP positions","Move the puck to find the open lane or shot"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"A power play starts with possession, then a clean zone entry, getting into formation, and then executing the puck movement to create a chance.",tip:"PP: win it, enter with control, get set, move the puck. Don't rush the setup."},
    {id:"u11seq4",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Defending a rush sequence",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"An attacker is rushing up ice toward you. Put the defensive steps in order.",items:["Skate backward and establish your gap","Read the attacker's speed and angle","Close the gap as they approach the blue line","Steer them to the outside with your body position"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"Good gap control is a sequence: establish position, read the attacker, close as they approach, then steer them wide. Skipping steps gets you beat.",tip:"Defend the rush in steps: gap, read, close, steer. Don't jump ahead."},
    {id:"u11seq5",cat:"Game IQ",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Faceoff routine",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"Your team is about to take a defensive zone faceoff. Put these steps in order.",items:["Know your assignment before the puck drops","Get to your position beside or behind the center","Win the draw back or tie up their center","Get to the puck first and make a quick play out of the zone"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"Faceoffs are structured. Know your job, get into position, compete on the draw, then execute. Players who don't know their assignment before the drop are already behind.",tip:"Faceoff: know your job, get set, compete, execute. Preparation wins draws."},
    {id:"u11seq6",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Turnover recovery sequence",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"Your team just turned the puck over in the offensive zone. Put the recovery steps in order.",items:["Recognize the turnover immediately","Nearest player pressures the puck carrier","Other forwards sprint back toward the defensive zone","Defensemen hold the blue line or retreat to proper gap"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"Transition defense is a chain reaction: recognize, pressure, backcheck, hold structure. The team that recovers fastest gives up the fewest odd-man rushes.",tip:"Turnover: recognize, pressure, backcheck, structure. Speed of reaction matters most."},
    {id:"u11seq7",cat:"Skating",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Line change sequence",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"You need to make a line change during play. Put these steps in the right order.",items:["Make sure your team has possession or the puck is in a safe area","Skate toward the bench — don't coast","Get close to the bench before your replacement jumps on","Fresh player jumps on and gets into the play immediately"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"A good line change requires timing. Changing at the wrong time or too slowly creates odd-man situations. Possession first, skate hard to the bench, short change, fresh player engages.",tip:"Line change: safe puck, skate hard to bench, short swap, fresh legs engage."},
    {id:"u11seq8",cat:"Puck Protection",pos:["F"],concept:"Cycle play sequence",d:3,type:"seq",sit:"Your team is starting a cycle in the offensive zone corner. Put the cycle steps in order.",items:["Win the puck battle along the boards","Protect the puck with your body and look for support","Pass to a teammate who's in motion along the wall or down low","Supporting players rotate to create the next passing option"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"The cycle is a continuous loop: win the battle, protect, pass, rotate. If any step breaks down — especially the rotation — the cycle dies.",tip:"Cycle: win the battle, protect, pass, rotate. Keep the loop going."},

    // === SPOT THE MISTAKE QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u11mis1",cat:"Coverage",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defensive zone coverage error",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"Your team is in the defensive zone. The other team has the puck. One of your teammates skates to the puck instead of covering their player. What's the mistake?",opts:["They should have stayed on the bench","They left their man open — in the D-zone, everyone needs to have a player covered before chasing the puck","They should have gone to the net","They skated too fast"],ok:1,why:"Chasing the puck in the defensive zone without covering your man first is one of the most common mistakes at U11. It leaves someone wide open for a pass and easy goal.",tip:"D-zone: cover your man first, then worry about the puck."},
    {id:"u11mis2",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Offside mistake",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"Your teammate carries the puck into the offensive zone. You're skating hard to join the rush but you cross the blue line before the puck does. What went wrong?",opts:["You were skating too slow","You entered the zone before the puck — that's offside. You need to time your entry so the puck crosses the line first.","You should have stopped at center","The puck carrier was too slow"],ok:1,why:"Offside kills momentum. The player without the puck must make sure the puck enters the zone before they do. Timing your entry is a basic but critical skill.",tip:"Blue line: puck goes first, then you. Time your entry."},
    {id:"u11mis3",cat:"Offensive Pressure",pos:["F"],concept:"Forecheck overcommit",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"On the forecheck, all three forwards go deep into the corner chasing the puck. The opposing D makes a quick pass up the middle and the other team breaks out with speed. What was the mistake?",opts:["The forwards weren't fast enough","All three forwards went deep — at least one forward needs to stay high to prevent the breakout pass through the middle","The defensemen were too far back","The goalie didn't stop the breakout"],ok:1,why:"Three forwards deep in the corner means nobody is covering the middle of the ice. The second or third forward needs to stay high to cut off the easy breakout pass.",tip:"Forecheck: never all three deep. Someone stays high. Always."},
    {id:"u11mis4",cat:"Blue Line Decisions",pos:["D"],concept:"Pinch at the wrong time",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"You're the D at the offensive blue line. The puck is loose along the boards. You pinch down to get it, but the opposing forward gets there first and goes around you for a breakaway. What was the mistake?",opts:["You should have pinched harder","You pinched when the puck wasn't clearly yours to win — if you can't get there first, hold the line instead of gambling","Your partner should have covered","The forward got lucky"],ok:1,why:"Pinching is a gamble. If you can't win the race to the puck, you're giving up your position and creating a breakaway. Only pinch when you're confident you'll get there first.",tip:"Pinch only when you'll win the race. If it's 50/50, hold the line."},
    {id:"u11mis5",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Slow backcheck",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"Your team loses the puck in the offensive zone. Two forwards stand and watch for a moment before skating back. The other team gets a 3-on-2 rush. What's the mistake?",opts:["The defensemen were out of position","The forwards didn't transition immediately — when you lose the puck, you turn and skate back right away, no watching","The goalie came out too far","The coach called the wrong play"],ok:1,why:"Standing and watching after a turnover is the number one transition mistake. The other team converts turnovers into rushes in seconds. Every moment of standing still is a step they gain on you.",tip:"Lose the puck? Turn and go. Immediately. No watching."},
    {id:"u11mis6",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK chasing the puck",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"Your team is on the penalty kill. One of your players keeps chasing the puck carrier around the zone instead of staying in the box formation. What's the mistake?",opts:["They should chase even harder","They're breaking the PK structure — on the penalty kill, stay in your box and force them to make plays around you instead of chasing","They should go to the bench","They need to ice the puck more"],ok:1,why:"The penalty kill box works because it covers passing lanes and takes away the middle of the ice. Chasing the puck opens up holes the power play will exploit.",tip:"PK: stay in the box. Let them move the puck around you. Don't chase."},
    {id:"u11mis7",cat:"Game IQ",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Too many men",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"During a line change, the fresh player jumps on the ice while the tired player is still at center ice skating slowly to the bench. The ref blows the whistle. What happened?",opts:["The ref made a bad call","Too many men on the ice — the fresh player jumped on before the tired player was close enough to the bench. The outgoing player needs to be within arm's reach of the bench.","Offside","Icing"],ok:1,why:"Too many men is an avoidable penalty. The outgoing player must be close to the bench before the new player jumps on. Communication and awareness prevent this.",tip:"Line change: don't jump on until the other guy is at the bench. Communicate."},
    {id:"u11mis8",cat:"Puck Protection",pos:["F"],concept:"Turning into pressure",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"You pick up the puck along the boards. A defender is coming from your right side. You turn to your right — directly into the defender — and lose the puck. What should you have done?",opts:["Turned faster","Turned away from the pressure — to your left — protecting the puck with your body between you and the defender","Shot the puck immediately","Called for help louder"],ok:1,why:"Turning into pressure is a guaranteed turnover. Always turn away from the check, putting your body between the puck and the defender. Read where the pressure is coming from before you turn.",tip:"Pressure coming? Turn away from it, not into it. Protect with your body."},

    // === WHAT HAPPENS NEXT QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u11next1",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"2-on-1 defender commits",d:1,type:"next",sit:"You're on a 2-on-1 with the puck. The lone defender suddenly slides toward your teammate to take away the pass. What happens next?",opts:["You pass anyway","You stop skating","You take the shot — the defender just opened the lane for you by leaving","You dump it in"],ok:2,why:"When the defender commits to the pass, they open the shooting lane. A smart player recognizes this immediately and shoots.",tip:"Defender leaves you to take the pass? Shoot. They just gave you the lane."},
    {id:"u11next2",cat:"Offensive Pressure",pos:["F"],concept:"Forecheck pressure result",d:2,type:"next",sit:"Your first forechecker pressures the D behind the net. The D panics and tries a blind backhand pass up the middle. What should happen next?",opts:["Your team backs off","Your second forward, who stayed high, intercepts the pass in the slot — that's exactly why they stayed high","Everyone goes to the corner","The play resets"],ok:1,why:"This is the payoff for staying high on the forecheck. The D under pressure makes a bad pass, and the high forward is in perfect position to intercept it in a dangerous area.",tip:"Forechecking works when someone stays high. They get the interception."},
    {id:"u11next3",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Attacker cuts inside",d:2,type:"next",sit:"You've steered the puck carrier to the outside with good gap control. Suddenly they cut hard back to the inside. What happens next?",opts:["You keep skating backward to the outside","You pivot and match their cut — stay on their inside hip and use your body to close them off","You stop and watch","You go for a hip check"],ok:1,why:"When an attacker cuts inside, the defender pivots with them and stays on the inside hip. You've already taken away the outside — now take away the middle too.",tip:"Attacker cuts inside? Pivot and stay on their inside hip. Don't let them get to the middle."},
    {id:"u11next4",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Quick counter-attack",d:2,type:"next",sit:"Your team forces a turnover at your own blue line. The other team's forwards are all deep in your zone. Your winger has the puck with open ice ahead. What happens next?",opts:["They dump it in and change","They attack with speed — the other team is caught deep, so this is a rush chance. Go now before they recover.","They pass it back to the goalie","They wait for everyone to get set"],ok:1,why:"Turnovers at the blue line with the other team caught deep are prime counter-attack opportunities. Speed is everything — attack before they recover their positions.",tip:"Turnover with them caught deep? Attack now. Speed beats recovery."},
    {id:"u11next5",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP cross-ice pass",d:3,type:"next",sit:"On the power play, the puck is on the left half-wall. The PK is overloading that side. Your teammate makes a sharp cross-ice pass to the right side where a player is wide open. What happens next?",opts:["The open player passes it back","The open player has a one-timer or clean shot — the PK can't recover across the ice fast enough, so this is a prime scoring chance","The open player skates to the corner","The play dies"],ok:1,why:"A cross-ice pass against an overloaded PK creates the best power play chance there is — a clean shot with the goalie moving laterally and the PK out of position.",tip:"Cross-ice pass finds the open man? That's the shot. The PK can't get there in time."},
    {id:"u11next6",cat:"Game IQ",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Icing the puck",d:1,type:"next",sit:"Your team is under heavy pressure in the D-zone. A defenseman panics and shoots the puck all the way down the ice from behind the red line. No one touches it. What happens next?",opts:["Play continues normally","The ref blows the whistle for icing — faceoff comes back to your zone and your tired players can't change","Your team gets a power play","The other team gets a penalty"],ok:1,why:"Icing brings the faceoff back to your zone and your tired players stay on the ice. It's a last resort, not a strategy. If you can make a short pass instead, that's always better.",tip:"Icing means a D-zone faceoff with tired legs. Avoid it if you can make any other play."},
    {id:"u11next7",cat:"Puck Protection",pos:["F"],concept:"Winning the board battle",d:2,type:"next",sit:"You're battling for the puck along the boards in the offensive zone. You get lower than the defender and pin the puck with your skate. Your linemate is calling for it. What happens next?",opts:["You hold it forever","You kick the puck to your stick and make a quick pass to your linemate before the next defender arrives — you won the battle, now use it","You leave it and skate away","You shoot it on net from the boards"],ok:1,why:"Winning the board battle only matters if you do something with it quickly. Get it to a teammate before the next wave of pressure arrives. Battle, win, move it.",tip:"Won the board battle? Move it quick. The next defender is already coming."},
    {id:"u11next8",cat:"Skating",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Gaining the zone with speed",d:2,type:"next",sit:"You pick up the puck at center ice with a full head of steam. The defender is flat-footed at the blue line. You have a clear speed advantage. What happens next?",opts:["You dump it in","You use your speed to carry the puck wide around the flat-footed defender — your speed advantage makes the carry the best option","You stop at the blue line","You pass it backward"],ok:1,why:"A flat-footed defender against a player with speed is a mismatch. Use the speed advantage to carry it wide. Dumping the puck in when you have a clear speed advantage wastes the opportunity.",tip:"Speed advantage against a flat-footed D? Carry it. Don't dump what you can carry."},

    // === TRUE/FALSE QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u11tf1",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Always shoot on 2-on-1",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"On a 2-on-1, you should always shoot no matter what the defender does.",ok:false,why:"On a 2-on-1, the right play depends on the defender. If they take you, pass. If they take the pass, shoot. Reading the defender is the whole point of a 2-on-1.",tip:"2-on-1 is about reading, not always shooting. Defender takes you? Pass. Takes the pass? Shoot."},
    {id:"u11tf2",cat:"Coverage",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Everyone covers a man in D-zone",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"In the defensive zone, every skater on your team should have an opposing player to cover.",ok:true,why:"Defensive zone coverage means every player picks up a man. If someone is left uncovered, the other team has an easy passing option for a scoring chance.",tip:"D-zone: five skaters, five assignments. Nobody floats."},
    {id:"u11tf3",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Wait after turnover",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"When your team loses the puck, it's okay to wait a second to see what happens before skating back.",ok:false,why:"There is no waiting after a turnover. Every second of standing still is a step the other team gains on their rush. Transition back is immediate — always.",tip:"Turnover means instant backcheck. No waiting. No watching. Go."},
    {id:"u11tf4",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK box formation",d:2,type:"tf",sit:"On the penalty kill, your team should form a box shape to protect the middle of the ice and the slot.",ok:true,why:"The penalty kill box takes away the most dangerous area — the slot and middle of the ice. It forces the power play to shoot from the outside where chances are lower.",tip:"PK box protects the slot. That's the whole idea. Stay in shape."},
    {id:"u11tf5",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Give lots of room on D",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"As a defenseman, you should give the attacker as much room as possible so they can't get around you.",ok:false,why:"Too much gap gives the attacker time and space to make plays. Good gap control means closing the distance so they have less time to decide, while still being able to match their speed.",tip:"Big gap = free time for the attacker. Close it down. Take away their time."},
    {id:"u11tf6",cat:"Game IQ",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Communicate on ice",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"Talking to your teammates on the ice — calling for the puck, calling out open players, warning about pressure — makes your team better.",ok:true,why:"Communication is one of the biggest advantages a team can have. Calling 'man on,' 'time,' 'wheel,' or 'open' gives your teammates information they can't see. Quiet teams get surprised.",tip:"Talk on the ice. Every call helps. Quiet teams lose pucks they didn't need to lose."},
    {id:"u11tf7",cat:"Offensive Pressure",pos:["F"],concept:"Everyone forecheck deep",d:2,type:"tf",sit:"On a forecheck, all three forwards should go deep into the zone to chase the puck.",ok:false,why:"If all three forwards go deep, there's nobody high to cut off the breakout pass or recover if the other team escapes the pressure. At least one forward stays high.",tip:"Forecheck: one or two deep, one stays high. Never all three in the corner."},
    {id:"u11tf8",cat:"Skating",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Glide to the bench",d:1,type:"tf",sit:"When making a line change, it's fine to glide slowly to the bench since your replacement is already coming on.",ok:false,why:"Gliding to the bench means you're on the ice longer without contributing and your team is effectively short a player in the play. Skate hard to the bench so the change is fast and clean.",tip:"Skate hard to the bench. Every second of coasting is a second your team plays short."},
    {id:"u11tf9",cat:"Puck Protection",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Body between puck and checker",d:2,type:"tf",sit:"When protecting the puck, you should keep your body between the puck and the opposing player at all times.",ok:true,why:"Puck protection is about body position. Your body is a shield — keep it between the defender and the puck, and they can't get it without going through you.",tip:"Puck protection = body position. Shield the puck with your body. Simple and effective."},
    {id:"u11tf10",cat:"Blue Line Decisions",pos:["D"],concept:"D always stays back",d:2,type:"tf",sit:"As a defenseman, you should never join the rush into the offensive zone.",ok:false,why:"Defensemen can and should join the rush when the situation is right — when there's a clear odd-man advantage or your partner is back to cover. Good D join the play; they just do it smartly.",tip:"D can join the rush — just make sure your partner has you covered. Smart D jump in at the right time."},
  ],
  "U13 / Peewee":[
    // EASY (d:1)
    {id:"u13q1",cat:"Blue Line Reads",concept:"Zone entry basics",d:1,sit:"You're the puck carrier entering the offensive zone. One defender is set at the blue line right in front of you. What's the right decision?",opts:["Dump it in because your teammates need time to set up and look for support","Read the defender — if they're set, use your linemate or chip it behind them","Dump it in rather than trying to force a risky play here before they score","Dump it in since the other team has committed to the other side right away"],ok:1,why:"A set defender at the blue line is telling you something. Read them — if they're set and you try to carry, you risk a turnover in the worst spot. Use your linemate or chip the puck in.",tip:"Defender set at the line? Read them. Chip, use your linemate, or carry — but read first."},
    {id:"u13q2",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"Man coverage",d:1,sit:"Three attackers enter your zone. You're the center on defense. Your two wingers have taken the two opposing wingers. Who do you cover?",opts:["Hold the puck now","The opposing center","Carry it wide now","Skate hard and recover"],ok:1,why:"In man-to-man defensive zone coverage, the center covers the opposing center. Covering your assignment — not the puck — is the foundation.",tip:"Three attackers in your zone? As the center, you've got their center. Find them and cover them."},
    {id:"u13q3",cat:"Rush Reads",concept:"3-on-2 middle lane",d:1,sit:"You're the center on a 3-on-2. Both defenders take your two wingers. The middle lane is completely open. What do you do?",opts:["Dump it in since the other team has committed to the other side hard","Shoot low since that creates the best look and look for support","Drive the middle lane and shoot — the defenders opened it for you","Shoot low before the play develops further and look for support"],ok:2,why:"When both defenders go wide to cover the wings, they've given you the middle. Drive it and shoot — the goalie is unscreened and the lane is open.",tip:"Both D go wide on a 3-on-2? Drive the middle. Shoot."},
    {id:"u13q4",cat:"Puck Management",concept:"Under pressure simple play",d:1,sit:"You have the puck in your own zone. A forechecker is closing hard. You have a D partner five feet away and wide open. What do you do?",opts:["Shoot low from your current spot hard","Pass immediately to your open D partner","Shoot low from your current spot soon","Dump it in since the lane is open now here"],ok:1,why:"Under pressure in your own zone, the simple play is almost always right. Open D partner five feet away — give it to them.",tip:"Under pressure with an open partner? Give it to them. Simple is smart."},
    {id:"u13q5",cat:"Finishing",concept:"Slot shot",d:1,sit:"You catch a pass in the slot. The goalie is set in the middle. You have a half-second. What's the best shot?",opts:["Skate hard rather than trying to force a risky play here while staying in position","Quick release low to the corner — the goalie has to move and can't get there in time","Skate hard because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice here","Protect the puck there and then get back into your defensive position before they score"],ok:1,why:"A set goalie in the slot means high shots are low-percentage — they're ready. Low, quick releases to the corner beat goalies who are set.",tip:"Slot with a set goalie? Quick low release to the corner. Speed beats power here."},
    {id:"u13q6",cat:"Breakouts",concept:"Breakout basics",d:1,sit:"Your defenseman picks up the puck in your own corner. As a winger, what's your job?",opts:["Shoot low along the boards from this spot","Get up the wall — be the outlet option","Pass back since the lane is open now","Skate hard while staying in position"],ok:1,why:"The winger's breakout job is to get up the wall fast and give the defenseman a clean outlet. If you go to the corner, you're in the same spot as the D with nobody to pass to.",tip:"D in the corner? You go up the wall. Get open."},
    {id:"u13q7",cat:"Special Teams",concept:"PP extra man",d:1,sit:"Your team is on the power play. You have the extra skater. What's the most important thing your team should be doing with that advantage?",opts:["Drop back and play defense since the other team has committed to the other side instead","Move the puck until you find the open player — the extra man means someone is always open","Get your stick in the lane because your teammates need time to set up before they score","Pull up at the hash marks rather than trying to force a risky play here and look for support"],ok:1,why:"The power play advantage is the extra skater. Moving the puck until you find who isn't covered exploits that advantage.",tip:"Power play: someone is always open. Move the puck until you find them."},
    {id:"u13q8",cat:"Gap Control",concept:"1-on-1 defense",d:1,sit:"An attacker is coming at you 1-on-1 at the top of your defensive zone. What's the right approach?",opts:["Get your stick in the lane and then get back into your defensive position at that point","Back up at a controlled pace, angle them toward the boards, and wait for their first move","Get your stick in the lane since the other team has committed to the other side quickly","Stay in the neutral zone and then get back into your defensive position and look for support"],ok:1,why:"Rushing a skilled attacker gives them the chance to blow past you. Backing up at a controlled gap while angling forces them to go where you want.",tip:"1-on-1 defense: angle, control your gap, make them decide first."},
    {id:"u13q9",cat:"Transitioning",concept:"Defensive transition",d:1,sit:"Your team just turned the puck over in the offensive zone. The other team has it and is breaking out. What should every forward do immediately?",opts:["Shoot low and hope for a better chance now","Turn around and backcheck hard — immediately","Shoot low since that creates the best look hard","Shoot low while your teammates recover now"],ok:1,why:"The instant the puck changes hands, every forward transitions back. The sooner you go, the less damage the other team can do.",tip:"Turnover? Turn around. Right now. Every forward."},
    {id:"u13q10",cat:"Cycle Play",concept:"Cycling purpose",d:1,sit:"Your team is cycling in the offensive zone. What is the cycle designed to create?",opts:["Set up behind the net and wait because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice again","Openings — shot lanes, slot passes, or players breaking free. Possession is the means, not the goal.","Crash the net for a rebound because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice now","Thread a pass to the slot and then get back into your defensive position while staying in position"],ok:1,why:"Cycling without purpose is just skating. The cycle is designed to move defenders and create openings — a slot pass, a shot lane, or a player breaking to the net.",tip:"Cycle: you're looking for the opening. Possession is the means, not the goal."},
    {id:"u13q11",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"Corner coverage",d:1,sit:"The puck goes into the corner in your defensive zone. You're the nearest forward. Your D is already going there. What do you do?",opts:["Pass back and hope for a better chance quickly","Hold the front of the net — don't leave it empty","Skate hard and then look for support from this spot","Pass back and hope for a better chance instead"],ok:1,why:"When your D goes to the corner, you cover the net front. Two players in the corner leaves the most dangerous area — the crease — completely empty.",tip:"D goes to the corner? You hold the net front. Don't follow them in."},
    {id:"u13q12",cat:"Finishing",concept:"Rebound position",d:1,sit:"Your teammate is about to shoot from the point. You're the nearest forward. Where should you be?",opts:["Carry it wide since that creates the best look and look for support","Crash the net — be there for the rebound before the shot arrives","Hold the puck from your current spot while staying in position","Hold the puck before the defense recovers and look for support"],ok:1,why:"Crashing the net before the shot arrives puts you in position for a rebound before the goalie can cover. Net-front presence on shots wins games.",tip:"Teammate shooting from the point? Crash the net. Get there before the puck does."},
    {id:"u13q13",cat:"Puck Management",concept:"Pre-read",d:1,sit:"A pass is coming to you in the offensive zone. Before the puck reaches you, what should you already be doing?",opts:["Take the outside lane since that creates the best look before they score","Looking up and deciding where you're going with the puck before it arrives","Take the outside lane before the play develops further before they score","Protect the puck there and hope for a better chance while staying in position"],ok:1,why:"Pre-reading the play — deciding where you're going before the puck arrives — is what separates slow players from fast ones.",tip:"Pass coming? Decide what you're doing with it before it arrives. Pre-read."},
    {id:"u13q14",cat:"Breakouts",concept:"Reading the forecheck",d:1,sit:"Your D picks up the puck. One forechecker is closing from the left. Your right winger is up the wall on the right — open. Your left winger is covered. What's the breakout call?",opts:["Drive to the net front rather than trying to force a risky play here instead","Pass to the open right winger — the forechecker has committed to the left side","Protect the puck there since the other team has committed to the other side early","Challenge at the line and hope for a better chance while staying in position"],ok:1,why:"The forechecker committing to one side creates an opening on the other side. Read the forechecker and use the open outlet.",tip:"Forechecker committed to one side? The outlet on that same side may be open."},
    {id:"u13q15",cat:"Gap Control",concept:"Back up fast",d:1,sit:"Two attackers are coming at you on a 2-on-1. They have speed. What's the first thing you do?",opts:["Hold your position at the crease since the other team has committed to the other side instead","Back up fast enough to not get beaten by their speed, stay in the middle, and force the shooter","Skate to the corner and dig it out since that creates the best look while staying in position","Skate to the corner and dig it out before the play develops further while staying in position"],ok:1,why:"Speed on a 2-on-1 is the attacker's advantage. Backing up fast enough while staying in the middle takes away the pass and forces the shot.",tip:"Fast 2-on-1? Back up fast. Stay in the middle. Force the shot."},
    // MEDIUM (d:2)
    {id:"u13q16",cat:"Blue Line Reads",concept:"Chip and chase",d:2,sit:"You're the puck carrier in the neutral zone at full speed. Two defenders are set at the blue line. Your linemate is trailing. Best entry?",opts:["Shoot from wherever you are now since that creates the best look while staying in position","Chip the puck past the inside defender and go get it, or use a give-and-go with your trailer","Shoot from wherever you are now before the play develops further while staying in position","Skate to the corner and dig it out since the other team has committed to the other side instead"],ok:1,why:"Carrying against two set defenders at the blue line is low-percentage. The chip-and-chase or give-and-go with the trailer are the smart options.",tip:"Two set defenders? Chip + go or use your trailer. Don't carry into a wall."},
    {id:"u13q17",cat:"Blue Line Reads",concept:"Pinch read",d:2,sit:"You're the offensive zone D at the blue line. The puck goes to the corner. Your winger is there and has possession, but a defender is closing. No coverage behind you. Your other winger is at the half-wall. Should you pinch?",opts:["Set up behind the net and wait since the other team has committed to the other side hard","No — your winger has possession and your half-wall winger can support. Hold the blue line.","Skate to the corner and dig it out since the other team has committed to the other side early","Set up behind the net and wait since the other team has committed to the other side soon"],ok:1,why:"Your winger has possession and the half-wall winger can support. You don't need to go. Pinching here with no coverage behind you risks a breakout against you.",tip:"Winger has it and half-wall can help? Hold the line."},
    {id:"u13q18",cat:"Blue Line Reads",concept:"D-to-D switch",d:2,sit:"You're the right D at the point on the power play. A PK forward is closing hard on you. Your left D partner is wide open. What do you do?",opts:["Challenge at the line rather than trying to force a risky play here again","Make a quick D-to-D pass to your partner — they're open and you're not","Chip it past them rather than trying to force a risky play here here","Chip it past them rather than trying to force a risky play here fast"],ok:1,why:"Under pressure at the point, the D-to-D pass resets the play. Your partner has time and a better look.",tip:"Pressure coming at the point? D-to-D. Let your partner reset."},
    {id:"u13q19",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"Reading the cycle",d:2,sit:"The other team is cycling below the dots in your zone. As the weak-side defenseman, when do you challenge the puck carrier?",opts:["Chip it past them because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice at that point","When a player with the puck is in a dangerous spot — near the slot or about to pass to the slot","Change lines because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice at that point","Back up and defend because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice quickly"],ok:1,why:"Defending the cycle means picking your moments. You don't challenge every pass — protect your position and challenge when the puck is in a truly dangerous spot.",tip:"Defending the cycle: stay in position. Challenge when dangerous, not just moving."},
    {id:"u13q20",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"Overload coverage",d:2,sit:"Three attackers enter your zone and overload the left side — two on the left, one on the right. Both your D are back. How do they adjust?",opts:["Chip it past them since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover hard","One D takes the two on the left, the other holds the middle and takes the weak-side attacker — both communicate","Chip it past them since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover soon","Back up and defend since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover now"],ok:1,why:"An overload forces the D to communicate and adjust. One D takes the strong side with two attackers, the partner takes the weak-side player and the slot.",tip:"Overload in your zone: communicate. One takes the strong side, the other holds the middle and weak side."},
    {id:"u13q21",cat:"Rush Reads",concept:"2-on-1 timing",d:2,sit:"You're the puck carrier on a 2-on-1. The lone defender is backing up in the middle, not committing to either side. What do you do?",opts:["Back up and defend while staying in position and look for support","Drive wide to force the defender to fully commit first, then decide","Drive to the net front since that creates the best look from this spot","Back up and defend and then look for support and look for support"],ok:1,why:"If the defender isn't committing, you haven't created the advantage yet. Drive wide to force their decision.",tip:"Defender not committing? Make them. Drive wide first."},
    {id:"u13q22",cat:"Rush Reads",concept:"Rush breakdown response",d:2,sit:"Your team rushes 3-on-2. The play breaks down and the other team gets the puck. You're the center, close to the play. What do you do first?",opts:["Change lines because your teammates need time to set up again","Pressure the puck carrier immediately to slow the breakout","Rim it around because your teammates need time to set up","Chip it past them before they react and look for support"],ok:1,why:"When a rush breaks down, the nearest forward pressures the puck immediately. Slowing their first move buys your teammates two seconds to recover.",tip:"Rush broke down? Pressure the puck immediately. Buy your team time."},
    {id:"u13q23",cat:"Finishing",concept:"Reading the goalie pre-shot",d:2,sit:"You're about to shoot from the slot. The goalie is leaning hard to your right. Where should you shoot?",opts:["Pull up at the hash marks because your teammates need time to set up on the play","Low left — the opposite side of where they're leaning. They can't recover in time.","Pull up at the hash marks and then get back into your defensive position quickly","Force a play through traffic because your teammates need time to set up at that point"],ok:1,why:"Pre-shot reads of the goalie give you a target before you release. A goalie leaning hard to one side is leaving the other side vulnerable.",tip:"Goalie leaning hard one way? Shoot the opposite side. They can't recover in time."},
    {id:"u13q24",cat:"Finishing",concept:"Breakaway — aggressive goalie",d:2,sit:"You're on a breakaway. The goalie is skating aggressively out to cut your angle. What's the most effective play?",opts:["Pass it to your D at the far point before the play develops further and look for support","Pull the puck wide, make the goalie commit to one side, then shoot or go to the other side","Challenge at the line because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice soon","Pass it to your D at the far point because your teammates need time to set up right away"],ok:1,why:"An aggressive goalie is looking for an early shot or for you to go straight. Make them commit — take the puck wide, let them follow, then shoot or go opposite.",tip:"Aggressive goalie on a breakaway: make them commit first. Then go where they're not."},
    {id:"u13q25",cat:"Breakouts",concept:"Reverse under pressure",d:2,sit:"Your team is under heavy forecheck pressure. The puck is won behind your net. Two forecheckers are pinching in from both sides. What breakout option gives you the best chance?",opts:["Carry it wide since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover instead","Reverse the puck to the other side — one forechecker can't follow, buying time for your winger to get position","Rim it around since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover quickly","Thread a pass to the slot because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice and look for support"],ok:1,why:"Under heavy forecheck pressure with two pinching forecheckers, the reverse gives you an extra second. One forechecker can't cover both sides simultaneously.",tip:"Two forecheckers pinching? Reverse the puck. One of them can't follow."},
    {id:"u13q26",cat:"Breakouts",concept:"Stretch pass",d:2,sit:"Your D picks up the puck. Both wingers are covered. Your center breaks free through the neutral zone — 40 feet away but completely open. What's the call?",opts:["Challenge at the line since forcing it would be risky here here","Thread the stretch pass to the center — they're breaking and open","Challenge at the line since forcing it would be risky here fast","Challenge at the line since forcing it would be risky here hard"],ok:1,why:"A stretch pass to a breaking center turns a defensive zone puck into an immediate rush chance. The reward — an odd-man rush — is worth the risk when the lane is clean.",tip:"Breaking center open on the stretch? Thread it. Risky but the reward is a rush."},
    {id:"u13q27",cat:"Cycle Play",concept:"Half-wall read",d:2,sit:"You're at the half-wall with the puck. The slot defender is watching the corner. Nobody is tight on you. What's the play?",opts:["Force a play through traffic since that creates the best look before they score","Shoot from the half-wall — you have time and the slot defender is distracted","Drop back and play defense because your teammates need time to set up hard","Drop back and play defense because your teammates need time to set up soon"],ok:1,why:"When the slot defender is watching the corner and nobody's tight on you at the half-wall, you have a shooting opportunity. Take it.",tip:"Nobody on you at the half-wall and slot D distracted? Shoot."},
    {id:"u13q28",cat:"Cycle Play",concept:"Cycle — when to quit it",d:2,sit:"Your team has been cycling for 30 seconds. The defenders have perfectly matched your cycle. Nothing is opening. What do you do?",opts:["Try to stickhandle through them and then get back into your defensive position first","Stop the cycle — dump the puck deep, change lines, and come back with a new entry","Force a play through traffic because your teammates need time to set up instead","Force a play through traffic rather than trying to force a risky play here here"],ok:1,why:"A cycle against a perfectly matched defense that isn't creating anything is burning your legs. Recognize when the cycle isn't working and come in with a different look.",tip:"Cycle going nowhere? Dump and change. Come back with a fresh entry."},
    {id:"u13q29",cat:"Special Teams",concept:"PP movement",d:2,sit:"Your power play is in a 1-3-1. The puck is at the top. A penalty killer closes hard on the top player. What should the top player do?",opts:["Pass it to your D at the far point because your teammates need time to set up on the play","Move the puck quickly before the pressure arrives — pass to the half-wall or the other side","Pass it to your D at the far point and then get back into your defensive position quickly","Swing wide along the boards since the other team has committed to the other side at that point"],ok:1,why:"On the power play, moving the puck before pressure arrives is the key. One extra skater means someone is always open — find them before the PK player gets there.",tip:"PP with pressure coming? Move the puck early. Someone is open."},
    {id:"u13q30",cat:"Special Teams",concept:"PK challenge timing",d:2,sit:"You're on the penalty kill. The power play is cycling below the dots. They're not shooting — just moving the puck. When should you challenge?",opts:["Drop back and play defense while your teammates recover at that point","When they slow down or seem to be setting up a shot — not on every pass","Get your stick in the lane because your teammates need time to set up hard","Drop back and play defense and wait for the play to reset on the play"],ok:1,why:"On the PK, challenging on every pass runs you out of position. Pick your moments — challenge when the puck carrier is stationary or loading up.",tip:"PK: don't bite on every pass. Pick your moment. Challenge when it counts."},
    {id:"u13q31",cat:"Puck Management",concept:"Leading late",d:2,sit:"Your team is winning by one goal with two minutes left. You win a faceoff in the offensive zone. What's most important?",opts:["Force a play through traffic since the other team has committed to the other side right away","Control the puck, cycle below the dots, use every second — only shoot on a high-quality chance","Dump it in since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover","Thread a pass to the slot rather than trying to force a risky play here and look for support"],ok:1,why:"Late-game puck management is a skill. Cycling below the dots burns clock, forces the other team to chase, and keeps the puck away from their skilled players.",tip:"Leading late: the clock is your ally. Protect the puck. Make them chase."},
    {id:"u13q32",cat:"Puck Management",concept:"Quick outlet",d:2,sit:"You win a puck battle in your own corner. Forecheckers are still coming hard. What's the fastest way out?",opts:["Pull up at the hash marks since that creates the best look from this spot","Move the puck quickly — first open option up the wall or through the middle","Swing wide along the boards before the play develops further before they score","Pull up at the hash marks before the play develops further from this spot"],ok:1,why:"When forecheckers are bearing down, speed of decision matters more than finding the perfect option. First clean outlet — take it.",tip:"Forecheckers coming fast? Move the puck. First clean option. Go."},
    {id:"u13q33",cat:"Transitioning",concept:"Counter read",d:2,sit:"Your team just had a power play chance and the goalie covered the puck. Faceoff in the offensive zone. You win the draw. Two of the other team's forwards are already breaking out. What's the immediate play?",opts:["Pass it to your D at the far point rather than trying to force a risky play here before they score","Get the puck to a breaking teammate immediately — the 2-on-2 counter is better than resetting the PP","Pass it to your D at the far point since the other team has committed to the other side right away","Dump it in because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice and look for support"],ok:1,why:"Reading a counter-opportunity after a dead puck is advanced hockey sense. If two forwards are breaking and you win the draw, the counter is a better chance than resetting the power play.",tip:"Win the draw and teammates are breaking? Go. Counter-attack beats a reset every time."},
    {id:"u13q34",cat:"Transitioning",concept:"PP transition defense",d:2,sit:"Your team is on the power play. The penalty kill gets the puck and two players immediately break the other way 2-on-2. What should your team do?",opts:["Swing wide along the boards rather than trying to force a risky play here soon","One forward pressures the puck, the others recover their positions — don't panic","Shoot from wherever you are now and wait for the play to reset and look for support","Swing wide along the boards and then get back into your defensive position now"],ok:1,why:"A PP counter-attack is dangerous but not a guaranteed goal. One player pressures, everyone else recovers. Panicking and all chasing creates a turnover.",tip:"PK breaks out on a counter? One pressures, others recover. Don't panic."},
    {id:"u13q35",cat:"Gap Control",concept:"Contain the skilled forward",d:2,sit:"A skilled forward is coming at you 1-on-1 at full speed. They're a known stickhandler. What do you avoid doing?",opts:["Drive to the net front since the lane is open now early","Poking check from maximum distance or charging them early","Drive to the net front before the defense recovers here","Drive to the net front before the defense recovers fast"],ok:1,why:"A skilled stickhandler wants you to commit early — a premature poke check gives them exactly the step they need to blow past you. Stay patient.",tip:"Skilled forward 1-on-1? Don't commit early. Stay patient. Make them decide first."},
    {id:"u13q36",cat:"Gap Control",concept:"Don't commit to a fake",d:2,sit:"You're the defenseman and an attacker fakes to the backhand. You start to move with the fake. What do you do next?",opts:["Swing wide along the boards since the lane is open now and look for support","Stop your movement, reset your feet, and regain your gap — don't fully commit","Swing wide along the boards since that creates the best look from this spot","Swing wide along the boards before the play develops further from this spot"],ok:1,why:"Getting caught on a fake is recoverable if you stop your feet and reset quickly. Fully committing to the fake loses the gap entirely.",tip:"Bit on a fake? Stop your feet immediately and reset. Don't chase the fake."},
    {id:"u13q37",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"Screening on PK",d:2,sit:"The other team is on the power play. A forward is screening your goalie right in front of the crease. The puck is at the point. What's your job as the nearest PK player?",opts:["Challenge at the line before the defense recovers right away","Move the screener out of the crease — your goalie needs to see","Challenge at the line and hope for a better chance right now","Pressure the carrier hard while staying in position at that point"],ok:1,why:"A screener blocking your goalie's sightline is the most dangerous player on the ice. Moving them out is the priority — before the shot is taken.",tip:"Screener in the crease? Move them out. Your goalie needs to see."},
    {id:"u13q38",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"PK box integrity",d:2,sit:"Your team is on the penalty kill in a box formation. The power play moves the puck quickly around the outside. One of your PK players starts chasing every pass. What goes wrong?",opts:["Hold your position at the crease because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice hard","Chasing breaks the box — gaps open up and the power play gets into the dangerous areas you were protecting","Hold your position at the crease because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice soon","Back up and defend since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover now"],ok:1,why:"The box on the penalty kill works because every player holds their position. Chasing every pass breaks the structure and creates gaps the power play exploits.",tip:"PK box: hold your spot. Don't chase every pass. The box works when everyone stays in it."},
    {id:"u13q39",cat:"Finishing",concept:"Front of net battle",d:2,sit:"You have the puck right in front of the opponent's net. A defender has grabbed your stick and a second is pushing you from behind. The goalie is scrambling. What do you do?",opts:["Pass it to your D at the far point and then get back into your defensive position soon","Keep your feet moving and get your stick free — any shot or swipe on net is worth taking","Shoot low because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice right now","Pass back because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice right now"],ok:1,why:"In front of the net under pressure, stopping your feet is the worst thing you can do. Keep moving, get your stick free, and put anything on net.",tip:"Front of net with defenders on you? Keep your feet moving. Get the stick free. Shoot anything."},
    {id:"u13q40",cat:"Finishing",concept:"Tip drill",d:2,sit:"A shot comes from the blue line right at the middle of the net. You're standing in front of the goalie. What's your job?",opts:["Skate to the corner and dig it out because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice fast","Tip the puck — even a slight redirection completely changes the trajectory and defeats the goalie's tracking","Skate to the corner and dig it out because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice hard","Hold your position at the crease because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice on the play"],ok:1,why:"Tipping a shot on net is one of the most effective plays in hockey. Even a small deflection changes the trajectory enough to beat a goalie who is tracking the original shot.",tip:"Shot coming from the point right at the goalie? Tip it. Any deflection beats their tracking."},
    // HARD (d:3)
    {id:"u13q41",cat:"Blue Line Reads",concept:"Point fake",d:3,sit:"You're the point on the power play. You have the puck and a shooting lane — but two PK forwards are closing on you hard. You have one second. What's the best play?",opts:["Pressure the carrier hard because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice from this spot","Fake the shot to freeze them, then pass to the half-wall player who opened up when the PKers committed to you","Drop back and play defense because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice at that point","Get your stick in the lane because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice at that point"],ok:1,why:"When two PK players commit to you, they've left someone open. A shot fake freezes them for a split second — the half-wall opens up the instant they both lean at you.",tip:"Two PKers closing? Fake the shot. Someone opened up when they committed."},
    {id:"u13q42",cat:"Blue Line Reads",concept:"Pinch timing",d:3,sit:"You're the offensive zone D at the blue line. Your forward is about to lose possession of the puck in the corner to a defender who can break with speed. Should you pinch?",opts:["Swing wide along the boards because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice again","No — if possession is about to be lost, pinching puts you deep with no coverage during a fast breakout","Swing wide along the boards because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice early","Try to stickhandle through them because your teammates need time to set up while staying in position"],ok:1,why:"The moment possession is about to be lost is the worst time to pinch. If the D gets the puck clean, they'll have a speed advantage with you caught deep.",tip:"Possession about to be lost in the corner? Don't pinch. Hold the line."},
    {id:"u13q43",cat:"Blue Line Reads",concept:"Cheat back for counter",d:3,sit:"You're the D at the point. You see the opposing center beginning to break toward your blue line for a potential counter. Your team still has the puck. What do you do?",opts:["Chip it past them because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice","Hold the blue line but cheat back slightly — be ready to pursue if the puck turns over","Force a play through traffic since the other team has committed to the other side quickly","Take the outside lane since forcing it would be risky here while staying in position"],ok:1,why:"Reading a player beginning to position for a counter lets you cheat back slightly. You stay at the line but you're ready. If the puck turns, you're in position.",tip:"Center positioning for a counter? Cheat back slightly. Ready for the turnover."},
    {id:"u13q44",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"Trap recognition",d:3,sit:"The other team is sitting back in a 1-2-2 neutral zone trap. Every time your team tries to enter, they get stopped at the red line. What adjustment do you make?",opts:["Back up and defend since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover again","Pull the puck back to your D, use a D-to-D pass to overload one side, or try a stretch pass to a breaking forward","Back up and defend since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover early","Try to stickhandle through them because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice before they score"],ok:1,why:"A 1-2-2 trap is designed to stop straight-line carries. The answer is patience and lateral movement — go backward to go forward.",tip:"Against a trap: go backward to go forward. Change the angle. Be patient."},
    {id:"u13q45",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"Last man back",d:3,sit:"You're the last defender back as two attackers come in on you. One has the puck on the left. One is cutting to the net on the right. What do you do?",opts:["Skate hard since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover now","Stay in the middle — take away the pass to the cutter and force the shot. Your goalie handles the shot.","Hold the puck because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice and look for support","Carry it wide because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice and look for support"],ok:1,why:"Last man back on a 2-on-1: take away the pass, force the shot, trust your goalie. Don't commit to either attacker until they force your hand.",tip:"Last man back on a 2-on-1: take away the pass. Let the goalie have the shot."},
    {id:"u13q46",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"Late attacker",d:3,sit:"Two attackers entered your zone and both D picked them up. A third attacker trails in 5 seconds later — nobody picked them up. You're the center on defense. What do you do?",opts:["Pass back because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice soon","Pick up the late attacker — your winger on that side needs to find their assignment","Drive to the net front because your teammates need time to set up and look for support","Skate hard since the other team has committed to the other side before they score"],ok:1,why:"A late attacker entering the zone creates a coverage breakdown. The center needs to pick them up or communicate a switch immediately.",tip:"Late attacker uncovered? Call it and pick them up. Coverage gaps get exploited."},
    {id:"u13q47",cat:"Rush Reads",concept:"Goalie reads the 2-on-1",d:3,sit:"You're the puck carrier on a 2-on-1. The defender commits fully to your teammate. The goalie slides across expecting your pass. What's the right call now?",opts:["Drop back and play defense while staying in position first","Shoot — the goalie has moved and there's a lane on your side","Pull up at the hash marks along the boards and look for support","Drop back and play defense while staying in position again"],ok:1,why:"When the defender commits to your teammate AND the goalie slides to take away the pass, they've left your side open. Shoot — the goalie has moved.",tip:"2-on-1: if the goalie chases the pass, shoot. Read the goalie."},
    {id:"u13q48",cat:"Rush Reads",concept:"Backcheck weak side",d:3,sit:"Your team turns the puck over. The other team has a 2-on-1 and you're the only forward close enough to get back. You can't catch the puck carrier. What do you do?",opts:["Skate to the corner and dig it out rather than trying to force a risky play here at that point","Skate back hard on the weak side — get between the second attacker and the net to support your D","Pass it to your D at the far point rather than trying to force a risky play here at that point","Take the outside lane because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice right away"],ok:1,why:"You can't catch the puck carrier, but you can take away the pass option on the weak side. Get behind the play on the weak side and take away the easiest option.",tip:"Can't catch the puck carrier? Get to the weak side. Take away the pass."},
    {id:"u13q49",cat:"Rush Reads",concept:"Counter after dead puck",d:3,sit:"Your team just finished a power play chance and the goalie covered the puck. You're a forward who just won the faceoff in the offensive zone. You see two opponents already breaking out. What's the immediate play?",opts:["Pass it to your D at the far point because your teammates need time to set up and look for support","Get the puck to a breaking teammate immediately — the 2-on-2 counter is better than resetting the PP","Pass it to your D at the far point rather than trying to force a risky play here before they score","Pass it to your D at the far point since the other team has committed to the other side right away"],ok:1,why:"Reading a counter-opportunity after a dead puck is advanced hockey sense. If two forwards are breaking and you win the draw, the counter is a better chance than resetting.",tip:"Win the draw and teammates are breaking? Go. Counter-attack beats a reset every time."},
    {id:"u13q50",cat:"Finishing",concept:"Slot — open but defended",d:3,sit:"You're in the slot with the puck. The goalie is square. A defender is closing from your left. Your teammate is breaking to the back post, completely open. The goalie has no idea. You have one second. What do you do?",opts:["Take the outside lane because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice while staying in position","Pass to the breaking teammate — open player at the back post with goalie unaware is the highest-percentage play","Set up behind the net and wait because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice on the play","Try to stickhandle through them because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice right away"],ok:1,why:"An open teammate at the back post with the goalie unaware is a higher-percentage chance than a slot shot against a set goalie. The selfless play is also the smart play.",tip:"Teammate open at the back post with the goalie unaware? Pass. That's the highest-percentage play in hockey."},
    {id:"u13q51",cat:"Finishing",concept:"Tight angle backhand",d:3,sit:"You're in tight to the net — five feet out. The goalie is set. You have the puck on your backhand but barely any time. What do you do?",opts:["Carry it wide since the other team has committed to the other side at that point","Release your backhand immediately — the goalie is set for the forehand anyway","Skate to the corner and dig it out and hope for a better chance on the play","Skate to the corner and dig it out while your teammates recover on the play"],ok:1,why:"In tight to the net with time running out, a quick backhand release is often better than taking the time to switch to your forehand. The goalie is already set for the forehand.",tip:"In tight with time running out? Shoot what you've got. Don't switch hands."},
    {id:"u13q52",cat:"Finishing",concept:"One-timer recognition",d:3,sit:"You're on the power play at the half-wall. The puck carrier passes it to you in stride. The goalie is leaning left. What's the right play?",opts:["Get your stick in the lane since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover now","One-time it to the right side where the goalie hasn't moved yet — quick release beats the goalie before they can adjust","Pull up at the hash marks since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover here","Pull up at the hash marks since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover fast"],ok:1,why:"A one-timer on the power play catches the goalie before they can reset. Stopping the puck gives them time to adjust — a quick release doesn't.",tip:"Pass comes in stride with the goalie leaning? One-time it. Quick release wins."},
    {id:"u13q53",cat:"Breakouts",concept:"D carry out",d:3,sit:"Two forecheckers are deep in your zone. Your winger is up the wall but covered. Your center in the middle is also covered. Your D has the puck behind the net. What's the best option?",opts:["Drop back and play defense since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover soon","Wheel and carry it out — both forecheckers are committed to your forwards. The D carrying it out is now the best option.","Shoot from wherever you are now since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover fast","Get your stick in the lane since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover here"],ok:1,why:"When both forecheckers have committed to your forwards and left the D unguarded, the D carrying it out is the right play.",tip:"Both forecheckers on your forwards? D carry it out. The lane is open."},
    {id:"u13q54",cat:"Breakouts",concept:"Reading both D pinching",d:3,sit:"Your team breaks out. As you cross the red line you see both opposing defensemen are pinching up — they're at the red line, not their blue line. What do you do?",opts:["Skate hard because your teammates need time to set up while staying in position","Skate hard behind them — you have a breakaway if you beat them to their blue line","Pull up at the hash marks since the other team has committed to the other side first","Change lines rather than trying to force a risky play here and look for support"],ok:1,why:"Defensemen pinching up means they've given up the space behind them. If you can beat them to the puck, you have a breakaway or a clean zone entry.",tip:"Both D pinching up? Burn them. Get behind them before they recover."},
    {id:"u13q55",cat:"Breakouts",concept:"Short side option",d:3,sit:"Your team is breaking out. The strong-side winger is completely covered. The D picks up the puck on the right side. The center is in the middle and the left winger is open on the short side. What's the right read?",opts:["Change lines since the other team has committed to the other side at that point","Pass to the open left winger on the short side — shortest distance, cleanest pass","Change lines because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice","Chip it past them and then get back into your defensive position from this spot"],ok:1,why:"The short-side winger being open is the clean, low-risk breakout pass. The shortest distance pass under pressure is usually the right one.",tip:"Short-side winger open? Take the short pass. Shortest distance = cleanest option."},
    {id:"u13q56",cat:"Cycle Play",concept:"D stepped in",d:3,sit:"You're low in the offensive zone with the puck. The D at the point just stepped down from the blue line into the zone at the top of the circles. They have a lane. What's the play?",opts:["Hold your position at the crease since the lane is open now on the play","Pass to the D who stepped in — they now have a shot from a dangerous area","Hold your position at the crease before the defense recovers right away","Pass it to your D at the far point since forcing it would be risky here hard"],ok:1,why:"A defenseman stepping down from the point into the top of the circles has created a scoring chance from a dangerous area. Hitting them in stride while inside the dots is a high-danger play.",tip:"D stepped in from the point? Hit them in stride. That's a dangerous shot location."},
    {id:"u13q57",cat:"Cycle Play",concept:"Open point — all D collapsed",d:3,sit:"Your team is cycling and the slot is clogged. All four opponents are below the dots. What's the play?",opts:["Take the outside lane rather than trying to force a risky play here while staying in position","Pass back to the open point — four defenders below the dots means the point shot is uncontested","Take the outside lane because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice here","Take the outside lane because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice fast"],ok:1,why:"When all four defenders collapse below the dots, the point is wide open. A point shot from there is uncontested and generates traffic and rebounds.",tip:"Four D collapsed below the dots? The point is open. Give it up. Free shot."},
    {id:"u13q58",cat:"Cycle Play",concept:"Seam pass in the cycle",d:3,sit:"You're at the half-wall with the puck. The near penalty killer is cheating toward you. The player in the middle — the seam — is now open. What's the play?",opts:["Take the outside lane because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice hard","Thread the seam pass to the middle player — the PK forward cheating toward you opened that lane","Take the outside lane because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice soon","Drive to the net front since the other team has committed to the other side before they score"],ok:1,why:"When the PK forward cheats toward you, they've vacated the seam. The middle player is open. The seam pass is the highest-danger play.",tip:"Defender cheated toward you? The seam is open. Thread it."},
    {id:"u13q59",cat:"Special Teams",concept:"PP — 10 seconds left",d:3,sit:"Your team has a power play with only 10 seconds left. You're in the offensive zone at the half-wall. No clear shot lane. What's the play?",opts:["Challenge at the line since that creates the best look while staying in position","Shoot from wherever you are — any shot is better than nothing with 10 seconds left","Challenge at the line before the play develops further while staying in position","Challenge at the line and then get back into your defensive position on the play"],ok:1,why:"With 10 seconds left on a PP, the time to set up is gone. Shoot from wherever you are — any shot is better than the power play expiring with no attempt.",tip:"10 seconds left on the PP? Shoot from anywhere. Time's up."},
    {id:"u13q60",cat:"Special Teams",concept:"PP adjustment",d:3,sit:"Your team's power play is struggling. The PK has collapsed everything to the slot and the point. What adjustment do you make?",opts:["Try to stickhandle through them and then get back into your defensive position while staying in position","Pull the puck back out of the zone, reset, and come in with a new entry that attacks a different spot","Hold your position at the crease since the other team has committed to the other side at that point","Hold your position at the crease because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice"],ok:1,why:"When the PK has your power play figured out and collapsed, pull back and re-enter with a different attack angle. Don't keep running the same play into a locked door.",tip:"PP getting shut down? Pull back and reset. Come in differently."},
    {id:"u13q61",cat:"Special Teams",concept:"PK faceoff forward",d:3,sit:"Your team is on the penalty kill. You're the center taking a defensive zone faceoff. The power play wants to win the draw back to the point for a shot setup. What's your goal on this draw?",opts:["Drive to the net front and then get back into your defensive position right now","Win it forward — kick it toward the corner or boards to prevent the PP shot setup","Swing wide along the boards since the other team has committed to the other side now","Drive to the net front since the other team has committed to the other side now"],ok:1,why:"On a PK defensive zone faceoff, winning it forward — toward the boards or corner — takes away the PP's plan. Winning backward gives the PP exactly what they want.",tip:"PK faceoff in your own zone: win it forward. Take away the point shot."},
    {id:"u13q62",cat:"Special Teams",concept:"PK mindset on a clear",d:3,sit:"Your penalty kill gets the puck out of your zone. It's a 2-on-3 as you exit. Do you try to score shorthanded or just clear?",opts:["Pull up at the hash marks and hope for a better chance early","Clear the zone and get back — a clean clear is a win on the PK","Force a play through traffic and wait for the play to reset early","Pull up at the hash marks while your teammates recover first"],ok:1,why:"A clean clear on the PK is a win — it kills clock and resets the power play. Shorthanded goals happen but they shouldn't be the plan.",tip:"PK clear: clean exit = success. Don't gamble on a shorthanded goal."},
    {id:"u13q63",cat:"Gap Control",concept:"Stick in the lane",d:3,sit:"You're a forward backchecking on a 2-on-1. Your D is in the middle taking away the pass. The shooter pulls up just inside the blue line and winds up for a slap shot. You're close. What can you still do?",opts:["Chip it past them since the other team has committed to the other side hard","Get your stick in the shooting lane to deflect or block — you're close enough","Chip it past them since the other team has committed to the other side soon","Protect the puck there since the other team has committed to the other side hard"],ok:1,why:"A backchecker who's close to the shooter has one job — get your stick in the lane. A deflected or blocked shot is massive. Every stick in the lane matters.",tip:"Shooter winding up and you're close? Get your stick in the lane. Deflect it."},
    {id:"u13q64",cat:"Gap Control",concept:"Rush gap — back up speed",d:3,sit:"Three attackers are rushing at your two defensemen. All three are at top speed. What's the biggest mistake a defenseman can make here?",opts:["Hold the puck and then get back into your defensive position at that point","Pinching up — closing aggressively on the puck carrier instead of backing up","Hold the puck since the other team has committed to the other side quickly","Hold the puck since the other team has committed to the other side instead"],ok:1,why:"Pinching up against a fast rush hands the attacking team a massive speed advantage. Backing up at the right controlled pace is the correct response.",tip:"Rush coming with speed? Back up controlled. Never pinch up against a fast rush."},
    {id:"u13q65",cat:"Puck Management",concept:"Read the whole play",d:3,sit:"You have the puck at center ice. A 3-on-2 is developing. Your left winger is on the left, your right winger is on the right, and a forward is trailing. Both defenders are inside. What's the read?",opts:["Try to stickhandle through them since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover fast","Look at both defenders first — pass to whichever winger the defenders are leaving more open, or drive the middle if it's open","Try to stickhandle through them since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover hard","Try to stickhandle through them since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover soon"],ok:1,why:"Reading both defenders first tells you which option is actually open before you commit. The best puck carrier reads the whole ice, not just one option.",tip:"3-on-2 developing? Read both defenders before picking your option."},
    {id:"u13q66",cat:"Puck Management",concept:"Delay game late",d:3,sit:"Your team is winning by one goal with 90 seconds left. You win a puck battle in the neutral zone. What's the right thing to do with the puck?",opts:["Cut to the middle of the ice because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice instead","Control the puck along the boards, protect it, and force the other team to come get it — use every second","Set up behind the net and wait and then get back into your defensive position while staying in position","Shoot from wherever you are now because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice right now"],ok:1,why:"Game management late means using the clock. Protecting the puck in the neutral zone makes the other team come to you and burns precious seconds.",tip:"Leading late and won the puck? Protect it. Use the clock. Make them come to you."},
    {id:"u13q67",cat:"Puck Management",concept:"PP or counter?",d:3,sit:"Your team just finished a power play. The puck is stopped and the penalty expires. Now your team is 5-on-5 but the other team's defensemen are still pinched in your offensive zone. What do you do?",opts:["Hold your position at the crease while staying in position while staying in position","Exploit the pinched D immediately — move the puck quick and attack before they recover","Hold your position at the crease and then look for support while staying in position","Pressure the carrier hard because your teammates need time to set up and look for support"],ok:1,why:"When the other team's D are caught pinched at the end of your power play, the transition to 5-on-5 creates an immediate odd-man opportunity. Attack before they recover.",tip:"Penalty expired and their D are still deep? Attack immediately. That's a transition chance."},
    {id:"u13q68",cat:"Transitioning",concept:"Quick exit after forecheck",d:3,sit:"Your team is forechecking and the other team wins a battle in the corner. They're about to break out with speed. You're the high forward. What's the most important thing you do right now?",opts:["Skate to the corner and dig it out from the point and look for support","Hold your position and intercept the first outlet pass — you're the plug","Skate to the corner and dig it out before they react before they score","Drive to the net front because your teammates need time to set up right now"],ok:1,why:"When the puck changes in the corner, the high forward's job is to be the first interceptor — not to chase. Holding position and reading the breakout gives you a chance to pick off the first pass.",tip:"They won the corner battle? High forward reads the breakout. Don't chase — intercept."},
    {id:"u13q69",cat:"Transitioning",concept:"Transition timing",d:3,sit:"Your team just won a puck battle in your own zone. Two of your forwards are already at center ice. The other team has one player back. A 3-on-1 is developing. What's the trigger?",opts:["Pass back since the other team has committed to the other side right now","Go immediately — the 3-on-1 window closes fast as the other team gets back","Skate hard and then get back into your defensive position from this spot","Hold the puck since that creates the best look while staying in position"],ok:1,why:"Transition opportunities close fast. If two forwards are already at center and you have a 3-on-1 developing, going immediately is how you exploit it.",tip:"Transition chance opening? Go now. Those windows close in seconds."},
    {id:"u13q70",cat:"Transitioning",concept:"Recognize the D pinch",d:3,sit:"Your team breaks out. As you cross the red line you see both opposing defensemen are pinching up — they're at the red line, not their blue line. What do you do?",opts:["Get your stick in the lane since the lane is open now while staying in position","Skate hard behind them — you have a breakaway if you beat them to their blue line","Hold your position at the crease and then get back into your defensive position fast","Get your stick in the lane because your teammates need time to set up right now"],ok:1,why:"Defensemen pinching up means they've given up the space behind them. If you can beat them to the puck, you have a breakaway or a clean zone entry.",tip:"Both D pinching up? Burn them. Get behind them before they recover."},
    {id:"u13q71",cat:"Finishing",concept:"Pre-read before shooting",d:3,sit:"You're about to receive a pass in the slot. The goalie is aggressive — they're coming way out of the net. Before the puck even reaches you, what should you already be deciding?",opts:["Carry it wide because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit soon","Already deciding: the goalie is out, so you're going low or to the side — your shot destination is chosen before the puck arrives","Shoot low because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit at that point","Change lines because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit first"],ok:1,why:"Pre-reading the goalie's position before the puck arrives lets you shoot the instant you catch it. A goalie out of the net is vulnerable low — decide that before the puck gets there.",tip:"Goalie out of the net and puck coming to you? Decide to go low before the puck arrives. Pre-read."},
    {id:"u13q72",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"Reading the eyes",d:3,sit:"You're a defenseman in your own zone. The opposing winger has the puck in the corner and keeps looking at the player in the slot. What do you do?",opts:["Change lines since the other team has committed to the other side quickly","Step in front of the anticipated pass lane — intercept it before it arrives","Change lines since the other team has committed to the other side instead","Rim it around rather than trying to force a risky play here at that point"],ok:1,why:"Reading a puck carrier's eyes tells you where the pass is going. If they keep looking at the slot, get in that lane before the pass is made — not after.",tip:"Puck carrier keeps looking at one spot? Get in that lane. Intercept before the pass arrives."},
    {id:"u13q73",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"Switch communication",d:3,sit:"You're the left defenseman. Your partner calls switch as an attacker cuts from the right side to the left in front of the net. What do you do?",opts:["Skate to the corner and dig it out and then get back into your defensive position fast","Take the attacker coming to your side, let your partner clean up their original man","Set up behind the net and wait rather than trying to force a risky play here soon","Set up behind the net and wait and then get back into your defensive position now"],ok:1,why:"A switch call means you take the player coming to your side while your partner recovers their original man. Communication and trust make it work.",tip:"Partner calls switch? Take the player coming to you. Trust the communication."},
    {id:"u13q74",cat:"Special Teams",concept:"PP seam — half-wall read",d:3,sit:"Your power play is in a 1-3-1. The half-wall player has the puck. The near PK forward is cheating toward the half-wall. The seam pass to the middle player is now open. What's the right play?",opts:["Change lines because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice at that point","Thread the seam pass to the middle player — the PK forward cheating toward you opened that lane","Back up and defend because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice quickly","Pull up at the hash marks because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice first"],ok:1,why:"When the PK forward cheats toward you, they've vacated the seam. The middle player is open. The seam pass is the highest-danger play.",tip:"PK forward cheated toward you? The seam is open. Thread it."},
    {id:"u13q75",cat:"Special Teams",concept:"Net-front PP",d:3,sit:"Your team is on the power play. You're the net-front player. A shot comes from the point and the goalie makes the save. The rebound goes to the corner. What do you do?",opts:["Swing wide along the boards since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover here","Hold your position at the net front unless the puck is about to leave the zone — the power play structure needs you there","Swing wide along the boards since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover fast","Swing wide along the boards since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover hard"],ok:1,why:"On the power play, structure wins. The net-front player holds position to maintain the formation. If you crash the corner, you leave the most dangerous area empty and the PP formation collapses.",tip:"PP rebound to the corner? Hold the net front. Structure beats chaos."},
    {id:"u13q76",cat:"Cycle Play",concept:"Wheel when covered",d:3,sit:"You're protecting the puck behind the net. A defender has you pinned. Two teammates are in the zone but both are covered. What do you do?",opts:["Take the outside lane because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice fast","Wheel to the other side of the net — moving forces the defender to move and may open a teammate","Take the outside lane because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice hard","Take the outside lane because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice soon"],ok:1,why:"Wheeling behind the net when both outlets are covered forces the defender to move with you, which can open a teammate, and resets the pressure.",tip:"Both outlets covered behind the net? Wheel. Force the defense to move."},
    {id:"u13q77",cat:"Cycle Play",concept:"Timing the attack",d:3,sit:"You're cycling below the dots. Your partner passes to you at the half-wall. As soon as the puck hits your stick, you see the slot is completely empty. What's the play?",opts:["Carry it wide because your teammates need time to set up from this spot","Shoot immediately into the open slot or pass to a teammate breaking there","Carry it wide rather than trying to force a risky play here on the play","Pressure the carrier hard rather than trying to force a risky play here soon"],ok:1,why:"The slot opening up is exactly what the cycle is designed to create. The instant you see it, attack it — don't keep cycling for its own sake.",tip:"Slot opens during the cycle? That's the goal. Attack it immediately."},
    {id:"u13q78",cat:"Gap Control",concept:"Contain the rush",d:3,sit:"A skilled attacker gets a step on you at the blue line and is now skating toward your net with speed. You can't catch them. What's the right approach?",opts:["Pressure the carrier hard because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice from this spot","Get your stick into their lane — angle them toward the boards and get your body in front of the shooting lane","Stay in the neutral zone because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice and look for support","Drop back and play defense because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice at that point"],ok:1,why:"When you can't catch an attacker, get in their lane. Angling them toward the boards takes away the shooting lane.",tip:"Can't catch them? Get your body in the lane. Take away the shooting angle."},
    {id:"u13q79",cat:"Puck Management",concept:"Protect in D zone late",d:3,sit:"Your team is winning by one goal. You win a battle behind your own net with 30 seconds left. The other team has pulled their goalie. What do you do?",opts:["Pass it to your D at the far point because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit first","Protect the puck — use your body and the net, move it to a teammate if needed, and force them to come get it. Only clear it when you have a clean lane.","Pass it to your D at the far point because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit again","Try to stickhandle through them because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit at that point"],ok:1,why:"With 30 seconds left protecting behind your net, protecting the puck and forcing the other team to come get it burns clock. A panicked clear into pressure turns the puck over.",tip:"Last 30 seconds behind your own net? Protect it. Force them to come get it. Clear when the lane is clean."},
    {id:"u13q80",cat:"Transitioning",concept:"Attack transition windows",d:3,sit:"The other team just changed lines mid-play in the neutral zone. Their new players are still getting up to speed. You have the puck. What does this create?",opts:["Drop back and play defense since the other team has committed to the other side while staying in position","A transition window — attack immediately while their fresh players aren't at full speed or in position","Force a play through traffic rather than trying to force a risky play here while staying in position","Force a play through traffic because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice here"],ok:1,why:"A line change mid-play creates a brief window where the fresh players aren't at full speed or position. Attacking immediately exploits that window before it closes.",tip:"Other team just changed mid-play? Attack now. Their fresh players aren't set yet."},
    {id:"u13q81",cat:"Finishing",concept:"Shoot while moving",d:3,sit:"You're skating at full speed toward the net. A defender is chasing from behind. Should you slow down to take a more accurate shot?",opts:["Back up and defend because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit here","No — shoot while moving at full speed. A moving shooter is harder for the goalie to track and slowing down lets the defender catch up.","Back up and defend because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit fast","Back up and defend because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit hard"],ok:1,why:"Shooting while moving at full speed is harder for a goalie to track. Slowing down also lets the defender catch up. Shoot while moving.",tip:"Full speed toward the net with a defender behind you? Shoot moving. Don't slow down."},
    {id:"u13q82",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"Puck tracker vs. player",d:3,sit:"You're defending in your own zone. The puck is in the corner behind your net. Your assignment is an attacker near the half-wall on the opposite side. Do you watch the puck or watch your man?",opts:["Skate hard because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit first","Watch your man — keep them in front of you so you know when they move. You can track the puck with your peripheral vision.","Crash the net for a rebound since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover again","Crash the net for a rebound since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover early"],ok:1,why:"In man coverage, losing sight of your assignment is how they get open for a pass. Keep them in front of you and use your peripheral vision for the puck.",tip:"Man coverage in your own zone: watch your man, not the puck. Use your peripheral vision for the puck."},
    {id:"u13q83",cat:"Breakouts",concept:"Second wave forecheck",d:3,sit:"Your first two forecheckers won the puck battle in the offensive zone. They passed it to you as the third forward coming in. The D is still scrambling. What do you do?",opts:["Swing wide along the boards rather than trying to force a risky play here hard","Attack the scrambled D immediately — they haven't recovered. Be the second wave.","Swing wide along the boards rather than trying to force a risky play here soon","Swing wide along the boards and then get back into your defensive position now"],ok:1,why:"The second wave of a forecheck attacks the scramble. If the first two forwards won the battle and the D hasn't recovered, the third forward attacks the confusion immediately.",tip:"First wave won and D is scrambling? Second wave attacks immediately. Go."},
    {id:"u13q84",cat:"Breakouts",concept:"Forecheck trap",d:3,sit:"You're forechecking. The D picks up the puck behind the net and starts to walk out to the left. You're closing from the right. Your linemate is on the left. How do you split?",opts:["Take the outside lane since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover quickly","You force the D's direction from the right, your linemate cuts off the outlet to the left — trap them between you","Back up and defend since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover again","Back up and defend since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover early"],ok:1,why:"A two-player forecheck trap works by forcing the puck carrier in a direction while the other player cuts off the outlet in that direction.",tip:"Two-man forecheck: one forces, one cuts the outlet. Trap them."},
    {id:"u13q85",cat:"Special Teams",concept:"Timeout assignment",d:3,sit:"Your coach calls a timeout with 30 seconds left and your team down by one. You're going back on after the timeout. What should be the first thing in your mind?",opts:["Challenge at the line and then get back into your defensive position before they score","Know your specific job for the next 30 seconds — faceoff role, where to go, who to cover","Cut to the middle of the ice since forcing it would be risky here while staying in position","Challenge at the line since the other team has committed to the other side on the play"],ok:1,why:"A timeout is a chance to execute a specific play. Walking back on the ice with a clear assignment is more valuable than general energy.",tip:"Timeout: know your specific job before you go back out. Assignment over energy."},
    {id:"u13q86",cat:"Puck Management",concept:"When to hold vs. shoot",d:3,sit:"You're in the offensive zone. You can shoot from where you are — a decent but not great angle. OR you can pass to a teammate in the slot who's slightly covered but would have a much better shot. What do you do?",opts:["Get your stick in the lane since forcing it would be risky here and look for support","Pass to the slot player — the higher danger location is worth the slight coverage risk","Skate to the corner and dig it out because your teammates need time to set up on the play","Get your stick in the lane because your teammates need time to set up from this spot"],ok:1,why:"A slightly covered player in the slot still represents a higher-danger chance than a clean shot from a poor angle. The math of chance quality favors the slot, even with some risk.",tip:"OK angle vs. slightly covered slot? The slot wins. Higher danger is worth the risk."},
    {id:"u13q87",cat:"Transitioning",concept:"Recognize the transition window",d:3,sit:"Your team has been in the offensive zone for 45 seconds. The other team's defensemen are tired. Your team wins a puck battle and the D are caught flat-footed. What do you do?",opts:["Drop back and play defense since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover right now","Attack immediately through the neutral zone — tired defensemen flat-footed after a long shift are vulnerable to a fast attack","Get your stick in the lane since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover right now","Pull up at the hash marks since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover right away"],ok:1,why:"Tired, flat-footed defenders after a long shift in their own zone are vulnerable to a fast transition. Attacking immediately — even if your team is also tired — exploits the window before it closes.",tip:"Their D flat-footed after a long shift? Attack now. That's a transition window."},
    {id:"u13q88",cat:"Finishing",concept:"Reading and reacting",d:3,sit:"You skate into the offensive zone with speed. You planned to shoot from the right side, but as you enter you see the goalie has that side covered and a teammate is breaking to the net on the left. What do you do?",opts:["Try to stickhandle through them rather than trying to force a risky play here at that point","Read and react — pass to your breaking teammate. The plan changes when the situation changes.","Shoot from wherever you are now rather than trying to force a risky play here at that point","Chip it past them since the other team has committed to the other side while staying in position"],ok:1,why:"Plans are starting points, not locks. If the situation changes — a breaking teammate with the goalie covering your planned shot is a change — read it and react.",tip:"Read what's actually there. Your plan is a starting point, not a commitment."},
    {id:"u13q89",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"PK third forward coverage",d:3,sit:"Your team is on the penalty kill and set in a box. The power play's point player steps down into the zone at the top of the circles. Nobody in the box has covered them. What does the nearest PK player do?",opts:["Shoot low rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set right away","The nearest PK player extends to pressure the point player who stepped in — a player inside the dots with space is too dangerous to leave alone","Pull up at the hash marks rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set","Pass back rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set right away"],ok:1,why:"A point player stepping inside the dots with space is one of the most dangerous power play plays. The nearest PK player has to extend and pressure — holding a rigid box against a smart power play gives up that shot.",tip:"PP player stepped inside the dots with space? The nearest PK player extends. Don't leave that shot open."},
    {id:"u13q90",cat:"Gap Control",concept:"Defending the rush with speed",d:3,sit:"A skilled forward has beaten your forecheck and is coming at you with a step of speed. You can't catch them before they enter the zone. What's your priority?",opts:["Take the outside lane because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice from this spot","Get to the inside position and your lane — angle them toward the boards and stay between them and the net","Skate hard since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover right away","Drive to the net front because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice at that point"],ok:1,why:"When you can't catch a fast attacker, getting to the inside position and your lane takes away their shooting angle and forces them to go wide. Your goalie can handle the angle.",tip:"Fast attacker beating you to the zone? Get to the inside. Take away the lane."},
    {id:"u13q91",cat:"Cycle Play",concept:"Read the point player",d:3,sit:"You're low in the offensive zone with the puck. The D at the point just stepped down from the blue line because they saw a lane. They're now inside the zone at the top of the circles. What's the play?",opts:["Drive to the net front because your teammates need time to set up again","Pass to the D who stepped in — they now have a shot from a dangerous area","Drive to the net front because your teammates need time to set up early","Challenge at the line and hope for a better chance and look for support"],ok:1,why:"A defenseman stepping inside the dots has created a scoring chance. Hitting them in stride while inside the dots is a high-danger play.",tip:"D stepped inside? Hit them in stride. That's a dangerous shot location."},
    {id:"u13q92",cat:"Special Teams",concept:"PK box adjust",d:3,sit:"Your penalty kill is in a box. The power play's center has dropped below the dots to create a 1-3-1. Your box is now mismatched against their formation. What adjustment do you make?",opts:["Change lines since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover early","Adjust — one PK forward drops to pressure the center who dropped in. The box has to mirror the threat.","Get your stick in the lane since the other team has committed to the other side and look for support","Pull up at the hash marks because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice quickly"],ok:1,why:"A 1-3-1 power play vs. a box requires a PK adjustment. One forward drops to pressure the center who's now below the dots — leaving them open in that area gives up the most dangerous shots in hockey.",tip:"PP dropped a player below the dots? One PK forward drops to match. Adjust to the threat."},
    {id:"u13q93",cat:"Puck Management",concept:"Faceoff assignment win",d:3,sit:"Your team wins a faceoff in the offensive zone. The opposing center had to fight hard to tie the draw. The puck goes back to your defenseman at the point. Before the opposing center gets their bearings, what should you do?",opts:["Thread a pass to the slot because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit quickly","Drive hard to the net immediately — the opposing center just spent all their energy on the draw and the lane to the net may be briefly open","Dump it in rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set again","Dump it in rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set early"],ok:1,why:"Winning a faceoff creates a split-second window where the opposing center is recovering. Driving hard to the net immediately exploits that window before they recover.",tip:"Win the OZ faceoff? Drive the net immediately. Their center is recovering from the draw."},
    {id:"u13q94",cat:"Transitioning",concept:"Attack after save",d:3,sit:"Your team is defending. The goalie makes a save and controls the puck. The other team has three forecheckers in your zone. Your wingers are pinned. What's the right breakout option?",opts:["Hold your position at the crease because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice before they score","Goalie finds the center breaking through the middle or a winger escaping — don't give the puck to a covered player","Dump it in since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover from this spot","Skate hard since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover from this spot"],ok:1,why:"After a save under forecheck pressure, the goalie needs to read the breakout. Finding the center or an escaping winger breaks the forecheck immediately.",tip:"Goalie made the save under pressure? Find the breaking player. Read the breakout."},
    {id:"u13q95",cat:"Defensive Zone",concept:"Prevent the second shot",d:3,sit:"The other team takes a shot and your goalie makes the save. The rebound goes to the corner. An opposing player is racing to it. What do you do?",opts:["Pass back since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover from this spot","Get to the rebound before the opposing player — or at least get your body position between them and the puck","Hold your position at the crease since the other team has committed to the other side and look for support","Skate to the corner and dig it out rather than trying to force a risky play here while staying in position"],ok:1,why:"Beating the opposing player to the rebound — or at minimum getting inside position — prevents the second shot. Letting them get a clean rebound in the corner means a second chance against you.",tip:"Rebound in the corner? Race to it or get inside position. Prevent the second shot."},
    {id:"u13q96",cat:"Finishing",concept:"Quick release vs. accuracy",d:3,sit:"You catch a pass in the slot. You see an opening to the top corner. But you hesitate for two seconds while repositioning the puck for what you think will be a better shot. The goalie recovers. What should you have done?",opts:["Protect the puck there since the other team has committed to the other side on the play","Released immediately on the catch — the opening was there when you first received it","Pass back because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice early","Skate hard rather than trying to force a risky play here while staying in position"],ok:1,why:"Hesitating in the slot gives the goalie time to recover. If there's an opening when you catch the puck, release immediately.",tip:"Opening in the slot? Release immediately. The best shot is the first one."},
    {id:"u13q97",cat:"Gap Control",concept:"Two-on-one — read the goalie",d:3,sit:"You're the lone defender on a 2-on-1. You've taken away the pass. The shooter pulls up and shoots. The goalie makes the save but the rebound comes right to the second attacker. What do you do?",opts:["Set up behind the net and wait because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice quickly","Get your body in front of the second attacker — between them and the net — before they can get the shot off","Set up behind the net and wait because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice instead","Hold the puck since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover right now"],ok:1,why:"When a rebound goes to the second attacker, your job shifts from pass prevention to body blocking. Getting your body between them and the net before they shoot is the only play.",tip:"Rebound goes to the second attacker? Get your body between them and the net. Block the shot."},
    {id:"u13q98",cat:"Puck Management",concept:"Read the game situation",d:3,sit:"It's a tied game in the third period. You have the puck in the neutral zone. Your team's fastest forward is breaking on your left, completely open. A defended pass is available on your right. What do you do?",opts:["Pressure the carrier hard rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set","Thread the pass to the breaking forward on the left — a tied game in the third is the time to take the calculated risk for a high-danger chance","Swing wide along the boards because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit here","Swing wide along the boards because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit fast"],ok:1,why:"A tied game in the third period is when high-danger chances matter most. An open breaking forward is a calculated risk worth taking — the reward is a scoring chance, the risk is a missed pass.",tip:"Tied late with a breaking forward open? Thread it. High-danger chances matter most now."},
    {id:"u13q99",cat:"Special Teams",concept:"PP or 5-on-5 read",d:3,sit:"Your team has been on the power play for 30 seconds with no shots. The penalty kill has been perfect. You have 30 seconds of PP time left. What do you do differently in the last 30 seconds?",opts:["Protect the puck there rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set quickly","Increase urgency — shoot earlier, move faster, take more risks. The last 30 seconds of a PP that hasn't scored should look more urgent than the first 90.","Protect the puck there rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set instead","Challenge at the line rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set at that point"],ok:1,why:"A PP that hasn't generated a shot in 90 seconds needs to change. The last 30 seconds should be more urgent — shoot earlier, move faster, take calculated risks. Running out the PP with the same conservative approach wastes the advantage.",tip:"PP almost over with no shots? Increase urgency. Shoot earlier. Move faster. Time is running out."},
    {id:"u13q100",cat:"Puck Management",concept:"The hardest decision",d:3,sit:"You're in the offensive zone with 5 seconds left in a tied game. You have the puck at the half-wall. A teammate is breaking to the net — open but a defender is almost there. You have a shooting lane. One second to decide. What do you do?",opts:["Drop back and play defense since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover right now","Pass to the breaking teammate — they'll get there before the defender and an open player at the net beats your half-wall shot","Get your stick in the lane since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover right now","Rim it around because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit again"],ok:1,why:"In a tied game with 5 seconds left, a breaking teammate who'll beat the defender to the net is a higher-danger chance than a half-wall shot. The risk is the pass, the reward is the highest-danger chance on the ice. That's the elite read.",tip:"Tied game, last 5 seconds, breaking teammate beating a defender to the net? Thread it. That's the highest-danger play. That's elite hockey IQ."},

    // === SEQUENCE ORDERING QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u13seq1",cat:"Breakouts",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Structured breakout",d:1,type:"seq",sit:"Your goalie makes a save and controls the puck. Put the breakout steps in order.",items:["D sets up behind the net and calls for the puck","Wingers sprint to their breakout lanes along the boards","Center supports low then curls through the middle","D reads pressure and hits the first open option"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"A structured breakout has defined roles. D retrieves, wings get to their lanes, center fills the middle, and the D reads and passes. The system only works when everyone hits their spots.",tip:"Structured breakout: D retrieves, wings to lanes, center supports, D reads. Hit your spots."},
    {id:"u13seq2",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Power play entry",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"Your team has a power play and needs to set up in the offensive zone. Put the PP entry steps in order.",items:["Win the draw or gain clean possession in the neutral zone","Puck carrier enters with speed and reads the PK's setup","Supporting players stretch the PK by driving wide and high","Puck moves to the strong side and the PP gets into formation"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"A clean PP entry is the first step to a successful power play. Possession first, enter with speed and a read, stretch the PK, then set up your formation.",tip:"PP entry: possess, enter with speed, stretch the PK, get into formation. Clean entries = more PP time."},
    {id:"u13seq3",cat:"Defensive Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D-zone faceoff play",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"Your team has a defensive zone faceoff with the other team's top line on the ice. Put the defensive steps in order.",items:["Everyone knows their assignment before the puck drops","Get to your assigned position around the faceoff circle","Center competes on the draw — win it back or tie up","If you lose the draw, immediately get to your coverage assignment"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"D-zone faceoffs are structured moments. Knowing your job, getting positioned, competing on the draw, and executing coverage immediately are the steps. Teams that wing it on faceoffs give up goals.",tip:"D-zone faceoff: know your job, get set, compete, execute coverage. No freelancing."},
    {id:"u13seq4",cat:"Cycle Play",pos:["F"],concept:"Offensive cycle initiation",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"Your team dumps the puck into the corner to start a cycle. Put the cycle steps in order.",items:["First forward wins the puck battle on the boards","Protect the puck and scan for support options","Second forward comes in low for the short pass or picks up a loose puck","Third forward stays high and the cycle rotation begins"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"The cycle is a system: win the board battle, protect, get support, and rotate. If the first battle is lost, the cycle never starts. If the third forward goes low, you lose your high option.",tip:"Cycle: win the battle, protect, support, rotate. Lose the first battle and nothing starts."},
    {id:"u13seq5",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Defending a rush — full sequence",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"A skilled forward is carrying the puck through the neutral zone at full speed, 1-on-1 against you. Put your defensive steps in order.",items:["Pivot and match their speed while establishing your gap","Read their body language — hips, head, stick position","Close the gap at the blue line and angle them to the outside","Use an active stick to take away their preferred move and force them wide"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"1-on-1 defending is a sequence of reads and actions. Match speed, read their intent, close at the right time, and take away their best option. Skip the read step and you'll commit too early.",tip:"1-on-1: match speed, read them, close at the line, steer wide. It's a sequence, not a gamble."},
    {id:"u13seq6",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Neutral zone regroup",d:2,type:"seq",sit:"Your team has the puck but can't enter the offensive zone — the D are too tight. Your center calls for a regroup. Put the steps in order.",items:["Puck carrier turns back and passes to the trailing defenseman","Forwards loop through the neutral zone and rebuild speed","D-to-D pass stretches the PK or defensive setup horizontally","Forwards attack with speed on the second entry attempt"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"A regroup is a tactical reset, not a failure. Bring it back, rebuild speed, stretch the defense, and attack again with better timing. Forcing a bad entry is worse than resetting.",tip:"Can't get in clean? Regroup. Bring it back, rebuild speed, attack again. Smart, not weak."},
    {id:"u13seq7",cat:"Finishing",pos:["F"],concept:"Net-front scoring sequence",d:3,type:"seq",sit:"You're set up in front of the net on the power play. A shot is coming from the point. Put your steps in order.",items:["Establish position in front of the goalie — between the dots","Screen the goalie by getting big without interfering","Read the shot — is it a tip opportunity or a rebound play?","React — tip on net, collect the rebound, or jam at a loose puck"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"Net-front presence is a skill with steps. Position, screen, read, react. Players who just stand there without reading the shot miss tip and rebound chances.",tip:"Net front: position, screen, read, react. Standing there isn't enough — you need to read the play."},
    {id:"u13seq8",cat:"Puck Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Clock management — protecting a lead",d:3,type:"seq",sit:"Your team is winning by one goal with 3 minutes left. The other team is pressing. Put the puck management steps in order.",items:["Make safe, simple passes — no high-risk plays in your own zone","Use the boards and the glass to clear when under pressure","Change lines quickly to keep fresh legs on the ice","Force them to earn zone entries — don't give up easy possession"],correct_order:[0,1,2,3],why:"Protecting a late lead is about discipline. Safe passes, smart clears, quick changes, and denying easy zone time. One high-risk turnover can cost you the game.",tip:"Protecting a lead: simple plays, clear when pressured, fresh legs, deny entries. Discipline wins."},

    // === SPOT THE MISTAKE QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u13mis1",cat:"Blue Line Reads",pos:["D"],concept:"Pinch with no support",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"Your team is in the offensive zone. The puck is loose along the boards near the blue line. You pinch down to get it, but your D partner has also jumped into the play low. The opponent chips it past both of you for a 2-on-0. What's the mistake?",opts:["You should have pinched harder","Both D went — one defenseman must always stay back to cover. If your partner is low, you hold the line. If you're pinching, they hold. Never both.","The forwards should have helped","The puck bounced wrong"],ok:1,why:"Two defensemen caught deep is a catastrophic defensive breakdown. One D always stays high as the safety valve. Communication between the D pair prevents this.",tip:"Both D can't go. Ever. One pinches, one stays. Communicate with your partner."},
    {id:"u13mis2",cat:"Defensive Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Chasing behind the net",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"In the defensive zone, the puck is behind your net. Both your defensemen go behind the net to battle for it. The opposing center sneaks to the front of the net completely uncovered. They score on a pass out front. What's the mistake?",opts:["The goalie should have stopped it","Both D went behind the net — one D battles for the puck, the other covers the front of the net. Leaving the front of the net empty is one of the most dangerous mistakes in hockey.","The forwards should have been there","The play happened too fast"],ok:1,why:"The front of the net must always be covered. When both D go behind the net, the most dangerous area on the ice is left wide open. One battles, one protects.",tip:"Both D behind the net? Someone better be in front. The front of the net is never optional."},
    {id:"u13mis3",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F"],concept:"Offside by overcommitting",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"Your team has a 3-on-2 rush. The puck carrier slows down to make a play at the blue line. Two forwards are flying into the zone at full speed and cross the blue line before the puck. Offside. Rush killed. What's the mistake?",opts:["The puck carrier was too slow","The two forwards didn't read the puck carrier and entered the zone early — on a rush, everyone times their entry off the puck. If the carrier slows down, you slow down.","The ref made a bad call","The D played it well"],ok:1,why:"Offside on a rush with numbers is one of the most frustrating mistakes in hockey. The forwards must read the puck carrier's speed and time their entry. The puck always crosses first.",tip:"Rush entry: read the carrier's speed. Puck crosses first. Always. Kill your speed if you have to."},
    {id:"u13mis4",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK overcommit on pressure",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"On the penalty kill, your forward leaves the box to chase the puck behind the net. The power play moves it quickly to the open slot area where your forward was supposed to be. Goal. What's the mistake?",opts:["The forward should have chased faster","The forward left their position in the PK box — on the penalty kill, you stay in structure and cover your zone. Chasing the puck out of position opens the most dangerous area on the ice.","The D should have shifted","The goalie wasn't ready"],ok:1,why:"PK discipline means staying in the box. When a player chases out of position, the slot opens up. The power play is designed to exploit exactly that mistake.",tip:"PK: stay in the box. Chase out of position and the slot opens. That's where PP goals come from."},
    {id:"u13mis5",cat:"Finishing",pos:["F"],concept:"Admiring the pass",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"Your linemate makes a beautiful cross-ice pass to you in the slot. You catch it cleanly and have a half-second to shoot. Instead, you look down to admire the pass and adjust the puck. The goalie sets and you shoot into their chest. What's the mistake?",opts:["The pass was too hard","You hesitated — in the slot with a half-second window, you shoot on the catch. Looking down and adjusting gave the goalie time to get set. Quick release beats perfect setup.","The goalie was lucky","You should have passed it back"],ok:1,why:"Slot chances are about speed of release, not perfection of setup. A half-second of puck adjustment gives the goalie time to square up. Shoot on the catch and beat them before they're ready.",tip:"Slot chance? Shoot on the catch. Don't look down. Don't adjust. Release beats perfection."},
    {id:"u13mis6",cat:"Breakouts",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D skates into pressure",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"Your D picks up the puck behind the net. The forechecker is closing hard from the left side. Instead of going right or using the boards, your D skates directly into the forechecker. Turnover. What's the mistake?",opts:["The D wasn't strong enough","The D skated into pressure instead of away from it — when a forechecker closes from one side, go the other way or use the boards. Skating into pressure is a guaranteed turnover.","The forechecker was too fast","The forwards didn't help"],ok:1,why:"Reading the forecheck and going away from pressure is breakout 101. Skating into the forechecker gives them exactly what they want — a turnover in a dangerous area.",tip:"Forechecker from the left? Go right. Away from pressure. Always away. Never into it."},
    {id:"u13mis7",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Backing up to the net",d:1,type:"mistake",sit:"An attacker is carrying the puck through the neutral zone. Your defenseman keeps backing up all the way to the top of the crease, giving the attacker the entire offensive zone to work with. What's the mistake?",opts:["The D should have been more aggressive","The D gave up too much ice — backing up to the crease gives the attacker time, space, and options. Close the gap at the blue line and take away their time to make plays.","The forwards should have backchecked","The attacker was too skilled"],ok:1,why:"A defender who backs up to the crease surrenders the entire offensive zone. Gap control means closing the distance at the blue line — taking away the attacker's time and space before they can set up.",tip:"Don't back up to your crease. Close the gap at the blue line. Take away their time and space."},
    {id:"u13mis8",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Slow change after turnover",d:2,type:"mistake",sit:"Your team turns the puck over in the offensive zone. Two forwards are exhausted and glide slowly to the bench for a change. The other team rushes 4-on-3 and scores before the fresh players get into position. What's the mistake?",opts:["The coach should have called for a change earlier","The tired forwards changed too slowly at the wrong time — after a turnover, you sprint back first, then change when the puck is safe. Changing during transition is how you give up odd-man goals.","The defensemen should have held","The other team got lucky"],ok:1,why:"Line changes during defensive transition are deadly. Sprint back first, stabilize the defense, then change when the puck is in a safe area. Gliding to the bench during a rush against is a gift to the other team.",tip:"Turnover? Sprint back first. Change when it's safe. Never change during a rush against."},

    // === WHAT HAPPENS NEXT QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u13next1",cat:"Cycle Play",pos:["F"],concept:"D-to-D opens the weak side",d:2,type:"next",sit:"Your team is cycling on the strong side. The defense has matched your cycle perfectly — nothing is opening up. Your D at the point makes a D-to-D pass to the weak side. What happens next?",opts:["The cycle continues on the same side","The weak-side D has an open shooting lane or passing option — the defense was overloaded to the strong side and the D-to-D pass shifts the play to open ice","Nothing changes","The weak-side D dumps it in"],ok:1,why:"A D-to-D pass against an overloaded defense opens the weak side completely. The defense was committed to the cycle side and can't recover across the ice in time.",tip:"Cycle stuck? D-to-D to the weak side. The defense overloaded to the strong side can't get there."},
    {id:"u13next2",cat:"Rush Reads",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Trailer on the rush",d:2,type:"next",sit:"Your team has a 3-on-2 rush. Both defenders focus on the three attackers. Your fourth player — the trailing D — jumps into the play late from the blue line, completely unnoticed. The puck carrier sees them. What happens next?",opts:["The trailing D stays back","The puck carrier drops it back to the trailing D who has a clean shot from the top of the circles — the defense never accounted for the trailer","The puck carrier shoots alone","Everyone regroups"],ok:1,why:"The trailing player on a rush is one of the most dangerous weapons in hockey. The defense accounts for the three rushers but forgets the trailer. A drop pass to an uncontested shooter at the top of the circles is a prime chance.",tip:"Trailer on the rush? Drop it back. The D has a clean look that nobody's covering."},
    {id:"u13next3",cat:"Defensive Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Forced turnover — quick counter",d:3,type:"next",sit:"Your center strips the puck from the opposing center in your defensive zone slot area. The other team's forwards are all deep in your zone. Your wingers are at the hash marks. What happens next?",opts:["Your center dumps it out","Your center headmans it to a winger breaking up ice — the other team is caught deep, and a quick pass to a winger with speed creates an odd-man rush the other way","Everyone regroups in the D-zone","Your center holds the puck and waits"],ok:1,why:"A turnover in the defensive zone with the other team caught deep is a counter-attack opportunity. The quick headman pass to a winger with speed can create a 2-on-1 or breakaway before the other team recovers.",tip:"Strip the puck in your zone with them caught deep? Headman it fast. Counter-attack before they recover."},
    {id:"u13next4",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK clears to center",d:2,type:"next",sit:"On the penalty kill, your team clears the puck to center ice. The power play's defenseman retrieves it, but your two PK forwards are already forechecking hard at the blue line. What happens next?",opts:["The PP sets up again easily","Your PK forwards pressure the D and force a turnover or a bad re-entry — aggressive PK forechecking at the blue line disrupts the PP's rhythm","Your PK falls back to the box","The PK changes lines"],ok:1,why:"A PK clear followed by immediate pressure on the retrieving D is elite penalty killing. You've broken their setup and now you're making them earn the zone entry all over again — under pressure this time.",tip:"PK clears it? Don't fall back. Pressure the retrieval. Make them earn the entry again."},
    {id:"u13next5",cat:"Puck Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D-zone faceoff loss — scramble",d:3,type:"next",sit:"Your team loses the defensive zone faceoff clean — the puck goes back to their point man who one-times it. Your goalie makes the save but can't control the rebound. It's loose in front. What happens next?",opts:["Everyone watches the goalie","Your forwards and D collapse to the net, box out opposing players, and either clear the puck or help the goalie freeze it — loose pucks in front after a faceoff loss require an all-hands response","The D pass it around the boards","Your goalie comes out to play it"],ok:1,why:"A loose puck in the crease after a faceoff loss is maximum danger. Everyone collapses to the net — box out, clear, freeze. Half a second of hesitation is a goal against.",tip:"Loose puck in front after a lost draw? Collapse. Box out. Clear or freeze. Everyone. Now."},
    {id:"u13next6",cat:"Finishing",pos:["F"],concept:"Goalie down — high shot",d:2,type:"next",sit:"You drive to the net and the goalie goes down in butterfly early. You still have the puck on your stick and you're in tight. The entire top of the net is open. What happens next?",opts:["You shoot low into the pads","You lift the puck high over the butterfly — goalie is down, the top of the net is wide open, and you have the puck and time to elevate it","You pass it across","You deke to the backhand"],ok:1,why:"A goalie in butterfly early leaves the top of the net open. If you have time and the puck, lifting it over the pads into the open net is the highest-percentage play. Read the goalie, not just the net.",tip:"Goalie down in butterfly early? Go high. Lift it. The top of the net is yours."},
    {id:"u13next7",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Forward stops up — danger",d:3,type:"next",sit:"You're defending a 1-on-1. The forward drives wide, then suddenly stops up at the top of the circle and cuts back to the middle. You were committed to the outside angle. What happens next?",opts:["You keep going to the outside","You pivot hard and recover to the inside — the forward just beat your angle, and if you don't recover inside, they'll have the slot. Pivot feet, close the inside lane.","You stop and watch","You go for a poke check from behind"],ok:1,why:"A stop-and-cut-back to the middle is designed to beat a defender committed outside. The recovery is a hard pivot to close the inside lane before they reach the slot. Feet must move — reaching from behind creates penalties.",tip:"Forward cuts back inside? Pivot and recover inside. Don't reach from behind. Move your feet."},

    // === TRUE/FALSE QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u13tf1",cat:"Breakouts",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Always go up the boards",d:2,type:"tf",sit:"On a breakout, the safest option is always to go up the boards.",ok:false,why:"The boards are often safe, but the best play depends on where the pressure is. Sometimes the middle is open. Sometimes a reverse behind the net opens the other side. Always use the boards and you become predictable. Read the forecheck.",tip:"Boards are often safe, but not always best. Read the forecheck and use what's open."},
    {id:"u13tf2",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP patience",d:2,type:"tf",sit:"On the power play, moving the puck quickly to find the open lane is more effective than holding onto it and trying to beat players one-on-one.",ok:true,why:"Power play efficiency comes from puck movement that forces the PK to shift. One player holding and deking lets the PK stay compact. Quick passes open seams the PK can't cover.",tip:"PP: move the puck. Quick passes open seams. Holding it lets the PK stay compact."},
    {id:"u13tf3",cat:"Defensive Zone",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Always freeze the puck",d:2,type:"tf",sit:"When you're under pressure in the defensive zone, you should always freeze the puck to stop play.",ok:false,why:"Freezing gives the other team a faceoff in your zone — a set play with their best players. If you can make a quick play to a teammate or clear it, that's better than giving them a structured offensive opportunity.",tip:"Freezing in your zone = giving them a set play. Clear or pass if you can. Freeze only when you must."},
    {id:"u13tf4",cat:"Finishing",pos:["F"],concept:"Shot selection matters",d:2,type:"tf",sit:"Taking a lot of shots from bad angles and low-danger areas is just as effective as fewer shots from high-danger areas.",ok:false,why:"Shot quality matters more than shot quantity. A shot from the slot is worth far more than five shots from the corner. Getting to high-danger areas and shooting from there produces more goals.",tip:"Shot quality over shot quantity. One slot shot beats five corner shots. Get to dangerous areas."},
    {id:"u13tf5",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["D"],concept:"Active stick beats body check",d:2,type:"tf",sit:"Using an active stick to poke the puck away is often more effective than going for a big body check.",ok:true,why:"An active stick disrupts plays without taking you out of position. A missed body check puts you behind the play. Good defenders use their stick first and their body when the timing is right.",tip:"Stick first, body second. Active stick keeps you in position. Missed hits put you behind the play."},
    {id:"u13tf6",cat:"Puck Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Turnovers kill more than missed shots",d:3,type:"tf",sit:"Turnovers in the neutral or defensive zone are more costly to your team than missed shots in the offensive zone.",ok:true,why:"A missed shot is a lost possession in the offensive zone — the other team still has to exit and come 200 feet. A neutral or defensive zone turnover gives them the puck in a dangerous area with less ice to cover. Location of turnovers matters.",tip:"Missed shot in their zone? Acceptable. Turnover in yours? Deadly. Location of turnovers matters."},
    {id:"u13tf7",cat:"Transitioning",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Best time to attack is after a turnover",d:2,type:"tf",sit:"The best time to create a scoring chance is immediately after your team forces a turnover, when the other team is out of position.",ok:true,why:"Transition offense works because the other team is still in their offensive mindset and out of defensive position. The fastest teams in transition create the most odd-man rushes and high-danger chances.",tip:"Turnover = attack window. They're out of position. Go now, before they recover."},

    // === U13 GOALIE QUESTIONS ===
    {id:"u13g1",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Depth on the rush",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"An attacker is carrying the puck through the neutral zone. You're set up in your net. How deep should you be as they approach the blue line?",opts:["Force a play through traffic since that creates the best look while staying in position","At the top of your crease — cut the angle and still have room to react to passes or dekes","Shoot from wherever you are now and then get back into your defensive position at that point","Force a play through traffic before the play develops further while staying in position"],ok:1,why:"The top of the crease gives you the best combination of angle coverage and recovery space. Going deeper gives up too much net. Going further out makes you vulnerable to dekes and passes.",tip:"Top of the crease on the rush. Cut the angle without sacrificing recovery."},
    {id:"u13g2",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Pre-shot scan",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is in the corner to your right. You're set on the post. Before the pass comes out, what should you be doing with your eyes?",opts:["Hold your position at the crease since forcing it would be risky here quickly","Scan the slot and weak side to locate the other attackers before the puck moves","Take the outside lane since the other team has committed to the other side quickly","Hold your position at the crease since forcing it would be risky here instead"],ok:1,why:"Pre-scanning while the puck is still — finding the backdoor player, the high slot shooter, the trailer — is what separates elite goalies. When the puck moves, you already know where the danger is.",tip:"Puck still? Scan the ice. Find the danger before the puck moves."},
    {id:"u13g3",cat:"Goalie",concept:"RVH vs VH post integration",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is tight to your right post, below the goal line — a sharp-angle walkout threat. What's the best way to seal the post?",opts:["Skate to the corner and dig it out rather than trying to force a risky play here on the play","Go into Reverse VH (RVH) — pad stacked against the post, blocker and glove up to cover the top","Skate to the corner and dig it out and then get back into your defensive position right away","Skate to the corner and dig it out since the other team has committed to the other side here"],ok:1,why:"RVH seals the bottom of the net against the post while keeping the top covered with the blocker and glove. It's the modern answer to walkouts and goal-line plays. Standing tall gives up the bottom.",tip:"Puck tight to the post below the goal line? RVH. Seal low, cover high."},
    {id:"u13g4",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Screen tracking through multiple bodies",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"There's a point shot coming and two players — one from each team — are in your sightline. You can only see flashes of the puck. What do you do?",opts:["Pass back since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover and look for support","Lower your stance slightly to find a gap, track the puck with micro-movements, and prepare for a tip or deflection","Pull up at the hash marks since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover","Stay in the neutral zone because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice and look for support"],ok:1,why:"Screens aren't all-or-nothing. A slight drop in stance, moving your head to find a sightline, and tracking through small gaps keeps you in the save. Expect tips — the shot won't necessarily arrive at the expected angle.",tip:"Multiple screens? Drop slightly, find gaps, track micro-movements. Expect a tip."},
    {id:"u13g5",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Puck handling under forecheck",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is rimming around the boards and will end up behind your net. Two opposing forwards are forechecking hard. What do you do?",opts:["Cut to the middle of the ice since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover hard","Get to the puck first and either rim it to your D's forehand on the weak side, or freeze it if your D can't get there","Protect the puck there since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover early","Stay in the neutral zone since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover now"],ok:1,why:"A goalie who plays the puck well under forecheck pressure is a huge weapon. Beat the forecheckers to the puck and either set up your D on the open side or freeze it to relieve pressure. Passive goalies let forechecks succeed.",tip:"Puck coming behind the net with pressure? Beat them to it. Set up your D or freeze."},
    {id:"u13g6",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Breakaway — patience and reads",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"A skilled forward is coming on a breakaway. They're moving fast. What's your strategy before they reach the top of the circles?",opts:["Stay in the neutral zone because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice soon","Stay patient on your feet, cut the angle at the top of the crease, and make them commit first","Set up behind the net and wait since the other team has committed to the other side quickly","Set up behind the net and wait since the other team has committed to the other side instead"],ok:1,why:"Patience wins breakaways. Staying on your feet as long as possible forces the shooter to show you their move first. Committing early — going down or lunging — gives the shooter the easy side.",tip:"Breakaway: patience. Stay up. Make them show you first. Then commit."},
    {id:"u13g7",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Lateral movement type",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is passed from the left point to the right half-wall. You're set for the point shot and need to get square to the new shooter. What's the right movement?",opts:["Pass it to your D at the far point because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice right now","T-push hard in your stance — stay on your feet because the shot isn't immediate and you need to be ready to track","Dump it in since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover at that point","Cut to the middle of the ice because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice and look for support"],ok:1,why:"The movement type depends on the situation. For a pass to a new shooting location where the shot isn't imminent, stay on your feet with a T-push. Reserve butterfly slides for when the shot is coming immediately and you need to drop.",tip:"Pass between shooters? T-push on your feet. Save butterfly slides for imminent shots."},
    {id:"u13g8",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Reading deflections",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"A point shot is coming and there's an opposing forward in front of you with their stick on the ice, ready for a tip. What should you prepare for?",opts:["Try to stickhandle through them because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit right away","The deflection — assume the puck will change direction. Stay in your stance, keep your stick on the ice, and read the deflection angle in real time.","Pressure the carrier hard rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set","Drop back and play defense because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit right away"],ok:1,why:"A stick on the ice in front of you is a deflection setup. You have to assume the puck gets tipped. Stay low, keep your stick on the ice, and track the puck through the deflection — it usually changes angle and elevation.",tip:"Stick on the ice in front? Expect a tip. Stay low, track through the deflection."},
    {id:"u13g9",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Rebound redirect — slot vs corner",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"You're making a save from a shot on the right side. You can control where the rebound goes with your pads or blocker. What's the best target for the rebound?",opts:["Pass back since the lane is open now while staying in position","Into the left corner — away from the shooter and out of the slot","Pass back because your teammates need time to set up right now","Pass back and then get back into your defensive position first"],ok:1,why:"Rebound direction is an active skill. Angling your pad to redirect the rebound to the far corner takes it out of the most dangerous area. A rebound in the slot is a goal waiting to happen.",tip:"Control your rebounds. Far corner. Away from the slot. Always."},
    {id:"u13g10",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Post-save recovery",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"You made a kick save with your right pad and you're now on the ice. The puck is still loose in front of you. What's your priority?",opts:["Skate to the corner and dig it out rather than trying to force a risky play here first","Get back to your feet immediately — the play isn't dead and a second shot is coming","Swing wide along the boards before the defense recovers while staying in position","Swing wide along the boards since that creates the best look and look for support"],ok:1,why:"Recovery speed separates average from elite goalies. The second after a save, the play continues. Getting back on your feet fast gets you set for the next shot. Staying down is a goal waiting to happen.",tip:"Made the save? Up. Now. Second shots are the danger."},
    {id:"u13g11",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Backdoor reads on PK",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"Your team is on the penalty kill. The power play is cycling and the puck moves from the half-wall toward the back-door player at the far post. You were set on the strong side. What do you do?",opts:["Stay in the neutral zone rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set fast","Push across the crease aggressively using a butterfly slide or T-push — the backdoor tap-in is the highest-danger chance and you need to close that post","Stay in the neutral zone rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set right now","Stay in the neutral zone rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set hard"],ok:1,why:"The back-door play on a power play is one of the highest-danger chances in hockey. The goalie has to push hard across the crease to take that away. Half-speed movement = goal. Commit to the save.",tip:"PP backdoor play? Push hard across. Close that post. Full commitment."},
    {id:"u13g12",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Freeze management — late game",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"Your team is leading by one goal with 45 seconds left. You make a save and have the puck in your glove. Your team is exhausted. What do you do?",opts:["Drive to the net front rather than trying to force something through the middle of the ice when the lane is not clean and the defenders are set quickly","Cover it completely and milk the whistle — a TV timeout-style faceoff with tired opposing forwards in your zone is actually fine when it kills clock","Shoot from wherever you are now because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit first","Shoot from wherever you are now because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit again"],ok:1,why:"Late-game freeze decisions are about clock management, not just safety. Freezing lets your tired team have a quick breather. Yes, the faceoff is in your zone — but the clock stops, you reset your lines, and your goalie gets a break too.",tip:"Late lead, tired team? Freeze and reset. Clock management over pressure avoidance."},
    {id:"u13g13",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Shooter tendencies",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"A shooter is coming down the right wing. You know from previous shifts they always shoot short side, top corner on the rush. What's your approach?",opts:["Stay in the neutral zone since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover now","Cheat slightly to take away their preferred shot — respect their tendency by giving a bit more of the opposite corner","Force a play through traffic since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover soon","Crash the net for a rebound because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice and look for support"],ok:1,why:"Elite goalies track shooter tendencies within a game. If a player has shown you their preferred spot multiple times, slightly cheating to take it away forces them to beat you somewhere else — often a spot they're less comfortable with.",tip:"Know a shooter's tendency? Respect it. Cheat slightly to take away their spot."},
    {id:"u13g14",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Communication — coverage call",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"You see an opposing player sneaking to the backdoor completely uncovered by your D. Your D are both focused on the corner battle. The pass hasn't come yet. What do you do?",opts:["Take the outside lane because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice instead","Yell loudly — 'Back door!' or 'Net front!' — to warn your D to get a stick on the open player","Hold the puck because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice right away","Carry it wide because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice right away"],ok:1,why:"The goalie has the best view of developing threats. A loud, specific call — 'Back door!' — can get a defender's stick into a passing lane before the pass even happens. Silent goalies watch goals happen.",tip:"See a coverage problem? Call it. Loud. Specific. 'Back door!' stops goals."},
    {id:"u13g15",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Post integration — VH vs overlap",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck carrier is skating in on your right post at a bad angle — they haven't gone below the goal line yet. What's the right post integration?",opts:["Shoot low because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit instead","Vertical Horizontal (VH) — lead pad up against the post, back knee down, so you can push off and track if they cut to the middle","Dump it in because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit on the play","Pass back because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit quickly"],ok:1,why:"VH is used when the puck is above the goal line and can still cut to the middle. RVH is for below the goal line. VH keeps your lead pad sealing the post while letting you push off if they attack the middle. Using the wrong post integration gives up the wrong side.",tip:"Above the goal line? VH. Below? RVH. Know the difference."},
    {id:"u13g16",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Odd-man rush positioning",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"It's a 3-on-2 rush. Your D are in decent position. The puck carrier is on the right side. Where should you set up?",opts:["Drop back and play defense because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit quickly","Slightly cheat right to match the puck carrier while staying square — trust your D on the pass, but give yourself the best angle on the shot","Thread a pass to the slot because in this situation the safest option is to keep possession and let the play develop before you commit now","Set up behind the net and wait since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover and look for support"],ok:1,why:"On an odd-man rush, the goalie cheats slightly to the puck side to take away the shot while trusting the D to handle passes. Dead center gives up too much on both sides. Cheating hard commits too much.",tip:"3-on-2: slight cheat to the puck side. Trust your D. Play the shot."},
    {id:"u13g17",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Puck handling — D-to-D option",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is shot around the boards behind your net. A forechecker is closing from your left. Your D is coming to the left side. Your other D is wide open on the right side. What's the best play?",opts:["Back up and defend since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover from this spot","Stop it, then make a short pass to your right D who is wide open on the weak side — a clean D-to-D breakout under pressure","Take the outside lane since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover on the play","Crash the net for a rebound since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover right away"],ok:1,why:"A goalie who can play a D-to-D pass under pressure is a major asset. Identifying the uncovered defender and getting them the puck clean starts the breakout before the forecheck sets up. This is an advanced skill worth developing.",tip:"Weak-side D wide open? Play it to them. D-to-D breaks forechecks."},
    {id:"u13g18",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Wraparound — seal the post",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"An attacker is skating fast behind your net from right to left, setting up a wraparound attempt on your left post. What do you do?",opts:["Skate to the corner and dig it out because the defenders have committed to the strong side of the ice while staying in position","Push off your right post and move with them, arriving at the left post before they do — seal the bottom of the post with your pad","Swing wide along the boards since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover before they score","Skate to the corner and dig it out since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover first"],ok:1,why:"On a wraparound, the race to the post is everything. Moving with the puck carrier and sealing the near post before they arrive eliminates the wrap option. Late arrival = goal.",tip:"Wraparound? Move with them. Beat them to the post. Seal the bottom."},
    {id:"u13g19",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Aggressive vs conservative positioning",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"Your team is down by two goals with three minutes left. The other team gets a rush chance. What should your positioning look like?",opts:["More aggressive than usual — come out further to cut angles and make them beat you","Shoot from wherever you are now before the play develops further and look for support","Crash the net for a rebound since the lane is open now while staying in position","Crash the net for a rebound because your teammates need time to set up right now"],ok:0,why:"When trailing late, goalies can and should play slightly more aggressively to make stops — because every save gives your team more time. But this is situational: elite goalies adjust their depth based on game state, not just the shooter.",tip:"Trailing late? Slightly more aggressive. Every save buys time. Adjust to game state."},
    {id:"u13g20",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Mental reset after a goal",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"You just gave up a soft goal. Your body language is visibly frustrated. There's a faceoff at center ice in 15 seconds. What's the most important thing to do?",opts:["Try to stickhandle through them since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover right now","Reset immediately — physical cue (tap posts, breathe, focus on the next shot) and put the goal behind you. Analyze later, not now.","Shoot from wherever you are now since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover right now","Pressure the carrier hard since forcing the pass through traffic in the neutral zone usually leads to a turnover and look for support"],ok:1,why:"Mental reset after a goal is a real skill. Elite goalies have a consistent physical cue — tap the posts, deep breath, water bottle — to clear the last save and focus on the next shot. Dwelling on a bad goal during the game causes the next one.",tip:"Soft goal? Physical reset. Post tap, breath, water. Analyze after the game, not during."},
  ],
  "U15 / Bantam":[
    // EASY (d:1) — questions 1-30
    {id:"u15q1",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Forecheck systems",d:1,sit:"Your coach calls a 1-2-2 forecheck. You're the first forward in. What's your primary job?",opts:["Angle the puck carrier to one side and cut off their reverse option","Skate directly at the puck carrier and try to finish your check now up","Wait at the red line until the puck carrier makes their first pass","Drop back to the neutral zone and set up a trap with your line now"],ok:0,why:"In a 1-2-2, F1 angles the puck carrier to one side and eliminates the reverse. You're steering them into your support.",tip:"F1 in a 1-2-2: angle and steer. Take away the reverse."},
    {id:"u15q2",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Quick transition",d:1,sit:"Your team just gained possession in the defensive zone. The opposing forwards are slow getting back. What do you do?",opts:["Hold the puck and wait for all five players to get set up really","Attack quickly — move the puck up ice before their D can organize","Dump it in deep and change lines since your team needs fresh now","Pass it back to the goalie to reset and let them get fully organized"],ok:1,why:"Quick transition exploits the other team before they're set. Attacking immediately creates odd-man advantages.",tip:"They're slow getting back? Go now. Speed in transition creates chances."},
    {id:"u15q3",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP formation",d:1,sit:"Your team runs a 1-3-1 power play. You're the player at the top of the umbrella. What's your primary responsibility?",opts:["Distribute the puck side to side to shift the penalty kill box apart","Crash the net every time the puck goes low to create a screen here","Stay at the top and take slap shots every time you receive the now","Rotate down low and replace the net-front player whenever they now"],ok:0,why:"The top of a 1-3-1 is the quarterback. You distribute and move the puck to shift the PK box, creating seams.",tip:"Top of the 1-3-1: distribute. Move the puck to move the PK."},
    {id:"u15q4",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Rush defense gap",d:1,sit:"An attacker is carrying the puck through the neutral zone at you. You're the lone D back. Where should your gap be?",opts:["One stick length at the top of the circles to force a quick decision","Back up to your own goal line to give yourself maximum time to here","At the far blue line so you can close the distance with a big right","At center ice so you can challenge them before they build full speed up"],ok:0,why:"A tight gap at the top of the circles forces the attacker to make their move early. Too far back gives them time and space.",tip:"Gap control: top of the circles. Force their hand early."},
    {id:"u15q5",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Finishing checks",d:1,sit:"The puck carrier dumps the puck in and skates past you along the boards. They no longer have the puck. Should you finish the check?",opts:["Yes — finishing the check discourages them from coming back for it","No — the puck is gone so contact now is always an interference up","Yes — hit every player near you regardless of where the puck went","No — save your energy for the next play and let them go past you here"],ok:0,why:"Finishing the check on a player who just released the puck is legal and smart. It separates them from the play.",tip:"Just dumped it? Finish the check. Legal and effective."},
    {id:"u15q6",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout patterns",d:1,sit:"Your D has the puck behind the net. The forecheck sends one player hard. You're the center. Where should you be?",opts:["In the middle around the hashmarks providing a short central option","In the corner on the same side helping the D win the board battle","At the far blue line waiting for a long stretch pass over instead","Behind the net with the D so you can take a direct handoff really"],ok:0,why:"The center's breakout job is to be the middle option at the hashmarks — short, safe, and transitions the puck quickly.",tip:"Center on the breakout: hashmarks. Be the middle option."},
    {id:"u15q7",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Backchecking assignment",d:1,sit:"Your team turns the puck over in the offensive zone. You're the high forward. The opposing center has the puck. What's your job?",opts:["Pick up the most dangerous opposing player and skate with them back","Chase the puck carrier from behind and try to poke check the right","Skate to your bench for a change since fresh legs are more instead","Stay in the offensive zone in case your team gets the puck back really"],ok:0,why:"The high forward's backchecking job is to pick up the most dangerous player. Chasing the puck carrier from behind rarely works.",tip:"Turnover? Pick up a man. Don't chase — cover the dangerous player."},
    {id:"u15q8",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"2-on-1 defense",d:1,sit:"You're the lone defenseman on a 2-on-1. The puck carrier is left, pass option is right. What do you do?",opts:["Take away the pass by staying in the middle and force them to shoot","Commit hard to the puck carrier and try to take the puck before up","Skate backward to the goal line and let your goalie handle the now","Ignore both and race back to get in front of your net before the right"],ok:0,why:"On a 2-on-1, the defenseman takes away the pass and forces the shot. Your goalie should handle the shooter.",tip:"2-on-1: take the pass away. Force the shot. Trust your goalie."},
    {id:"u15q9",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK box structure",d:1,sit:"Your team is killing a penalty in a box formation. The PP moves the puck from the half-wall to the point. What does the box do?",opts:["Shift up and toward the puck as a unit to pressure and close lanes","Collapse to the net and let the point player shoot from right now","Break formation and send one player to chase the puck at the point up","Stay completely still and don't move until the puck enters the up"],ok:0,why:"The PK box shifts as a unit toward the puck. When it goes to the point, the box shifts up to close shooting and passing lanes.",tip:"PK box: shift as a unit toward the puck. Stay connected."},
    {id:"u15q10",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Bench communication",d:1,sit:"You come off the ice after a shift and notice the other team keeps exploiting weak-side coverage. What do you do?",opts:["Tell your linemates what you're seeing so they adjust on the next go","Keep it to yourself since making adjustments is only the right now","Yell at the players currently on the ice to fix the coverage issue","Wait until after the game to mention it so you don't distract here"],ok:0,why:"Communicating what you see from the ice to your linemates is leadership. Share information so the team adjusts.",tip:"See something? Share it with your line. That's leadership."},
    {id:"u15q11",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Neutral zone regroup",d:1,sit:"Your team gains the puck in the neutral zone but forwards are all on the wrong side. The D have control. What's the right play?",opts:["Regroup — swing the puck back to the D and let forwards get to lanes","Force the puck forward anyway since speed matters more than instead","Dump it in deep and change lines to get a fresh group onto the ice n up","Hold the puck at center ice and wait for forwards to come back here"],ok:0,why:"Regrouping lets your team attack with structure. Swinging back to the D while forwards find their lanes creates clean zone entries.",tip:"Forwards out of position? Regroup. Swing it back and attack with structure."},
    {id:"u15q12",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D-to-D under pressure",d:1,sit:"You're a D with the puck in your own zone. A forechecker closes from your left. Your D partner is open on the right. What do you do?",opts:["Move the puck to your D partner on the weak side before pressure hits","Try to skate through the forechecker since you have enough room now","Rim the puck hard around the boards behind your net and hope it now","Shoot the puck up the middle of the ice through the traffic out now"],ok:0,why:"D-to-D passes under pressure are fundamental. The forechecker committed to one side — the other is open.",tip:"Forechecker closing from one side? D-to-D to the open side."},
    {id:"u15q13",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Board play positioning",d:1,sit:"You're battling for the puck along the boards. The opponent has their back to you and the puck is at their feet. What's the proper technique?",opts:["Get your stick on the puck while using your body to hold your position","Cross-check them in the back to separate them from the puck right now","Reach around them with your stick and try to pull the puck away first","Back off and wait for a teammate to come help you win the board battle up"],ok:0,why:"Stick on the puck, body in position. That's legal, effective board play.",tip:"Board battle: stick on the puck, body in position. Win it clean."},
    {id:"u15q14",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Angling on the forecheck",d:1,sit:"You're F1 on the forecheck. The D picks up the puck and starts to skate behind their net. How do you approach?",opts:["Angle your skating to cut off one side and force them toward your F2","Skate directly at them at full speed to try to get a big hit really","Peel off and go back to the neutral zone since they have possession now","Slow down and wait to see what they do before committing to any now"],ok:0,why:"Angling as F1 takes away options. Cut off one side and force them into your support.",tip:"F1 forecheck: angle and cut off one side. Force them into support."},
    {id:"u15q15",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defensive zone faceoff",d:1,sit:"There's a defensive zone faceoff to the left of your goalie. You're the right winger. Where should you be set up?",opts:["On the hash marks on your side covering the opposing player there n","At center ice ready to break out fast if your center wins the draw now","In front of the net to help your goalie with any shots after right","Behind the opposing D at the point to block any shot from that now"],ok:0,why:"Every player has a faceoff assignment. The winger lines up at the hash marks on their side to cover their assignment.",tip:"Defensive zone faceoff: hash marks, your side. Know your assignment."},
    {id:"u15q16",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Stretch pass recognition",d:1,sit:"You're a forward and your D just won the puck. You see the opposing D pinching deep with open ice behind them. What do you do?",opts:["Sprint to the open ice and call for the stretch pass behind them now","Stay in your lane and wait for the standard breakout pattern to now","Come back deep to help your D move the puck even though ice is open","Skate to the bench for a quick change since your team just got it right"],ok:0,why:"Recognizing when the opposing D is out of position and sprinting behind them creates a stretch pass opportunity.",tip:"Their D pinching? Sprint behind them. Call for the stretch pass."},
    {id:"u15q17",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP zone entry",d:1,sit:"Your team is on the power play entering the offensive zone. The PK is set up 1-1-2 at the blue line. What's the best entry strategy?",opts:["Use speed and carry the puck wide to beat the first layer and enter","Dump it in deep to the corner and chase since that is the for sure","Pass across to the far-side player who has more open space right right","Shoot the puck in from center ice and hope it bounces to your here"],ok:0,why:"Against a 1-1-2, carrying wide with speed beats the first layer. Possession entries are better than dump-ins on the PP.",tip:"PP entry: carry wide with speed. Possession entries create more chances."},
    {id:"u15q18",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Pinch decision",d:1,sit:"You're the O-zone D at the blue line. The puck is rimmed to your side. You could pinch but an opposing forward is behind you. Should you pinch?",opts:["Only pinch if you're sure you'll get to the puck first — else hold n","Always pinch because keeping the puck in the zone is the top right","Never pinch when there's a forward behind you since it is for sure","Pinch every time because your goalie and other D can cover if here"],ok:0,why:"The pinch decision is risk-reward. If you're sure you'll get there first, pinch. If not, hold the line.",tip:"Pinch decision: will you get there first? Yes = pinch. No = hold."},
    {id:"u15q19",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Net-front defense",d:1,sit:"You're a D and an opposing forward is setting up in front of your net for a screen or deflection. What do you do?",opts:["Tie up their stick and box them out of the prime scoring area there","Push them hard from behind with both hands to get them away right","Ignore them and focus only on the puck carrier since that's right","Skate away from the net front and let your goalie deal with it up"],ok:0,why:"Net-front defense is about stick work and body position. Tie up their stick and box them out.",tip:"Opponent at your net front? Tie up stick. Box out. Protect goalie's eyes."},
    {id:"u15q20",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"2-1-2 forecheck",d:1,sit:"Your coach runs a 2-1-2 forecheck. You're one of the two forwards going in first. How does this differ from a 1-2-2?",opts:["You and your partner pressure together aggressively to create turnovers","You go in alone first and your partner hangs back at the red line area now","You both stay at center ice and wait for them to bring the puck to you","You pinch from the blue line while your partner forechecks alone there"],ok:0,why:"In a 2-1-2, two forwards pressure together. More aggressive than 1-2-2 with immediate support.",tip:"2-1-2: two in, pressure together. More aggressive with immediate support."},
    {id:"u15q21",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"OZ turnover pressure",d:1,sit:"Your team has the puck in the O-zone and it gets turned over. You're the nearest forward. What's the first thing you do?",opts:["Apply immediate pressure on the new puck carrier to force a quick error","Chase the puck carrier all the way back into your defensive zone alone","Skate straight to the bench for a change since your offensive shift really","Stand still and watch what the other team does before you react to now"],ok:0,why:"Immediate pressure on the turnover is the first line of defense. Force a quick decision before they break out.",tip:"OZ turnover? Pressure immediately. Force a bad decision."},
    {id:"u15q22",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Shift length",d:1,sit:"You're having a great shift creating chances. But you've been on the ice for over a minute. What do you do?",opts:["Get off the ice for a change — tired players make costly mistakes now","Stay on as long as possible since you're playing really well out up","Wait until the puck is in the O-zone and then stay on for right now","Keep playing until you score since you are the best option out here"],ok:0,why:"Shift discipline matters more than individual performance. Tired players make turnovers that cost goals.",tip:"Great shift but tired? Get off. Discipline over heroics."},
    {id:"u15q23",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading speed",d:1,sit:"The puck carrier enters the neutral zone with speed. You're the D. They're fast. How does their speed change your gap?",opts:["Slightly bigger gap so they can't blow past you with their speed now","Tighter gap because fast players need to be challenged before right","Same gap regardless of how fast the puck carrier is skating at here","Back up to your goal line and let your goalie handle the fast player up"],ok:0,why:"Against a fast puck carrier, a slightly bigger gap prevents getting caught flat-footed.",tip:"Fast carrier? Slightly bigger gap. Don't get caught flat-footed."},
    {id:"u15q24",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK forecheck",d:1,sit:"Your team is killing a penalty. The opposing D has the puck in their zone setting up their PP breakout. What's your approach as the forechecker?",opts:["Controlled pressure — take away the easy first pass without going deep","Forecheck aggressively with two players to get the puck back right up","Hang back at your own blue line and let them enter before you engage n up","Sprint at the D as fast as possible to force an immediate turnover up"],ok:0,why:"PK forechecking is controlled pressure. Take away the easy pass without overcommitting.",tip:"PK forecheck: controlled pressure. Don't get caught deep."},
    {id:"u15q25",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Protecting yourself",d:1,sit:"You're carrying the puck through the neutral zone and see a defender setting up for a big open-ice hit. What do you do?",opts:["Keep your head up, absorb or avoid the contact, keep the puck moving","Stop skating and give up the puck to avoid the hit since it's right","Skate directly into the hit to try to deliver one back even instead","Drop your head and power through with your shoulders down and eyes here"],ok:0,why:"Head up, protect yourself, keep the puck moving. Never skate into a hit with your head down.",tip:"Defender lining you up? Head up. Protect yourself. Keep the puck moving."},
    {id:"u15q26",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Cycle play reads",d:1,sit:"Your team is cycling in the O-zone. You've made three passes along the boards but the defense isn't moving. What do you look for?",opts:["A change in the defensive structure — a seam to the slot or open man","Keep cycling along the boards forever until the period ends right right","Dump the puck behind the net and chase it to restart the cycle here","Shoot from the boards even though there's no lane since it's really"],ok:0,why:"The cycle creates openings by moving defenders. When they don't move, look for the seam — slot pass, net drive, or point shot.",tip:"Cycling but D isn't moving? Look for the seam. Slot, net, or point."},
    {id:"u15q27",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading the forecheck",d:1,sit:"You're a D with the puck. The forecheck sends two hard. Your center is covered. Your winger on the wall is open. What do you do?",opts:["Move the puck quickly to your open winger before the pressure arrives","Try to skate through both forecheckers since you have room to right","Hold the puck behind your net and wait for the forecheck to back up","Shoot the puck off the glass and out of the zone for immediate here"],ok:0,why:"Two forecheckers closing means less time. Your open winger is the right play — move the puck before pressure arrives.",tip:"Two forecheckers? Find the open man fast. Don't hold it."},
    {id:"u15q28",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Responding to a bad call",d:1,sit:"The referee makes a call you disagree with. Your team is now on the PK. How do you respond?",opts:["Focus on the penalty kill — the call is made and arguing won't help n","Yell at the referee from the penalty box to let them know it was up","Complain to your teammates so everyone knows the call was unfair to","Take a retaliatory penalty to send a message that you won't instead"],ok:0,why:"Arguing with refs doesn't reverse calls. Channel that energy into a strong PK.",tip:"Bad call? Kill the penalty. Channel the energy productively."},
    {id:"u15q29",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defending with support coming",d:1,sit:"An attacker is coming at you 1-on-1, but your partner is hustling back and will arrive in two seconds. How does this change your approach?",opts:["Contain and slow the attacker down — buy time for your partner to get back","Attack the puck carrier aggressively to end the play before help for sure","Back up to the goal line and wait for your partner to handle the play now","Step up at the blue line and go for a big hit to end the play right now right"],ok:0,why:"Help is coming. Contain, slow them down, and let your partner arrive to create a 2-on-1 in your favor.",tip:"Help coming? Contain. Slow them down. Turn 1-on-1 into 2-on-1."},
    {id:"u15q30",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"OZ faceoff set play",d:1,sit:"Your team has an offensive zone faceoff. The coach calls a set play — puck back to the point for a shot. What's everyone's job?",opts:["Win the draw back, forwards set a screen, D walks and shoots through","Everyone crashes the net immediately after the puck drops right now","The center tries to score directly off the faceoff since that's instead","Only the center and one winger are involved — everyone else just up"],ok:0,why:"Set plays require execution from all five players. Win it back, screen, shoot.",tip:"Faceoff set play: everyone has a job. Execute together."},
    // MEDIUM (d:2) — questions 31-70
    {id:"u15q31",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Forecheck adjustment",d:2,sit:"Your team has been running a 2-1-2 forecheck but the other team keeps breaking it with quick D-to-D passes. What adjustment should you suggest?",opts:["Take away the D-to-D pass by positioning F1 between the two D when they have the puck","Keep running the same 2-1-2 since eventually it will work if you just skate for sure","Switch to a 1-2-2 trap and don't forecheck at all since nothing seems to be working here","Send all three forwards deep into their zone to pressure both D and the center at up"],ok:0,why:"If D-to-D passes are beating your forecheck, F1 needs to position between the two D to take that option away. Adjusting forecheck positioning is smarter than just skating harder.",tip:"D-to-D beating you? F1 positions between the two D. Take it away."},
    {id:"u15q32",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Activating D in the rush",d:2,sit:"Your team is breaking out cleanly. You're a D and the forwards have speed through the neutral zone. There's a trailer lane open. Should you jump into the rush?",opts:["Yes — fill the trailer lane and give your team an extra option in the offensive zone attack","No — both D should always stay back regardless of how clean the breakout looks right right","Only jump if the other team has already committed all their players back into their zone right","Wait until the forwards dump the puck in and then join the forecheck as the fifth for sure"],ok:0,why:"When the breakout is clean and there's a trailer lane, an activating D creates an overload in the offensive zone. The key is reading when it's safe.",tip:"Clean breakout with a trailer lane? Jump in. Extra option in the attack."},
    {id:"u15q33",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP puck movement",d:2,sit:"Your team's PP is set up in the zone. The PK is in a tight box. Every pass to the slot is getting intercepted. What do you do?",opts:["Move the puck around the perimeter faster to force the box to shift and create the seam","Keep forcing passes to the slot since eventually one will get through if you throw instead","Pull the puck out of the zone and re-enter to reset since the formation isn't for sure","Have all five players crash the net at the same time to create chaos in front of right"],ok:0,why:"A tight PK box is beaten by fast puck movement around the perimeter. Force them to shift — the seam opens when they can't rotate fast enough.",tip:"Tight PK box? Move the puck faster around the perimeter. Force them to shift."},
    {id:"u15q34",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"3-on-2 rush defense",d:2,sit:"You're one of two D on a 3-on-2 rush. The three attackers are spread across the ice. The puck is in the middle. What's your read?",opts:["You take the wide player on your side and trust your partner to take the other and play shot","Both D collapse to the middle to take away the shot and leave the wide players for your now","Both D back up to the goal line together and let the goalie handle everything that comes at now","One D steps up aggressively on the puck carrier while the other covers both wide players up"],ok:0,why:"On a 3-on-2, each D takes a wide player. The middle player (shooter) is the goalie's responsibility. Collapsing both D to the middle leaves two wide options open.",tip:"3-on-2: each D takes a wide player. Goalie plays the shot."},
    {id:"u15q35",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Separating player from puck",d:2,sit:"An opposing forward receives a pass in the slot with their head down, looking at the puck. You're the nearest D. What's the right play?",opts:["Close quickly and deliver a clean check through their body to separate them from the puck","Stand back and poke check from a distance since body contact in the slot is too risky really","Wait for them to shoot and then try to block the shot with your body as it comes instead","Skate behind them and reach around with your stick to try to lift theirs off the puck up"],ok:0,why:"A player with their head down in the slot is vulnerable. A clean check through the body separates them from the puck and sends a message.",tip:"Head down in the slot? Close and separate. Clean hit, big message."},
    {id:"u15q36",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defensive zone rotation",d:2,sit:"Your winger goes to the corner to help the D battle for the puck. You're the center. The opposing point man is now uncovered. What do you do?",opts:["Rotate up to cover the point man since your winger left that assignment to go to the corner","Stay in the slot and hope your winger gets back to their assignment before the puck goes up up","Follow your winger into the corner to help create a 3-on-1 battle there for the loose puck","Skate to the bench for a change since the coverage is broken and fresh legs can sort it up"],ok:0,why:"When a winger drops to the corner, the center rotates up to cover the vacated point assignment. This is basic defensive zone rotation.",tip:"Winger goes to the corner? Center rotates up to the point. Cover the vacated man."},
    {id:"u15q37",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Controlled breakout vs rim",d:2,sit:"Your D has the puck in the corner. Two forecheckers are closing. Your winger is on the wall but covered. There's no clean pass. What's the safest play?",opts:["Rim the puck hard around the boards behind the net to your D partner on the weak side of ice","Try to force the pass to the covered winger and hope they can handle the pressure on the up","Skate with the puck through both forecheckers since you have enough room to beat them right","Hold the puck in the corner and take the hit to draw a penalty from the aggressive forecheck up"],ok:0,why:"When there's no clean pass, rimming to the weak side moves the puck away from pressure and gives your D partner a chance to make the next play.",tip:"No clean pass under pressure? Rim to the weak side. Move the puck away from danger."},
    {id:"u15q38",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK pressure timing",d:2,sit:"Your team is on the PK. The PP has the puck at the point and they're looking to pass to the half-wall. When do you pressure the point man?",opts:["When they look down to make the pass — that's when they're vulnerable and can be forced to rush","Immediately — constant pressure on the point prevents any pass from being made at all times up","Never — the PK box should stay in formation and not chase the puck to the perimeter of the now","Only when there are less than 30 seconds left in the penalty since that's when pressure matters up"],ok:0,why:"Timing the pressure when the point man looks down to pass disrupts their rhythm. Constant pressure pulls you out of position; no pressure gives them all day.",tip:"PK: pressure the point when they look down to pass. Timing over aggression."},
    {id:"u15q39",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading the deke",d:2,sit:"An attacker is coming at you 1-on-1. They drop their shoulder to the left. You've seen them do this before — they always go right after the fake. What do you do?",opts:["Stay patient on the inside — don't bite on the shoulder fake and take away their right side","Commit to the left side since that's where their shoulder is going and you should follow it up","Back up to the goal line and wait since trying to read fakes at this level is too risky up","Step up aggressively and try to hit them before they can complete any deke in either right"],ok:0,why:"Recognizing tendencies is an elite defensive skill. If you've seen the fake before, don't bite. Stay patient on the inside and take away their preferred move.",tip:"Seen the fake before? Don't bite. Stay patient. Take away their preferred side."},
    {id:"u15q40",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Taking a hit to make a play",d:2,sit:"You have the puck along the boards and a defender is closing to hit you. You see your center open in the slot. You can make the pass but you'll get hit after the release. What do you do?",opts:["Make the pass to the open center and absorb the hit — the scoring chance is worth the contact","Protect yourself first and chip the puck up the boards away from both the defender and right","Hold the puck and try to deke around the closing defender to avoid the contact and keep here","Turn your back to the defender and shield the puck while waiting for another option to open here"],ok:0,why:"Making the play while absorbing contact is a sign of hockey maturity. The center is open in the slot — that's a scoring chance. Take the hit, make the pass.",tip:"Open man in the slot? Make the pass. Take the hit. Scoring chances are worth it."},
    {id:"u15q41",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Video review application",d:2,sit:"In video review, your coach shows that the opponent's breakout always sends the puck up the left wall. Your team is about to play them. What do you do with this information?",opts:["Overload the left side on the forecheck to intercept and force them to adjust mid-game now","Ignore it since every game is different and scouting reports don't apply once the puck really","Set up the exact same forecheck as always since you shouldn't change your system for here","Tell only the coach what you noticed and let them decide if the team should make for sure"],ok:0,why:"Video review is only valuable if you apply it. Overloading the side they favor forces adjustments and creates turnovers.",tip:"Scouting report says left wall? Overload it. Make them adjust to you."},
    {id:"u15q42",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Offensive blue line decisions",d:2,sit:"You're a D at the offensive blue line. The puck is dumped into the corner by your forward. The opposing D gets to it first. You see their winger starting to leak out. What do you do?",opts:["Hold the blue line and be ready to close on the winger if they try to exit on your side now","Pinch into the corner to try to force a turnover since your forward needs help winning it here","Skate backward to center ice to give yourself a head start in case the puck comes back out","Leave the blue line completely and go help your forward in the corner win the puck instead"],ok:0,why:"With a winger leaking out, holding the line is critical. If you pinch and the puck gets to that winger, it's a breakaway.",tip:"Winger leaking out? Hold the line. Don't pinch into a breakaway against."},
    {id:"u15q43",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP one-timer setup",d:2,sit:"You're on the PP half-wall. The puck is at the point. You see the PK is cheating toward the point shooter. The back-door player on the far side is open. What do you call for?",opts:["The cross-ice pass from the point to the far side for the one-timer since the PK shifted away","A pass to you on the half-wall since you're in a better position to shoot from your for sure","A shot from the point through traffic since that's the highest percentage play from that instead","The puck back to the D in the corner to reset and try a new play since this look isn't right"],ok:0,why:"When the PK shifts toward the point, the far side opens up. A cross-ice pass for a one-timer exploits that shift perfectly.",tip:"PK shifting to the point? Cross-ice one-timer on the far side. Exploit the shift."},
    {id:"u15q44",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defending the cycle",d:2,sit:"The opposing team is cycling in your zone. The puck carrier is below the goal line. You're the weak-side D. Where should your eyes be?",opts:["On the weak-side player and the slot — the most dangerous pass is coming to your side next","Only on the puck carrier since you need to see what they do before you can react to right","On your goalie to make sure they're set and tracking the puck through all the traffic now","On the opposing point man at the blue line since they might pinch down from their position up"],ok:0,why:"The weak-side D must have eyes on the weak-side player and the slot. The cross-ice pass or back-door play is the most dangerous option when the puck is below the goal line.",tip:"Weak-side D during a cycle: eyes on the weak-side player and slot."},
    {id:"u15q45",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Penalty avoidance",d:2,sit:"You're battling hard in front of the net. The referee has already warned you about cross-checking. The opponent is pushing back hard. What do you do?",opts:["Adjust your technique — use your body and stick position instead of the crosscheck motion","Keep playing the same way since the referee probably won't call it if you've only been right","Back off completely and let the opponent have the net-front position so you avoid a here","Push even harder to establish dominance since the referee usually lets the second really"],ok:0,why:"After a warning, adjusting technique is smart. Use body position and stick placement instead of the crosscheck motion. A penalty here could cost a goal.",tip:"Warned by the ref? Adjust your technique. Same result, legal method."},
    {id:"u15q46",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Forechecking read — dump vs carry",d:2,sit:"Your team's forecheck pressure has been working — you're getting turnovers. Entering the zone, a defender backs off and gives you space at the blue line. Do you carry or dump?",opts:["Carry the puck in since the defender is backing off and giving you time and space to attack","Dump it in deep because that's what the forecheck system calls for regardless of what here","Pass it back to your D and regroup since you're not sure what to do with the extra space given","Stop at the blue line and wait for all five players to get set before you make any instead"],ok:0,why:"When a defender backs off and gives you space, carrying the puck in is the right read. Dumping when you have space wastes a possession advantage.",tip:"Defender giving you space? Carry it in. Don't dump when you have time."},
    {id:"u15q47",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Quick up vs controlled breakout",d:2,sit:"Your D wins a puck battle in the corner. The opposing forwards are deep in your zone. Your center is wide open at the hashmarks with a lane up the middle. What's the call?",opts:["Quick up to the open center — get the puck moving before the opposing forwards recover position","Controlled breakout — make a safe pass behind the net and let the team set up in their instead","Rim it around the boards to your winger on the wall since that's the standard breakout pattern now","Hold the puck and wait for the forwards to recover since there's no rush to move it up the ice"],ok:0,why:"When the center is open and opposing forwards are deep, the quick-up pass creates a transition advantage before the other team recovers.",tip:"Center open, their forwards deep? Quick up. Attack before they recover."},
    {id:"u15q48",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK shot blocking",d:2,sit:"You're on the PK and the PP point man winds up for a slap shot. You're in the lane. What's the right technique for blocking?",opts:["Get down on one knee with your stick on the ice and angle your body to deflect the puck to corner","Stand tall and try to catch or bat the puck out of the air since that gives you more puck really","Turn sideways and close your eyes since the most important thing is just getting in the way here","Stay standing in front of the shot and try to kick the puck away with your skate before it right now"],ok:0,why:"Shot blocking technique matters. One knee down, stick on the ice, body angled to deflect wide. Turning sideways or closing eyes is dangerous.",tip:"Blocking on the PK: one knee, stick down, angle to deflect. Technique matters."},
    {id:"u15q49",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D-pair communication",d:2,sit:"You're playing defense and the puck carrier enters the neutral zone. Your D partner is on the other side. The carrier cuts toward the middle. What do you communicate?",opts:["Call 'I've got the middle' or 'push him wide' — let your partner know who has what assignment","Stay quiet and assume your partner knows what you're thinking based on your body positioning now","Yell 'hit him!' so your partner comes across and you both converge on the puck carrier right","Don't say anything since talking on the ice is distracting and interferes with your for sure"],ok:0,why:"D-pair communication prevents confusion. A quick call tells your partner who has the carrier and whether to support or hold their side.",tip:"D-pair: communicate. 'I've got him' or 'push wide.' Quick and clear."},
    {id:"u15q50",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Puck protection below the goal line",d:2,sit:"You have the puck below the goal line in the offensive zone. A defender is closing on you. You're not in a position to pass. What do you do?",opts:["Use your body to shield the puck and buy time until a teammate gets open for a pass option","Try to force a centering pass through the defender's legs since that might create a here","Skate behind the net at full speed to the other side since speed alone will beat the now","Leave the puck against the boards and skate away since there's no play to be made really"],ok:0,why:"Below the goal line, puck protection is king. Use your body as a shield, keep the puck on your backhand, and buy time for support to arrive.",tip:"Below the goal line with pressure? Shield the puck. Buy time. Wait for support."},
    {id:"u15q51",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"NZ trap recognition",d:2,sit:"The other team is playing a 1-3-1 neutral zone trap. Your forwards keep skating into it and turning the puck over. What's the adjustment?",opts:["Use your D to carry the puck through the trap since they have more room to operate from behind","Keep skating into it faster since eventually speed alone will break the trap if you go right","Dump the puck every single time and never try to carry through any neutral zone formation at","Slow the game down and force them to come out of the trap by holding the puck in your own up"],ok:0,why:"Against a 1-3-1 trap, having your D carry or using east-west passes to move the trap opens seams. Skating into it plays right into their hands.",tip:"Facing a 1-3-1 trap? D carry, east-west passes, or pull them out. Don't skate into it."},
    {id:"u15q52",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading the play after the whistle",d:2,sit:"There's a whistle in the neutral zone. Before the faceoff, you notice the other team is making a line change and their right D looks tired. What do you do with this information?",opts:["Tell your center to try to win the draw to the right side to exploit the tired D on the next play","Keep it to yourself since there's nothing your team can do about the other team's fatigue right here","Shout it loud enough for the other team to hear so they know you're watching and paying for sure","Ignore the other team entirely since what they do before the faceoff doesn't matter in this game"],ok:0,why:"Noticing fatigue or matchup weaknesses before faceoffs is hockey IQ. Sharing that with your center helps your team exploit the advantage immediately.",tip:"Tired D on the other side? Tell your center. Exploit the matchup."},
    {id:"u15q53",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP below the dots",d:2,sit:"You're on the PP in the offensive zone. You have the puck below the dots on the half-wall. The PK is collapsing to the net. The point is wide open. What do you do?",opts:["Pass to the open point man since the PK collapsed and left the top of the zone completely open","Force a pass through the collapsed PK to the net-front player since that's the highest danger","Hold the puck and try to walk around the collapsed PK since you have more skill than they do here","Shoot the puck from below the dots since you have a partially obstructed view of the net from"],ok:0,why:"When the PK collapses to the net, the point opens up. Getting the puck to the point creates a shot through traffic or a pass back down to an opening.",tip:"PK collapses? Pass to the open point. The shot through traffic is dangerous."},
    {id:"u15q54",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Switching in defensive zone",d:2,sit:"In the defensive zone, your winger's man cuts across the ice toward your side. Your man stays put. Should you and your winger switch assignments?",opts:["Yes — switch and communicate so each D-man stays in their zone and covers the nearest threat now","No — always stay with your original man regardless of where they go on the ice during the right","Only switch if the coach specifically told you to switch before the game or during the last timeout","Let the winger decide since they had the original assignment and it's their responsibility here"],ok:0,why:"Switching when opponents cross is smart defensive zone play. The key is communication — both players need to know who has who.",tip:"Opponent crosses zones? Switch and communicate. Don't chase across the ice."},
    {id:"u15q55",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"After the whistle composure",d:2,sit:"The whistle blows and an opponent gives you a shove after the play. They're trying to bait you into a reaction. What do you do?",opts:["Skate away and don't react — a retaliatory penalty hurts your team more than their shove did","Shove them back harder to show them you won't be pushed around by anyone on the other team here","Get in their face and challenge them since backing down will only encourage more after that","Complain to the referee about the shove so they know the other team is playing dirty really"],ok:0,why:"After-the-whistle composure is discipline. The shove is designed to draw a reaction. A retaliatory penalty gives them the advantage they wanted.",tip:"Shoved after the whistle? Skate away. Don't take the bait. Discipline wins."},
    {id:"u15q56",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading the opponent's breakout",d:2,sit:"You notice the opposing team always sends their center up the middle on breakouts. Your team's F2 isn't picking the center up. What's the adjustment?",opts:["Have F2 take away the middle lane on the forecheck so the center can't receive the breakout pass","Have F1 chase the D harder into the corner since that will prevent the breakout pass after that","Pull all three forwards back to the neutral zone and stop forechecking completely to stay right","Ignore the center and focus on the wingers since the center usually isn't the most dangerous option"],ok:0,why:"If the opposing center is consistently getting the middle breakout pass, F2 needs to take that lane away. Recognizing patterns and adjusting is systems hockey IQ.",tip:"Center always getting the middle pass? F2 takes the lane away. Adjust."},
    {id:"u15q57",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Controlled exit under pressure",d:2,sit:"Your team is under heavy forecheck pressure in your own zone. You get the puck behind your net. Two forecheckers are closing. Your only option is the glass. Do you use it?",opts:["Yes — get the puck off the glass and out of the zone to relieve the immediate pressure safely now","No — always try to make a play with the puck even if that means holding it under heavy pressure here","Yes — but aim for a teammate at the blue line to turn the clear into a breakout opportunity here","No — freeze the puck and take a faceoff instead since that resets the play more effectively here"],ok:0,why:"Using the glass to exit the zone under heavy pressure is a smart play. It relieves pressure and gets the puck out safely.",tip:"Heavy pressure, no options? Use the glass. Get it out. Live to play another shift."},
    {id:"u15q58",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK lane discipline",d:2,sit:"You're on the PK in the box. The PP moves the puck to the half-wall and the shooter looks like they're going to shoot. You're the nearest PK player. What do you do?",opts:["Get your stick in the shooting lane to block or deflect the shot without fully committing out","Charge at the shooter to close the distance and try to block the shot with your body right right","Stay in the box and don't move since staying in formation is more important than blocking up","Drop to both knees and slide toward the shooter to cover as much of the lane as you possibly"],ok:0,why:"Stick in the lane without overcommitting keeps you in the PK structure while disrupting the shot. Charging out leaves a gap in the box.",tip:"PK: stick in the lane. Don't overcommit. Disrupt without leaving a gap."},
    {id:"u15q59",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading the drop pass",d:2,sit:"Two attackers are entering your zone. The puck carrier slows down at the blue line — you suspect a drop pass to the trailing player. How do you defend it?",opts:["Hold your position and read the play — if they drop it, your partner should be taking the trailer","Commit to the puck carrier and try to hit them before they can drop the pass back to the trailer now","Ignore the puck carrier and skate directly at the trailer since they'll end up with the puck now","Back up to the goal line and give them the blue line since the drop pass is too difficult to now"],ok:0,why:"The drop pass is a read. If you commit to the carrier, the trailer is free. Hold position, let your partner take the trailer, and stay in the play.",tip:"Suspect a drop pass? Hold position. Your partner takes the trailer."},
    {id:"u15q60",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Winning the wall",d:2,sit:"You're forechecking and the D is going to the boards to play the puck. You arrive at the same time. How do you win this battle?",opts:["Arrive with speed and pin them to the boards — use your body to separate them from the puck first","Slow down before you arrive and try to poke check the puck away without making any body contact","Skate past them and go behind the net to wait for the puck to come around the boards to you now","Stop before the boards and wait to see what they do with the puck before engaging in any really"],ok:0,why:"Winning the wall means arriving with speed and using your body. Pin them, separate them from the puck, and get possession.",tip:"Forechecking to the wall: arrive with speed. Pin. Separate. Win the puck."},
    {id:"u15q61",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout under heavy pressure",d:2,sit:"The opponent is running a hard 2-1-2 forecheck. Your standard breakout keeps getting disrupted. The coach calls a timeout. What breakout adjustment makes sense?",opts:["Use a reverse breakout — go behind the net and use the weak side to escape heavy-side pressure","Keep running the same breakout but harder since the issue is effort and not the system really","Stop trying to break out and just dump the puck out every time since it's safer than a after that","Have the goalie freeze every puck to get faceoffs instead of attempting breakouts under right"],ok:0,why:"Against a heavy forecheck, reversing the puck behind the net exploits their overcommitment to one side. The weak side usually has more time and space.",tip:"Heavy forecheck? Reverse behind the net. Escape to the weak side."},
    {id:"u15q62",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Supporting the puck carrier",d:2,sit:"Your D has the puck and is skating up ice with it. You're a forward skating alongside. They're approaching a defender. What's the best support position?",opts:["Stay slightly behind and to the outside to be an outlet if they get pressured or need support","Skate ahead of them into the zone to get open for a pass even if that means going offside up","Stay at exactly the same height as them since parallel support is always the best option for now","Slow down and go back to the defensive zone to make sure someone is covering in case of here"],ok:0,why:"Trailing support — slightly behind and to the outside — gives the puck carrier an outlet without cluttering their space.",tip:"D carrying the puck? Trail slightly behind and outside. Be the outlet."},
    {id:"u15q63",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"6-on-5 with goalie pulled",d:2,sit:"Your team pulls the goalie for an extra attacker. You're the sixth skater. It's late in the game and you're trailing by one. What's your role?",opts:["Take the net-front position or the point — add presence where you create the most overload chance","Carry the puck around the zone yourself since having an extra player means you have more room up","Stay at center ice in case the other team gets the puck so you can backcheck and prevent the now","Float between positions and go wherever the puck is since the extra player means more flexibility up"],ok:0,why:"The extra attacker needs to add value in a specific spot — net front for screens/tips or the point for shots. Floating around wastes the advantage.",tip:"6-on-5: take a specific spot. Net front or point. Don't float."},
    {id:"u15q64",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Transition D gap",d:2,sit:"Your team just turned the puck over at the opposing blue line. Their fastest forward picks it up with speed. You're the nearest D and you're caught flat-footed. What do you do?",opts:["Open your hips and skate hard to match their speed — maintain a gap you can work with as you go","Stand your ground at the blue line and try to make a big hit as they come through the neutral zone","Turn and sprint to your own net to beat them there since that's the only way to stop the right","Stay at the offensive blue line and let your D partner handle the rush since you're out of now"],ok:0,why:"When caught flat-footed, the priority is to open your hips and match speed. Maintaining any gap is better than standing still or giving up.",tip:"Caught flat-footed? Open hips, match speed. Don't stand still. Recover."},
    {id:"u15q65",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Playing through fatigue",d:2,sit:"You're in the third period and your legs are heavy. You still have to compete for loose pucks along the boards. How do you adjust?",opts:["Use smarter body positioning — get there early and use angles to compensate for your tired legs","Play the exact same way as the first period since showing fatigue is a weakness your opponent sees","Stop competing for loose pucks and focus only on positioning since your legs can't handle here","Ask for shorter shifts but don't change anything about how you compete during the time instead"],ok:0,why:"Fatigue is real. Smart players adjust — they use positioning and angles to compensate when their legs are heavy. You can compete smart, not just hard.",tip:"Legs heavy? Use positioning and angles. Compete smart when you can't compete just hard."},
    {id:"u15q66",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defensive zone wall play",d:2,sit:"The opposing team is cycling along your boards. The puck carrier is below the dots with support. Your D is on them. You're the nearest forward. Where do you position yourself?",opts:["In the passing lane between the puck carrier and their support player to intercept the next pass","Directly behind your D to help with the board battle since two bodies are better than one in up","In front of the net since that's always the forward's job regardless of where the puck is right","At the blue line to prevent the opposing D from keeping the puck in the zone if it comes up high up"],ok:0,why:"Taking the passing lane between the puck carrier and their support cuts off the cycle. If your D has the board battle, your job is to eliminate the next pass.",tip:"D has the board battle? Take the passing lane. Cut off the cycle."},
    {id:"u15q67",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Tape-to-tape breakout passing",d:2,sit:"You're a D making a breakout pass. Your winger is open on the wall but skating at full speed. Where do you put the pass?",opts:["Tape-to-tape — lead them slightly so the puck arrives in stride without them slowing down at all","Right at their feet so they have to stop and collect it before they can continue skating up the","Behind them so they have to turn around and come back for the puck before continuing with right","Loft it high in the air so it goes over the forechecker's stick and lands near your winger up ahead"],ok:0,why:"A breakout pass to a player in stride must lead them. Tape-to-tape in stride keeps the speed of the transition — a pass to their feet kills the momentum.",tip:"Breakout pass to a player in stride: lead them. Tape-to-tape. Keep the speed."},
    {id:"u15q68",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Lifting a teammate",d:2,sit:"Your linemate made a bad turnover that led to a goal. They're clearly frustrated and their effort is dropping. What do you do?",opts:["Talk to them — encourage them and remind them the next shift is a fresh start for both of you","Ignore it since their mental state is their own responsibility and not yours to manage right","Tell them they need to play better since honest criticism is what they need to hear at right","Ask the coach to bench them for a few shifts so they can figure things out on their own for sure"],ok:0,why:"Lifting a teammate after a mistake is real leadership. A quick word of encouragement on the bench can reset their mindset for the next shift.",tip:"Teammate struggling? Lift them up. Next shift is a fresh start."},
    {id:"u15q69",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Late-game defending",d:2,sit:"Your team is up by one goal with two minutes left. The opposing team is pressing hard. You're the D. How does your gap change?",opts:["Slightly tighter gap — force quick decisions and don't give them time or space to create anything","Much bigger gap — play ultra-conservative and back up to the goal line to make sure nothing gets now","Same gap as always since you shouldn't change your defensive approach based on the game for sure","Abandon gap control entirely and just try to block every shot and clear every puck out of the up"],ok:0,why:"With a lead late, slightly tighter gap forces the other team into quick, low-percentage decisions. Backing up too far invites pressure.",tip:"Protecting a lead? Slightly tighter gap. Force quick decisions. Don't back up."},
    {id:"u15q70",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Board battle technique",d:2,sit:"You're on the forecheck and the D receives the puck along the boards. You arrive just after them. They're bigger than you. How do you win this battle?",opts:["Get low, use leverage and quick feet to get your stick on the puck — body position over raw size","Match their size by standing tall and pushing straight through them with your upper body really","Wait until they try to move the puck and then intercept the pass instead of engaging in the instead","Avoid the battle entirely and let a bigger teammate handle it while you cover a passing lane up"],ok:0,why:"Board battles are won with leverage, not size. Getting low, using quick feet, and getting your stick on the puck beats bigger players.",tip:"Bigger opponent? Get low, use leverage. Quick feet beat size on the boards."},
    // HARD (d:3) — questions 71-100
    {id:"u15q71",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Adjusting forecheck mid-game",d:3,sit:"Your 1-2-2 forecheck has been effective all game. In the third period, the other team starts using their D to carry the puck instead of passing. What adjustment do you make?",opts:["Have F1 play higher to cut off the D carry option while F2 drops to take away the first pass lane","Keep the same 1-2-2 since it's been working all game and one adjustment by the other team really","Switch to a full trap and stop forechecking entirely since they've shown they can beat your for sure","Send all three forwards deep on every play to overwhelm their D before they can carry it out now"],ok:0,why:"When D start carrying, F1 needs to play higher to take away the carry option. In-game adjustments based on opponent behavior separate good teams from great ones.",tip:"They're adjusting? You adjust back. F1 higher to cut the D carry."},
    {id:"u15q72",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Transition from defense to offense",d:3,sit:"Your D wins the puck in a board battle deep in your zone. You're the center. The opposing forwards are all deep. You have a clear lane through the neutral zone but the puck carrier hasn't looked up yet. What do you do?",opts:["Sprint to the open ice and call loudly for the puck to let your D know the lane is there for a quick transition play","Stay at the hashmarks in your normal breakout position and wait for the standard pattern to develop before moving right","Skate toward the D to give them a short safe option since the long pass through the neutral zone is too risky right","Change lines since the D will probably just rim it around the boards anyway and fresh legs are more important right"],ok:0,why:"Recognizing the transition opportunity and communicating it is elite hockey IQ. Your D can't see you — calling for the puck creates the play.",tip:"Lane open but D hasn't seen it? Call loud. Create the transition play."},
    {id:"u15q73",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP adjustment mid-game",d:3,sit:"Your PP has been struggling. The PK keeps blocking your one-timer from the circle. They've figured out your setup. What do you change?",opts:["Add a net-front screen to block the PK's sightline on the shooter and create a new passing option to the slot or back door","Keep running the same play since the execution just needs to be better and changing the setup mid-game will confuse your","Pull the goalie for a 6-on-4 advantage since that extra skater will solve the problem of the PK blocking your after that","Have the shooter move to the other circle since switching sides will confuse the PK and give you a fresh look on the now"],ok:0,why:"When the PK adjusts to your one-timer, adding a screen creates a new layer of deception. The screen blocks their read and the screener becomes a passing option.",tip:"PK adjusted to your one-timer? Add a screen. Create a new layer of deception."},
    {id:"u15q74",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defending a skilled 1-on-1 player",d:3,sit:"Their best player is coming at you 1-on-1. They're known for their speed and deking ability. They've beaten you before with a wide fake and cut back inside. How do you approach?",opts:["Take away the inside lane and force them to the outside — accept the lower-percentage shot from the angle over a deke from slot","Aggressively close your gap and try to force a turnover at the blue line before they can get up to speed and start their moves","Back up to the goal line and give them space since they're too skilled to challenge one-on-one at any gap in the neutral right","Stand completely still at the top of the circles and wait for them to make the first move before reacting to anything they do here"],ok:0,why:"Against a skilled deking player, taking away the inside lane and forcing them wide reduces their options. They have to beat you from a bad angle instead of the slot.",tip:"Skilled deker? Take away inside. Force them wide. Bad angle beats slot deke."},
    {id:"u15q75",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Strategic physicality",d:3,sit:"It's the second period and their top player has been dominant. Every time they get the puck, they create chances. Within the rules, how can physicality change this?",opts:["Finish every legal check on them to make them aware of the physical price — it changes their decision speed and puck-holding time","Avoid any physical play with them since hitting a skilled player usually results in a penalty for your team and gives them a instead","Only play physical in the third period when it matters most since being physical early wastes your energy when the game is still","Target their teammates instead since hitting their linemates will send a message without risking a penalty against their best up"],ok:0,why:"Legal, consistent physical pressure on a skilled player changes their decision-making. They hold the puck less, make quicker choices, and think about the hit instead of the play.",tip:"Their star is dominant? Legal, consistent pressure. Change their decision speed."},
    {id:"u15q76",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading PP vs PK matchup",d:3,sit:"You're on the PP and you notice the PK's best penalty killer keeps matching up against your half-wall shooter. They're shutting down that option. What's the counter?",opts:["Use the half-wall player as a decoy — have them draw the PK killer and open up the other side for a different shooting option","Replace the half-wall shooter with a bigger player who can physically overpower the PK killer and force the shot through them up","Call a timeout and draw up an entirely new power play formation since the PK has completely solved your current setup design","Have the half-wall shooter go to the net front instead so they can use their shooting ability to deflect pucks from the here"],ok:0,why:"Using a covered player as a decoy is advanced PP strategy. The PK killer commits to the half-wall — now the other side opens up for an even better look.",tip:"PK targeting your shooter? Use them as a decoy. Open up the other side."},
    {id:"u15q77",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading neutral zone coverage",d:3,sit:"You're entering the neutral zone with speed. The opposing team has set up a 1-2-2 trap with the two forwards at the red line clogging the middle. How do you attack this?",opts:["Use the wide lanes to get around the trap — chip pucks to the outside or use east-west passes to move the two cloggers out of the middle","Skate directly up the middle at full speed since the best way to beat a trap is with speed right through the heart of their on the play","Dump the puck in every single time you see the trap because there is no way to carry through a 1-2-2 neutral zone trap with on the play","Stop at your own blue line and hold the puck to force them to come out of the trap since they will eventually have to attack you here right"],ok:0,why:"A 1-2-2 trap clogging the middle is beaten by using the wide lanes. East-west passes and outside speed move the trap and create seams.",tip:"1-2-2 clogging the middle? Use the wide lanes. East-west to move the trap."},
    {id:"u15q78",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"3-on-3 overtime defending",d:3,sit:"You're playing 3-on-3 overtime. The other team has the puck and is cycling in your zone. There's significantly more open ice. How do you defend?",opts:["Stay compact as a unit, protect the slot and high danger areas, and force them to shoot from the outside perimeter where it's safe","Spread out to cover as much ice as possible since the extra open space means you need to cover all the lanes to the net at really","Play ultra-aggressive and try to take the puck away immediately since 3-on-3 overtime rewards aggression more than defensive patience","Back off to the goal line and let them cycle since eventually they'll make a mistake and you can transition to offense quickly up"],ok:0,why:"In 3-on-3, staying compact protects the high-danger areas. Spreading out creates gaps. Force them to shoot from low-percentage areas.",tip:"3-on-3: stay compact. Protect the slot. Force outside shots."},
    {id:"u15q79",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Protecting the crease",d:3,sit:"An opposing forward establishes position in front of your net. They're screening your goalie and deflecting pucks. You've tried to box them out but they keep coming back. What's your next approach?",opts:["Tie up their stick on every shot attempt and use your body to redirect their momentum away from the net front between whistles only","Hit them as hard as you can from behind every time they set up in front since that's the only way to permanently remove them right","Give up on the net front and go cover someone else since if they want that position that badly there is nothing you can do to stop","Ask the referee to call a penalty on the forward for goaltender interference since standing in front of the net is not allowed in here"],ok:0,why:"Net-front defense requires continuous effort. Tying up their stick prevents deflections, and using body position between whistles resets the battle. It's a war of attrition.",tip:"They keep coming back to the net front? Keep battling. Tie up stick on shots. Reset between whistles."},
    {id:"u15q80",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Late-game systems",d:3,sit:"Your team is up by one with three minutes left. The coach calls for a 1-3-1 neutral zone trap. You're F1. How aggressive should you be on the forecheck?",opts:["Controlled — angle and steer but don't overcommit, maintain the trap structure and let them make mistakes as they try to break through","Very aggressive — pressure hard to force turnovers since a second goal would end the game and the best defense right now is a really","Not aggressive at all — just stand at center ice and wait for them to come to you since the trap will work on its own without any up","Ignore the trap call and play your normal game since changing your system with only three minutes left will confuse the team and now"],ok:0,why:"Late-game trapping F1 is about controlled pressure. Angle and steer — don't overcommit. The trap works when F1 funnels the puck into the structure.",tip:"Late-game trap: F1 controls the funnel. Angle, steer, don't overcommit."},
    {id:"u15q81",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Activating both D",d:3,sit:"Your team is in the offensive zone with full possession. Both wingers are below the dots cycling. Both D are at the blue line. The opposing team has dropped into a passive box. Should one D jump into the play?",opts:["Yes — one D steps down to create a numerical advantage low while the other holds the line as safety in case of a turnover or breakout","No — both D should always stay at the blue line since leaving the line is too risky regardless of how much possession your team has here","Yes — both D should jump into the play since you have full possession and there's no risk of a breakout when your team controls here","No — the D should pass the puck between each other at the blue line until a shooting lane opens up and then take a long-range really"],ok:0,why:"With full possession against a passive box, one D jumping down creates an overload. The key is one stays back as safety. Both going creates transition risk.",tip:"Passive box? One D steps down for the overload. Other holds the line."},
    {id:"u15q82",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK faceoff strategy",d:3,sit:"You're taking a defensive zone faceoff on the PK. Your team's faceoff play is to win it back to the D and clear it. You lose the draw cleanly to the PP center. What's the immediate priority?",opts:["Sprint to cover the shooting lane and get in front of any shot — the PP will look to shoot immediately after a won O-zone faceoff draw","Stand still and wait for the PP to set up before you react since you can't do anything about losing the faceoff at this point in the","Chase the center who won the draw and try to take the puck back from them before they can pass it to one of their power play instead","Skate to the bench for a change since you lost the faceoff and a fresh penalty killer will be more effective than you right now here"],ok:0,why:"After losing a PK faceoff, the PP often looks for an immediate shot. Getting into the shooting lane quickly prevents the most dangerous opportunity.",tip:"Lost the PK faceoff? Sprint to the lane. Block the immediate shot."},
    {id:"u15q83",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Recovering when beaten",d:3,sit:"An attacker has beaten you wide on a 1-on-1. They're now inside your zone with a step on you. Your goalie is set. What do you do to recover?",opts:["Angle your recovery to take away the pass option while your goalie plays the shot — don't chase directly behind the puck carrier now","Sprint directly behind the puck carrier and try to catch them from behind to poke check or knock the puck off their stick blade here up","Give up on the play since they've already beaten you and you'll only make things worse by being out of position chasing from behind","Dive at their feet to try to trip them or knock the puck away since that's the only option left once you've been beaten on the rush"],ok:0,why:"Recovery angle is critical. Don't chase directly behind — angle to take away the pass while your goalie plays the shot. Your goalie can handle the shooter; the pass is the danger.",tip:"Beaten wide? Angle your recovery to the pass lane. Goalie has the shot."},
    {id:"u15q84",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Penalty management",d:3,sit:"You've been playing physical all game and you've already been warned twice by the referee. It's the third period of a tied game. How do you adjust your physical play?",opts:["Stay physical but clean up your technique — use body position and legal contact that the referee can't call as a penalty against you","Keep playing exactly the same way since backing down from physical play will show the other team that the referee's warnings right","Stop all physical play completely for the rest of the game to make sure you don't take a single penalty at any point in the really","Play even more physical to intimidate the referee into not making the call since they usually let more go in the third period of a"],ok:0,why:"Adjusting technique while maintaining physicality is smart. You can be just as effective with cleaner methods. A penalty in a tied third period can cost the game.",tip:"Multiple warnings? Clean up technique. Same intensity, cleaner methods."},
    {id:"u15q85",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defensive zone faceoff play with less than a minute",d:3,sit:"There's 45 seconds left in a tied game. Defensive zone faceoff. Your team needs to get the puck out cleanly. What's the priority for every player on the draw?",opts:["Win the draw and get the puck deep into the opposing zone — everyone executes their assignment to clear the puck immediately after draw","Win the draw and set up in the offensive zone with controlled possession to try to score a late goal and avoid overtime entirely right","Tie up the opposing center and just prevent them from winning the draw cleanly even if that means the puck stays in the defensive zone now","It doesn't matter what happens on the faceoff since 45 seconds is too little time for either team to do anything meaningful in this up"],ok:0,why:"With 45 seconds in a tied game, the priority is a clean zone exit. Win the draw, execute assignments, get the puck deep. Giving up a goal with under a minute is devastating.",tip:"45 seconds, tied game, D-zone faceoff: win it and get it out. Clean execution."},
    {id:"u15q86",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Odd-man rush creation",d:3,sit:"You're a forward and your D just intercepted a pass in the neutral zone. Their forwards are caught deep. You and one teammate are ahead of the play. The D has options. What do you want?",opts:["Sprint wide and call for the puck — create a 2-on-1 with your teammate by getting into your lane before the opposing D can recover position","Stay in the middle of the ice and wait for the D to carry it themselves since they might be able to create a chance without needing to now","Go back and help the D handle the puck in the neutral zone since they might need support even though the opposing forwards are all caught deep","Skate to the bench for a change since the D can handle the transition themselves and you need fresh legs for the next defensive zone right"],ok:0,why:"When their forwards are caught, sprinting wide creates the odd-man rush. Speed and lane discipline turn an interception into a scoring chance.",tip:"Their forwards caught? Sprint. Get wide. Create the odd-man rush."},
    {id:"u15q87",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP recovery after failed entry",d:3,sit:"Your PP tried to enter the zone but the PK forced a turnover at the blue line. The PK is now breaking the puck out. What's the immediate PP response?",opts:["Get back and regroup — the PP needs to recover defensively first and then re-enter with possession to avoid giving up a shorthanded goal","Chase the puck carrier individually since the PP has more players and can afford to be aggressive even in transition defense after the here","Let them have the puck since the PP should never backcheck and it's better to wait for them to dump it in and re-establish offensive up","Immediately pull the goalie for the extra attacker to compensate for the lost time on the power play since you need to score as fast as"],ok:0,why:"A PP turnover at the blue line is a shorthanded chance. The PP must recover defensively first — getting back and regrouping prevents the SH goal.",tip:"PP turnover at the blue line? Get back. Regroup. Don't give up a SH goal."},
    {id:"u15q88",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"High slot coverage",d:3,sit:"You're a forward in the defensive zone. The puck is in the corner and your D has it handled. An opposing forward is lurking at the top of the slot between the two circles. Nobody is covering them. What do you do?",opts:["Move to cover the high slot player immediately since a pass to the high slot is one of the most dangerous plays from the corner area","Stay where you are since the D has the puck and the immediate danger is in the corner battle not the high slot player standing here","Go to the corner to help the D even though they have it handled since an extra body in the corner is always better for winning here","Skate to the far side of the zone to cover the weak-side boards in case the puck gets rimmed around to the other side of the ice on now"],ok:0,why:"An uncovered player in the high slot is a prime scoring threat from the corner. A pass up to the slot is a one-timer in the most dangerous area on the ice.",tip:"Player lurking in the high slot uncovered? Get there. That's the danger."},
    {id:"u15q89",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Contact in transition",d:3,sit:"You're backchecking and an opposing forward is receiving a pass in the neutral zone at full speed. You're at an angle where you can deliver a legal body check. The puck is arriving in one second. What do you do?",opts:["Time the hit to arrive just as the puck does — a clean check at the moment of reception separates them from the puck and kills the rush dead","Hold off on the hit and try to poke check the puck away since body contact in the neutral zone during transition is usually penalized by up","Skate past them and get ahead to set up your defensive positioning since the hit might not connect and then you'd be completely out of the play","Wait until they have full possession and have made their first move before deciding whether to hit or play the puck on the defensive really"],ok:0,why:"Timing a hit to arrive with the puck is legal and devastating. It kills the rush and sends a message. The key is timing — too early is interference, too late is ineffective.",tip:"Hit timed with the puck arrival: legal, devastating, rush-killing. Timing is everything."},
    {id:"u15q90",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading the opponent's PP",d:3,sit:"You're killing a penalty. The opponent's PP runs a 1-3-1 with a one-timer option from the left circle. You've seen this three times. How do you adjust your PK?",opts:["Overplay the one-timer side slightly and have the high PK player pressure the passer when the puck goes to the set-up spot on the left side","Keep the box exactly the same since adjusting to one option will open up other options and the standard PK box is designed to handle right","Switch to a diamond PK formation since the 1-3-1 PP always beats the box and the diamond is designed specifically to counter the 1-3-1 offense","Have all four PK players collapse to the one-timer side to completely take it away even if that leaves the entire other side of the ice up"],ok:0,why:"Recognizing the PP's go-to play and overplaying it is elite PK hockey IQ. You don't abandon the box — you adjust within it to take away their best option.",tip:"Seen their PP play three times? Overplay it. Adjust within your structure."},
    {id:"u15q91",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Creating time with the puck",d:3,sit:"You're a D with the puck in your zone. The forecheck is closing hard from both sides. Your outlets are covered. You have a split second. What creative option do you have?",opts:["Use the back of the net as a shield to buy time — skate behind it and wait for the forecheck to commit before choosing your outlet play","Try to split both forecheckers by skating between them since skilled D should be able to handle the puck under pressure in their own right","Shoot the puck directly at the forechecker and hope it bounces off them and goes to one of your teammates who can break out of the now","Hold the puck still and wait for a whistle since the referees will eventually blow the play dead when they see the pressure closing in"],ok:0,why:"The back of the net is a tool. Using it as a shield buys time for outlets to open and forces the forecheck to commit to a side.",tip:"Outlets covered? Use the net. Shield the puck. Wait for the forecheck to commit."},
    {id:"u15q92",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Timeout decision input",d:3,sit:"Your team is in a tight game and the coach calls a timeout. You've been on the ice and noticed the other team changes their breakout pattern in the third period. How do you contribute to the timeout?",opts:["Share what you've observed calmly and specifically — what changed and which side they're favoring so the coaching staff and team can adjust","Stay quiet since timeouts are for coaches to talk and players should only listen and not contribute observations during team stoppages of","Talk over the coach to make sure everyone hears your observation since the information you have is more important than what the coach now","Wait until after the timeout is over and then tell the coach privately so you don't embarrass them by correcting their strategy in really"],ok:0,why:"Sharing on-ice observations during a timeout is valuable — you see things the bench can't. Do it calmly and specifically so the information is actionable.",tip:"Timeout: share what you see. Calmly, specifically. Players see things coaches can't."},
    {id:"u15q93",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Playing against a dump-and-chase team",d:3,sit:"The opposing team dumps the puck in on every entry. They're fast and aggressive on the forecheck after the dump. How do you adjust your retrievals as a D?",opts:["Communicate with your partner before each dump — one retrieves, one covers the net front. Move the puck quickly before their forecheckers arrive","Both D go after every dump-in together since having two defensemen on the puck means you'll always win the race to the puck in the corner area","Ignore the dump-in and let your goalie play the puck every single time since they're better at handling pucks behind the net than the D are at","Leave the puck for the forwards to retrieve since that's their job and the D should only play the puck when it's passed directly to them on up"],ok:0,why:"Against a dump-and-chase team, D communication on retrievals is critical. One goes, one covers. Quick puck movement before their speed arrives prevents the forecheck from working.",tip:"Dump-and-chase team? One D retrieves, one covers. Move the puck fast."},
    {id:"u15q94",cat:"Physical Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Physical play in overtime",d:3,sit:"It's 3-on-3 overtime. Both teams are being cautious. You have the puck in the neutral zone. A defender is angling you toward the boards. There's open ice if you can get past them. What do you do?",opts:["Use your body to power through the angling attempt — in 3-on-3, getting past one defender opens up massive scoring chances with open ice","Dump the puck in and change since there's too much risk in trying to beat a defender one-on-one in overtime when the game is on the up","Pass the puck back and regroup since a turnover in the neutral zone in 3-on-3 overtime is the most dangerous play that can happen here","Stop skating and hold the puck at center ice since eventually the other team will have to come to you and that gives your team the now"],ok:0,why:"In 3-on-3, getting past one defender with physicality opens up the ice dramatically. The risk-reward of powering through is worth it when there's space behind them.",tip:"3-on-3, one defender in the way? Power through. The space behind them is worth it."},
    {id:"u15q95",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Switching systems mid-period",d:3,sit:"Your team has been playing a high-pressure forecheck. In the middle of the second period, your team is getting tired and the other team is breaking through your forecheck regularly. What do you suggest?",opts:["Drop back to a more conservative 1-3-1 or trap to conserve energy while still maintaining structure in the neutral zone against their breakouts","Keep running the same high-pressure forecheck since changing systems mid-period will confuse the team and create more problems than it solves","Call a timeout to rest since the real problem is fatigue and not the system — the forecheck will work again once the team has fresh legs here","Switch to a completely new system that you've never practiced since the element of surprise will catch the other team off guard and create up"],ok:0,why:"Recognizing when fatigue is compromising your system is hockey IQ. Dropping to a more conservative forecheck conserves energy while maintaining structure.",tip:"Team tired and forecheck breaking down? Drop back. Conserve energy. Maintain structure."},
    {id:"u15q96",cat:"Transition",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading the goalie's puck play",d:3,sit:"Your goalie is aggressive playing the puck. On dump-ins, they often leave the net to stop the puck behind the net. You're a D. How does this change your retrieval approach?",opts:["Adjust your routes to support the goalie — be ready for their pass instead of racing them to the puck behind the net on every dump-in play","Ignore the goalie's puck play and race to the puck yourself every time since it's your job as a D to retrieve dump-ins regardless of now","Tell the goalie to stop playing the puck since it creates confusion and the D should be the only players handling pucks behind the right","Stand at the blue line and let the goalie handle everything behind the net since they clearly want to play the puck and you should right"],ok:0,why:"A puck-playing goalie changes D routes. Instead of racing to the puck, support their pass. The partnership between goalie and D on dump-ins creates faster breakouts.",tip:"Puck-playing goalie? Adjust. Support their pass. Don't race them to the puck."},
    {id:"u15q97",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK in the last minute of a penalty",d:3,sit:"There are 15 seconds left in your penalty kill. The PP is set up and looking dangerous. They're cycling the puck looking for the perfect play. What's the PK mindset?",opts:["Stay disciplined in the box for 15 more seconds — don't chase, don't gamble, deny the high-danger shot and let the clock run out on the penalty","Get aggressive and try to steal the puck since with only 15 seconds left you can take a risk to end the penalty kill early with a clear or now","Collapse everyone to the net and let them shoot from anywhere outside the slot since most shots from the perimeter miss the net entirely at up","Pull one PK player off and play more passively since with only 15 seconds left the PP probably won't score and you can start transitioning to here"],ok:0,why:"15 seconds of discipline ends the PK. Gambling or chasing with that little time left is unnecessary. Stay in structure, deny the dangerous play, and run the clock.",tip:"15 seconds left on the PK? Stay disciplined. Don't chase. Run the clock."},
    {id:"u15q98",cat:"Gap Control",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defending with a broken stick",d:3,sit:"Your stick breaks during a defensive play. The other team has the puck and is entering your zone. You can't get to the bench. What do you do?",opts:["Stay in the play without a stick — use your body and positioning to take away space and force the puck carrier into a teammate who has a stick","Immediately leave the ice even though the other team is entering your zone since playing without a stick is completely useless in every here","Grab a teammate's stick since they can go get a new one from the bench easier than you can while the other team is already attacking in your","Lay down on the ice to block passing and shooting lanes since without a stick that's the only way you can contribute to the defensive really"],ok:0,why:"A broken stick doesn't take you out of the play. Body positioning and taking away space still has value. Force the carrier into a teammate who can make the play.",tip:"Stick breaks? Stay in the play. Use your body. Take away space."},
    {id:"u15q99",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Leading after a loss",d:3,sit:"Your team just lost a tough game. The room is quiet. Some players are visibly upset. As a leader, what do you do?",opts:["Acknowledge the tough loss, point out something specific the team did well, and remind them of the next opportunity to compete and improve as a group","Give a long speech about everything that went wrong so the team knows exactly what to fix before the next game and doesn't repeat the same right now","Stay silent and let the coach handle everything since it's not your job to say anything after a loss — that's the coaching staff's responsibility to","Blame specific players for the loss so the team knows who was responsible and can hold them accountable for the mistakes that cost the game that instead"],ok:0,why:"Post-loss leadership is about honesty and perspective. Acknowledging the loss, finding a positive, and looking forward gives the team something to build on.",tip:"Tough loss? Acknowledge it. Find one positive. Point to the next one. That's leadership."},
    {id:"u15q100",cat:"Systems Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Adapting to a new system",d:3,sit:"Your team just got a new coach mid-season who runs a completely different system than you're used to. You're struggling to execute it. What's the right approach?",opts:["Commit fully to learning the new system even if it feels uncomfortable — watch video, ask questions, and practice the details every single rep","Keep playing the old system since it worked and the new coach should adapt to what the team already knows how to do instead of changing right","Only run the new system when the coach is watching and go back to the old one during games since the old system is what the team is right now","Refuse to buy into the new system and tell your teammates it won't work since the old coach's system was better and the new one doesn't fit right"],ok:0,why:"Buying into a new system is a character test. Even when it's uncomfortable, committing fully — video, questions, practice — is how good players adapt.",tip:"New system? Commit fully. Watch video. Ask questions. Discomfort is growth."},
    // U15 GOALIE (u15g1-u15g20)
    {id:"u15g1",cat:"Goalie",concept:"RVH decision making",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is below the goal line on your right side. The attacker is tight to the post. What's the correct post integration?",opts:["RVH — pad stacked against the post, blocker and glove covering high to seal the entire post","Stand tall in butterfly at the post since that covers more of the net opening from that up","Leave the post and challenge out aggressively since you want to cut down the shooting angle up","VH with your lead leg up since that gives you more mobility to push across if they go here"],ok:0,why:"Below the goal line, RVH is the correct integration. It seals the bottom against the post while keeping blocker and glove covering high.",tip:"Below the goal line? RVH. Seal the bottom, cover the top."},
    {id:"u15g2",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Tracking through screens",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"A point shot is coming and there's a screen in front of you. You can't see the puck clearly. What do you do?",opts:["Lower your stance slightly to find a sightline below the screen and track the puck through","Stand tall and hope the shot hits the screen since most screened shots get deflected wide","Move laterally out of the net to get around the screen even if that means leaving part of net","Close your eyes and just react to the sound of the shot hitting a stick or the ice really"],ok:0,why:"Lowering your stance to find a sightline below the screen keeps you tracking the puck. You can't save what you can't see — find a gap.",tip:"Screen in front? Lower your stance. Find a gap. Track the puck."},
    {id:"u15g3",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Puck handling communication",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is dumped in behind your net. You leave to play it. A forechecker is closing. Your D is on the boards. What do you communicate?",opts:["Call the play — 'Leave it!' if you have time, or 'Rim it!' to your D if pressure is too close now","Stay silent and make the play yourself since talking behind the net can distract your defensemen now","Yell 'Help!' to get all your teammates to come back behind the net and assist with the puck here","Don't communicate anything specific and let your D figure out on their own what the right really"],ok:0,why:"Goalie communication behind the net directs traffic. 'Leave it' tells the D you've got it. 'Rim' tells them you need them to take it. Clear calls prevent confusion.",tip:"Behind the net: direct traffic. 'Leave it' or 'Rim.' Be specific."},
    {id:"u15g4",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Butterfly slide timing",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is passed from the half-wall to the slot. The new shooter is about to release. When do you use the butterfly slide?",opts:["When the shot is imminent — the butterfly slide gets you across the crease quickly with coverage low","Before the pass is made so you're already in position at the far side before the puck even arrives","Only after the shot has been released and you can see which direction the puck is traveling toward","Never — you should always use a T-push on your feet to get across the crease on any lateral really"],ok:0,why:"The butterfly slide is for imminent shots during lateral movement. It gets you across with coverage. T-pushes are for non-shooting passes.",tip:"Shot imminent on a lateral play? Butterfly slide. Get across with coverage."},
    {id:"u15g5",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Rebound control direction",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"You're making a pad save on a shot from the right wing. Where should you angle your rebound?",opts:["To the left corner — away from the shooter and out of the dangerous slot and scoring area here","Back toward the shooter on the right side since they already shot and probably can not shoot","Directly in front of you into the slot where your defensemen are positioned to clear the now","Straight up into the air so the puck stays near you and you can try to catch it on the right"],ok:0,why:"Rebounds go to the far corner — away from the shooter and out of the slot. A rebound in the slot is the most dangerous second chance in hockey.",tip:"Rebound direction: far corner. Away from the shooter. Out of the slot."},
    {id:"u15g6",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Challenge depth on breakaways",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"A breakaway is coming. The shooter is a known deker who likes to go to the backhand. Where do you set your depth?",opts:["Top of the crease — cut the angle but stay controlled, give yourself room to react to the deke backward","Come out to the hash marks aggressively to cut all the angle and force them to make their move really","Stay deep in the net at the goal line since you need maximum reaction time against a skilled deker up","Come out past the top of the circles to cut the angle off completely before they even reach your zone"],ok:0,why:"Top of the crease on a breakaway balances angle cutting with reaction space. Too deep gives too much net. Too far out makes you vulnerable to dekes.",tip:"Breakaway: top of the crease. Cut the angle. Leave room to react."},
    {id:"u15g7",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Post-to-post movement",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck goes from the right corner to behind the net and is continuing to the left side. You were set on the right post. The player is moving fast. How do you move across?",opts:["Push off your right post and drive hard across in your stance to arrive at the left post before them","Spin around backward and skate across the crease while following the puck carrier with your head up","Step out of the crease and skate around the front of the crease in a semi-circle to reach the right","Stay on the right post and wait to see if the puck carrier comes back to your side before committing up"],ok:0,why:"Post-to-post on a behind-the-net play means pushing off hard and driving across. Arriving at the far post before the puck carrier eliminates the wraparound and far-side play.",tip:"Behind-the-net play? Push hard. Beat them to the far post."},
    {id:"u15g8",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Handling deflections",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"A point shot is coming and you see a forward in front with their stick on the ice, ready to tip. What do you prepare for?",opts:["Expect the deflection — stay low in your stance with your stick on the ice and track the puck through the screen and forward's deflection","Ignore the forward and focus only on the original shot from the point since the deflection might not happen and you can't prepare right","Stand up taller to see over the forward since a higher stance gives you a better view of the point shot as it comes through the traffic","Drop into a full butterfly before the shot even arrives to cover the bottom of the net since deflections usually go low and you need to"],ok:0,why:"A forward with their stick on the ice is a deflection setup. Stay low, track through, and expect the direction change. Deflections change angle and elevation.",tip:"Stick on the ice in front? Expect the tip. Stay low. Track through."},
    {id:"u15g9",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Puck handling under pressure",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"You stop the puck behind the net on a dump-in. Two forecheckers are coming hard — one from each side. You have limited time. What's the safest play?",opts:["Rim the puck hard to your D on the weak side before the first forechecker arrives at your position","Try to make a saucer pass over the forecheckers to a forward in the neutral zone for a breakout right","Hold the puck and take the hit since the referee will blow the whistle when the forechecker right","Leave the puck behind the net and go back in the crease since your D can battle for it when right"],ok:0,why:"Under heavy pressure behind the net, rimming to the weak side is the safest play. It moves the puck away from pressure and gives your D a chance.",tip:"Two forecheckers closing? Rim to the weak side. Quick and safe."},
    {id:"u15g10",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Reading the 2-on-1 as a goalie",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"It's a 2-on-1. Your D is taking away the pass. The puck carrier is on the right side driving to the net. What's your positioning?",opts:["Square to the shooter on the right side with good depth — trust your D on the pass and play the shot","Cheat slightly to the far post since if the pass gets through you need to be ready for the instead","Stay in the exact center of the net since you don't know if it's a shot or pass until it right now","Come out aggressively past the crease to cut down every possible angle on the shooter coming at up"],ok:0,why:"When your D takes the pass, you play the shot. Square to the shooter with good depth — trust the D's job. If the pass gets through, that's a breakdown, not your read.",tip:"D takes the pass on 2-on-1? You play the shot. Square. Good depth. Trust."},
    {id:"u15g11",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Recovery after going down",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"You made a butterfly save but the puck squirted to the side. You're on the ice and the puck is loose. An attacker is closing. What's your priority?",opts:["Get to your feet immediately — recover your stance so you're ready for the next shot from any angle","Stay down and try to reach the puck with your stick or pad to cover it before the attacker arrives","Slide on your knees toward the puck since that's faster than getting up and you can cover it right now","Call for help from your D and stay down in butterfly since getting up will take too long at really"],ok:0,why:"Recovery speed is critical. Getting to your feet gives you the best chance to make the next save. Staying down limits your movement and commits you to one angle.",tip:"Puck loose after a save? Get up. Recovery speed wins second-chance saves."},
    {id:"u15g12",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Playing the angle on the cycle",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"The opposing team is cycling the puck below the dots. The puck moves from the corner to behind the net. How do you track it?",opts:["Follow the puck with short controlled pushes, keeping your angle — don't lose your position by over-rotating and getting too deep in the crease","Spin all the way around and skate out of the crease to play the puck yourself since it's behind your net and that's your territory to play up","Stay completely still in the center of your net and wait for a shot since all the passes are happening below the goal line and aren't instead","Drop into butterfly and cover the bottom of the net since the cycle usually generates low shots from below the dots and you want to be really"],ok:0,why:"Following the cycle with controlled pushes keeps your angle without overcommitting. Over-rotating leaves you exposed when the puck reverses or comes out front.",tip:"Cycle below the dots? Follow with controlled pushes. Don't over-rotate."},
    {id:"u15g13",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Glove-side awareness",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"Shooters in your league have started targeting your glove side high consistently. You've given up three glove-side goals in the last two games. How do you adjust?",opts:["Work on your glove positioning in practice — start with the glove slightly higher and more visible to shooters to take away that visual cue for targeting","Switch to catching with your blocker hand since your glove side is clearly a weakness and changing hands will confuse the shooters who have been instead","Don't change anything since three goals is a small sample size and adjusting your technique based on a few goals will create new problems in other areas now","Tell your D to never let anyone shoot from your glove side since it's their job to take away that angle and any goal scored glove side high is a instead"],ok:0,why:"Adjusting glove positioning is the right response. Starting slightly higher takes away the visual cue shooters are using. Address the weakness in practice.",tip:"Getting beaten glove side? Adjust the starting position. Work it in practice."},
    {id:"u15g14",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Backdoor play on the PK",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"Your team is on the PK. The PP is cycling and the puck goes from the half-wall toward the back-door player at the far post. You were set strong side. What do you do?",opts:["Push across aggressively with a butterfly slide — the backdoor tap-in is the highest-danger play and you need to get to that post immediately right now","Stay on the strong side and trust your PK player to get a stick in the lane on the back-door pass since you can't get across fast enough to make here","Drop to butterfly and cover the bottom of the net on the strong side since that's where most PK goals are scored and the backdoor play rarely gets up","Don't move until you see the puck actually get to the far side since committing early to the back door leaves the strong side completely open for now"],ok:0,why:"The backdoor play is the highest-danger PK chance. Push hard across with commitment. Half-speed movement on a backdoor play is a goal.",tip:"PP backdoor? Full commitment across. Push hard. Close that far post."},
    {id:"u15g15",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Game state awareness",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"Your team is winning by two goals in the third period. The other team pulls their goalie for an extra attacker. How does this change your positioning?",opts:["Be slightly more conservative with your depth — stay tighter to the net since 6-on-5 creates unusual passing lanes and deflection opportunities on the play","Play more aggressively since the other team is desperate and will take lower percentage shots from poor angles and you can challenge them more effectively","Don't change anything since your positioning should always be the same regardless of the score or whether the other team has pulled their goalie or not in now","Come way out of the net to the top of the circles to cut every angle since with 6 attackers the net will be screened and you need to be as far out as here"],ok:0,why:"6-on-5 creates unusual passing lanes. Being slightly more conservative protects against the cross-ice plays and deflections that come with the extra attacker.",tip:"6-on-5 against? Slightly more conservative. Protect against unusual lanes."},
    {id:"u15g16",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Controlled aggression",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"Your team is losing 1-0 with five minutes left. You've been solid all game. An attacker is coming on a breakaway. Do you change your approach?",opts:["Stay patient and play your game — the same technique that's kept you in the game all night will give you the best chance to stop this breakaway too","Be way more aggressive than normal since you need to stop this at all costs and coming out past the circles is the only way to guarantee a really","Play more conservatively and back up deeper into the net since you absolutely cannot give up another goal and depth gives you more reaction right","Skate out to the blue line and try to poke check the puck away since the best save on a breakaway is to stop it before the shooter even gets a up"],ok:0,why:"Game state doesn't change breakaway technique. The same patience and fundamentals that kept you in the game give you the best chance on any single save.",tip:"Losing and facing a breakaway? Same technique. Trust your game."},
    {id:"u15g17",cat:"Goalie",concept:"D-to-D pass initiation",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"You stop a dump-in behind your net. The forecheck is closing from the left side. Your left D is covered. Your right D is wide open. Can you start the breakout?",opts:["Yes — set the puck on your strong side for a quick pass to the open right D to start a clean breakout before the forechecker can close you down","No — leave the puck for the left D to battle for even though they're covered since the goalie should never make passes to start the after that","Yes — but skate the puck yourself all the way up to the neutral zone since you're a good puck handler and can contribute more by carrying than","No — freeze the puck every time and take a faceoff since making passes under forecheck pressure is too risky for a goalie and turnovers behind the"],ok:0,why:"A goalie who can start breakouts under pressure is a huge advantage. Setting the puck for the open D bypasses the forecheck entirely.",tip:"Open D on the weak side? Start the breakout. Quick pass. Bypass the forecheck."},
    {id:"u15g18",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Mental reset between periods",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"You gave up two goals in the second period — both on plays you'd normally save. The team is still in the game. What's your intermission routine?",opts:["Reset mentally — review what went wrong briefly, then visualize making saves in the third. Focus on the next period, not the mistakes that happened","Dwell on the two goals for the entire intermission so you can understand exactly what you did wrong on each play and make sure it never happens up","Tell the team it was your fault and apologize repeatedly since your teammates need to know that you know the goals were soft and that you feel bad now","Don't think about hockey at all during the intermission — completely clear your mind and think about other things so you come out fresh with a now"],ok:0,why:"Brief review, then visualization of success. Dwelling causes doubt. Ignoring prevents learning. The balance is quick acknowledgment, then forward focus.",tip:"Bad period? Brief review. Visualize saves. Forward focus. Next period is new."},
    {id:"u15g19",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Shot through traffic reads",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"There are four bodies in front of you — two from each team. A shot is coming from the point and you can barely see the release. How do you give yourself the best chance?",opts:["Get as compact as possible in your stance, stick on the ice, and react to whatever comes through the traffic — trust your reflexes and positioning to save it","Stand up as tall as you can to see over the traffic since height is the best way to track shots through screens and you need every inch of visibility you can up","Move to one side of the net to get a clear sightline around the traffic even if that means leaving part of the net exposed since you need to see the shot up","Drop to butterfly before the shot even arrives since most shots through traffic end up low and you want to cover the bottom of the net before the shot right"],ok:0,why:"Compact stance through traffic maximizes coverage. You may not see the full release — being compact and trusting reflexes gives you the best chance on unexpected angles.",tip:"Traffic in front? Get compact. Stick down. Trust your reflexes."},
    {id:"u15g20",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Communicating coverages to defense",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"You see the opposing PP cycling and your PK is starting to rotate out of position. The weak-side player is drifting toward the back door uncovered. What do you do?",opts:["Yell loudly and specifically — 'Back door!' or 'Weak side!' to redirect your PK player to the uncovered threat before the puck gets there for the tap-in goal","Stay quiet and focus only on tracking the puck since yelling during the play will distract your PK teammates and cause more confusion than it solves instead","Point with your stick at the open player since visual cues are better than yelling and your PK players are trained to look at you for direction during right","Wait until after the play to tell the PK what they missed since correcting them during the play will make them second-guess themselves and play worse overall up"],ok:0,why:"A loud, specific call from the goalie can prevent a goal. You have the best view of developing threats — use it. 'Back door!' redirects a PK player before it's too late.",tip:"See the coverage breakdown? Call it. Loud. Specific. Save a goal with your voice."},
  ],
  "U18 / Midget":[
    // EASY (d:1) — questions 1-30
    {id:"u18q1",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Score effects on play",d:1,sit:"Your team is up by two goals midway through the second period. How should your approach to the game change compared to a tied game?",opts:["Play smart and protect the puck — don't take unnecessary risks that could give them momentum back","Play the exact same way regardless of the score since changing your approach shows fear to right","Get more aggressive since you have the cushion to take bigger risks and score even more goals now up","Coast for the rest of the game and save energy since the two-goal lead is basically safe already"],ok:0,why:"Leading by two means playing smart — protecting the puck, avoiding unnecessary risks, and not giving the opponent momentum. It's not passive, it's controlled.",tip:"Up by two? Play smart. Protect the puck. Don't give them life."},
    {id:"u18q2",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Pre-scout application",d:1,sit:"Your coach shows video of the opposing team's breakout. Their D always goes behind the net and passes to the winger on the left wall. How do you use this in the game?",opts:["Position your forecheck to take away the left wall pass and force the D into an unfamiliar play","Ignore the scouting since video from a previous game doesn't predict what they'll do right now","Tell your teammates about the tendency but don't adjust your forecheck system based on instead","Watch for it in the game but don't change anything until you see them actually do it multiple here"],ok:0,why:"Pre-scout information is most valuable when it directly changes your positioning. Taking away their go-to play forces them into uncomfortable decisions.",tip:"Scouting shows a tendency? Position to take it away. Force them into Plan B."},
    {id:"u18q3",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP zone time",d:1,sit:"Your team is on the power play and has been cycling in the zone for 30 seconds without a shot. The PK is set and patient. What do you do?",opts:["Change the point of attack — move the puck to the other side quickly to shift the PK and find a new seam for a shot or pass to the slot","Keep cycling on the same side since eventually the PK will break down if you maintain possession long enough without trying after that","Pull the puck out of the zone and re-enter to reset since the PK has figured out your formation and you need a completely new look to here","Shoot from a low-percentage spot just to get a shot on net since shot volume is more important than shot quality on the power play now"],ok:0,why:"Changing the point of attack shifts the PK. A patient PK on one side can be exploited by quick east-west movement to the other side where the seam opens.",tip:"PK set on one side? Change the point of attack. East-west creates seams."},
    {id:"u18q4",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"NZ structure",d:1,sit:"The opposing team is trying to carry the puck through the neutral zone. Your team is in a 1-2-2. You're one of the two forwards at the red line. What's your job?",opts:["Clog the middle of the ice and force the puck carrier to the outside where they have less options","Chase the puck carrier aggressively regardless of where they are since speed solves every really","Back up to your own blue line and let them enter the zone since the neutral zone doesn't instead","Move to the same side as the other forward at the red line so you can double-team the puck right now"],ok:0,why:"The two forwards in a 1-2-2 clog the middle. Forcing the carrier outside reduces their options — wide entries are lower percentage than middle-lane attacks.",tip:"1-2-2 middle forward: clog the center. Force them wide."},
    {id:"u18q5",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout options",d:1,sit:"Your D picks up the puck in your zone. The forecheck is sending one player with moderate pressure. You're the center. What's the standard first option?",opts:["Be available in the middle for a short, quick pass that starts the transition up ice cleanly now","Sprint to the offensive zone blue line to stretch the ice for a long pass from the defensive up","Go to the same corner as the D to help with the puck battle since they might need physical for sure","Skate to the bench for a change since the D can handle one forechecker by themselves in the now"],ok:0,why:"The center is the middle option on breakouts. Being available for a short, quick pass is the primary responsibility that starts clean transitions.",tip:"One forechecker? Center in the middle. Short, quick pass. Start the transition."},
    {id:"u18q6",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Pre-game preparation",d:1,sit:"It's game day against the first-place team. Your team has lost to them twice this season. As a leader, how do you approach the pre-game room?",opts:["Bring calm confidence — acknowledge the challenge but focus on specific things your team does well that can win this game tonight against them","Give an emotional speech about how important this game is and how everyone needs to play their best game of the season or the season is right","Don't say anything since the coach handles pre-game talks and players should just focus on their own individual preparation without at this level","Talk about how the other team isn't that good and you should have beaten them both times since overconfidence will motivate your team to play"],ok:0,why:"Pre-game leadership is about calm confidence. Acknowledge the challenge, focus on specific strengths, and set a tone of preparation, not panic.",tip:"Big game? Calm confidence. Specific strengths. Set the tone."},
    {id:"u18q7",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Shift management",d:1,sit:"You've been on the ice for 50 seconds and the puck is in the neutral zone. Your team has possession. You're slightly tired. What do you do?",opts:["Get off for a change — make a quick pass and head to the bench before fatigue leads to mistakes","Stay on since 50 seconds isn't long and you can push through for another 30 seconds without really","Wait until the puck is in the offensive zone before you think about changing since momentum up","Keep playing until you're completely exhausted since every second on the ice helps your really"],ok:0,why:"50 seconds with possession in the neutral zone is the right time to change. Getting off before fatigue sets in prevents the mistakes that cost goals.",tip:"50 seconds and team has possession? Get off. Fresh legs prevent mistakes."},
    {id:"u18q8",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Line matching awareness",d:1,sit:"You're on the ice and you notice the opposing coach has matched their checking line against your top line. What does this tell you about the game situation?",opts:["They respect your line — play your game but be aware that this line is built to shut you down now","It doesn't matter who they put on the ice since your line should play the same way every single here","This means they're scared of your line so you should play more aggressively and take more really","You should ask your coach to change lines to avoid the matchup since playing against checkers up"],ok:0,why:"Line matching awareness helps you adapt. A checking line is built to limit you — play smart, protect the puck, and look for their weaknesses instead of playing into their strength.",tip:"Checking line matched? Play smart. Protect the puck. Find their weakness."},
    {id:"u18q9",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"NZ faceoff strategy",d:1,sit:"There's a neutral zone faceoff. Your team needs possession to maintain pressure. What's the priority on this draw?",opts:["Win the draw back to your D so your team retains possession and can set up a controlled entry","Win the draw forward aggressively to try to create an immediate scoring chance off the faceoff n","Tie up the opposing center and let the wingers battle for the puck since the draw itself now","It doesn't matter who wins the draw since neutral zone faceoffs don't significantly for sure"],ok:0,why:"Winning the draw back to your D starts a controlled possession. It's not flashy, but it gives your team the puck and sets up an organized entry.",tip:"NZ faceoff: win it back to your D. Start with possession."},
    {id:"u18q10",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Winger wall support",d:1,sit:"Your D has the puck in the corner and the forecheck is closing. You're the winger. Where do you need to be?",opts:["Up the wall on your side — be the outlet and give the D a clear, safe passing option up the ice","In the slot area in front of the net since that's always the most dangerous area to receive a","At the far blue line waiting for a stretch pass since that creates the biggest transition now","Behind the D to provide close physical support in case they need help winning the board right"],ok:0,why:"The winger's wall position is the primary breakout outlet. Getting up the wall fast and being ready for the pass is your most important job on the breakout.",tip:"D in the corner? Get up the wall. Be the outlet. Fast."},
    {id:"u18q11",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Holding teammates accountable",d:1,sit:"A teammate has been taking lazy penalties all game — hooking, tripping, holding. It's costing your team. How do you address it?",opts:["Pull them aside privately and have an honest conversation about how the penalties are hurting the team's ability to win the game tonight","Yell at them in front of everyone on the bench to embarrass them into playing more disciplined since public accountability is most now","Don't say anything since it's the coach's job to manage discipline and if you say something it could create a conflict within the team","Take the same kind of penalties yourself to show solidarity with your teammate since they'll appreciate the support and stop right now"],ok:0,why:"Private, honest conversations are the most effective way to hold teammates accountable. Public embarrassment creates resentment, not improvement.",tip:"Teammate taking bad penalties? Private conversation. Honest, not hostile."},
    {id:"u18q12",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Playing with the lead late",d:1,sit:"Your team leads by one with five minutes left. The other team is pressing. What's the team-wide approach?",opts:["Smart clears, no turnovers in the neutral zone, and take what the defense gives you without risk","Turtle completely — dump the puck out every time you touch it and don't try to create any right now","Play the exact same way you've played all game since changing your approach shows you're scared","Get ultra-aggressive and try to score another goal to put the game away with an insurance tally"],ok:0,why:"Protecting a lead late means smart hockey — clean exits, no neutral zone turnovers, and taking what's given without unnecessary risk. It's not turtling, it's managing.",tip:"Lead with five left? Smart clears. No turnovers. Take what they give you."},
    {id:"u18q13",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Exploiting a defensive breakdown",d:1,sit:"You notice the opposing D keeps pinching aggressively on your breakouts. There's open ice behind them every time they pinch. How do you exploit it?",opts:["Use stretch passes behind the pinching D to create breakaway chances for your fastest forwards now","Ignore it since taking advantage of other teams' mistakes is unsportsmanlike and not how you play","Tell the other team's coach about their D's pinching habit so the game stays fair for both really","Dump the puck into the corner every time since you don't want to get caught trying to be too fancy up"],ok:0,why:"Recognizing and exploiting defensive mistakes is not unsportsmanlike — it's hockey IQ. Stretch passes behind an over-aggressive D create the highest-danger chances.",tip:"Their D pinching too much? Stretch behind them. Exploit the mistake."},
    {id:"u18q14",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Countering the trap",d:1,sit:"The opposing team is running a neutral zone trap. Your team keeps turning the puck over trying to carry through it. What's the adjustment?",opts:["Use D-to-D movement and east-west passes to pull the trap apart before trying to carry through it","Keep trying to carry through since eventually speed and skill will beat the trap if you keep up","Dump the puck every single time and never try to carry through any trap formation the right now","Have your best player try to beat the trap alone since they're the only one skilled enough here"],ok:0,why:"Traps are beaten by east-west movement. D-to-D passes and lateral puck movement pull the trap apart and create lanes.",tip:"Facing a trap? East-west. D-to-D. Pull it apart. Don't skate into it."},
    {id:"u18q15",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout under aggressive forecheck",d:1,sit:"The opposing team sends all three forwards hard on the forecheck. Your D has the puck but every standard option is covered. What's the emergency outlet?",opts:["Use the boards or glass to get the puck out of the zone and relieve the pressure before turnover","Try to stickhandle through all three forecheckers since your skill should be good enough at U18 now","Hold the puck and take the hit hoping the referee will blow a whistle for interference or right","Pass the puck back to your goalie and let them freeze it for a faceoff since that's the instead"],ok:0,why:"When the forecheck sends everyone and standard options are covered, the boards/glass relieve pressure. It's not pretty, but a turnover in your own zone costs goals.",tip:"All options covered? Use the glass. Get the puck out. Live to play the next shift."},
    {id:"u18q16",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Momentum awareness",d:1,sit:"The opposing team has just scored two quick goals and the crowd is energized. Your team is rattled. What do you do on your next shift?",opts:["Play a simple, clean shift — get the puck deep, make smart decisions, and stop the momentum now","Try to score immediately to get one back since that's the only way to swing momentum in your favor","Play extra cautiously and don't cross center ice since you need to make sure they don't really","Get in a fight to change the energy in the building and show the other team you won't back now"],ok:0,why:"After the other team builds momentum, a simple, clean shift stops the bleeding. You don't need to score — you need to stop the avalanche.",tip:"Momentum against you? Play simple. Smart shift. Stop the bleeding."},
    {id:"u18q17",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D activation in the O-zone",d:1,sit:"You're a D in the offensive zone. The forwards are cycling below the dots. You see a lane to walk down from the point. When is this the right play?",opts:["When you have clear support behind you and the puck cycle is controlled — one D jumps, one stays","Whenever you feel like it since D should always be looking to jump into the play for more right","Never — D should always stay at the blue line and only shoot from the point in the offensive really","Only in overtime since that's the only time the risk of a D joining the rush is worth the right"],ok:0,why:"D activation requires clear support. One D jumps into the play while the other covers the point. Without that safety net, a turnover creates a breakaway.",tip:"D activation: only when the other D covers. One jumps, one stays. Safety first."},
    {id:"u18q18",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"NZ transition speed",d:1,sit:"Your team gains the puck in the neutral zone off a turnover. The other team's forwards are caught on the wrong side. What's the priority?",opts:["Attack with speed immediately — the other team is out of position and every second of delay lets them recover and get back into defensive positioning","Slow down and regroup so you can enter the zone with all five players in proper formation for the attack since structure is more important than here","Dump it in and change lines since the neutral zone turnover means your shift is getting long and you need fresh legs on the ice for the upcoming now","Hold the puck at center ice and wait to see if they set up a trap before deciding how to enter the zone since you don't want to skate into a neutral now"],ok:0,why:"Speed in transition is the biggest weapon in hockey. When the other team is out of position, attacking immediately creates odd-man advantages before they recover.",tip:"They're caught? Attack now. Speed in transition. Don't let them recover."},
    {id:"u18q19",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reverse breakout",d:1,sit:"Your D is behind the net with the puck. The forecheck has overloaded the strong side — both forecheckers went to the same side. What breakout option does this create?",opts:["Reverse the puck to the weak side where the ice is wide open since the forecheck left it vacant","Pass up the strong side anyway since that's the standard breakout and you should stick to here","Hold the puck behind the net and wait for the forecheck to back off before making any breakout","Shoot the puck off the glass on the strong side to get it past the forecheckers and out of the now"],ok:0,why:"An overloaded forecheck leaves the weak side open. Reversing the puck behind the net exploits their aggressiveness and creates a clean exit.",tip:"Forecheck overloaded one side? Reverse. The weak side is open."},
    {id:"u18q20",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Supporting a struggling teammate",d:1,sit:"Your goalie has let in three goals on ten shots. They're clearly struggling. The team is getting frustrated. As a leader, what do you do?",opts:["Rally the team to play better defense in front of them — talk to the goalie with encouragement now","Call a team meeting on the bench and suggest the coach pulls the goalie for the backup immediately up","Avoid the goalie entirely since anything you say might make them feel worse about their right now","Tell the goalie to figure it out since at this level they should be able to handle adversity here"],ok:0,why:"Supporting a struggling goalie means playing better in front of them and offering encouragement. Goalies respond to confidence from teammates, not criticism.",tip:"Goalie struggling? Play better in front of them. Encourage, don't criticize."},
    {id:"u18q21",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Penalty management",d:1,sit:"You've taken two penalties this game. The coach benched you for a shift as a message. How do you respond when you go back out?",opts:["Play disciplined but don't change your compete level — show the coach you can be physical and smart","Play timidly and avoid all contact since you can't afford another penalty that might bench you up","Play the exact same way that got you the penalties since you were just unlucky with the officials","Get angry at the coach for benching you and take an even more aggressive approach to show them up"],ok:0,why:"The right response to being benched for penalties is disciplined compete. Physical and smart. Not timid, not reckless — the balance in between.",tip:"Benched for penalties? Come back disciplined but competitive. Show you learned."},
    {id:"u18q22",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Shot selection from different zones",d:1,sit:"You have the puck at the top of the left circle. The goalie is set and square to you. There's traffic in front. What's the best shot selection?",opts:["Low shot through traffic — the goalie can't see through the screen and a low shot creates a rebound chance off pads or deflects off traffic in front","High shot over the traffic since going over the screen eliminates the chance of the puck being blocked by bodies and gives you a clear look at the here","Hold the shot and try to walk to the middle of the ice for a better angle since the left circle isn't a high enough percentage area to shoot really","Pass across to the other circle since a cross-ice one-timer is always a better play than shooting from the top of the circle with traffic in really"],ok:0,why:"With traffic and a set goalie, low through traffic creates rebounds and deflections. The screen makes the goalie's job harder. High shots over the screen are often caught.",tip:"Traffic in front, goalie set? Shoot low through it. Screen + rebound = goals."},
    {id:"u18q23",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Forechecking adjustments",d:1,sit:"Your team's forecheck has been effective all game. In the third period, the opposing D starts moving the puck faster — they're not holding it. What adjustment do you make?",opts:["Time your forecheck arrivals better — arrive when the puck arrives, not after they've already passed","Forecheck harder since the only reason they're moving the puck faster is because you're not getting now","Stop forechecking entirely and play a trap since they've figured out your forecheck and you instead","Send an extra player on the forecheck to outnumber their D since having more players deep will here"],ok:0,why:"When D starts moving the puck faster, it means your forecheck is arriving late. Timing your arrivals to match the puck movement keeps the pressure effective.",tip:"They're moving the puck faster? Adjust your timing. Arrive with the puck."},
    {id:"u18q24",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Goalie-to-D communication",d:1,sit:"Your goalie stops a dump-in and sets the puck up behind the net. You're the D. The goalie calls 'Rim right!' What does this mean?",opts:["The puck is set for you to rim it along the right boards to the winger — execute the call quickly","The goalie wants you to leave the puck and they'll handle it themselves on the right side of the net","The goalie is warning you that a forechecker is coming from the right side and you should go now","The goalie wants you to pass the puck back to them so they can make a play themselves behind the"],ok:0,why:"Goalie communication directs the breakout. 'Rim right' means the puck is set for a rim to the right-side winger. Execute the call — the goalie has the best view.",tip:"Goalie calls 'Rim right'? Execute. They have the best view behind the net."},
    {id:"u18q25",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Handling a losing streak",d:1,sit:"Your team has lost four games in a row. Morale is low. Players are pointing fingers. As a leader, what do you do?",opts:["Refocus the team on process — work ethic, preparation, and executing the details in the next game","Call out the specific players who have been making the most mistakes so they can be held accountable","Tell everyone to relax since losing streaks happen and there's nothing anyone can do about it up","Have a team party to boost morale since the problem is clearly that the team isn't having enough"],ok:0,why:"Losing streaks are broken by refocusing on process, not results. Work ethic, preparation, and details. Teams that focus on the next game instead of the last four recover.",tip:"Losing streak? Process over results. Work ethic. Preparation. Next game."},
    {id:"u18q26",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading the referee",d:1,sit:"The referee has been letting a lot of physical play go — they're not calling minor hooks and holds. How does this change your approach?",opts:["Adjust — use more physicality since the referee is allowing it, but stay within their definition of legal for this game since that can change quickly","Play the exact same way since you should never adjust your game based on officiating standards and your style should be consistent regardless of the","Complain to the referee every time something isn't called since eventually they'll start calling those penalties if you bring enough attention to the up","Play less physical since if the referee is letting things go the other team will play even rougher and you don't want to get into a physical game up"],ok:0,why:"Smart players read the referee's standard and adjust. If they're letting physical play go, use it to your advantage — but stay within the game's definition of legal.",tip:"Ref letting it go? Adjust. Use the physicality they're allowing. Stay smart."},
    {id:"u18q27",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Creating space for linemates",d:1,sit:"You're on the ice and your linemate is the team's best shooter. They're consistently getting covered tightly. How can you create space for them?",opts:["Drive to the net and pull a defender with you — the space you vacate opens up for your linemate now","Stay as close to your linemate as possible to provide support in case they need help with the puck","Tell them to find their own space since creating room is their responsibility and not yours on the","Screen the goalie every time even when the puck is in the corner and nowhere near a shooting right now"],ok:0,why:"Creating space for linemates is an underrated skill. Driving to the net pulls defenders and opens ice. The best playmakers create space without the puck.",tip:"Linemate getting smothered? Drive the net. Pull a defender. Create their space."},
    {id:"u18q28",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Controlled zone entry",d:1,sit:"You're entering the offensive zone with possession. The D is backing up and giving you the blue line. What type of entry should you make?",opts:["Carry the puck in with speed and possession since the D is conceding the blue line to you right now","Dump it in hard to the corner since every zone entry should be a dump to protect against turnovers now","Stop at the blue line and wait for your entire team to catch up before you enter the zone with now","Pass the puck backward to your D and let them carry it in since D entries are more effective right"],ok:0,why:"When the D gives you the blue line, carry the puck in. A possession entry against a retreating D creates more offense than a dump-in.",tip:"D backing up? Carry it in. Possession entry. Don't give up the puck for free."},
    {id:"u18q29",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Stretch play timing",d:1,sit:"You're a forward sprinting up ice on a stretch play. Your D has the puck. The opposing D is flat-footed at the blue line. When should the stretch pass arrive?",opts:["Timed so you receive it in stride at the blue line — not too early to be offside, not too late to stop","As early as possible so you have maximum time with the puck before you reach the defensive zone right","After you've already crossed the blue line so there's zero risk of offside on the play at all cost now up","It doesn't matter when it arrives as long as it's in the general area and you can skate to go get now"],ok:0,why:"Stretch pass timing is critical. In stride at the blue line maximizes speed and minimizes offside risk. Too early forces offside; too late kills momentum.",tip:"Stretch pass: in stride at the blue line. Timing is everything."},
    {id:"u18q30",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Draft/showcase awareness",d:1,sit:"You're playing in a showcase tournament with scouts watching. You're tempted to play more individually to stand out. What's the smart approach?",opts:["Play your game within the team structure — scouts value players who make the team better, not solo acts","Go for highlight-reel plays since that's what scouts remember and individual skill is what gets really","Avoid all risk since a mistake in front of scouts could cost you a draft pick or a scholarship instead","Ask the coach for extra ice time so scouts see more of you since the more you play the better you look now"],ok:0,why:"Scouts value hockey IQ, character, and team play as much as individual skill. Playing within the system while showcasing your strengths is the winning approach.",tip:"Scouts watching? Play your game. Team play + hockey IQ impress more than solo acts."},
    // MEDIUM (d:2) — questions 31-70
    {id:"u18q31",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Third-period trailing strategy",d:2,sit:"Your team is down by one goal entering the third period. The other team plays a tight defensive system. What's the overall approach?",opts:["Increase offensive zone time through sustained pressure and cycling — force turnovers in their zone to create chances rather than rushing the attack up the ice","Pull the goalie immediately at the start of the third to get an extra attacker for the full twenty minutes since you need to score and this maximizes your now","Keep playing the same way and hope for a lucky bounce since changing your approach when you're down usually makes things worse and creates more turnovers for sure","Play ultra-aggressive with no regard for defense since you need a goal and the best defense when trailing is a good offense that puts constant pressure on now"],ok:0,why:"Trailing by one requires sustained offensive zone pressure, not desperation. Cycling, winning puck battles, and creating chances through possession is more effective than rush attacks against a tight system.",tip:"Down one in the third? Sustained pressure. Cycle. Win battles. Don't force it."},
    {id:"u18q32",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Opponent tendency recognition",d:2,sit:"You've noticed the opposing center always cheats to the right on faceoffs. They win draws to their forehand consistently. You're taking the next draw against them. What do you do?",opts:["Counter their forehand by positioning your stick to block the right-side win and use your body to gain inside leverage for the draw at the dot against them","Take the draw exactly the same way you always do since adjusting your technique based on one player's tendency is overthinking the faceoff situation in up","Let the opposing center win the draw and focus on the puck battle after since faceoffs aren't important enough to spend time strategizing about before the","Ask your winger to line up where the puck usually goes on their forehand win so at least you'll have the puck battle covered if they win it to their preferred"],ok:0,why:"Reading an opponent's faceoff tendency and countering it is a competitive advantage. Blocking their forehand win and using body leverage directly addresses their strength.",tip:"Know their faceoff tendency? Counter it. Block the forehand. Use leverage."},
    {id:"u18q33",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP structure variation",d:2,sit:"Your team's PP has been running a 1-3-1 all season. The opponent's PK has scouted it and is shutting it down. What variation can catch them off guard?",opts:["Switch to an overload formation or a 1-4 briefly to give them a different look they haven't prepared for in their scouting of your power play system","Keep running the 1-3-1 since it's what you've practiced all season and changing formations mid-game will create confusion and more turnovers for up","Have all five players stand still and pass the puck between them without moving since movement is what the PK reads and being stationary will right","Add a sixth player to the power play by having the goalie skate out since the extra man advantage of 6-on-4 will overwhelm even a well-scouted for sure"],ok:0,why:"PP formation variation catches a scouted PK off guard. Switching from 1-3-1 to an overload or 1-4 gives them a look they haven't prepared for.",tip:"PK scouted your PP? Switch the formation. Give them a new look."},
    {id:"u18q34",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"1-3-1 trap execution",d:2,sit:"Your coach wants to run a 1-3-1 trap in the neutral zone to slow down a fast team. You're the center in the middle of the three. What's your specific role?",opts:["Control the middle of the ice — take away the center lane and force everything wide where your D can close on the puck carrier as they approach your blue line","Chase the puck carrier wherever they go since the center in the 1-3-1 should always be closest to the puck regardless of where it is on the ice at all really","Stand at center ice and don't move since the 1-3-1 is a passive system where everyone stays in their spot and waits for the opponent to make a mistake first here","Drop back to the blue line and play as a third defenseman since the neutral zone isn't where the trap works and the real defense starts at your own blue line"],ok:0,why:"The center in a 1-3-1 controls the middle lane. You're the key to the trap — take away the center and funnel everything wide where the structure has advantages.",tip:"Center in the 1-3-1: own the middle lane. Force everything wide."},
    {id:"u18q35",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout under extreme pressure",d:2,sit:"The opposing team is forechecking with all five players aggressively in your zone. Every outlet is covered. Your D has the puck with zero time. What's the best option?",opts:["Get the puck off the glass or boards and out of the zone — accept the icing if needed to relieve the pressure since a turnover here is a guaranteed scoring chance for them","Try to make a play through five forecheckers since at U18 your puck skills should be good enough to escape any pressure situation in your own defensive zone cleanly right","Hold the puck and absorb the hit since the referee will blow the play dead when five players converge on one puck carrier in the corner of the defensive zone area instead","Pass the puck back to your goalie every time there's pressure since the goalie can always freeze it and you'll get a faceoff which is better than any other option here really"],ok:0,why:"Five-man forechecking creates maximum danger. Getting the puck out — even off the glass with an icing — is the priority. A turnover with all five opponents deep is catastrophic.",tip:"All five forechecking? Get it out. Glass, boards, anything. Icing is okay."},
    {id:"u18q36",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Post-game accountability",d:2,sit:"Your team won the game 5-2 but played poorly in the second period — gave up two goals and took bad penalties. As a leader, how do you address it?",opts:["Acknowledge the win but address the second period specifically — good teams are honest about poor stretches even in wins and use them to improve for next time","Don't say anything negative since you won the game and criticizing the team after a victory will kill the positive momentum and confidence the team is right","Only talk about the positives since reinforcing good plays is more effective than pointing out mistakes and the team should feel only good things after here","Give a detailed analysis of every mistake in the second period so the team understands exactly what went wrong and can fix each specific issue before the up"],ok:0,why:"Accountability after a win shows maturity. Acknowledge the result, but address the bad stretch honestly. Good teams don't hide from poor play just because they won.",tip:"Won but played poorly? Acknowledge the win AND the bad stretch. Honest teams improve."},
    {id:"u18q37",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Clock management",d:2,sit:"Your team is up by one with two minutes left. You win a faceoff in your zone. What do you do with the puck?",opts:["Get the puck deep into the opposing zone and make them use time retrieving it to run down the clock","Rush the puck up ice and try to score another goal to make the lead safer with an insurance tally here","Hold the puck behind your own net for as long as possible since that kills the most time on the up","Pass the puck around in your own zone between your D since that's the safest way to maintain it up"],ok:0,why:"Getting the puck deep makes the other team spend time retrieving it while the clock runs. Holding it in your zone invites pressure. Deep dumps kill clock safely.",tip:"Up one, two minutes left? Get it deep. Make them spend time retrieving."},
    {id:"u18q38",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Creating mismatches",d:2,sit:"Your team's fastest line is matched against the other team's slowest D pair. Your coach notices this. What should your line do to exploit the mismatch?",opts:["Use speed to attack with rush chances and create turnovers — force the slow D to skate and make decisions under speed pressure from your faster forwards on the ice","Play a slow, controlled game to protect the puck since even with a speed advantage turnovers are always costly and controlled play is always safer than speed here","Play a dump-and-chase game since dumping the puck in is the most effective strategy regardless of your speed advantage because it's the safest entry every instead","Ignore the mismatch since exploiting individual matchups is not good team hockey and you should always play the same system regardless of who is on the ice for the up"],ok:0,why:"Speed against slow D is a clear mismatch. Attacking with pace, forcing them to skate, and creating turnovers through pressure is how you exploit it.",tip:"Fast line vs slow D? Attack with speed. Force them to skate. Exploit the mismatch."},
    {id:"u18q39",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Neutral zone regroup timing",d:2,sit:"Your team is regrouping in the neutral zone. The forwards have swung back and are getting into their lanes. The D has the puck. When should the D start the play?",opts:["When the forwards are in their lanes and have speed going up ice — timing the pass with their speed maximizes the transition advantage into the offensive zone here","Immediately — the D should pass the puck forward as soon as they get it regardless of where the forwards are positioned since speed of play is always the top here","Wait until the forwards are standing still at the blue line so they can receive the puck cleanly without having to control a pass while skating at full speed here","Hold the puck until the opposing team has fully set up their neutral zone defense since regrouping should take as long as possible to give your team the best possible"],ok:0,why:"The regroup pass works best when forwards have speed in their lanes. Too early and they're not ready. Too late and they're standing still. Timing the pass with their speed maximizes the entry.",tip:"Regroup: time the pass with forward speed. Not too early, not too late."},
    {id:"u18q40",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D-zone awareness after icing",d:2,sit:"Your team just iced the puck. You can't change lines. The other team sends out their top line for the offensive zone faceoff. What do you focus on?",opts:["Win the draw and get a clean zone exit on the first touch since a tired team on an icing can not afford to spend time in the D-zone against a fresh top line","Let them win the faceoff and focus on defending since you're tired and it's better to play defense than risk a bad faceoff play that leads directly to a up","Don't worry about it since icings happen and whatever happens on the faceoff is fine since you can't control whether you're tired or not on this particular","Argue with the referee about the icing call to try to get a few extra seconds of rest before the faceoff is taken since every second of rest counts when you're"],ok:0,why:"After an icing, the priority is a clean zone exit on the first touch. Your team is tired and can't change — spending time in the D-zone against their fresh top line is dangerous.",tip:"Icing, tired team: win the draw. Get out clean. First touch matters most."},
    {id:"u18q41",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Leading in the room",d:2,sit:"Your team has a new player who's talented but hasn't bought into the team system. They freelance on the ice and it's creating problems. As a veteran leader, what do you do?",opts:["Have a private conversation explaining how the system works and why buying in makes everyone better including them personally — welcome them and show them the culture","Ignore it since they'll either figure it out or the coach will bench them and it's not your responsibility to integrate new players into the team culture and system","Publicly call them out in front of the team to pressure them into conforming since embarrassment is the fastest way to change behavior and get new players to buy up","Tell the coach to bench them until they agree to play within the system since that's the most effective way to force compliance from talented players who won't here"],ok:0,why:"Integrating new players through private conversation is leadership. Welcoming them, explaining the culture, and showing why the system helps everyone — including them — builds buy-in.",tip:"New player not buying in? Private conversation. Welcome them. Show the 'why.'"},
    {id:"u18q42",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Timeout usage",d:2,sit:"Your team is in a tight game. The coach calls a timeout after a goal against. You have 30 seconds. What's the most productive way to use this time as a player?",opts:["Listen to the coach, catch your breath, and focus on one specific adjustment for the next shift to execute — don't try to process everything at once or change too many things","Drink water and zone out since the timeout is for the coach to talk and you just need physical rest not tactical information during these short breaks in the game flow right","Talk over the coach to share what you've been seeing on the ice since your perspective is more important than theirs and the team needs to hear your observations right right","Use the time to argue about the goal that was just scored and assign blame for the breakdown since accountability during timeouts prevents the same mistake from happening really"],ok:0,why:"Timeout productivity: listen, breathe, focus on one adjustment. Trying to fix everything at once during a 30-second break creates confusion. One focus, one fix.",tip:"Timeout: listen, breathe, one focus. Don't overload. One adjustment at a time."},
    {id:"u18q43",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Late-game goalie pull timing",d:2,sit:"Your team is down by one with 90 seconds left. You have a faceoff in the offensive zone. The coach signals to pull the goalie for the extra attacker. What's the team's approach?",opts:["Set up the 6-on-5 with the extra player at the net front or point — use the overload to create a shot through traffic or a cross-ice play with the numerical advantage","Panic and shoot the puck every time you touch it since you need a goal and shot volume is the only thing that matters when the goalie is pulled and time is right now","Have the extra player roam around the zone without a specific assignment since having an extra body creates natural chaos that the defending team can not handle here","Don't pull the goalie since an empty-net goal against ends the game and the risk outweighs the reward of having six attackers when there's still 90 seconds left to right"],ok:0,why:"6-on-5 requires structure. The extra player takes a specific position — net front or point — to create the overload. Random movement wastes the advantage.",tip:"6-on-5: extra player takes a specific spot. Net front or point. Structure wins."},
    {id:"u18q44",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Neutral zone turnovers",d:2,sit:"Your teammate turns the puck over in the neutral zone. The other team has a 3-on-2 rush coming at your defense. You're the forward closest to the play. What's your job?",opts:["Backcheck hard and take away the trailing player — reduce the 3-on-2 to a 2-on-2 by picking up the third attacker coming late with speed from behind the play","Chase the puck carrier since taking away the puck is the most direct way to stop the rush and your speed should be enough to catch them from behind on this play","Skate to the bench since you can't catch the play and a fresh forward on the next shift will be more valuable than a tired one chasing a 3-on-2 rush from up","Stay in the neutral zone in case the rush fails and the puck comes back since being in position for a counter-attack is more valuable than backchecking here"],ok:0,why:"Backchecking to take away the trailer turns a 3-on-2 into a 2-on-2. Your D handle two — you eliminate the third. That's the highest-value backcheck play.",tip:"3-on-2 against? Backcheck and take the trailer. Turn it into 2-on-2."},
    {id:"u18q45",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading the forecheck formation",d:2,sit:"The opposing team switches between a 1-2-2 and a 2-1-2 forecheck throughout the game. How do you identify which one they're running on each play?",opts:["Watch how many players come below the hash marks on the initial puck retrieval — one means 1-2-2, two means 2-1-2, and that tells you what outlet options are available","You can't identify the forecheck in real time since everything happens too fast and you should just run the same breakout every time regardless of their forecheck now","The goalie should identify the forecheck and call it out since they have the best view and can communicate the forecheck formation to the D before they make a play really","It doesn't matter what forecheck they run since your breakout should be the same every time and adjusting based on the forecheck is overthinking the game at this here"],ok:0,why:"Reading the forecheck in real time is an elite skill. Counting how many come below the hash marks tells you the formation — and that dictates which breakout options are open.",tip:"Count the forecheckers below the hashmarks. One = 1-2-2. Two = 2-1-2. Read and react."},
    {id:"u18q46",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Captain in overtime",d:2,sit:"Your team is going to overtime. It's 3-on-3. As captain, what do you communicate to the team in the 60 seconds before overtime starts?",opts:["Keep it simple: protect the puck, take smart risks, and don't turn it over in the neutral zone since turnovers in 3-on-3 create breakaway chances with all the open ice","Tell everyone to play it safe and not take any chances since overtime is too risky for aggressive play and a tie in the standings is better than a loss if you try up","Give a long speech about the importance of this game to fire everyone up since emotional energy is the most important factor in overtime and skills take a back right","Don't say anything since the coach handles all overtime strategy and your job as captain is just to play well when you're on the ice rather than to communicate or up"],ok:0,why:"Overtime communication: simple and focused. Protect the puck, smart risks, no neutral zone turnovers. In 3-on-3, turnovers create breakaways. The message is clarity, not emotion.",tip:"3-on-3 overtime: protect the puck. Smart risks. No NZ turnovers. Keep it simple."},
    {id:"u18q47",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Faceoff importance awareness",d:2,sit:"There's a faceoff in your offensive zone with 30 seconds left and you're tied. The coach puts you on the ice specifically for this draw. What's the priority?",opts:["Win the draw to a specific spot — your team should have a set play ready for this exact situation to get a shot on goal quickly before time expires in the period","Just try to win the faceoff anywhere since the direction doesn't matter as long as your team gets possession of the puck and can try to create something really","Let the other team win the draw since it's only the end of a period and overtime is fine — the faceoff isn't worth risking a turnover that could lead to a goal","Win the draw and then cycle the puck for a full 30 seconds to get the perfect shot since patience is more important than urgency even with only 30 seconds here"],ok:0,why:"Late-game O-zone faceoffs require a set play. Win the draw to a specific spot and get a shot on net quickly. 30 seconds isn't enough time for cycling — execute the play.",tip:"30 seconds, tied, O-zone draw: set play. Win it to a spot. Get the shot."},
    {id:"u18q48",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Video review self-analysis",d:2,sit:"You watch video of your last game. You notice you consistently get caught flat-footed on defensive transitions — you're slow to recognize turnovers. What do you do with this information?",opts:["Work on your transition recognition in practice — focus on reading the play and reacting within one second of a turnover to improve your gap and positioning speed","Ignore it since video always makes things look worse than they actually are and in real time your transitions are probably fine and don't need any specific here","Tell the coach to stop showing you video since it's making you overthink things and you play better when you just react naturally without analyzing your own now","Blame your linemates for the slow transitions since you're only slow because they turn the puck over in bad spots and better puck management would fix the right"],ok:0,why:"Self-analysis from video is a development tool. Identifying a pattern (slow transitions) and working on it in practice is exactly how players improve at the U18 level.",tip:"Video shows a pattern? Work on it in practice. Self-analysis drives improvement."},
    {id:"u18q49",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Countering a skilled team",d:2,sit:"You're playing against the most skilled team in the league. They dominate when they have the puck in the offensive zone. What's the neutral zone strategy to limit their zone time?",opts:["Play a tight neutral zone system to prevent clean entries — force them to dump and chase instead of carrying the puck in with speed and control through the middle of the ice","Open up the neutral zone and let them carry the puck in since trying to stop a skilled team in the NZ is pointless and you should focus on D-zone defense after they instead","Forecheck aggressively with all three forwards since the best way to stop a skilled team is to take the puck from them before they even reach the neutral zone with for sure","Play a spread-out neutral zone that gives them more room since skilled teams struggle with too much space and make mistakes when they have to make decisions quickly with really"],ok:0,why:"A tight NZ system forces a skilled team to dump instead of carry. Dump-and-chase is lower percentage for skilled players. It takes away their strengths.",tip:"Skilled team? Tight NZ. Force them to dump. Take away clean entries."},
    {id:"u18q50",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"F1 backcheck responsibility",d:2,sit:"You're F1 on the backcheck. Your team just turned the puck over. The opposing D has the puck and their center is open in the middle. What's your assignment?",opts:["Take the center away — get in the middle lane and prevent the pass to the most dangerous player in their breakout since the center pass starts their transition cleanly","Chase the D who has the puck since taking the puck away directly is always better than covering a passing lane and your speed should be enough to catch them from here","Skate to the far winger's side since they're the most open player on the ice and a long pass to the winger creates a bigger offensive threat than the center in the middle","Go to the bench for a change since backchecking F1 should be a fresh player and you've been on the ice too long to be effective in a footrace with the opposing center"],ok:0,why:"F1 backcheck takes away the center. The middle lane is the most dangerous breakout pass — eliminating it forces the D to use the boards, which is slower and easier to defend.",tip:"F1 backcheck: take the center away. Eliminate the middle lane."},
    {id:"u18q51",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Playing in hostile environments",d:2,sit:"You're playing a road game. The crowd is loud and hostile. Your team is rattled after a bad first period. How do you approach the second period?",opts:["Use the crowd energy as fuel — play with a chip on your shoulder and focus on executing your game plan since road adversity builds mental toughness for the team in the long run","Complain about the crowd and the referee since the hostile environment is creating an unfair advantage for the home team and someone needs to acknowledge that publicly to the team","Try to quiet the crowd by playing passively and making no mistakes since the crowd feeds on big plays and errors and if you play boring hockey they'll lose interest eventually","Tell the team to ignore the crowd completely and pretend nobody is in the building since awareness of the crowd is a distraction and has no place in competitive hockey at here"],ok:0,why:"Hostile crowds are fuel, not a problem. Playing with intensity and focus on the road builds toughness. Use the energy — don't run from it.",tip:"Hostile crowd? Use it as fuel. Play with a chip. Road adversity builds toughness."},
    {id:"u18q52",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defensive coverage rotation",d:2,sit:"In the defensive zone, the opposing team passes the puck from the corner to the point. Your winger was covering the point but got caught low. You're the center. What do you do?",opts:["Rotate up to cover the point man since your winger can't get there — communicate so the coverage gap is filled before the point player can shoot or pass it down to the slot","Stay in the slot since that's always the center's responsibility and if the winger got caught low that's their mistake to fix and not your responsibility to cover for them","Follow the puck to the corner since the puck is what scores goals and being near the puck is always the right decision regardless of where your coverage assignment is here","Don't rotate and let the point man have the shot since shots from the point are low percentage and your goalie can handle a point shot without any defensive help from you here"],ok:0,why:"Defensive coverage is fluid. When a winger gets caught, the center rotates to fill the gap. Communication prevents confusion. Rigid assignments without rotation create open shooters.",tip:"Winger caught low? Rotate to the point. Fill the gap. Communicate."},
    {id:"u18q53",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP faceoff play execution",d:2,sit:"Your team has a PP offensive zone faceoff with a set play designed: draw back to the point for a one-timer. The PK knows this play — they've seen it. What adjustment do you make to the play?",opts:["Run the same draw but add a secondary option — if the PK overplays the point shot, have the center fake the draw-back and go directly to the net with the puck instead","Run the exact same play without any adjustment since execution beats scouting and if you win the draw cleanly the PK can't stop a clean point shot regardless of what","Abandon the set play entirely and just try to win the draw forward aggressively for a quick shot since set plays don't work when the other team knows what you're instead","Skip the faceoff entirely — don't even try to win it and focus all your energy on defending the PK's counter-attack since their scouting has made your PP faceoff now"],ok:0,why:"Adding a secondary option to a scouted play keeps the PK guessing. If they overplay the point shot, the center going direct to the net exploits their adjustment.",tip:"PK knows your play? Add a secondary option. Keep them guessing."},
    {id:"u18q54",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading gap and pressure",d:2,sit:"You're a D defending in the neutral zone. The puck carrier has speed and is heading right at you. A second attacker is filling the far lane. Your gap is tight. What do you do?",opts:["Match their speed while maintaining your gap — force the puck carrier to make a decision while keeping yourself in position to recover to the far-lane attacker if they pass","Step up and try to hit the puck carrier at the blue line since a big hit will end the rush and your tight gap gives you the perfect distance to deliver a clean body check here","Back up to the goal line and give them the entire neutral zone since your tight gap means you're too close and you need more space to react to their speed and any for sure","Ignore the puck carrier and skate directly at the far-lane attacker since the second player is usually more dangerous than the puck carrier on a two-player rush into right"],ok:0,why:"Matching speed while maintaining gap forces the carrier to decide. You're in position to play the shot or recover to the pass. Committing to either player gives up the other.",tip:"Speed coming at you with a second option? Match speed. Maintain gap. Force the decision."},
    {id:"u18q55",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Headman pass decision",d:2,sit:"You're a D with the puck after winning a board battle. You see a forward open at the far blue line. There's one forechecker between you and the forward. Do you attempt the headman pass?",opts:["Only if the lane is clean — a headman pass through a forechecker is high-risk and a turnover in the NZ gives them a rush chance against your D partner who's alone back there","Always attempt the headman pass since getting the puck to the forward as fast as possible is always the right play regardless of whether there's a forechecker in the really","Never attempt a headman pass since they're too risky and a simple play along the boards is always better than a long pass through traffic in the neutral zone at any time in","Fake the headman and carry the puck yourself since D-men at U18 should be able to beat any forechecker one-on-one and carrying is always safer than passing through traffic here"],ok:0,why:"The headman pass is the best play when the lane is clean. Through a forechecker, it's a coin flip — and the downside of a NZ turnover is far worse than the upside of a successful pass.",tip:"Headman pass: only through clean lanes. Through traffic = too risky."},
    {id:"u18q56",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Leading with actions",d:2,sit:"Your team isn't competing hard enough in practice. The coach has spoken to them about it but nothing has changed. As a leader, what's the most effective thing you can do?",opts:["Lead by example — compete at maximum effort every drill, every rep, and your standard will raise the standard of the players around you over time through action not words","Give another speech about compete level since what the team really needs is more verbal accountability from the leaders and not just the coaching staff telling them to right","Stop competing hard yourself since clearly the culture of this team doesn't value effort and you should save your energy for games instead of wasting it in practices now","Threaten to go to the coach and name the players who aren't competing so they get benched since that level of fear and accountability is what lazy players need to change"],ok:0,why:"Actions are the most powerful form of leadership. When you compete at maximum effort every rep, it raises the standard for everyone around you. Words without actions are empty.",tip:"Team not competing in practice? Set the standard with your effort. Lead by doing."},
    {id:"u18q57",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"End of period awareness",d:2,sit:"There are 10 seconds left in the second period. Your team has the puck in the neutral zone. What's the smart play?",opts:["Get the puck deep into the offensive zone and create a scoring chance — a late-period goal changes momentum going into the intermission break between periods here","Hold the puck at center ice and let the clock run out since there isn't enough time to create anything meaningful and risking a turnover at the buzzer could here","Dump the puck in and go for a change since the period is essentially over and there's no point in trying to create a scoring chance with only 10 seconds of right","Shoot the puck on net from center ice since any shot from anywhere is a good shot when time is running out and you might score a lucky goal from long distance at the"],ok:0,why:"10 seconds is enough to get a shot. Getting the puck deep and creating a late-period chance can shift momentum. Wasting the opportunity is a missed chance.",tip:"10 seconds left with possession? Get it deep. Create a chance. Momentum matters."},
    {id:"u18q58",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Exploiting icings against",d:2,sit:"The other team just iced the puck. They can't change. You can see their D are tired. What's the offensive approach on this O-zone faceoff?",opts:["Win the draw and attack their tired D immediately — cycle hard and force them to skate, exploiting their fatigue before the next whistle gives them a change opportunity","Play conservatively on the faceoff since icing doesn't guarantee your team an advantage and playing too aggressively after an icing can lead to a turnover and rush the now","Win the draw and dump the puck in deep since tired players recover when they have time and dumping it gives them time to rest while your forecheckers chase the puck in","Ignore the icing advantage entirely since game state advantages like tired opponents are overblown at the U18 level and skilled players can perform just as well really"],ok:0,why:"Icing with tired opponents is a clear advantage. Win the draw and immediately cycle — force them to skate. Fatigue compounds with every second they spend in the D-zone.",tip:"Icing, tired opponents? Win the draw. Cycle hard. Make them skate."},
    {id:"u18q59",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Supporting the rush through the NZ",d:2,sit:"Your D is carrying the puck through the neutral zone. You're a forward and there's open ice on the right side. But another forward is already filling that lane. Where do you go?",opts:["Fill the middle or left lane — don't double up in the same lane as your teammate and give the rush three distinct options across the ice to attack with maximum width and numbers","Go to the right side anyway since being close to the puck carrier is always better than being in a different lane and double coverage on one side creates an overload the D here","Stop skating and let the rush develop without you since three forwards in the rush is too many and one forward should always stay back as a safety valve in case of a after that","Sprint ahead of the play and get to the offensive zone before anyone else since getting there first gives you the best position for a rebound or deflection near the opposing net up"],ok:0,why:"Rush support requires lane discipline. Three distinct lanes (left, middle, right) give the puck carrier maximum options. Doubling up in a lane wastes a player.",tip:"Teammate already in a lane? Take a different one. Three lanes, three options."},
    {id:"u18q60",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout timing",d:2,sit:"Your D has the puck behind the net. You're the winger on the wall. The D is looking at you. You see the forechecker is about to close the lane. When do you call for the puck?",opts:["Call for it now — before the forechecker closes the lane, since timing the pass before pressure arrives is critical to a clean breakout exit from your own zone","Wait until the forechecker has fully committed to closing the lane and then call for the puck since having more information about their positioning leads now","Don't call for it since the D should be able to read the play themselves and calling for the puck might distract them from making the best decision with here","Call for the puck after the forechecker has closed the lane since receiving the puck under pressure is good practice for developing your puck-handling skills"],ok:0,why:"Calling for the puck before the lane closes gives the D the timing cue they need. Late calls mean late passes — and late passes get intercepted.",tip:"See the lane about to close? Call now. Not after. Timing the call wins breakouts."},
    {id:"u18q61",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Controlling game tempo",d:3,sit:"Your team is faster than the opponent. The opponent is trying to slow the game down with dump-ins and clutching. How does your team speed the game back up?",opts:["Quick puck movement on breakouts, fast transitions, and minimal puck-holding time to force the pace and prevent them from clogging the neutral zone and slowing you down","Accept the slow pace since the other team is dictating the tempo and you should adjust to play their game instead of trying to force yours on them throughout the rest here","Dump the puck in every time since that eliminates the neutral zone where they're slowing you down and forces a footrace to the puck in the offensive zone where you now","Fight to change the tempo since physical intimidation is the only way to speed up a game when the opponent is clutching and grabbing and the referees aren't calling up"],ok:0,why:"Quick puck movement and fast transitions are the antidote to a slow game. Minimize puck-holding, move the puck early, and force the pace through speed of play.",tip:"They're slowing it down? Quick puck movement. Fast transitions. Force your tempo."},
    {id:"u18q62",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Penalty kill strategy late in game",d:3,sit:"Your team is up by one with four minutes left and takes a penalty. The opposing PP is strong. What's the PK strategy?",opts:["Ultra-disciplined box — collapse to the net, block shots, and clear every puck. Deny the high-danger shots and force them to score from the perimeter if they can at all","Aggressive PK — pressure the puck carrier at every opportunity since taking the puck away ends the power play instantly and that's better than sitting back and really","Play a normal PK without any adjustment for the game situation since your PK should be the same regardless of the score or the time remaining on the clock in the game","Send a player after the PP puck carrier every time to try to force a shorthanded chance since the best PK is one that scores a goal and that would seal the game right"],ok:0,why:"Late-game PK with a lead: ultra-disciplined. Collapse, block, clear. The goal is to survive the two minutes — not create offense. Force them to score from low-percentage areas.",tip:"Leading late, PK? Ultra-disciplined. Collapse. Block. Clear. Survive the two minutes."},
    {id:"u18q63",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP sustained pressure",d:3,sit:"Your PP has been in the zone for a full minute. The PK is tired but still in structure. You have the puck at the point. The PK is sagging to block shots. What's the next-level read?",opts:["Walk the puck lower to change the shooting angle and draw the PK out of their collapsing position, creating a lane for a pass to the slot or a higher-percentage shot from a new spot","Take the shot from the point through all the bodies since the PK is sagging and even though they're blocking lanes a hard shot from the point might get through their wall eventually up","Pass the puck back and restart the PP setup since the current setup isn't working and cycling back will give the PK a chance to reset and you can try a completely new approach this","Hold the puck at the point for as long as possible since the PK is tired and if you just wait long enough they'll eventually break down and give you a wide open look at the net now"],ok:0,why:"Walking the puck lower changes the geometry. A sagging PK is beaten by changing the angle — it draws them out and creates passing lanes that didn't exist from the point.",tip:"PK sagging at the point? Walk lower. Change the angle. Draw them out."},
    {id:"u18q64",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"NZ puck support",d:3,sit:"Your forward has the puck in the neutral zone but is getting pressured. You're the D behind them. They're about to lose the puck. What do you do?",opts:["Get close enough to be an outlet for a drop pass — give them an escape option before the pressure forces a turnover in a dangerous area of the neutral zone on the play","Stay back at your own blue line since if they lose the puck you need to be in defensive position already and moving forward would leave the back end completely really","Yell at them to dump the puck since they're going to turn it over and you don't want to deal with the consequences of a neutral zone turnover from this position on up","Sprint past them into the offensive zone since if they can manage the pressure for one more second your speed will create a stretch pass option that beats the pressure up"],ok:0,why:"Being an outlet for a drop pass when your forward is pressured prevents the turnover. Close support gives them an escape option in a dangerous area.",tip:"Forward under pressure in NZ? Get close. Be the drop-pass outlet."},
    {id:"u18q65",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout under sustained pressure",d:3,sit:"The other team has been forechecking aggressively for the last three shifts. Your team has been pinned in the D-zone. You finally get the puck. What's the priority?",opts:["Make a quick, smart pass to exit the zone — don't try to be a hero with the puck since one clean exit can change the momentum of the entire game for your team right now","Hold the puck and try to deke through the forecheck since after three shifts of pressure your team needs a highlight play to change the momentum and fire up the bench here","Dump the puck over the glass intentionally to get a whistle and a break since the delay of game penalty is worth the rest your team will get during the penalty kill up","Pass the puck back to the goalie and have them freeze it for a faceoff every single time since faceoffs are the only reliable way to reset when you're under after that"],ok:0,why:"After sustained pressure, one clean exit changes everything. Quick, smart pass — don't try to be a hero. Clean exits relieve pressure and shift momentum.",tip:"Pinned for three shifts? One clean exit changes everything. Quick, smart pass."},
    {id:"u18q66",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Adapting to a new role",d:3,sit:"Your coach moves you from the top line to the third line to balance the lineup. You're frustrated. How do you handle it?",opts:["Accept the role and dominate it — prove you can impact the game from any line and trust that your effort and attitude will be recognized by the coach over time here","Refuse to play on the third line and tell the coach you deserve to be on the top line since you've earned it and demotion is unacceptable at this point in the now","Play on the third line but give minimal effort since if the coach doesn't value you enough for the top line you shouldn't give them your best effort on a lower up","Go to the coach and demand an explanation and threaten to quit the team if they don't move you back to the top line since your talent is being wasted on the third"],ok:0,why:"Accepting a role and dominating it shows character. Great players impact the game from any line. Attitude in adversity defines leadership more than performance in ideal situations.",tip:"Moved to the third line? Dominate it. Impact the game from anywhere. That's character."},
    {id:"u18q67",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Overtime 3-on-3 strategy",d:3,sit:"Your team is in 3-on-3 overtime. You have possession. There's a ton of open ice. What's the strategic approach?",opts:["Control the puck and wait for the right moment to attack — don't force anything since a turnover in 3-on-3 creates a high-danger chance the other way with open ice everywhere","Attack immediately every time you get the puck since 3-on-3 is about scoring and hesitation gives the defense time to set up and take away the open ice that overtime creates","Pass the puck between your three players at center ice without attacking since the other team will eventually make a mistake and give you a perfect 2-on-0 or breakaway right","Dump the puck in every time and forecheck since dump-and-chase works in 3-on-3 just like it works in 5-on-5 and it's the safest way to generate offensive zone time in after that"],ok:0,why:"3-on-3 is about controlled aggression. Control the puck, read the play, and attack when the opening appears. Forcing the play creates turnovers — and turnovers in OT are breakaways.",tip:"3-on-3 OT: controlled aggression. Wait for the moment. Don't force it."},
    {id:"u18q68",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading defensive systems",d:3,sit:"You notice the opposing team plays a passive 1-4 defensive zone setup — all four players collapse to the net front and one player pressures loosely at the top. How do you attack this?",opts:["Use point shots through traffic and crash the net for rebounds since a collapsing defense gives up the outside and traffic in front creates deflections and rebound chances now","Try to walk through all four defenders with individual skill since the best way to beat a passive defense is to use superior stickhandling and speed to beat them one-on-one right","Pass the puck around the outside forever until they come out since eventually a passive defense will get bored and break down if you just keep moving the puck along the right","Dump the puck behind the net and chase it since the net-front congestion from a 1-4 means the puck behind the net is the only area of the ice where you can gain possession up"],ok:0,why:"A 1-4 gives up the outside. Point shots through traffic exploit the screen that their own collapsing defense creates. Crashing the net generates rebounds from the traffic.",tip:"Passive 1-4? Point shots through traffic. Their own players screen the goalie."},
    {id:"u18q69",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK against a high-skill PP",d:3,sit:"You're killing a penalty against the best PP in the league. They move the puck incredibly fast. Your standard box can't keep up with their puck movement. What adjustment do you make?",opts:["Apply more pressure on the puck carrier — disrupt their rhythm by not letting them make comfortable passes. A slightly aggressive PK takes time off the clock and forces errors.","Keep the same box and hope they miss their shots since adjusting against a skilled PP will create gaps that they'll exploit even faster than they're exploiting your current up","Collapse all four PK players to the crease and let them shoot from anywhere since most shots miss and the ones that do hit the net will be blocked by the bodies in front of the up","Switch to a man-to-man PK where each player follows an opponent wherever they go since taking away their individual players is better than trying to maintain a zone after that"],ok:0,why:"Disrupting the PP's rhythm with controlled pressure on the puck carrier takes away their comfort. They can't make fast passes if the passer is being pressured on every touch.",tip:"High-skill PP? Pressure the puck carrier. Disrupt their rhythm. Don't let them get comfortable."},
    {id:"u18q70",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"NZ counterattack off a failed entry",d:3,sit:"The opposing team tries to enter your zone but your D steps up and forces a turnover at the blue line. The puck is loose. Three of their players are deep in your zone. What's the opportunity?",opts:["Counterattack immediately — get the puck moving up ice while three of their players are behind the play, creating a potential odd-man rush with numbers advantage in your favor","Slow the play down and regroup even though their players are caught deep since rushing a counterattack usually leads to turnovers and a more controlled approach is always now","Clear the puck down the ice and take an icing since getting the puck as far from your net as possible is always the right play after a defensive zone turnover at your blue really","Hold the puck and wait for all five of your players to be in position before attacking since counterattacking without a full five-player rush is too risky at this level of up"],ok:0,why:"A forced turnover with three opponents deep is a prime counterattack opportunity. Speed up ice creates odd-man advantages before they can recover.",tip:"Forced a turnover, three of theirs are deep? Counterattack now. Numbers advantage."},
    // HARD (d:3) — questions 71-100
    {id:"u18q71",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Managing a blowout win",d:3,sit:"Your team is winning 7-1 in the third period. The game is clearly decided. How should your team approach the remaining time?",opts:["Play with full effort but focus on team play — no individual heroics, protect the puck, and play respectfully while maintaining your competitive standard throughout","Coast through the rest of the game with minimal effort since the outcome is decided and there's no reason to risk injury or embarrass the opposing team any further now","Try to score as many goals as possible to pad your personal stats since every goal counts for your season total and scouts look at point totals when evaluating now","Play dirty to intimidate the other team for future matchups since a blowout is the perfect time to send a physical message without worrying about the score or here"],ok:0,why:"Blowout management: full effort, team play, no individual heroics. Maintaining your standard while playing respectfully shows character. Coasting builds bad habits.",tip:"Blowout? Full effort, team play, respectful. Maintain your standard. Character matters."},
    {id:"u18q72",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading the opponent's timeout adjustments",d:3,sit:"The opposing coach calls a timeout. When play resumes, you notice they've changed their forecheck from a 1-2-2 to a more aggressive 2-1-2. What do you do with this recognition?",opts:["Adjust your breakout immediately — use the weak side and quick D-to-D passes since a 2-1-2 overloads one side and leaves the other side more open for a clean breakout exit","Ignore it since trying to identify and adjust to mid-game tactical changes is overthinking and you should just run your standard breakout regardless of what they're here","Panic and call your own timeout since the opponent has changed tactics and your team needs time to discuss and plan a completely new strategy to counter their aggressive","Slow the game down and hold the puck in your own zone to waste time and prevent the new forecheck from being effective since if you don't have the puck they can't really"],ok:0,why:"Recognizing a mid-game tactical change and adjusting immediately is elite hockey IQ. A 2-1-2 overloads one side — the weak side is the outlet.",tip:"They changed their forecheck after a timeout? Recognize it. Adjust. Use the weak side."},
    {id:"u18q73",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PP with under a minute",d:3,sit:"There's a minute left in the power play and you haven't scored. The PK is tired but still holding structure. You have the puck at the half-wall. What's the highest-percentage play?",opts:["Quick pass to the slot or net front and shoot immediately — tired PKs react slowly and a fast play to the high-danger area exploits their fatigue in the final minute of the kill","Hold the puck on the half-wall and try to find the perfect play since with only a minute left you need to make sure every pass is perfect and you can't afford any turnovers now","Shoot from the half-wall every time since shots from anywhere create chaos and with a minute left you need as many shots as possible regardless of the quality or the after that","Pass the puck back to the point and take a slap shot since the point shot through traffic is always the highest percentage PP play and that's what you should default to every right"],ok:0,why:"A tired PK reacts slowly. A quick pass to the slot or net front and an immediate shot exploits their fatigue. The high-danger area is where late PP goals come from.",tip:"Tired PK, minute left? Quick to the slot. Shoot fast. Exploit their fatigue."},
    {id:"u18q74",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"NZ faceoff with game on the line",d:3,sit:"Neutral zone faceoff with 10 seconds left. Game is tied. Your coach wants you to win the draw and get a shot. The opposing center is one of the best faceoff players in the league. What's your approach?",opts:["Study their stance and hand position — adjust your technique to counter their strength. Have your wingers ready to jump on a loose puck if the draw isn't won cleanly by either side.","Take the draw the same way you always do since adjusting your technique at the last second is more likely to cause you to lose the draw than to win it against a strong faceoff now","Let them win the draw and focus on defense since with 10 seconds left it's better to play for overtime than to risk a turnover that gives them a chance to win it in regulation now","Cheat on the draw and try to get the puck before it hits the ice since the referee probably won't kick you out with 10 seconds left and the advantage of getting the puck first now"],ok:0,why:"Big faceoffs require preparation and support. Study the opposing center, counter their technique, and have your wingers ready for a loose puck. It's not just the center's battle.",tip:"Big faceoff: study them. Counter their technique. Wingers ready for the loose puck."},
    {id:"u18q75",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout creativity",d:3,sit:"Your team's standard breakouts have been getting picked off all game. The forecheck has figured you out. What creative breakout option can you add?",opts:["Use a double-swing or overload one side to create an extra option — change the pattern the forecheck has been reading all game and force them to adjust on the fly now","Keep running the same breakouts since they've worked all season and one game of struggle doesn't mean you should change what you've practiced repeatedly in practice","Have the goalie play the puck on every dump-in and make long passes up the ice since that eliminates the need for a breakout entirely and bypasses the forecheck now","Tell the D to carry the puck themselves every time since individual skill should be enough to beat any forecheck if the D are skilled enough to handle the puck here"],ok:0,why:"When the forecheck has figured out your breakouts, adding a creative option changes the pattern. A double-swing or overload gives the forecheck a look they haven't seen.",tip:"Breakouts getting picked off? Change the pattern. Double-swing. Overload. Be creative."},
    {id:"u18q76",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Leading in a championship game",d:3,sit:"It's the championship game. Pre-game nerves are high. Some teammates look tight. As a leader, what do you do?",opts:["Keep the room loose but focused — remind the team to play their game, trust the preparation, and enjoy the moment since this is what you've worked for the entire season here","Give an intense, emotional speech about how this is the most important game of everyone's life and anyone who doesn't perform at their best will regret it for the rest now","Don't say anything since every player handles pressure differently and any pre-game talk might make the nervous players feel worse and the confident players feel right now","Tell everyone to pretend it's a regular game since acknowledging the significance of the championship will add to the pressure and the team should treat it like any really"],ok:0,why:"Championship leadership: loose but focused. Trust the preparation, play your game, enjoy the moment. Over-intensity creates tightness. Dismissing the moment loses its power.",tip:"Championship game? Loose but focused. Trust preparation. Enjoy the moment."},
    {id:"u18q77",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Managing emotions after a bad hit",d:3,sit:"An opponent delivers a questionable hit on your linemate. No penalty is called. Your linemate is shaken up. The bench is furious. What do you do on the next shift?",opts:["Play hard and physical but within the rules — channel the emotion into compete level, not retaliation, since a penalty hurts your team more than it helps your linemate right now","Go after the player who delivered the hit and fight them since your teammate needs to know you have their back and physical retaliation is the only language some players really","Take a run at the nearest opposing player to send a message to the other team that they can't get away with hits like that without consequences from your team in the next shift now","Ignore it completely and play passively since getting emotional after a bad hit is exactly what the other team wants and the best response is to pretend nothing happened at all"],ok:0,why:"Channeling emotion into compete, not retaliation, is elite emotional management. A penalty after a bad hit is exactly what the other team wants. Play harder, not dirtier.",tip:"Bad hit on a teammate? Channel the emotion into compete. Don't give them the penalty."},
    {id:"u18q78",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Exploiting line changes",d:3,sit:"You notice the opposing team consistently makes sloppy line changes — players coming off early or too many on the ice momentarily. How can your team exploit this?",opts:["Attack during their changes — when you see players heading to the bench, push the pace immediately since the transition moment of a line change creates a brief numerical advantage","Ignore their line changes since trying to time your attacks to their changes is too complicated and you should just play your own game regardless of what the opposing team is now","Tell the referee about their sloppy changes so they get a too many men penalty since that's the proper way to deal with a team that doesn't manage their bench substitutions right now","Time your own line changes to match theirs exactly so both teams change at the same time and the sloppy changes cancel out and give neither team an advantage during the right now"],ok:0,why:"Attacking during sloppy line changes creates brief numerical advantages. The 2-3 seconds when players are between the ice and the bench is an exploitable window.",tip:"Sloppy changes? Attack during the transition. Brief numerical advantage."},
    {id:"u18q79",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK momentum shift",d:3,sit:"Your PK just killed a big penalty and your bench is energized. You're the first player on the ice after the penalty expires. What do you do with the momentum?",opts:["Channel the energy into a strong, aggressive shift — the PK momentum carry-over often leads to scoring chances if the team capitalizes on the emotional shift immediately","Calm down and play conservatively since the PK was tiring and the team needs to recover their energy before pushing the pace again so you should ease into the next here","Call a timeout to celebrate the kill and let the momentum sink in since stopping play after a big PK allows the team to savor the moment and build even more emotional right","Ignore the momentum since hockey is played in individual shifts and what happened on the PK has no bearing on what happens in the next five-on-five shift for your right"],ok:0,why:"PK momentum is real. The first shift after a big kill is often the best chance to capitalize — the team is energized and the opponent is frustrated their PP failed.",tip:"Big PK? First shift after: channel the energy. Momentum is real. Capitalize."},
    {id:"u18q80",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"NZ positioning against a skilled team",d:3,sit:"You're playing against a team with elite puck carriers who consistently beat your NZ defense one-on-one. Your 1-2-2 isn't holding. What's the adjustment?",opts:["Tighten the formation and focus on taking away east-west passing lanes — force them to go north-south into your structure where numbers are in your favor at the blue line","Spread out more and give the puck carriers room since a looser formation will confuse their decision-making and skilled players actually struggle when given too much now","Switch to man-to-man coverage in the neutral zone where each player follows an opponent wherever they go to prevent anyone from getting open for a pass or a carry through up","Add a fourth player to the neutral zone by pulling a D forward to create a 1-3-1 trap since the extra body in the NZ will make it impossible for even skilled players now"],ok:0,why:"Against elite carriers, tightening the NZ formation and removing east-west lanes forces them north-south into your structure. They beat you wide — take away wide.",tip:"Elite carriers beating you wide? Tighten up. Take away east-west. Force north-south."},
    {id:"u18q81",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D puck decisions under pressure",d:3,sit:"You're a D with the puck behind your net. The forecheck is closing hard from both sides. You have maybe one second. Your outlets are: winger on the wall (covered with pressure coming), center at the hashmarks (partially open), or glass. What do you choose?",opts:["Quick pass to the center at the hashmarks since it's partially open and the center can handle some pressure — it starts the breakout while the winger option risks a board turnover","Pass to the winger on the wall even though they're covered since at U18 your winger should be skilled enough to handle a pass under pressure and fight through the coverage easily","Use the glass every time you're under pressure since it's the safest option and you should never attempt a pass when the forecheck is closing hard from both sides during the game","Hold the puck and try to skate through both forecheckers since D-men at this level should be able to handle the puck well enough to beat a forecheck by themselves most of the time up"],ok:0,why:"The partially open center at the hashmarks is the best read. It starts the breakout while the winger option risks a board turnover. The glass is last resort. Quick decision, smart pass.",tip:"One second, outlets limited? Read the best option. Center partially open = go there."},
    {id:"u18q82",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Leading a younger player",d:3,sit:"A first-year player on your team is struggling with confidence. They're talented but afraid to make mistakes. As a veteran, what do you do?",opts:["Take them under your wing — tell them mistakes are part of learning, share your own early struggles, and encourage them to play their game without fear of failure on the team here","Leave them alone since building confidence is a personal journey and anything you say might come across as patronizing to a player who's just starting their career at this really","Tell them to just play harder since confidence comes from effort and if they compete hard enough the results will come naturally without any specific guidance or mentoring from right","Push them into uncomfortable situations publicly to force them to develop mental toughness since the only way to build confidence is to survive difficult moments under after that"],ok:0,why:"Mentoring a younger player through their early struggles is one of the most impactful forms of leadership. Sharing your own experiences normalizes the struggle and builds trust.",tip:"Younger player struggling? Share your story. Normalize the struggle. Build them up."},
    {id:"u18q83",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Strategic icing",d:3,sit:"Your team is exhausted. It's late in the third. You have the puck in your zone with no clean exit. Your team desperately needs a line change. Is icing ever the right play?",opts:["In extreme cases yes — icing to get a line change when your team is completely exhausted prevents a more costly turnover that could lead to a goal against in a tired defensive zone","Never — icing is always a mistake and you should always find a way to exit the zone cleanly regardless of how tired your team is or how much pressure the forecheck is applying now","Always — icing should be used every time you're tired since the faceoff gives your goalie a rest and even though you can't change lines the stoppage is worth the cost of staying right","Only if you're losing since icing when winning gives the other team a faceoff in your zone and that's too dangerous to risk when protecting a lead in the final minutes of the game"],ok:0,why:"Strategic icing is a real tool. When the team is exhausted and a turnover is imminent, icing gets the puck out safely. The trade-off (no change, D-zone draw) is better than a goal against.",tip:"Team exhausted, no clean exit? Sometimes icing is the smart play. Better than a turnover goal."},
    {id:"u18q84",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Faceoff strategy by zone",d:3,sit:"Your team is in the offensive zone for a faceoff late in the game while tied. The coach gives you a specific play. What's the difference between an O-zone and D-zone faceoff mentality?",opts:["O-zone: aggressive, go for the scoring chance. D-zone: protect first, get the puck out clean. The zone changes the risk-reward calculation of every decision after the draw.","There's no difference — faceoffs should be approached the same way regardless of which zone they're in since the technique for winning the draw is the same everywhere now","O-zone: play conservatively to maintain possession. D-zone: be aggressive to try to score a shorthanded-style breakaway goal off the draw since the element of surprise up","The zone doesn't matter at all since faceoffs are 50-50 by nature and you can't control which way the puck goes after it's dropped so preparing specific plays is mostly a"],ok:0,why:"Zone changes everything. O-zone faceoffs are about creating chances — aggressive. D-zone faceoffs are about getting the puck out — protective. The risk-reward shifts with location.",tip:"O-zone: aggressive, create chances. D-zone: protect, get it out. Zone changes everything."},
    {id:"u18q85",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK against a 5-on-3",d:3,sit:"Your team is down two players — it's a 5-on-3 for the opponent. Your three players need to kill two minutes. What's the strategy?",opts:["Form a tight triangle in front of the net — protect the slot and crease, block shots, and clear every rebound. Accept perimeter shots and force them to be perfect to score here.","Play aggressively and try to steal the puck since the 5-on-3 gives the PP so much space that passive defense won't work and your only chance is to take the puck away from them now.","Spread out to cover as much ice as possible since three players spread out can cover the same amount of ice as five players in a normal PK if they skate hard enough to close up","Give up and accept the goal since a 5-on-3 for two minutes is essentially an automatic goal at U18 and there's nothing three players can do to prevent a team of five from right"],ok:0,why:"5-on-3: tight triangle, protect the slot, block shots, clear rebounds. You accept perimeter shots — the goalie can handle those. Slot and crease shots are what score.",tip:"5-on-3: tight triangle. Protect the slot. Block shots. Accept perimeter shots."},
    {id:"u18q86",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"NZ puck retrieval",d:3,sit:"In the neutral zone, a loose puck is sliding toward the boards. Both you and an opponent are racing for it. You're slightly behind but at a better angle. How do you win this race?",opts:["Use your angle to arrive at the puck first by taking a shorter path — angle beats speed when the puck is along the boards and body position determines who gets possession here","Sprint in a straight line at maximum speed since pure speed always beats angle when racing to a loose puck and the fastest player always wins regardless of their position on","Give up on the race since you're behind and conserve energy for the next play since chasing pucks you probably won't get is a waste of energy that could be used more instead","Try to take out the opponent with a hip check before they get to the puck since if they can't reach the puck it doesn't matter who had the better angle or the better instead"],ok:0,why:"Angles beat speed when the puck is along the boards. A shorter path with body position gets you to the puck first — even when the opponent has a speed advantage.",tip:"Behind but better angle? Use the angle. Shorter path + body position wins races."},
    {id:"u18q87",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout chemistry with your D partner",d:3,sit:"You and your D partner have been playing together all season. You know their tendencies. They always look backhand first on retrievals. How does this knowledge change your breakout support?",opts:["Position yourself on their backhand side immediately when they retrieve the puck since you know that's where they'll look first and being there creates a faster and cleaner breakout exit","Ignore their tendencies and always go to the same spot regardless since the breakout system dictates your positioning and individual player tendencies shouldn't change your execution up","Tell them to stop always looking backhand first since having a predictable tendency makes the breakout easier for the forecheck to read and they should vary their retrievals more really","Position yourself on their forehand side since that will force them to look forehand instead of backhand and over time this will help them develop a more well-rounded breakout game now here"],ok:0,why:"Chemistry with your D partner means anticipating their tendencies. If they look backhand first, being there creates a faster breakout. Playing to your partner's strengths is smart hockey.",tip:"Know your D partner's tendency? Be where they look. Chemistry speeds up breakouts."},
    {id:"u18q88",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Handling team conflict",d:3,sit:"Two players on your team are in a conflict that's affecting the room. It's spilling onto the ice — they won't pass to each other. As a leader, what do you do?",opts:["Address it directly but privately — talk to each player separately, understand both sides, and help them find a resolution that puts the team first above personal issues here","Stay out of it since interpersonal conflicts between other players aren't your business and getting involved will only make things more complicated and potentially worse for now","Take sides with the player you agree with and publicly support them since showing loyalty to one side will resolve the conflict faster than trying to mediate between two now","Bring it up in front of the whole team and force them to resolve it publicly since everyone is affected by the conflict and the entire team deserves to hear both sides of up"],ok:0,why:"Private, separate conversations show respect for both players while addressing the problem. Understanding both sides and focusing on team-first resolution is mature leadership.",tip:"Team conflict? Private conversations. Both sides. Team-first resolution."},
    {id:"u18q89",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Reading the game for adjustments",d:3,sit:"You're in the second period and your team is struggling. You've been watching the game carefully from the bench. You notice the other team overloads the strong side on every O-zone entry, leaving the weak side open. How do you use this?",opts:["Tell your linemates to look for the weak-side switch on their entries — a quick east-west pass after they overload one side creates a high-danger chance on the open side of the ice","Keep it to yourself since your observation might be wrong and sharing incorrect information with your linemates could cause them to make bad decisions based on your flawed instead","Tell the coach during a stoppage so they can address it with the whole team since individual adjustments won't work and the entire team needs to be on the same page for any changes to","Ignore the pattern since the opponent's system is what it is and trying to exploit their tendencies is too complicated to implement mid-game and your team should just focus on now"],ok:0,why:"On-ice observations shared with linemates create real-time adjustments. A weak-side switch against an overloaded strong side is a high-percentage counter — and you don't need the whole team to execute it.",tip:"See a pattern? Share it with your line. Real-time adjustments win games."},
    {id:"u18q90",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Defending the cycle against a physical team",d:3,sit:"The opposing team is bigger and more physical. They're cycling in your zone and winning every board battle. Your D are getting outmuscled. What's the tactical adjustment?",opts:["Beat them to the puck with speed and positioning — don't engage in the physical battle, get to the puck first and move it quickly before they can establish the cycle and grind you down","Hit them harder since the only way to beat a physical team is to be more physical and your D need to step up their compete level and match the opponent's size with more aggression now","Let them cycle and collapse to the net — eventually they'll have to shoot from outside and your goalie can handle perimeter shots since the cycle only works if you engage with it for sure","Pull all your players out of the defensive zone and let them cycle with nobody there since the cycle requires opposition to work and if nobody is there to battle they can't cycle here"],ok:0,why:"Against a bigger, physical team, speed and positioning beat size. Getting to the puck first and moving it quickly prevents the physical cycle from establishing.",tip:"Bigger team cycling? Beat them with speed. Get there first. Move the puck quick."},
    {id:"u18q91",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"PK pressure reads",d:3,sit:"You're on the PK and the PP is cycling. The puck goes below the goal line to the player behind the net. Your PK has been passive. Should you pressure behind the net?",opts:["Yes — controlled pressure behind the net disrupts the cycle setup and can force a turnover before the PP can get organized in the dangerous areas of the offensive zone above the dots","No — stay in the box and let the goalie handle anything from behind the net since leaving the box creates gaps that the PP will exploit with quick passes to open players in the slot now","Yes — send two PK players behind the net aggressively to trap the puck carrier and force a turnover since a shorthanded 2-on-1 behind the net will overwhelm the PP puck carrier here","No — the PK should never pressure above or below the goal line since the box formation is designed to work without any players leaving their assigned positions at any point for sure"],ok:0,why:"Controlled pressure behind the net disrupts the cycle. The key word is controlled — one player pressures, the box adjusts. You're not trapping, you're disrupting.",tip:"Puck behind the net on PP? Controlled pressure. Disrupt, don't trap."},
    {id:"u18q92",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"NZ play with the lead in the third",d:3,sit:"Your team is up by one in the third. The other team is pressing. Your neutral zone play has been loose — they're getting clean entries. What do you tighten up?",opts:["Clog the middle lane, backcheck harder to the puck side, and force everything wide — clean entries are coming through the middle so take it away systematically with your positioning","Play the same NZ system since you're winning and changing anything in the third period shows the other team you're afraid and gives them confidence that their pressure is for sure","Open up the NZ and let them enter since trying to prevent entries is futile when a team is pressing and you should focus all your defensive energy on the zone defense after really","Have all five players back behind the blue line before the opposing team reaches the neutral zone so there's no chance of a clean entry through the NZ since depth is more for sure"],ok:0,why:"Clean entries through the middle mean the NZ is too loose. Clogging the middle and forcing wide entries reduces the quality of their zone possessions.",tip:"Clean entries through the middle? Clog it. Force wide. Reduce quality."},
    {id:"u18q93",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Breakout against a trap",d:3,sit:"The opposing team is trapping in the NZ after your breakout exits the zone. They're sitting at the red line in a 1-3-1. Your breakout gets out of the zone but stalls every time. What's the fix?",opts:["Use speed through the middle with support or D carry — the trap is beaten by quick puck movement and players attacking the seams between the stationary trap players at the red line","Dump the puck through the trap every time since you can't carry through a 1-3-1 trap and dumping is the only way to get past a structured NZ defense at any competitive level of up","Have your D hold the puck in your own zone and refuse to enter the neutral zone until the trap breaks down since eventually the trap will have to come get you and then lanes right","Add a sixth player to the breakout by sending the goalie up to the red line to create a numerical advantage against the trap since 6-on-5 in the NZ will overwhelm any trap on the play"],ok:0,why:"Traps are beaten by speed and quick puck movement through the seams. D carry or quick passes through the gaps between stationary trap players exploit the formation's weakness.",tip:"Trap stalling your breakout? Speed through the seams. Quick passes. D carry."},
    {id:"u18q94",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"End-of-season reflection",d:3,sit:"The season is over. Your team didn't make it as far as you hoped. As a leader, what's the most important message in the final team meeting?",opts:["Acknowledge the disappointment, celebrate what the team accomplished and grew through, and challenge everyone to use the offseason to come back better for next year together here","Focus entirely on what went wrong so the team understands their failures and doesn't repeat the same mistakes next year since accountability after a disappointing season is here","Don't say anything emotional since the season is over and there's nothing anyone can do about it now — everyone should just go home and move on to whatever comes next in their lives","Blame the coaching staff for the team's failures since the players did their best and the results were a reflection of poor coaching decisions and strategy throughout the really"],ok:0,why:"End-of-season leadership: acknowledge, celebrate, challenge. The balance between processing disappointment and finding forward momentum defines how a team handles adversity.",tip:"Season over, fell short? Acknowledge, celebrate, challenge. That's how leaders close a season."},
    {id:"u18q95",cat:"Game Management",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Adapting to playoff hockey",d:3,sit:"Your team makes the playoffs. The games are immediately more physical and structured than the regular season. What adjustments do you make to your game?",opts:["Protect the puck more, finish every check, and be disciplined with penalties — playoff hockey punishes mistakes and rewards structure and compete level above all else in every shift","Play the exact same way you played in the regular season since changing your style for the playoffs means your regular season preparation was flawed and you can not change now at right","Take more risks since playoff hockey rewards bold plays and the teams that play conservatively always lose to the teams that take chances and play with more creativity and flair up","Focus entirely on individual stats since playoff performance determines your future and personal numbers are what scouts and coaches remember when they evaluate players after right"],ok:0,why:"Playoff hockey rewards discipline, physicality, and puck protection. Mistakes are amplified. Adjusting your game to protect the puck and finish checks is the playoff formula.",tip:"Playoffs? Protect the puck. Finish checks. Discipline. Mistakes are amplified."},
    {id:"u18q96",cat:"Advanced Tactics",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Controlling faceoff wins",d:3,sit:"You've been winning faceoffs to your forehand all game. The opposing center has adjusted and is now countering your forehand win. How do you re-adjust?",opts:["Switch to a different technique — use a backhand tie-up or a draw to a different spot. Varying your faceoff technique prevents the opponent from timing your move consistently.","Keep using the same forehand technique since it's worked all game and one adjustment from the opponent shouldn't change your approach to taking faceoffs in this game or here","Stop trying to win faceoffs and focus on tying the opposing center up so the wingers can battle for the puck since faceoff wins aren't as important as the puck battle really","Let the opposing center win every faceoff for the rest of the game since they've figured out your technique and there's nothing you can do to adjust mid-game against a right"],ok:0,why:"Faceoff adjustments are a game within the game. When they counter your forehand, switch techniques — backhand tie-up, different draw spot. Varying keeps them guessing.",tip:"They're countering your faceoff? Switch technique. Vary to keep them guessing."},
    {id:"u18q97",cat:"Special Teams",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Shorthanded scoring chance",d:3,sit:"You're on the PK and you intercept a PP pass at your own blue line. Two PP players are caught deep. You have a 2-on-1 with a teammate against one D. Do you take the chance or dump it in?",opts:["Attack the 2-on-1 — shorthanded goals are demoralizing and the risk of a 2-on-1 rush is worth the potential reward of scoring while killing a penalty and swinging momentum hard","Dump it in and go for a change since the PK's job is to kill time and not to score goals and risking a turnover on a shorthanded rush could lead to a PP goal against your team","Hold the puck at your own blue line and waste time since killing clock is more important than scoring and any risk during the PK is unnecessary when you're already successfully up","Pass the puck back to your goalie and let them freeze it for a faceoff since that's the safest way to kill time on the penalty and avoid any risk of a turnover in the for sure"],ok:0,why:"Shorthanded 2-on-1 chances are high-reward and demoralize the PP. Attack it — the risk is acceptable because of the huge momentum swing a SH goal creates.",tip:"SH 2-on-1? Attack it. SH goals are demoralizing. The reward is worth the risk."},
    {id:"u18q98",cat:"Neutral Zone Play",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Transition defense in 3-on-3",d:3,sit:"It's 3-on-3 overtime. Your team turns the puck over at the opposing blue line. Two opponents have the puck with speed. You and one D are back. It's a 2-on-2. How do you defend?",opts:["One player takes the puck carrier while the other takes the passing option — communicate instantly and commit to your assignment since hesitation in 3-on-3 creates breakdowns quickly","Both players back up to the goal line and let the goalie handle everything since 2-on-2 in 3-on-3 with speed means you can't stop them and your goalie is the last line of defense up","Both players converge on the puck carrier since taking the puck away immediately is the only way to stop the rush and the passing option is less dangerous than the carrier in 3-on-3 now","One player stays at center ice as a safety valve while the other defends the 2-on-1 alone since having a player back for the counter-attack is more valuable than defending with here"],ok:0,why:"2-on-2 in 3-on-3 requires instant communication. One takes the carrier, one takes the pass. Hesitation or doubling up creates the open man. Commit and communicate.",tip:"2-on-2 in 3-on-3? Communicate instantly. One takes the carrier, one takes the pass."},
    {id:"u18q99",cat:"Breakout Execution",pos:["F","D"],concept:"D reading the forecheck in real time",d:3,sit:"You're a D retrieving a dump-in. As you pick up the puck, you scan and see: F1 closing hard from the right, F2 drifting to the middle, F3 high in the NZ. Your winger is on the left wall. What do you do?",opts:["Quick pass to the left winger on the wall — F1 is coming from the right so the left side is the safe outlet. The scan told you everything you needed in one second to make the play.","Hold the puck and wait to see what happens since making decisions in one second is too fast and you need more time to process all the information before committing to a right now","Carry the puck up the right side directly at F1 since the best way to beat a forecheck is to attack it head-on and your puck skills should be good enough to beat one in this case","Shoot the puck off the glass and out of the zone since any time you're under forecheck pressure the safest play is to clear the zone and let the team reset on the next possession"],ok:0,why:"One-second scans dictate breakout decisions. F1 from the right means the left is open. Quick processing and execution is the difference between a clean breakout and a turnover.",tip:"Scan: one second. F1 right = outlet left. Quick process, quick execute."},
    {id:"u18q100",cat:"Leadership",pos:["F","D"],concept:"Legacy and team culture",d:3,sit:"You're in your final year at this level. The younger players will take over next season. What's the most important thing you leave behind?",opts:["A standard of compete, preparation, and team-first culture that the younger players carry forward — your legacy is how the team plays after you leave, not your personal stats","Your personal stats and achievements since the best way to inspire younger players is to show them what individual greatness looks like and they'll try to match your really","Nothing — every team builds its own culture and trying to leave a legacy is presumptuous since the next group of players will create their own identity regardless of really","A list of rules and expectations that younger players must follow since culture is built through strict rules and any deviation from the established norms should result now"],ok:0,why:"Legacy is culture. The standard you set — compete, preparation, team-first — is what younger players carry forward. Stats fade. Culture lasts.",tip:"Final year? Leave a standard. Compete. Preparation. Team-first. That's your legacy."},
    // U18 GOALIE (u18g1-u18g20)
    {id:"u18g1",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Advanced angle play",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"A shooter is approaching from the right wing on an angle. You're set at the top of the crease. How do you maximize your coverage?",opts:["Square your body to the puck and adjust your depth to cut the angle — telescope out slightly to reduce the visible net from the shooter's perspective","Stay deep in the net to give yourself maximum reaction time since advanced shooters have such quick releases that depth is more valuable than really","Come out past the crease aggressively to cut every possible angle since the closer you are to the shooter the less net they can see from any shooting up","Lean toward the short side since most shooters go short side from that angle and cheating there gives you the best chance of making the save on here"],ok:0,why:"Squaring to the puck and telescoping out slightly maximizes coverage while maintaining reaction space. The goal is to minimize visible net from the shooter's angle.",tip:"Angle play: square to the puck. Telescope out. Minimize visible net."},
    {id:"u18g2",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Reading shooter body language",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"A shooter is winding up for a shot from the slot. Their body position and stick blade angle suggest they're going low blocker. What do you do?",opts:["Prepare for the low blocker shot but don't fully commit — be ready to adjust if they change the angle at the last moment since good shooters vary their release late","Commit entirely to the low blocker side and drop your blocker hand to cover the area since trusting your read is more important than staying balanced in your right","Ignore the body language cues since trying to read shooters is guessing and a goalie should always stay centered and react to the puck after the release without up","Move to the other side since shooters always try to go against their body language and the best goalies always go opposite to what the shooter's body is telling really"],ok:0,why:"Reading body language is valuable but shouldn't override fundamentals. Prepare for the read but stay balanced enough to adjust. Good shooters disguise their intentions.",tip:"Read the shooter's body but don't overcommit. Prepare and adjust. Stay balanced."},
    {id:"u18g3",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Puck management in traffic",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"You make a save and the puck drops in front of you. There are three players from each team battling in the crease. You can see the puck. What's your priority?",opts:["Cover the puck immediately if possible — in heavy traffic, freezing the puck eliminates the chaos and gives your team a defensive zone faceoff reset to clear the zone","Try to push the puck to a teammate since keeping the play alive is better than a faceoff and your team might be able to transition to offense if you make a clean now","Leave the puck and let the players battle for it since getting involved in the scrum as a goalie is dangerous and you might get injured or accidentally push it into your","Kick the puck out to the slot area where there's more open ice since getting it away from the crease is the priority even if that means it goes to an area where a up"],ok:0,why:"In heavy traffic, covering the puck is the priority. It eliminates chaos, prevents second chances, and gives your team a reset. Trying to play it in traffic risks an own goal.",tip:"Traffic in front, puck visible? Cover it. Eliminate the chaos. Reset."},
    {id:"u18g4",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Lateral movement selection",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is passed from the right half-wall to the left point. The shot isn't imminent — the point man will look to pass before shooting. How do you get across?",opts:["T-push across in your stance on your feet — stay standing since the shot isn't imminent and you need to be ready to adjust to wherever the next pass or shot comes from","Butterfly slide across since that gets you from post to post the fastest and speed of lateral movement is always the most important factor regardless of when the now","Drop to butterfly where you are and wait since moving laterally when the shot isn't imminent is unnecessary and you should conserve energy by staying in place really","Sprint out of the crease on your skates to get to the other side as fast as possible since using skating speed gets you across faster than any really during the game"],ok:0,why:"T-push on your feet is the right movement when the shot isn't imminent. It keeps you in a ready stance to adjust. Butterfly slides are for when the shot is coming and you need coverage.",tip:"No imminent shot? T-push on your feet. Stay in stance. Stay ready."},
    {id:"u18g5",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Communication on the PK",d:1,pos:["G"],sit:"Your team is on the PK. The PP is cycling and you see the slot player drifting backdoor unnoticed by your PK. What do you do?",opts:["Call it immediately — 'Backdoor!' or 'Slot!' directs your PK player to the threat before the pass gets there and prevents the highest-danger scoring chance available here","Stay quiet and prepare for the backdoor play yourself since calling out the coverage gap might confuse your PK teammates and cause them to make a worse mistake than the here","Point at the open player with your stick since visual cues are better than verbal cues during a penalty kill when there's a lot of noise and your players might not right","Wait to see if the pass actually goes backdoor before saying anything since calling out a potential threat that doesn't materialize will make your teammates lose instead"],ok:0,why:"Immediate, loud communication prevents goals. The goalie has the best view of the developing play — calling 'Backdoor!' before the pass gets there is more valuable than any save.",tip:"See the backdoor threat? Call it NOW. Loud. Specific. Prevention beats saves."},
    {id:"u18g6",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Playing the puck in the trapezoid",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is dumped into the trapezoid area behind the net. You know you can only play it within the trapezoid. A forechecker is coming. What's your decision framework?",opts:["Read the forechecker's speed and angle — if you can get there first and have time to make a play, go. If not, leave it for the D and get back to your net in your ready stance position","Always play the puck in the trapezoid regardless of pressure since goalie puck handling is a weapon and you should use it every chance you get to help your team start the breakout up","Never play the puck since the risk of a turnover behind the net is too high and goalies should always stay in their crease and let the defensemen handle all puck retrievals behind the up","Only play the puck if the coach specifically told you to before the game since goalie puck handling decisions should be made by the coaching staff and not by the goalie in real right"],ok:0,why:"The decision framework is: speed, angle, and time. Can you get there first and make a play? If yes, go. If no, get back to the net. Every play is a read, not a default.",tip:"Puck in the trapezoid: read speed, angle, time. Go or stay. Every play is a read."},
    {id:"u18g7",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Pre-scout goalie preparation",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"You've studied video of the opposing team's top scorer. They have a deadly one-timer from the right circle. How do you prepare for this specific threat?",opts:["Cheat slightly to take away the one-timer zone and be ready to push hard to that spot when the puck goes to the setup man — knowing the threat helps you pre-position for the save","Don't change anything based on scouting since every game is different and adjusting your positioning based on video of a previous game could make you worse in other areas of your up","Over-commit entirely to the one-timer side for the entire game since that's the biggest threat and taking it away completely is more important than being balanced for other here","Ignore the scouting report and play your normal game since goaltending is about reacting to the puck and not about pre-positioning based on information from previous games right"],ok:0,why:"Pre-scout preparation lets you cheat slightly without overcommitting. Knowing the one-timer threat means pre-positioning when the setup begins — you're reacting faster, not guessing.",tip:"Scouted their one-timer? Pre-position when the setup starts. React faster, not guess."},
    {id:"u18g8",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Reading the shooter on a breakaway",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"A breakaway is coming. The shooter is approaching at moderate speed — they're not rushing. They're a known deker. At what point do you commit to your save?",opts:["Wait as long as possible — let them show their hand first, then react. Committing early against a deker gives them the advantage since they can adjust to your commitment easily","Commit early and aggressively since the best way to stop a deker is to take away as much net as possible before they start their move and force them to go around you with now","Drop to butterfly immediately when they cross the blue line since most breakaway goals go low and covering the bottom of the net early gives you the best chance against right","Poke check from the top of the circles since stopping the breakaway before they get a shot is always better than trying to make a save and the poke check eliminates the right"],ok:0,why:"Against a known deker, patience is your weapon. Let them show their move, then react. Committing early gives them the read and the advantage.",tip:"Known deker? Be patient. Let them show you. Then commit. Patience wins."},
    {id:"u18g9",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Rebound management on hard shots",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"A hard slap shot is coming from the point. You know this shooter has a heavy shot that creates big rebounds. How do you prepare to control the rebound?",opts:["Get compact and absorb the shot into your body — angle your pads to direct the rebound to the corner rather than letting it bounce back into the slot for a second chance opportunity","Stand tall and try to catch every slap shot in your glove since catching eliminates the rebound entirely and is always the best option regardless of how hard the shot is at this up","Stay loose and relaxed since tension makes rebounds worse and a loose body naturally absorbs pucks better than a tense one that deflects pucks unpredictably into dangerous areas up","Drop to butterfly early so your pads are flat on the ice and the puck will slide under your body and stop dead behind you where no one can get to it for a rebound or second shot really"],ok:0,why:"Compact stance and angled pads direct rebounds to the corners. Absorbing hard shots requires deliberate pad angle — letting rebounds go to the slot creates the most dangerous second chances.",tip:"Hard shot coming? Get compact. Angle pads to the corner. Control the rebound."},
    {id:"u18g10",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Playing against screens at the U18 level",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"The opposing team consistently sets screens on every point shot. You've been getting beat through screens all game. What adjustment do you make?",opts:["Be more active with your positioning — move laterally to find sightlines around screens and communicate with your D to clear the screen or give you a lane to track the puck through","Accept that screens are part of the game and don't adjust since trying to look around screens takes you out of position and you should just stay centered and react to whatever up","Tell your D to clear every screen before the shot comes since it's their job to keep the front of the net clean and any goal scored through a screen is a defensive breakdown here","Drop deeper in the net to give yourself more time to react to shots through screens since depth is the best counter to screened shots and being further back gives you more really"],ok:0,why:"Active positioning around screens is the adjustment. Move laterally to find sightlines, communicate for clears, and track the puck through gaps. Passive goalies get beaten by screens.",tip:"Getting beat through screens? Be active. Move to find sightlines. Communicate for clears."},
    {id:"u18g11",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Cross-crease save technique",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"The puck is passed cross-ice from the right wing to a player on the left side who's one-timing it. You were set on the right side. How do you make this save?",opts:["Butterfly slide hard across the crease — lead with your pad and get as much of your body across as possible to seal the far side before the one-timer release comes at the net","T-push across on your feet since staying standing gives you more coverage and being on your feet is always better than being in butterfly when moving laterally across right","Drop to butterfly on the right side and hope the shot goes to your pad side since cross-crease saves are too difficult and the best option is to stay where you are and here","Turn around and skate across the crease on your feet since skating is faster than any goaltending slide and you'll arrive at the far side with more time to set up and right"],ok:0,why:"Cross-crease one-timers require a committed butterfly slide. Lead with the pad, seal the far side. T-pushes are too slow and staying put gives up the entire far side of the net.",tip:"Cross-crease one-timer? Butterfly slide. Lead pad. Full commitment across."},
    {id:"u18g12",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Post-save awareness",d:2,pos:["G"],sit:"You make a pad save and the rebound goes to the corner. An opposing player picks it up. While they're in the corner, what should you be doing?",opts:["Reset your position — get square to the new puck location and scan for the developing play. Find the slot player and the backdoor option before the puck moves out of the corner area.","Celebrate the save and take a moment to regroup mentally since making a big save deserves recognition and your teammates need to see your confidence before the next shot comes here","Stay exactly where you are from the save and don't move until the puck comes back to a shooting position since unnecessary movement wastes energy and takes you out of your best now","Skate out of the crease toward the corner to challenge the puck carrier since an aggressive goalie puts pressure on the opponent and prevents them from making a clean play out here"],ok:0,why:"Post-save reset is critical. Square to the puck, scan for threats (slot, backdoor), and prepare for the next shot. Every second the puck is in the corner is time to get ready.",tip:"Made the save? Reset. Square up. Scan. Find the threats. Get ready."},
    {id:"u18g13",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Handling the wraparound from both sides",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"An attacker is behind the net and you don't know which side they'll attack. They've used both sides effectively. How do you position yourself?",opts:["Stay centered and patient — read their body language and commit to the side they choose at the last possible moment. Moving too early gives them the other side of the net for free.","Pick a side and commit early since being aggressive on one side gives you the best chance of making the save and if they go the other way it was just a good play by them and right","Leave the net entirely and poke check behind the net since that's the only way to stop a skilled player behind the net and traditional goaltending positioning won't work in really","Stay on the right post since statistically more wraparounds come from the right side and playing the percentages is smarter than trying to read the attacker's body language in real up"],ok:0,why:"Patience and centering against a dual-threat wraparound forces the attacker to commit first. Moving early gives up the other side. Read their body language and react.",tip:"Wraparound, both sides dangerous? Stay centered. Be patient. Let them commit first."},
    {id:"u18g14",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Game state positioning adjustments",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"Your team is up by one in the final minute. The other team pulls their goalie. Six attackers are coming. How do you adjust your positioning?",opts:["Stay slightly deeper and more compact — 6-on-5 creates unusual passing lanes and deflection opportunities. Being compact maximizes your coverage against tips and redirections from any angle.","Play more aggressively and come out further since six attackers will screen you and being further out cuts the angle on all six players and reduces the visible net they can see for for sure","Don't change anything since your positioning should be the same in every game situation and adjusting for the extra attacker is overthinking the moment and will take you out of your normal here","Leave the net and go to the bench since the game is almost over and a fresh goalie from the bench would have more energy to handle the six attackers in the final minute of the game here. up"],ok:0,why:"6-on-5 creates unusual angles. Being slightly deeper and more compact protects against the tips, deflections, and cross-ice plays that the extra attacker generates.",tip:"6-on-5 against? Slightly deeper. More compact. Protect against the unusual."},
    {id:"u18g15",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Mental toughness after multiple goals",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"You've given up three goals in the first period — two were soft. The coach hasn't pulled you. The team needs you to be better. How do you reset for the second period?",opts:["Use the intermission to do a focused mental reset — brief review of what went wrong, then visualize making saves. Come out for the second period with a clean mental slate and sharp focus.","Dwell on each goal during the intermission to make sure you understand exactly what you did wrong so you never make the same mistake again in the second or third period of this game here. up","Tell the coach to put in the backup since you're clearly not having a good game and the team deserves a goalie who's playing better tonight even if that means sitting for the rest of the","Pretend the goals didn't happen and don't think about them at all since any analysis of what went wrong will only make you more likely to repeat the mistakes when you get back on the ice"],ok:0,why:"Intermission mental reset: brief review (30 seconds), then visualization of success. Come out sharp. Dwelling causes doubt; ignoring prevents learning. The balance is the skill.",tip:"Bad first period? Brief review. Visualize saves. Clean slate. Come out sharp."},
    {id:"u18g16",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Handling the slot deke",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"An attacker receives a pass in the slot and is coming at you with a deke move. They're known for a forehand-to-backhand roof deke. You're at the top of the crease. What's your approach?",opts:["Stay patient on your feet as long as possible — respect their move but don't bail early. When they commit to the forehand, track the puck and push across if they go backhand side.","Drop to butterfly immediately since most slot dekes require the puck to go low at some point and being in butterfly covers the bottom of the net where the majority of deke goals","Poke check aggressively since taking the puck off their stick before they can start the deke is the only reliable way to stop a skilled deker in the slot at the U18 level of now","Back up deeper into the net to give yourself more reaction time since the closer you are to the goal line the more time you have to react to their deke move and make the save on"],ok:0,why:"Patience on your feet against a slot deke forces the attacker to commit first. Bailing into butterfly early gives them the top of the net. Stay up, track the puck, then react.",tip:"Slot deke? Stay on your feet. Be patient. Let them commit. Then react."},
    {id:"u18g17",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Goalie-D partnership",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"You and your D have different communication preferences. They want specific calls ('left,' 'time,' 'pressure'). You usually just play the puck without talking. How do you resolve this?",opts:["Adapt your communication to give them what they need — specific, clear calls that help them make better decisions. The partnership improves when both players speak the same language here.","Keep doing what you've been doing since changing your communication style will slow you down and make you less effective and the D should adapt to your style instead of you adapting here","Stop communicating entirely since any communication that isn't natural will be confusing and it's better to let each player figure things out on their own without verbal cues during the here","Only communicate during timeouts and stoppages since trying to talk during live play is too distracting for both the goalie and the D and leads to more confusion than clarity on breakout"],ok:0,why:"Adapting your communication to your D's needs strengthens the partnership. Specific calls ('left,' 'time,' 'pressure') help them make better decisions. The partnership is worth the adjustment.",tip:"D wants specific calls? Give them. Adapt. The partnership is worth it."},
    {id:"u18g18",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Tracking through tip plays",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"The opposing PP runs a set play: point shot with a forward at the crease specifically positioned to tip the puck. You know it's coming. How do you prepare?",opts:["Get compact and low — when the tip comes, the puck changes direction unpredictably. Being compact maximizes coverage for any angle the tip might create. Keep your stick on the ice firmly.","Focus only on the point shot and ignore the tipper since you can't predict where a tip will go and the best strategy is to play the original shot and hope the tip goes wide of the right","Stand tall to see over the tipper since tracking the original shot through the screen is more important than being ready for the tip and height gives you the best view of the release up","Move to one side of the net to avoid the tipper entirely since getting a clear view of the shot is worth leaving some net exposed and you'll make up for it with better reaction time now"],ok:0,why:"Against a known tip play: compact, low, stick on ice. Tips are unpredictable — being compact maximizes coverage for whatever angle the deflection creates.",tip:"Known tip play? Get compact. Low. Stick on ice. Cover maximum net."},
    {id:"u18g19",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Self-scouting and improvement",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"You review your season stats and notice you're weak on low blocker shots. Your save percentage on that shot type is significantly below your average. What do you do?",opts:["Work specifically on low blocker saves in practice — have shooters target that area repeatedly until your technique and positioning improve to match the rest of your game consistency.","Ignore the stats since they're probably due to random variation and changing your technique based on stats could make other parts of your game worse while trying to fix one right now","Compensate by cheating your blocker lower in games to cover the weakness since the quickest fix for a low blocker weakness is to pre-position your blocker closer to the save location","Tell the coach to instruct the D to take away all low blocker shots since the goalie shouldn't have to make those saves if the defensive system is working properly in front of them. here"],ok:0,why:"Self-scouting drives improvement. Identifying a weakness in your stats and specifically training it in practice is exactly how elite goalies develop. Data-driven improvement.",tip:"Stats show a weakness? Train it specifically. Self-scouting drives improvement."},
    {id:"u18g20",cat:"Goalie",concept:"Clutch performance mindset",d:3,pos:["G"],sit:"It's the championship game. Third period. Score is tied. Every save matters. You can feel the pressure building. How do you manage the mental side?",opts:["Trust your preparation — focus on the next puck, not the situation. Use physical cues (post tap, deep breath) to stay present. The moment is big, but the puck is still the same size.","Try not to think about the pressure since acknowledging the pressure makes it worse and the best thing you can do is pretend it's a regular game and that nothing special is instead","Embrace the pressure completely and use the adrenaline to make bigger, more dramatic saves since clutch performances require superhuman effort and the pressure gives you that extra","Tell yourself that it doesn't matter if you give up a goal since taking the pressure off yourself by accepting failure will actually make you play better and more freely in the big"],ok:0,why:"Clutch mindset: trust preparation, focus on the next puck, use physical reset cues. The moment is big, but the save technique is the same. Presence over pressure.",tip:"Championship moment? Trust preparation. Next puck. Physical reset. Presence over pressure."},
  ],

}

